<SLUG> BC-GAMBLE-REPORT-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATIONAL REPORT ON GAMBLING URGES A PAUSE IN CREATING CASINOS AND
GAMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN MURPHY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A national pause in the rush to ever more gambling
was urged Friday in a long-awaited report that people on both sides
of the issue touted.
</P>
<P>
   The National Gambling Impact Study Commission said gambling had
been a boon to local economies but a bane in the lives of millions
of people who fell victim to its promise of easy riches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yielding more than $50 billion in gross revenues and still
growing, and with little end in sight to the proliferation of
gambling, our country stands at a crossroads,'' the commission said
in the opening paragraph of its report.
</P>
<P>
   The commission says states and Indian tribes that regulate most
casinos should consider a halt to more expansion until the true
costs and benefits can be weighed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no easy formula for this,'' commission Chairwoman Kay
C. James said Friday. ``I am deeply disturbed by the impact of
gambling on the lives of individuals, families and on
communities.''
</P>
<P>
   The gambling industry has grown tenfold since 1975, and only
three states _ Utah, Hawaii and Tennessee _ have no form of legal
betting, the study found. There are now 100 riverboat or dockside
casinos in America, including nine in Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   The report offered other statistics: Revenue from legal wagering
had grown nearly 1,600 percent between 1976 and 1997; gambling
expenditure as a percentage of personal income had more than
doubled from 0.3 to 0.74; Indian tribe revenue had risen from $212
million to $6.7 billion since 1988.
</P>
<P>
   ``The commission has issued an eye-opening report, which I hope
communities across the country will take time to consider,'' said
Rep. Tim Roemer, an Indiana Democrat who co-sponsored a House
resolution Friday to adopt the 76 recommendations in the report.
</P>
<P>
   Gambling proponents took heart in the report, which found that
most Americans favored legalized gambling, that only a small
percentage were problem gamblers, that gambling created jobs and
that the industry was not controlled by organized crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we come out of this looking very good,'' said Frank J.
Fahrenkopf Jr., president and chief executive officer of the
American Gaming Association. ``The commercial casino industry had a
good story to tell, and they made a good case to the commission.''
</P>
<P>
   The commission, however, also heard from people who went broke
at casinos and whose gambling addictions led to divorce, spousal
abuse and attempted suicide.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the study found, compulsive gamblers cost taxpayers,
employers and creditors $6 billion to $9 billion annually in lost
jobs, crime, bankruptcies, divorce and health-care costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am more convinced now than ever that gambling is a
destroyer, that it undermines the work ethic, that it is
devastating to those who give in to it and that it has major
implications for families,'' said James C. Dobson, a commission
member and founder of a Colorado-based group called Focus on the
Family.
</P>
<P>
   The commission study was about a lot more than casinos. Many of
its 76 recommendations focused on lotteries, horse and dog racing
and other forms of gambling.
</P>
<P>
   Among its recommendations:
</P>
<P>
   Set the legal gambling age at 21 for all forms of gambling in
all states. The limit is already 21 in Missouri and Kansas casinos.
</P>
<P>
   Scale back on advertising by state lotteries, especially
advertising aimed at the poor.
</P>
<P>
   Eliminate so-called ``convenience gambling,'' in which slot
machines and video poker machines are put in groceries, gas
stations, bars and other places at which people might play them on
impulse.
</P>
<P>
   Ban automated-teller cash machines inside casinos.
</P>
<P>
   Ban gambling on the Internet, in which people run up credit-card
bills placing wagers at home. Missouri and Kansas already have laws
against Internet gambling, laws that are being enforced.
</P>
<P>
   Prohibit bets on college and other amateur athletic events.
</P>
<P>
   Restrict what casino companies can donate to political
campaigns. Gambling interests gave $6.3 million to candidates for
Congress in 1997 and 1998, compared with $10.1 million the previous
eight years, according the group Common Cause.
</P>
<P>
   The gambling-impact commission was appointed by the president
and leaders of Congress and held two years of hearings. The nine
members had strong views for and against gambling but reached
unanimous votes on most issues.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Coccimiglio, a gambling industry analyst for Prudential
Securities in New York, said the report was good news in that it
did not propose federal taxes on gambling and alleges no widespread
corruption.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mainstream commercial industries, especially destination
casino resorts, come out well,'' he said. ``By and large, it's
pretty positive for the industry.''
</P>
<P>
   The commission said the federal government should not attempt to
override states and tribes on gambling regulations, except to ban
Internet gambling.
</P>
<P>
   The commission's call on states and tribes to pause to consider
curtailing gambling's growth drew mixed reaction in industry. New
gambling operations are pursued only after some study is done, a
gambling official said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's interesting that they don't think that is already
happening,'' said Pat Martin, director of external communications
for Harrah's Entertainment, which has casinos in Missouri and
Kansas. ``We work with the states on that.''
</P>
<P>
   Missouri has not approved a new casino in two years and only one
new casino is now under study, said Kevin Mullally, deputy director
for legal and legislative affairs for the Missouri Gaming
Commission. MORE
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Missouri Gaming Commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always had the go-slow approach and only when it appears
there is significant demand for a new facility have we licensed
one,'' Mullally said.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri, however, is considering loosening gambling regulations
by abolishing boarding time restrictions on the riverboats. At the
same time, efforts would be made to retain the $500 loss limit and
to move ATM machines off the boats.
</P>
<P>
   A halt to further development of casinos would hit the Indian
gambling industry hardest, said a spokeswoman for the National
Indian Gaming Association. The report said there were 260 Indian
reservation casinos, including four in Kansas, but Sheila Morago of
the Indian gaming association said her group counted 311.
</P>
<P>
   Casinos bring jobs and therefore more money and services to
reservations, many which are economically depressed, Morago said,
so plans are in place for more casinos.
</P>
<P>
   ``A pause would be detrimental to some tribes,'' Morago said.
``Indian tribes have been in a pause for 150 years.''
</P>
<P>
   But just as gambling may boost the fortunes of some, it can sap
the resources of people it lures, the study said. In that regard,
lotteries took heat for spending about $400 million a year
nationwide on advertising.
</P>
<P>
   In Missouri, the state lottery spends about $8 million on
broadcast and newspaper advertising annually but does not aim at
the poor with images of quick riches, said a lottery spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the lottery, like any other business, you have to advertise
your product,'' said Gary Gonder, director of communications for
the lottery. ``We don't target any demographic area or race.''
</P>
<P>
   The commission, however, said not enough consideration was being
given to the problems gambling could cause. It cites a study
showing that 2.5 million Americans are pathological gamblers and 3
million are problem gamblers.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Whyte, executive director of the National Council on
Problem Gambling, said its study found that states spent only $20
million a year to deal with problem gambling and that 17 states
spent nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Whyte's group proposes that every ad for gambling have a warning
about the addictive possibilities and that ads include a help-line
phone number.
</P>
<P>
   William A. Bible, a member of the national commission, said he
hoped that the group's legacy would be that it successfully pressed
for more research into the ills of gambling.
</P>
<P>
   Another commission member advised a balanced view of the
economic and social effect of gambling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Economically depressed cities that have been ignored by
private business are being helped,'' Richard C. Leone said. ``But
there is a price to pay unless we aggressively go after the
downside.''
</P>
</TEXT>
