<SLUG> BC-STAR-JOURNAL-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A STROKE IS THE LATEST OBSTACLE TO CONFRONT SUCCESSFUL RESTAURANT
DUO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE POPPER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, MO. _ Every morning as Mike Daniels opens his
restaurant _ Jake Edwards Bar-B-Q _ he has an aching sense that
he's about to face the world with only one good hand.
</P>
<P>
   And if you understand the substance behind that figure of
speech, you know he's right.
</P>
<P>
   Metaphorically, his other hand is a man named Jesse Smith. And
six months ago, at the age of 39, Smith had a stroke from which he
is now struggling to recover.
</P>
<P>
   ``For more than 15 years it was just me and Jesse running this
place,'' said Daniels. ``We did it all together. I never would have
made it a success without him.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, until he met Smith, he barely made it at all.
</P>
<P>
   Daniels, now 41 and a former bricklayer, entered the restaurant
business alone and on a whim 18 years ago. It was almost a
disaster.
</P>
<P>
   One of Daniels' relatives owned the building that housed the
restaurant popularly known as Jake's. And Daniels, who cleaned the
parking lot on weekends, got to know Edwards, a colorful, old-time
restaurateur, over a more-than-occasional beer.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards, slick-bald and round as he was tall, was a
beer-drinking, hard-gambling, lovable fellow. But he wanted out of
his business.
</P>
<P>
   So one day when Daniels, then 23, drove up in a brand-new
Trans-Am, Edwards took a look and said, ``Kid, you ought to turn
that car in and use the money to buy this place.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's what Daniels did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sold the car and bought Jake's for $10,000 on the spot. The
problem was that Jake just sort of left after that, sort of
disappeared. He didn't teach me a thing. And I'd never run a
restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't really get things going until I met Jesse.''
</P>
<P>
   Daniels met Smith one morning at a restaurant where Smith was a
short-order cook.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could see Jesse knew what he was doing,'' Daniels said. ``So
I told him I needed help. He said he'd come over and take a look.
And he did. But he didn't say anything at first, and neither did I.
With Jesse, you sense right away that you don't tell him things. No
one tells him what to do. No one.''
</P>
<P>
   And that, said Smith's sister, Shirley Knighten, who raised her
brother after their mother died, is the rock-hard truth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jesse's a stubborn, independent man,'' she said. ``He keeps
things to himself until he thinks they're ripe. Before that, he's
not showing you anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, barely out of high school when he met Daniels, looked
things over, pondered the situation, and finally said he'd help.
</P>
<P>
   ``From that day on things changed,'' Daniels said. ``Jesse is a
really smart man. And working together we learned how to make this
place something special.''
</P>
<P>
   Together they mastered pit cooking, using only Ozark white
hickory, cooking the meat 24 hours, cooling it for days, aging it
in its own juice, and then bringing it back up to serving
temperature.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some days in that kitchen we'd just look at each other and
say, `Wow, that's some good stuff,' &UR; '' Daniels said.
</P>
<P>
   They got rid of the restaurant's old meat slicer and began
carving every portion by hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was all trial and error. We taught ourselves how to slice
hot brisket so you could pull the meat apart like an accordion and
see light through it. It was that tender.''
</P>
<P>
   They created a new sauce, adding many fresh ingredients to Jake
Edwards' old recipe. They began making sweet potato fries, perhaps
the first in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   One year after they teamed up, a three-star newspaper review
raved about Jake's ``dark, sweet sauce,'' the sweet potatoes and
the ``intense naturally smoked flavor'' of the meat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our business tripled overnight,'' Daniels said.
</P>
<P>
   The buzz was on. Jake's was hot. A radio host called it one of
his favorites.
</P>
<P>
   During lunch hour a line of customers often extended half a
block up Main street.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their success, Daniels and Smith knew they were an odd
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like night and day,'' said Daniels. ``And maybe that's why it
worked. I'm an affable, beer-drinking kind of guy, and Jesse, well,
he's a world-class loner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found out that he is an artist, a musician, a photographer,
a kind of genius with electronics, but also a man who keeps his own
life very private. For years he never even gave me his phone
number. He was that solitary.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we shared a desire for perfection in the restaurant. We
wanted every hand-carved serving to look like a picture. And we
went through some serious times together making it happen. We came
to trust each other completely.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, when Daniels married a Panamanian woman and had to
remain in Panama for five weeks, Smith took over the entire
operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't take long vacations in this business. And I wouldn't
have trusted anyone else to run the place,'' Daniels said. ``For
that alone, I owe him more than I can express.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith shouldered the added responsibility despite increasing
concerns about his own health.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   his own health.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago he lost an eye to diabetes, which left him even
more inwardly focused, more intense and solitary.
</P>
<P>
   And then, on Jan. 5 of this year, just after noon, he suddenly
developed an agonizing headache followed by an eerie sense of
lightheadedness.
</P>
<P>
   Characteristically, he called no one, sought no help.
</P>
<P>
   He drove himself to the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``To this day, I don't understand how he did that,'' said
Knighten, his sister.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was already becoming paralyzed on his right side, and his
car has a stick shift.''
</P>
<P>
   But he made it to Truman Medical Center's emergency entrance
before he collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   That evening, hospital officials contacted Knighten.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jesse couldn't move or talk at all,'' she said. ``I don't
think the doctors expected him to make it back.''
</P>
<P>
   But he has.
</P>
<P>
   Several days ago, Smith was in the kitchen of his East Side
house, standing, walking, cooking his own dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to take care of him,'' said his sister, ``but he wants
to do for himself. That's the way he's always been.''
</P>
<P>
   Now in physical therapy six hours a day at Trinity Lutheran
Hospital, Smith has made astonishing progress.
</P>
<P>
   Although one arm remains partly paralyzed, and he still has
trouble forming complete sentences, he indicated that he intended
to return to Jake's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will,'' he said. ``I will.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He says that to me every day,'' said Knighten. ``It's so
important to him.''
</P>
<P>
   It is equally important to Daniels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without Jesse I have to close down at five o'clock in the
afternoon during the week now,'' he said, ``because there's no
replacing him. I wouldn't even try. I wouldn't think of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It started out as just me and Jesse, and that's the way it
will be again. It may take time, but he'll be back. If it can be
done, that man can do it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
