<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-CARDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS BEAT CARDS, 6-2, FOR 10TH WIN IN 12 GAMES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Manager Bobby Valentine of the Mets invited trouble
for himself 12 days ago by placing a timetable on his job. Sitting
in Yankee Stadium, on the heels of a season-high eight-game losing
streak that had just cost three of his coaches their jobs,
Valentine said, ``I believe within the next 55 games if we're not
better, I shouldn't be the manager.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, Valentine has met his challenge. Because after the Mets
defeated the St. Louis Cardinals, 6-2, here Friday night to give
them 10 victories in the 12 games since the skipper issued what
appeared to be his managerial death sentence, Valentine is off to a
pretty good start.
</P>
<P>
   At 37-30, the Mets are back to where they were when they began
the slide: seven games over .500, one shy of their season high. And
Friday night at Busch Stadium, a pair of 40-year-olds, Orel
Hershiser and Rickey Henderson, struck a blow for both Valentine
and middle age.
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser (7-5) tossed five shutout innings of one-hit ball and
won for the fifth time in his last six starts. Valentine gambled _
and lost _ in the top of the sixth when he pinch-hit Matt Franco
for Hershiser with one out and the bases loaded in a 2-0 game. Juan
Acevedo struck Franco out, but Henderson followed with a two-out,
two-run single to center to help put the game away.
</P>
<P>
   In 13 starts with the Mets, Hershiser has lasted longer than six
innings just once. But the Mets' bullpen has been deep enough to
cover for him, as it did Friday night. Turk Wendell tossed two
scoreless innings in relief of Hershiser before allowing a 2-run
home run to Thomas Howard in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Later that inning, Armando Benitez came on with a runner on
first and walked Edgar Renteria on four pitches to give the
Cardinals runners on first and second with two out. But Benitez
roared back from a 3-ball 0-strike count to Mark McGwire to catch
McGwire looking at a 96 mph fastball for a called strike three;
McGwire had represented the tying run.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Piazza then belted his 14th home run of the season to lead
off the ninth to finish out the scoring and extend his career-best
hitting streak to 21 games.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza's blast provided the insurance for what was arguably
Hershiser's finest performance with the Mets. The right-hander, who
signed with the team near the end of spring training, faced two
batters over the minimum 15 through his five innings, as he earned
his 197th career victory.
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser did it with both style and guile. He picked off the
first runner he allowed, Ray Lankford, who worked a walk to open
the second. The only hit Hershiser allowed was a lead-off single to
Joe McEwing in the fourth, and McEwing was erased when shortstop
Rey Ordonez made a nifty turn to throw out Renteria and complete a
double play.
</P>
<P>
   In all, Hershiser threw just 69 pitches, 47 for strikes. He
walked three and struck out four and was in trouble only once. That
was in the fifth, when he walked Fernando Tatis with one out and
then Darren Bragg an out later to give the Cardinals runners on
first and second with two out. But Eli Marrero flew out to right
and Hershiser departed with a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Over his last six starts, Hershiser has allowed 14 runs in 34
2/3 innings, for a very respectable 3.63 ERA. And Friday night's
outing followed a trend: Since the housecleaning that erased
pitching coach Bob Apodaca and bullpen coach Randy Niemann after
the Mets' eighth straight loss, the team's starters are a spotless
9-0 with a 2.82 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' hitters have done their share, too. One of the reasons
given for dismissing hitting coach Tom Robson was that the Mets
were leaving too many runners on base. Edgardo Alfonzo belted a
hit-and-run double inside third to score Henderson from first in
the third to give the Mets a 1-0 lead. And then, after Roger Cedeno
beat out a bunt single with two out in the fourth and advanced to
third on a wild pickoff attempt, the rejuvenated Ordonez singled up
the middle for the Mets' second run.
</P>
<P>
   The 24-year-old Cedeno and the 26-year-old Ordonez did their
best to represent their generation. Cedeno, who had missed two
starts with a bruised calf, had three hits and stole two bases, as
he extended his major-league lead in steals to 37. Ordonez had
three more hits in four at-bats to raise his season average to
.286. And that is significant because the Gold Glove shortstop has
never hit better than .257 in the major leagues.
</P>
</TEXT>
