<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-REPRISAL-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKER SAYS HE HAS BEEN UNFAIRLY INVESTIGATED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GROMER JEFFERS JR.  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ State Rep. Terry Riley said Friday that
Kansas City police are unfairly focusing on him in an investigation
into a reported break-in at the office of Mayor Kay Barnes' chief
campaign consultant.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference, Riley said detectives asked him Thursday
to turn over a copy of a document that described a St. Louis
company's strategy to privatize the Water Services Department in
Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Riley, who was elected as an independent from Kansas City,
referred to the document when he helped lead a municipal employees'
protest at City Hall two weeks ago that questioned the involvement
of Barnes and her campaign consultant Pat Gray with the company.
Riley also called for Barnes to resign and for U.S. Attorney Steve
Hill to investigate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they (police) are coming after me for what transpired
at City Hall,'' said Riley, who added he knew nothing about the
theft of documents from Gray's office. ``I guess this is what you
get when you try to stand up for the working people of this city.''
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City Police Chief Rick Easley declined to comment Friday
on Riley's allegations. ``That's under investigation,'' Easley said
of the break-in. ``We don't comment on active investigations.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Barnes said she also would make no comment.
</P>
<P>
   Gray, who ran Barnes' successful campaign for mayor this spring,
did not return calls for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Gray reported that his office was burglarized in early March and
petty cash was taken. A supplemental police report, filed March 31,
indicated that ``documents'' also were taken.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star reported May 28 that Gray was working for
Environmental Management Corp. while he was running the Barnes
campaign. The company is part of a consortium called EA2/Systems,
which is interested in managing the Water Services Department.
</P>
<P>
   Gray's involvement with Barnes' campaign and EA2/Systems at the
same time did not violate any laws.
</P>
<P>
   But Riley, city workers and community activists were angered by
a document _ obtained anonymously through the mail by The Star _
outlining a plan for taking over Water Services. It included a
strategy to elect a mayor and council that favored privatization.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes has said she met twice with officials from EA2/Systems
before being elected March 30, and one 45-minute meeting included
Gray. She said she had not been influenced by Gray and that she had
been an advocate of exploring public-private partnerships for
years.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, city workers demonstrated for the second time in
two weeks at City Hall, demanding that Barnes explain her
relationship with Gray and EA2/Systems.
</P>
<P>
   In a later interview, Barnes said the city has no plans to sell
Water Services and that she ``never has been coerced or urged to do
so.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley said Friday that, to his knowledge, he's the ``lone
suspect'' in the police investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's strange, because hundreds of people in this city have a
copy of that document,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Riley reiterated that he did not burglarize Gray's office. At
the time, he was running for Kansas City's vacant 43rd District
seat in the Missouri House and said he had no political motivation
to break into Gray's office.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what happens in Kansas City when you call for an
investigation,'' Riley said. ``You get investigated.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he would turn over his copy of the document _ which he
said was put anonymously in his mailbox about the time The Star
article was published May 28 _ to police in the presence of his
attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Michael Fletcher called the questioning of Riley by
police a ``blatant abuse of power.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you select Terry Riley as the person to investigate?''
Fletcher asked. ``It's not a coincidence that someone who contested
the actions of the mayor is subjected to a police investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Ron McMillan, a community activist who attended both City Hall
protests, appeared at the news conference in Riley's defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``These tactics are not new,'' McMillan said of Gray. ``Setting
people up. Political intimidation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
