<HEADER>
A1789 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-SPURS-ART-     06-19 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-SPURS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPURS TAKE COMMANDING 2-0 LEAD OVER KNICKS IN NBA FINALS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo of is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ The Knicks' brazen Latrell Sprewell glared at the
Spurs and scowled at them, too. But the unassuming Tim Duncan and
the serene David Robinson just took all of the aggression and
intensity he brought with every drive and slapped it silly.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, the Knicks had no answer for the Spurs' towering
duo, who combined to block nine shots and lead the San Antonio
Spurs to an 80-67 victory tonight in Game 2 of the NBA finals at
the Alamodome. The Spurs, who took a 2-0 lead in the best-of-7-game
series, were led by 25 points from Duncan, who was dominating.
Robinson and Duncan combined for 41 points and 26 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks had 19 points from Allan Houston and 26 from
Sprewell, but Sprewell shot 8 for 22 and tried to make every trip
down the floor a one-on-one challenge. As a team, the Knicks shot
32.9 percent from the floor, while the Spurs shot 42.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The series will move to Madison Square Garden for the next three
games, if three are necessary, beginning with Game 3 on Monday
night.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks came into the game understanding how timid they had
become as Game 1 wore on, how their layups had been too tentative
and their drives too awkward as they tried to steer around the
shot-blocking force of Robinson and Duncan in the paint.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to know they are there,'' Sprewell said. ``Those guys
are good. You have to have a certain amount of respect for them.
But you can't let that respect make you soft going to the basket.
You have to go in strong and hard and still think attack.''
</P>
<P>
   They went in strong and hard to start the game. Houston and
Sprewell made repeated attacks on the rim in the first half, but
almost every single dunk and layup had to go through Duncan and
Robinson, who combined for six blocks in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Undeterred, the Knicks kept coming, and by sheer volume of
attempts _ 47 first-half shots compared to the Spurs' 34 _ they
managed to come through just enough to stay close, trailing by
39-34 at the half. With Sprewell playing a lot of one-on-one
basketball, the Knicks shot 29.8 percent for the half, while the
Spurs methodically hit 44.1 percent, riding Duncan's 12 first-half
points.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell also had 12 points in the half, but was 4 for 12 from
the field. Next to him, Houston scored 11 points on 5-of-10
shooting. More efficient, Houston was the calm beside the stormy
Sprewell.
</P>
<P>
   Just before the start of the second half, Sprewell was spotted
sitting outside the locker room, with one teammate beside him,
staring straight through the cinderblock wall before him. He was a
picture of intensity.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell came out firing the ball in the third period, but he
was backing away from driving and reverting to jump shooting and
missing. Meanwhile, the Spurs were living inside the paint, with
Robinson and Duncan each converting 3-point plays on the way to a
49-38 lead with 7 minutes 30 seconds left in the third.
</P>
<P>
   The never-say-die Knicks started creating opportunities by
forcing the Spurs into turnovers and taking advantage of missed
shots by Mario Elie and Sean Elliott. While Duncan and Robinson
were doing their thing, the Spurs' perimeter players were missing
open shots. Those misses allowed Houston to get hot and bring the
Knicks to within &UR;  &LR; three points.
</P>
<P>
   But after failing on three straight possessions, the Knicks
allowed Elliott to dart inside for a layup while drawing a foul on
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The layup was good, but when Elliott missed the free throw,
Marcus Camby allowed Duncan to slip inside him, grab the rebound
and go up for a dunk with 0.7 seconds left in the third period to
give the Spurs a 56-49 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the first half had been a study in frustration for the
Knicks. At one point, Sprewell, who was 2 for 8 in the first
quarter, began airing out his frustrations by trash-talking at
Elliott. It was as if Sprewell was trying to maintain the edge and
anger he needed to keep forging into the paint.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks missed six shots in the first quarter going right at
the rim, part of the reason they finished the quarter shooting 25.9
percent, and were behind, 20-15. The Spurs' frontcourt duo was
causing damage without drawing fouls. As hard as it was to believe
after Game 1's foul fest, there were no team fouls in the first
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The second started with plenty of whistles as the aggressors,
Robinson and Duncan, went to the free-throw line on consecutive
possessions and the Spurs built a 22-16 lead with 10 minutes left
in the half.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks needed a lift, and they got one when Camby came in
and countered the lengthy twin towers with some long arms and
lively steps of his own. He scored on a layup, then came back with
a runner to pull the Knicks to within 22-20 with eight minutes left
in the half.
</P>
<P>
   Just as the Knicks crept close, the Spurs began to make them pay
for double-teaming Robinson, who passed out beautifully to the open
man. Two jumpers and a 3-pointer later, the Spurs had a 29-22 lead.
</P>
<P>
   This was the same issue that haunted the Knicks in Game 1, when
they left Jaren Jackson open to bury them from the perimeter with
five 3-pointers. But just as in Game 1, the Knicks found a way to
stay close despite their mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   After falling behind, 39-30, the Knicks finished the half with a
drive by Houston for a layup and a trip to the free-throw line by
Sprewell, who hit both free throws with 4.7 seconds on the clock,
cutting the Spurs' lead to 39-34 at the half.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks' gutsy shots and their uninhibited attempts to drive
to the basket despite the presence of Robinson and Duncan were part
of an effort that helped them stay with the Spurs, who were
dominating in every way but the score.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not intimidated,'' Sprewell had said. ``We're not
intimidated at all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
