<HEADLINE>
STRAWBERRY AWAITS HIS FATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Although Darryl Strawberry received a 120-day
suspension Friday from Major League Baseball, it remains uncertain
whether he will return to the New York Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry, the former Dodger whose long-awaited punishment for
possession of cocaine and solicitation of a prostitute last April,
has been waiting for a decision since negotiations started between
the Major League Players Association and the commissioner's office.
</P>
<P>
   The suspension is retroactive to April 24, the day Strawberry
was given an administrative leave by the commissioners office. He
was arrested April 14 in Tampa, Fla. Strawberry, 37, pleaded no
contest to the charges on May 26. He was tested for drugs the day
before his arrest, which proved negative.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner Bud Selig was seeking a season-long ban as part of
his increasing hard line against drug offenders, but several
factors weighed in Strawberry's favor _ including his battle with
colon cancer and his previously clean record regarding his drug
aftercare program. Selig also wanted to avoid a lengthy appeal
process by the union.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry completed a one-month drug rehabilitation program in
1994 when he played with the Dodgers. He was suspended for 60 days
in 1995 after testing positive for cocaine. He also underwent
treatment for alcohol abuse in 1990 when he played for the New York
Mets.
</P>
<P>
   It is uncertain whether Yankees owner George Steinbrenner will
bring back Strawberry after he becomes eligible to play later this
summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We respect the commissioners decision and have no further
comment at this time,'' Yankees general manager Brian Cashman said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Erstad dropped: Angels manager Terry Collins is such a fan of
Darin Erstad that he was quick to point out that Friday's demotion
from the leadoff spot to No. 7 was just part of the club's strategy
against left-hander Andy Pettitte.
</P>
<P>
   Erstad entered the game batting .242 and his average was only
that high because of a seven-game hitting streak (.357, 10 for 28).
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, Erstad went 1 for 3 with an eighth-inning single
that followed Troy Glaus' home run.
</P>
<P>
   Seventh is the lowest Erstad has batted this year. He has led
off 36 times, batted second twice, third 13 times, fifth six times
and sixth six times. But Collins, pointing out two solid seasons
that included an All-Star appearance last year, said Erstad is not
overwhelmed by trying to live up to past performance..
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody works harder or impresses you more with his dedication
than Darin,'' Collins said. ``We just wanted to switch things up a
little. It is nothing more than that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
