<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR EWING, THE TOUGHEST ACT OF ALL
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ He smiles and swears that he is wrapped up in
rooting, just another well-dressed fan with a courtside seat.
``Just like the Indiana series,'' said Patrick Ewing, but you know
this has to be an act, the toughest act of all, sitting close
enough that he can practically feel the finals he can't touch.
</P>
<P>
   He can't limp out there, even to be just another 7-footer, a
tag-team defender against Tim Duncan and the Spurs. If Ewing could
have played, Larry Johnson would not be asked to do what he can't,
cover a highly skilled player half a foot taller. It would be the
most bitter irony of all if the Knicks don't win because Patrick
Ewing couldn't be a generic big body, another six fouls.
</P>
<P>
   Game 2 of the NBA finals began Friday night with an air of
premature inevitability, based mostly on Game 1's having been an
extension of pre-series conventional wisdom. This is not the first
time people have overreacted to one game, but the view from here
was that the Spurs looked unbeatable only when Duncan or David
Robinson were posting up against a gimpy Johnson, waiting for him
to foul, or grow.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's 6-5 against a 7-1 guy, and that's going to hurt,''
Robinson said, matter of factly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have Patrick, we're short-handed,'' said the Knicks'
assistant coach, Don Chaney. ``Larry's going to have play one of
the big guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago in Houston, Ewing could have stepped in at any
point in the fourth quarter of Game 7 and demanded the ball from
the wild-eyed John Starks. The Knicks needed him to be the
franchise player against Hakeem Olajuwon then. Not now. Not here.
Thirty-some minutes matching up against Duncan or Robinson would
have been sufficient, along with a few short, spot-up jumpers when
Latrell Sprewell and Allan Houston found themselves looking up at
the towers inside the lane.
</P>
<P>
   That possibility ended with Ewing's torn Achilles' tendon early
in the Indiana series. Are we still allowed a teeny criticism of
Ernie Grunfeld's roster construction? Given the advanced age of the
Knicks' two centers, maybe it wasn't such a good idea to have had
41-year-old Herb Williams and Georgetown alum David Wingate taking
up space as proverbial good guys and friends to Ewing. Buck
Williams, or some other veteran of interior playoff wars, sure
would be useful now.
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly, that's retrospective nit-picking, but front-line
attrition was one of the primary issues confronting Jeff Van Gundy
Friday night at the Alamodome _ the reality of finally confronting
a go-to star at the top of his game, of moving far up in class from
Rik Smits, the foul-plagued Pacer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Smits is big, 7-4, but you can get into his legs and he's not
the athlete that Duncan is, as far as catching and finishing,'' Van
Gundy said. ``With Duncan, if you play behind him, he can keep post
position because he's so strong. If you double him after you play
behind him, he's a great, great passer. And if you front him, he's
got great strength and hands. And then Robinson makes the high-low
pass as well as anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   The operative word here is great, but as has been the case with
every great player, rising to the level of championship greatness
requires impeccable fundamentals as well.
</P>
<P>
   When David Stern's handpicked committee to restore fluidity and
scoring to professional basketball convenes on Tuesday in New York,
the first order of business should be popcorn and a movie. Watch a
Game 1 tape of Duncan, the emerging standard-bearer who doesn't
waste motion, who shoots layups when he can dunk, who intuitively
understands the difference between a decent shot and a better one.
</P>
<P>
   By all means, widen the lane, make it tougher to grind. Just
don't think the dearth of offense is all related to athleticism and
rules. Duncan, like Olajuwon, didn't grow up with Amateur Athletic
Union coaches trying to raise their own profiles through a
developing adolescent. Maybe that is something for the NBA
committee to look into: the notion that American kids place a
higher priority on winning than learning.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks went through three playoff series and did not meet up
with one player who made them pay a price, no matter which tactic
they tried. Ewing, competitive against Alonzo Mourning on one good
leg, could not have stopped Duncan any more than Chris Dudley,
Marcus Camby or Kurt Thomas. But one more big man would have freed
Larry Johnson from the task of needing a ladder to guard an agile
7-footer. This series was already a tall enough order for the
Knicks. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
