<HEADLINE>
HARRY S. TRUMAN GOOD NEIGHBOR AWARD FOUNDATION SELECTS NEW
PRESIDENT AND APPOINTS FIRST AFRICAN-AMERICAN BOARD MEMBER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN BURNES  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The Harry S. Truman Good Neighbor Award
Foundation has selected a new president, as well as the first
African-American member to serve on its board.
</P>
<P>
   Business executive Charles W. Battey is the president of the
foundation, which gives an award each year to a national figure who
exemplifies the ideals of President Truman.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very proud of the foundation's rich history, but it is
an appropriate time for a changing of the guard and to reappraise
what we have done,'' Battey said.
</P>
<P>
   Battey, of Mission Hills, Kan., replaces Philip Pistilli, the
Kansas City hotel executive who had been foundation president since
1982. Pistilli will now be foundation chairman.
</P>
<P>
   The first black board member is Cordell D. Meeks Jr., a
Wyandotte County District Court judge.
</P>
<P>
   The changes suggest the arrival of a new era for the foundation.
In the last year the foundation has been criticized for not having
selected an African-American to receive its annual award, and also
for having little diversity on its governing board.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Cordell Meeks is a good start,'' Battey said. ``We
want to be more inclusive.''
</P>
<P>
   Meeks said he joined the board for several reasons.
</P>
<P>
   He has several friends on the board. He shared a dormitory with
one of them, Willard Snyder, at the University of Kansas in the
1960s.
</P>
<P>
   His late father, Cordell D. Meeks Sr., was a friend of Truman's
and served as a delegate to the 1948 Democratic National Convention
in Philadelphia. The younger Meeks also has long admired Truman's
initiatives on civil rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is more than just trying to satisfy the board's need for
diversity,'' said Meeks. ``It is also a strong desire on my part to
honor the name of Harry Truman.''
</P>
<P>
   Other new board members are Kevin Pistilli of the Raphael Hotel
Group and E. Gerald Farrell, a Kansas City accountant.
</P>
<P>
   Last year U.S. District Judge Scott O. Wright criticized the
foundation for not having selected an African-American to receive
the annual award, which the foundation has presented since 1973.
</P>
<P>
   The first black honoree was historian John Hope Franklin,
honored last month.
</P>
<P>
   A foundation board member for about 15 years, Battey was
chairman and chief executive officer of KN Energy of Lakewood,
Colo., from 1989 through 1994. Before then he held various
executive positions with United Telecommunications, predecessor of
Sprint Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Another concern is the foundation's financial future. Battey
deemed the foundation's condition ``satisfactory.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the board recently decided to charge a fee _ yet to be
determined _ for persons who attend the annual lunch at which the
Good Neighbor Award is presented. The fee would help sustain both
the event and the scholarships the foundation awards each year.
</P>
<P>
   It is a change for the foundation, which has followed the
tradition established by Kansas City businessman Henry Talge, who
for years organized the event.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have never charged for lunch,'' said Battey. ``Mr. Talge
wanted to celebrate Mr. Truman's birthday, and it started
relatively small.''
</P>
<P>
   Talge, who died in 1990, did leave money for the foundation. But
the lunches have grown along with their cost. In recent years about
500 guests have attended.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we as a board chose, we could (serve lunch free) for a few
more years more and then go out of existence,'' Battey said. ``But
we want to perpetuate the foundation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
