</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLLANDSWORTH SPOT ALL READY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ The flexibility that manager Davey Johnson says
is missing from the Dodgers' offense could return today with
left-handed hitting Todd Hollandsworth.
</P>
<P>
   Hollandsworth went 1 for 1 with a double and was hit by a pitch
in a rehab stint for Single-A San Bernardino on Friday. Barring a
setback, he's slated to be activated before this afternoon's game
against the Philadelphia Phillies.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said if Hollandsworth, nursing a sore oblique muscle in
his right side, is ready, he wouldn't hesitate using him to rest
his outfielders, particularly Gary Sheffield and Raul Mondesi.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he comes through clean, we have the option to use him,''
Johnson said. ``I think we need to start trying a few different
things, getting more people in the lineup, rest more people, using
the whole bench more often. . . . I'm going to be able to rest a
few guys with the left-handed bat.''
</P>
<P>
   During spring training, Johnson talked extensively about using
Hollandsworth to rest each of his outfielders and give him a
left-handed bat against a tough right-hander.
</P>
<P>
   The situation was ideal in the series opener against the
Phillies, who started Curt Schilling. Sheffield sat out with
tightness in his hamstring but was replaced by the
right-handed-hitting Trenidad Hubbard because the Dodgers don't
have a left-handed-hitting reserve outfielder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody on the bench has a purpose, not just to sit there,''
Johnson said. ``It's been difficult for me to rest a guy like
(Eric) Young and use (Tripp) Cromer against a tough righty. I
planned on (Hollandsworth) being a big part of the club, but with
his hamstring and his ribs, I haven't been able to.''
</P>
<P>
   Hollandsworth's missed 29 of 65 games and is on the disabled
list for the second time. He started in center field for San
Bernardino at Bakersfield. In his brief spell with the Dodgers,
he's hitting .304.
</P>
<P>
   ``Davey's thinking, and he's right, we've been short-handed most
of the year in getting the proper matchups,'' Dodgers general
manager Kevin Malone said. ``This should help. We'll wait and make
sure Hollandsworth is healthy, though.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Dodgers activate Hollandsworth, they'll most likely
trim their pitching staff from 12 to 11. The pitchers to lose out
are either Doug Bochtler or Mike Maddux.
</P>
<P>
   If the Dodgers make a decision based on performance, it could
mean the left-handed Bochtler, who has a 5.54 ERA in 12 games.
Maddux, a right-hander, has a 2.25 ERA in 14 games with the
Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   __ Slow starters: The Dodgers entered the Phillies series with
11 losses in their last 15 games, and part of it is the
slow-starting offense. Adrian Beltre's second-inning homer off
Schilling was the sixth run the Dodgers scored in the first two
innings in their last 16 games. They've scored three runs in each
of the first two innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Young) and myself, we're trying to do too much,'' said
Vizcaino, who is 11 for 49 (.224) and scored five runs since being
activated June 4. ``You have to be more patient. You have to think
it through, but sometimes it comes more natural. If you have a
plan, most times you're going to be successful. I guess we're
trying to do too much.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Balks, walks and chalk: Johnson reiterated what bullpen coach
Rick Dempsey said a day earlier by stating that he thought Todd
Hundley might be ready to catch next weekend in San Francisco.
Hundley has been working vigorously on the side with Dempsey the
last four days in a mini-spring training. ``I probably could have
done this out of the spring. Halfway in the back of my mind I knew
better, but I was hoping,'' Johnson said. However, Johnson didn't
say Hundley would take back the every-day catching duties. . . .
With Sheffield sitting, Raul Mondesi and Eric Karros each moved up
a slot to bat third and fourth. . . . Young has 23 steals but one
since May 26.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
