<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-WRITER-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KC GIRL WRITES BOOK ABOUT AVIATOR, FRIEND OF EARHART 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK WIEBE  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ For the better part of 18 months, Sara
Rimmerman, budding writer, and Fay Gillis Wells, pioneering aviator
and friend of Amelia Earhart, talked long-distance nearly every
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Sara, 12, of Kansas City, was writing a book about Wells.
</P>
<P>
   Wells, 90, was giving her plenty of material.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just so amazed,'' Sara said. ``If she was talking about
someone famous, she'd just kind of mention it and go on. And you're
like, `Wait. You worked with him?' ''
</P>
<P>
   She talked, of course, about Earhart, with whom Wells founded
the International Organization of Women's Pilots, which today has
more than 6,500 members.
</P>
<P>
   But she also talked about helping Oklahoma aviator Wiley Post in
1933 become the first person to fly solo around the world. And she
told about world travels. As a correspondent for the New York
Herald Tribune in the 1930s, Wells covered a war between Ethiopia
and Italy, dignitaries in the Soviet Union and movie stars in
Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the stories appear in Sara's 40-page paperback book,
Hidden Heroine, which was released Friday by Zeus Publications of
Reston, Va.
</P>
<P>
   The book will go on sale again July 24 at the Atchison, Kan.,
annual celebration of Amelia Earhart's birthday. It is not yet
available in bookstores.
</P>
<P>
   Sara said the idea for the book came in January 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Wells, of Alexandria, Va., had spoken to Debbie Sack's
third-grade class. Sara's sister, Rachel (who wrote a poem that
appears in the book), was in the class and came home talking about
Wells.
</P>
<P>
   Rachel's excitement rubbed off on the whole family. Her mother,
Carol, a retired English teacher, asked Sack whether they could
meet Wells someday. Later that year Sack arranged a lunch with
Wells, who was visiting in the area.
</P>
<P>
   At the lunch, Wells entertained with stories about her life.
Sack, Sara recalled, asked Wells whether anyone had written a book
about her. No one had.
</P>
<P>
   Then Sack turned to Sara and said, ``Well, Sara, you like to
write....''
</P>
<P>
   Sara accepted the challenge. She spoke to people who knew Wells.
She thumbed through files and clicked away on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, I started writing it as a report,'' Sara said.
``Then it got really long, so I started breaking it up (into
chapters).''
</P>
<P>
   With editing help from Sack and another teacher, Sara finished
the job.
</P>
<P>
   The book takes a chronological look at Wells' life, starting
with her birth in Minneapolis. Sara recounts many adventures,
including how Wells survived the midair disintegration of a plane
in 1929 when she was taking flying lessons in Long Island, N.Y.
(Wells parachuted unhurt into a tree.)
</P>
<P>
   The book ends with the creation of the International Forest of
Friendship. Wells came up with the idea for the forest, which
includes trees donated by each state of the union, as a
bicentennial gift to Atchison from the International Organization
of Women's Pilots. In a concrete path winding through the forest
are the names of people who have made significant contributions to
aviation and aerospace.
</P>
<P>
   One day this week, Sara and Wells sat on a bench in the forest
near a gazebo named after Wells.
</P>
<P>
   Sara talked about Wells. But Wells seemed more interested in
talking about Sara. She showed off the necklace Sara had made her,
a string of small wooden cubes that spells out Wells' name.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's not just a writer,'' Wells said, listing Sara's other
passions: basketball, percussion, dancing.
</P>
<P>
   Sara interrupted: ``I don't take dance anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't dance?'' Wells said. ``Honey, it's the beginning of
your life. You've got to dance.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, Sara is content to write.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'd like to try a mystery next,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
