<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-ANGELS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PETTITTE ENDS SLUMP AS YANKEES DOWN ANGELS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Maybe Andy Pettitte needed to see his father in a
hospital bed again to give himself some perspective about his
pitching slump. Maybe Pettitte needed to feel that queasiness in
his stomach again to remind himself that baseball is merely a game.
Maybe Pettitte needed to be shocked off the field in order to relax
on the field.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reasons for his revival, Pettitte was very relaxed
Friday night while pitching the New York Yankees past Chuck Finley
and the Anaheim Angels, 4-1, at Yankee Stadium. Pettitte's best
game of the season ended a vicious slide in which he had lost three
straight starts while allowing 15 earned runs in 13 2/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Three days after Pettitte returned from visiting his ailing
father, the Yankee left-hander was matched against the Angels'
left-hander who usually owns the Yankees. Finley was solid, as
usual, but Pettitte was superb in stifling Anaheim on one run and
five hits in 7 1/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called my Dad today and he told me he was feeling better
than he has in 20 years,'' said Pettitte, who chuckled at the
obvious ploy designed to calm him. ``I told him, `Whatever. This
game is not that important. I'm worried about you.' It's easy to
focus once you get out on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   With their new No. 3 hitter, Derek Jeter, scoring one run,
driving in one run and getting two hits, the Yankees scored two
more runs than they had managed in the preceding two games and
halted the Angels for the first time in four games. Still, the
Yankees were most pleased with Pettitte.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's probably the best he's pitched all year,'' said Jeter.
``He had a sinker and a cutter. Hitters didn't know what to look
for.''
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte's performance was a dramatic change from last Sunday's,
when he was battered for six runs in an ugly 8-2 loss to the lowly
Florida Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   After Pettitte returned to New York around midnight, he learned
that his father, Tom, had been hospitalized because he felt pain in
his chest. The 49-year-old Tom Pettitte underwent double-bypass
heart surgery last Oct. 16, five days before his son clinched the
World Series title in Game 4.
</P>
<P>
   Once Pettitte received the sobering news, he never slept. The
pitcher had a car service pick him up at 4 a.m. and he took a 6
a.m. flight to Houston on Monday and spent the day with his father.
While a battery of tests showed that Tom's heart was fine, he is
scheduled to be examined by a neurosurgeon to determine the reason
for his dizzy spells.
</P>
<P>
   ``He still gets light headed and that's not right,'' Pettitte
said. ``He's off from work, so hopefully it'll help him.''
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte needed no help Friday night through the first seven
innings. How efficient was he? Until Troy Glaus belted a homer with
one out in the eighth, the Angels did not have one runner reach
second. After Pettitte allowed a single to Darrin Erstad, he was
replaced and received a rousing ovation. The game got stickier, but
Mariano Rivera stranded a total of four runners in the eighth and
ninth for his 18th save.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very calm tonight,'' manager Joe Torre said of
Pettitte. ``That told me he was in that zone I've seen him in so
often in '96 and '97. Tonight was one of those nights. He didn't
have that distressed look in his eyes. He was very calm and very
determined. This is big for him, especially with what he's been
through in the last week.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre made a lineup change that he had been mulling for several
days when he shifted Jeter from second place to third and put
Bernie Williams second. Jeter, who is second in the American League
in batting at .377, had never batted third in his blossoming
career.
</P>
<P>
   The switch worked because Jeter scored the first run and knocked
in the third as the Yankees ended a streak of six straight losses
to Finley. After Finley hit Jeter in the ribs in the fourth, Jeter,
who was also drilled by Anaheim's Troy Percival on May 10, flicked
the ball away with his bat.
</P>
<P>
   When Chili Davis blooped a single to center, Jeter scampered to
third. On a 3-2 pitch to Scott Brosius, Davis, with little speed
afoot, chugged toward second base. As Brosius struck out, Matt
Walbeck, the Anaheim catcher, whipped the ball to second baseman
Randy Velarde, who was charging toward the plate. But as soon as
the ball left Walbeck's hand, Jeter scooted for home and was
credited with a steal as the off-balance return throw sailed past
Walbeck.
</P>
<P>
   Two innings later, more shabby defense by the Angels and more
Jeter boosted the Yankees. Chuck Knoblauch singled and Williams
lined a ball to center that somehow skidded past Garret Anderson
and rolled to the wall. Knoblauch scored and Williams wound up on
third with a single and a two-base error.
</P>
<P>
   Jeter ripped Finley's next pitch past the drawn-in infield for a
single to make it 3-0. Expect Jeter to bat third again today and
tomorrow and so on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't do anything differently,'' said Jeter. ``It's just a
matter of my first at-bat being a minute and a half later.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
