<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-SEATTLE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A RELAXED AL GORE APPLAUDS RUSSIAN DEAL, CRITICIZES GOP VOTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Vice President Al Gore on Friday voiced relief and
enthusiasm that the United States had worked through ``a sticky
wicket'' with the Russians on Kosovo, while excoriating the
Republican-controlled Congress as having ``nothing to show'' on gun
safety at home.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview as his plane approached touchdown in Seattle,
Gore decried House GOP leaders for their ``cravenness'' to the
National Rifle Association. The House early Friday voted to kill
legislation to force background checks on those purchasing firearms
at gun shows. Gore was here to wrap up a cross-country tour after
formally announcing his candidacy for next year's presidential
race.
</P>
<P>
   Relaxed, with wife, Tipper, by his side, the vice president
shucked his suit coat and hosted a town meeting on trade and
technology before about 400 people at the Seattle Center. Gore was
unfazed even when an animal rights protester yelled ``Whale
killer!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I come out here I appreciate the First Amendment
more,'' Gore joked.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's stopover in Seattle, his eighth visit since the 1996
election, took place against a backdrop of hopeful news abroad and
political impasse at home.
</P>
<P>
   Gore _ a key administration point man in U.S. dealings with
Russia _ celebrated the deal that ended the six-day standoff over
Moscow's peacekeeping role in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an excellent agreement,'' he said in the interview. ``We
got everything that we needed. Cool heads prevailed. I believe the
forbearance shown by NATO was most impressive.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-Russian relations are ``back on the upswing,'' Gore added.
The vice president praised his friend, former Russian Premier
Viktor Chernomyrdin, for his ``great courage and wisdom'' in
helping bring about the withdrawal of Serbian forces.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was particularly pleased that Russia stepped away from its
initial demand to be given a sector of Kosovo as its exclusive
peacekeeping zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no Russian sector,'' he said. ``There is no partition
of Kosovo. It preserves the unity of command for Russian forces who
will serve in Kosovo. But all forces will follow common rules of
engagement. The (Russian-occupied) airport at Pristina will be open
to all KFOR (NATO-led) forces under procedures established by
KFOR.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what Russia was trying to show by occupying the Pristina
airport in the first place, Gore joked: ``You'll have to ask
President Yeltsin the next time he's out here.''
</P>
<P>
   On the home front, by contrast, Gore was talking the language of
a political Cold War. The object of his ire was a series of votes
in which the House of Representatives first weakened, and then
killed entirely, efforts to regulate gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the defection of 45 Democratic House members on a key
vote, the vice president blamed House Republican leaders. He said
fear of the National Rifle Association caused lawmakers to ignore
public sentiment for gun safety stirred by shootings at high
schools in Colorado and Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the House Republican leadership ended its work, it had
nothing to show,'' Gore said. ``After the nationwide soul-searching
over school violence that followed Columbine High, this is the
clearest demonstration imaginable that House Republicans and
Republican leaders around the country are doing the bidding of the
NRA _ not the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore charged that Republican leaders intended all along to head
off gun-control measures. The prospects for such legislation are in
turmoil after Friday's House votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is some chance their plans will be complicated
by public outrage,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was trying to perform in a dual capacity yesterday _ as a
top policy-maker in the Clinton administration, and as a
presidential candidate trying to map out different policy
directions if he is elected.
</P>
<P>
   It is a tricky role. Only one incumbent vice president in the
last 160 years _ George Bush in 1988 _ has won election to the
White House.
</P>
<P>
   Gore boasted of the 19 million new jobs that ``President Clinton
and I'' have created, and contrasted the administration's
performance to the ``economic catastrophe'' at the end of the
Reagan-Bush years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of quadrupling the national debt, we have nearly
quadrupled the stock market,'' the vice president said. He warned
that the ``extreme right philosophy'' of Republicans in Congress
could derail continued job and income growth.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore was also seeking to position himself as an agent of
change. The vice president promised to work for ``revolutionary
improvements'' in public education.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problems of 2001 will be completely different from what
Bill Clinton and I faced in the campaign of 1992,'' Gore added.
``We must continue to show economic strength, but use it to assure
that nobody is left behind. We need to revolutionize public
education. We need dramatic changes in public health care, and in
policies toward the family.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore laid out a number of specific programs. He promised
creation of a national college tuition savings plan, under which
parents can put away education money from the time of their
children's birth. The vice president would also create what he
called 401 ``J'' accounts, allowing citizens to set aside money for
future job training.
</P>
<P>
   As with Clinton in 1992, Gore identified himself as a Democrat
who supports expanded international trade _ with a caveat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will ask Congress for authority to negotiate new trade
agreements to expand our markets,'' Gore said. But he also pledged
to seek agreements governing working conditions and environmental
standards ``where possible.''
</P>
<P>
   There were a few signals Friday day of a campaign to distance
Gore from Clinton. With nary a mention of turbulence in Clinton's
private life, the laid-back stability of Al and Tipper Gore's home
life was emphasized.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy is incredibly committed to his family,'' Gov. Gary
Locke said in warming up the crowd for Gore at the Seattle Center.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts were also made to defuse the anti-Gore rhetoric of GOP
Sen. Slade Gorton, who has sought to blame the vice president for
the Justice Department's antitrust lawsuit against Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was introduced at the Seattle Center by a Grays Harbor
County-based high-tech entrepreneur, Bo Wandell. The vice president
``promotes the information economy,'' said Wandell.
</P>
<P>
   Gore noted that, seven years ago, Washington's unemployment rate
was 8.5 percent with technology innovation ``stifled by huge
deficits and high interest rates.''
</P>
<P>
   The 2000 presidential campaign appears to be here to stay. In
less than three weeks, Gore and leading GOP presidential hopeful,
Texas Gov. George W. Bush, are likely to make back-to-back Seattle
appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Bush will be in Seattle on July 8, his schedule not yet
announced. Gore is tentatively slated to return the same week, for
UNITY '99, a convention of four national minority journalist
associations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
