<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SPURS-KNICKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPURS RIP KNICKS IN SLOPPY GAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Break out the brooms, the NBA Finals has turned
into a Cakewalk on the Riverwalk.
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio's 80-67 Game 2 victory against the New York Knicks
last night was far from Spur-fect, but it gave the Spurs a
seemingly insurmountable 2-0 lead in the best-of-seven series and
crept them within two victories of their first NBA Championship.
</P>
<P>
   In the second-lowest-scoring game in Finals history, Tim
Duncan's second-half offensive rebounding and 25 points performed
CPR on his team's gasping offense before Presidential hopeful
George W. Bush and an Alamodome crowd of 39,554 that spent most of
the fourth quarter chanting ``Sweep, Sweep.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not thinking sweep,'' Duncan said. ``But we like our
position. It wasn't the prettiest game, but that's our type of
basketball. We're not a pretty team, but our results are good.''
</P>
<P>
   The game, which topped the lowest-scoring Finals game of 145
points set by Fort Wayne (74) and Syracuse (71) in 1955 only with a
meaningless five-point flurry in the final 10 seconds, might have
been hideous, but it left the Spurs sitting pretty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our margin for error just got real slim,'' Knicks coach Jeff
Van Gundy said. ``Our effort is fine, but we've got to find a way
to score against what is a great defensive team.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks must now win four of the next five games against a
Spurs team that:
</P>
<P>
   Has won a record 12 consecutive playoff games, something not
accomplished by even Bill Russell's Celtics, Magic Johnson's Lakers
or Michael Jordan's Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   Is 44-6 since March, and hasn't lost consecutive games since
Feb. 26-28.
</P>
<P>
   Is 6-0 on the road in the playoffs, winning by at least seven
points and an average of 13.
</P>
<P>
   Game 3 is scheduled for Monday night at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   For historical perspective, last night's game might as well have
been a Game 7 for the Knicks,because only two teams _ the 1969
Celtics and the '77 Blazers _ have rallied from 0-2 deficits in the
Finals. For entertainment value, the game might as well have been
played at the local YMCA.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks shot 33 percent (27 of 82), missed 12 of their 14
3-pointers, got a measly four fast-break points and never cracked
20 points in any quarter. The Spurs weren't much better, but they
did get 41 points, 26 rebounds and a crucial nine blocks from their
Twin Towers, Duncan and David Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   How pitiful were the Knicks? Trailing 68-57 with less than three
minutes remaining, they inexplicably had shot-clock violations on
back-to-back possessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got real stagnant on offense,'' Knicks forward Marcus Camby
said. ``Their big guys are really bothering us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks, who at one point were shooting 30 percent but
trailing by only three, self-destructed in the final five seconds
of the third quarter. After a Sean Elliott baseline layup and foul,
he missed the free throw. Duncan, however, beat Camby to the
rebound and his follow layup pushed San Antonio's margin to 56-49.
As in Game 1, the Knicks got no closer than six in the fourth
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs led 39-34 after a hideous first half that featured
air-ball jumpers, blown layups and fast breaks without finishes.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks took a 13-12 lead on a Latrell Sprewell transition
dunk, then went scoreless for almost five minutes because of their
carelessness, eight consecutive missed shots and San Antonio's shot
blockers. New York had four layups blocked, Camby blew a wide-open
layup and Charlie Ward committed silly back-to-back turnovers as
their frenetic pace didn't result in points.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs led 20-15 after the first quarter but failed to widen
the gap despite the Knicks missing 18 of 19 shots during one
ridiculous stretch. A jump hook by Duncan over the smaller Larry
Johnson followed by an up-and-under layup over the weaker Camby
pushed the Spurs' margin to 38-30.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the core of our defense, intimidation and blocking
shots,'' Duncan said. ``We've got to affect shots, make them miss
and then next time make them take a bad shot.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
