r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-RANGERS-RED-SOX-T     06-19 0516
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-RED-SOX-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS TIME, FENWAY FRIENDLY TO RANGERS' MORGAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Last night marked the second start at Fenway Park for
39-year-old right-hander Mike Morgan.
</P>
<P>
   The other occurred nearly 20 years ago, and Boston's Carl
Yastrzemski _ a Red Sox legend _ spoiled a 19-year-old pitcher's
afternoon by hitting his 400th home run.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan surrendered another long ball last night, but this
second-inning, solo home run by left fielder Troy O'Leary would be
one of only three hits the Red Sox mustered during the Rangers' 4-1
victory.
</P>
<P>
   The 3-2, split-fingered fastball O'Leary hit over Fenway's
fabled Green Monster was the only blemish in Morgan's 61/3-inning
appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of good things have happened to me during my career in
those 20 years since then,'' said Morgan, who beat the Red Sox for
the first time and needs only victories against the Arizona
Diamondbacks and Tampa Bay Devil Rays to become the first pitcher
to beat 30 major-league teams.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Jeff Zimmerman recorded the final eight outs with
23 pitches and didn't allow a base runner for his first
major-league save, and first baseman Lee Stevens delivered the
game-winning hit with his sixth-inning, solo home run off
right-hander Mark Portugal (3-6).
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers won their third consecutive game without catcher
Ivan Rodriguez, who remains sidelined after suffering muscle spasms
in his back Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the pitching staff continues to thrive with reserve Gregg
Zaun behind the plate. The Rangers have allowed only three runs
during Zaun's past three starts, which lends itself to speculation
about the significance of his role in the recent performance of the
staff.
</P>
<P>
   It could, of course, be coincidental.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been very fortunate here with Dave Valle, Bill Haselman
and now Gregg Zaun,'' manager Johnny Oates said of his reserve
catchers during his stint with the Rangers. ``All three of those
guys loved to catch when it was their turn, and you have to when
you're the backup and playing only once a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Zaun talks a good ballgame. I enjoy listening to him in the
dugout. He knows what he's doing out there behind the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   Morgan lacked the armor that knowledge brings before stepping
onto Fenway Park's mound on July 24, 1979.
</P>
<P>
   A fly ball lost in the sun in foul territory prolonged
Yastrzemski's historic at-bat, Morgan recalled, and that allowed
the Hall of Famer another swing that resulted in a game-winning,
three-run homer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't even belong on the mound out there then,'' recalled
Morgan, Oakland's first-round selection and the fourth overall in
the 1978 amateur free-agent draft. ``I didn't even know what was
going on. I didn't know he was going for his 400th home run, and he
hit one out. I shouldn't have even been out there. I should have
been in rookie or low-A ball.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be much different for Morgan (7-5) nearly two decades
later.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight,'' Oates said, ``was probably the best game he's
pitched for us.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
