<SLUG> BC-BKN-WHITT-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUNCAN'S RETURN COULD HINGE ON NEW ARENA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Are you sitting down, Spurs fans?
</P>
<P>
   Tim Duncan might leave San Antonio, and not just on today's
charter flight to New York for the NBA Finals.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan, the biggest hero in this city since Davy Crockett, is
eligible to sign a contract extension this summer or become a
restricted free agent after the 1999-2000 season. Obviously, the
Spurs want to get the deal done now and lock up the game's best
player into the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   But Duncan's agent, and even Duncan himself are not so sure.
Spurs owner Peter Holt is desperately trying to get San Antonio's
taxpayers to vote on a new arena so the Spurs will no longer have
to play in the cavernous, football-first Alamodome. Holt has even
hinted of moving the team if a new basketball-only arena isn't
built.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan, who will command a maximum $70 million contract, has an
eye on the political red tape.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting a new arena is a big \Rfactor\S for me staying here,''
Duncan said. ``But now is not the time to think about it.
Hopefully, we can win this thing and give the new arena some
momentum.''
</P>
<P>
   Said agent Lon Babby, ``I don't think there's any urgency to do
Tim's deal now. Everyone understands that the timing is not the
best with the arena issue. And that's just an important piece of
information Tim needs to make his decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Teammate David Robinson is in the fourth year of a six-year, $66
million contract, but will also have the ability to opt out of the
deal after the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are thoughts, but now is not the time for me to think
about it,'' Robinson said. ``Obviously with a team like this,
especially if we win it, there's no reason at all I would want to
leave. There's no amount of money in the world that would make me
want to leave after finally getting an opportunity to win. To put
together a championship or even two or three is an incredible
opportunity, so I probably would not even consider it.''
</P>
<P>
   If he stays in San Antonio, Robinson will make $13.3 million
next season and $14.7 million for the 2000-2001 season.
 &LR; subheds:Best and worst Best strategy: The Knicks' decision to
aggressively double-team Duncan in the post early in Game 2 forced
the Spurs to shoot perimeter jumpers.
</P>
<P>
   Worst strategy: New York continually beat its head against a
brick wall, getting six shots blocked in the first half of last
night's game.  &LR; subheds:Numbers game 19: Players in the Finals
wearing Nike sneakers. Two wear Reebok and one each for Fila,
Converse and And1.
</P>
<P>
   10, 14, 15, 19: Four of the six quarter-point totals by the
Knicks through a game and a half.  &LR; subheds:24 seconds And you
thought Cowboys fans got into their team. There isn't a corner or
office window in San Antonio without the ``Go Spurs Go'' slogan.
One entire street near the Alamodome has put up its Christmas
lights early and the owners of a house mowed the slogan into their
lawn. ``We love the support,'' said Robinson, ``but they can get
out of control.'' The Spurs have a unique, small-town fan base of
65 percent public, 35 percent corporate. ... With the Sabres and
Stars battling for the Stanley Cup and the Spurs and Knicks playing
in the Finals, it's the first time since 1973 that teams from the
same state have played for major championships. It was 26 years ago
that the Knicks defeated the Lakers in the summer, followed by the
A's downing the Mets in the World Series. ... Surprising face in
the crowd was Vikings receiver Randy Moss. ... Because of NBC's
coverage of the U.S. Open, Game 3 of the Finals won't be played
until Monday night in Madison Square Garden.
