<SLUG> BC-PIPELINE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROPERLY WORKING VALVE MIGHT HAVE LIMITED PIPELINE SPILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SCOTT SUNDE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The gasoline spill that culminated in a deadly
explosion and fire in Bellingham might have been greatly limited
had a valve worked properly, federal regulators say.
</P>
<P>
   A block valve, which is intended to close a section of pipeline,
is located just one-tenth of a mile north of where last week's
rupture occurred near Whatcom Creek in Bellingham, a town about 90
miles north of Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   But the valve ``either malfunctioned or was not closed in a
timely fashion,'' investigators found. As a result, up to 130,200
additional gallons were released, the U.S. Transportation
Department wrote in describing the preliminary findings of an
investigation into the accident.
</P>
<P>
   The Transportation Department estimated the total spill at
151,200 to 277,200 gallons.
</P>
<P>
   After fuel began leaking June 10, gasoline vapor ignited,
killing two 10-year-old boys. A teenager was overcome by fumes and
drowned in Whatcom Creek.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Klinger, a spokeswoman for the department, said the
findings about the block valve are preliminary but still
significant. That is why the Transportation Department has ordered
Olympic Pipe Line Co. to test valves on the upper 37 miles of its
pipeline in the northerwestern part of the state. Regulators also
ordered the company to focus on valves in populated or
environmentally sensitive areas and add more if they are needed.
</P>
<P>
   The block valve near the spill can be closed to stop the flow of
gasoline or other liquid fuel coming from refineries in Cherry
Point and Ferndale. It works by remote control, closed by operators
in a Renton office.
</P>
<P>
   Olympic officials are reviewing the preliminary findings and
aren't certain that the valve played a major role, said Joann
Hamick, a spokeswoman for Olympic Pipe Line Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know,'' she said. ``It's something they (regulators)
put there and it needs to be looked at.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the company has already begun complying with the
Transportation Department's order, including reducing pressure on
some segments of the pipeline.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators trying to determine a cause of the spill and to
assess its aftermath will pay attention to the valve, said Keith
Holloway, a spokesman for the National Transportation Safety Board.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are looking at the SCADA (computer) system and operations
of valves,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   SCADA is a computerized system by which Olympic controls,
monitors and detects leaks in the pipeline.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't working right before and during the spill, according
to preliminary investigative evidence cited by the Transportation
Department, which oversees pipeline safety in the United States.
``System response time was reported as slow, and the system's
recording of some data was not consistent with normal operation.''
</P>
<P>
   Olympic officials say about an hour before they had the first
reports of a possible leak their computer system crashed.
</P>
<P>
   The Transportation Department also noted that the pipe in the
section that failed was manufactured before 1970 and had been the
subject of government warnings in the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Pipe of its type had 12 failures of seams in 1988 and 1989,
prompting the Transportation Department's Office of Pipeline Safety
to twice issue warnings.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1990s, the Office of Pipeline Safety also determined that
the same type of pipe developed hairline cracks as it was being
carried for delivery on railroad cars, Klinger said. The leaks
couldn't be seen by visual inspection, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Transportation Department urged operators who used this type
of pipe to make sure pipelines had corrosion protection, limit
pressure in them and to hydrotest them, which involves putting
water at high pressure through the pipe.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I know, they (Olympic officials), took corrective
action,'' Klinger said.
</P>
<P>
   The preliminary findings of the investigation are contained in a
Transportation Department order issued Thursday against Olympic.
</P>
<P>
   The order requires Olympic to keep the 37-mile section of
pipeline from Cherry Point to the Skagit County town of Allen
closed while a number of safety improvements and checks are made.
</P>
<P>
   Those safety improvements and checks focus on several factors
that could have caused or contributed to the spill: corrosion,
pressurization, computer systems and faulty valves.
</P>
<P>
   Olympic, for example, will have to check the pipeline for
corrosion.
</P>
<P>
   Once the 37-mile section begins operating, the pressure can only
reach 80 percent of what the pipeline had been running at, the
Transportation Department ordered.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, regulators have ordered that the next section of
pipeline from Allen to Renton can operate at no more than 80
percent of normal operating pressure.
</P>
<P>
   That line is already operating at only 45 percent of capacity.
Only two refineries in Anacortes currently are supplying oil to the
pipeline. The rupture cut off refineries in Cherry Point and
Ferndale.
</P>
<P>
   The Transportation Department noted in its order to Olympic that
the cause of the spill hasn't been pinpointed.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the damaged section of pipe probably won't be removed
from the gasoline-saturated soil until at least next week.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to corrosion, federal investigators also will be
looking for any construction damage, Holloway said.
</P>
<P>
   There was construction as recently as 1997 in the area, when
crews put in a 20-inch water line above the pipeline and a 24-inch
line below it, said Jack Garner, Bellingham's public works
director.
</P>
<P>
   But that construction was under close scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   ``The plans for work were reviewed with Olympic Pipe Line, and
they had personnel on the site when the work was done,'' Garner
said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Hamick said Olympic had two people watching the
installation of the water lines. Olympic then inspected its
pipeline for construction damage and found none, she said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Olympic also used an internal device known as a ``smart
pig'' to inspect that section of pipeline. The inspection found
some wall thinning but within Olympic's standards.
</P>
<P>
   However, it couldn't be determined Friday whether the inspection
took place before or after the water line construction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
