<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-U.S. </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREE SHARE LEAD IN A DAY OF HIGH SCORES AT U.S. OPEN
</HEADLINE>
 OPEN-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINEHURST, N.C. _ Cancel those players' complaints, voiced by
Lee Westwood and others, about scoring conditions being too easy at
Pinehurst Resort and Country Club because the rough failed to meet
traditional U.S. Open lengths.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, instead, the warning uttered Friday by Corey Pavin,
the 1995 Open champ. Pavin predicted that, with more days of wind
and sunshine, Pinehurst might produce a round when no player breaks
even-par 70 before a winner is crowned Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Pinehurst came close to pitching a shutout Friday, but Payne
Stewart, Jeff Maggert and John Huston prevented it. Stewart grabbed
a share of the lead with a second-round 69, joining David Duval and
Phil Mickelson at 3 under par for the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Maggert and Huston moved within three strokes of the lead, both
at even par, by matching Stewart's 69. No one else broke par on a
day when Pinehurst played to a scoring average of 75.4 _ 2.5 shots
per player higher than Thursday _ and elicited 13 scores of 80 or
higher.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're seeing players backing up all over the place and
there's nothing we can do about it,'' Duval said. ``I think even
par is going to be a real nice position by Sunday. And if you're 1
or 2 over, you might not be too bad off, either.''
</P>
<P>
   Well-tucked pins and wind gusts of 20 mph helped dry greens and
complicate club selections on a sun-splashed day that ended with
the world's highest-ranked players _ Duval and Tiger Woods _
earning tee times in the final two groups of Saturday's third
round. Duval and Stewart will play together, with Phil Mickelson (3
under) joining Woods (1 under).
</P>
<P>
   One day after 23 players broke par in the opening round, only
seven golfers have sub-par totals through 36 holes. Hal Sutton,
Vijay Singh and Billy Mayfair all join Woods at 1 under.
</P>
<P>
   How tough was Pinehurst during the second round?
</P>
<P>
   Greg Norman, the PGA Tour's career money leader, found just two
of 18 greens in regulation. Fred Couples, the 1992 Masters champ,
split only five of 14 fairways. Lee Janzen, the defending champ,
needed a chip-in for birdie from 70 feet on the 18th hole to
survive the cut at 7-over par.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Nicklaus, a four-time champ, missed the cut with his worst
score in relation to par (14 over) since his Open debut as an
amateur in 1957.
</P>
<P>
   Woods questioned the fairness of pin placements at Nos. 5 and 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were both right on knobs. If you take a look at them,
you'd say that a pin really shouldn't be there,'' Woods said.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Lehman, who has finished fifth or better in the past four
Opens, said the pin at No. 10 was ``so far left, it looked like it
was in the concession stand.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, who offset two bogeys with three birdies, described the
pins as ``tough'' but not inaccessible. He backed that claim by
draining three birdie putts from inside 18 feet, including a tap-in
at No. 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people that are complaining about the pins, they haven't
played in enough U.S. Opens,'' said Stewart, the 1991 Open champ
and a runner-up to Janzen in 1993 and 1998. ``This was tough, not
questionable. You just had to be willing to take pars, however you
could get them.''
</P>
<P>
   Duval, the model of consistency in the opening round, took only
nine of them Friday. He collected more birdies (five) than any
player in the second round but trumped those by flushing four
strokes from the sand.
</P>
<P>
   Duval took a double bogey after blasting over the green from a
bunker at No. 6, then took bogeys from bunkers at Nos. 9 and 11. He
also failed to save par after his approach fell short of the green
at No. 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed like every time I was in the fairway, I was
in-between clubs,'' Duval said. ``When you try and hit a lot of
knockdown and three-quarter shots in this wind, you hit some bad
shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Bad shots proved to be the affliction of the day at Pinehurst,
where 68 golfers survived to play the weekend rounds. Based on
Friday's results, said Mickelson, any of them could win. But the
buzz is building about a potential Woods-Duval weekend shootout
that could trigger a rivalry between the game's top-ranked players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would love to be part of a battle like that,'' Duval said.
``As long as I'm part of the rivalry, I'm all for it.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
