<SLUG> BC-HEARTLAND-CONFERENCE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS WESLEYAN JOINS NEW CONFERENCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Texas Wesleyan University is joining two
other Texas schools and three in Missouri to form a new NCAA
Division II conference for their athletic programs, the Fort Worth
school announced.
</P>
<P>
   Joining Texas Wesleyan in the Heartland Conference will be St.
Edward's University (Austin), the University of the Incarnate Word
(San Antonio), Rockhurst University (Kansas City, Mo.), Lincoln
University (Jefferson City, Mo.) and Drury University (Springfield,
Mo.).
</P>
<P>
   Texas Wesleyan officials said school president Jake B. Schrum
led the move to form the new conference after it was determined in
the fall of 1998 that several schools in the Rams' Heart of Texas
Conference were moving in different directions.
</P>
<P>
   Schrum approached nine schools in Texas, Oklahoma, Missouri and
New Mexico to discuss forming a new conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the HOT Conference effectively ending as of July 1, Texas
Wesleyan would have been forced to be an NCAA independent,'' said
Dr. Albert G. Applin, Wesleyan's associate vice president of
student life and athletics. ``That would have been a difficult row
to hoe. Fortunately, these six schools are similar academically and
athletically, and some schools, like Texas Wesleyan, have already
won championships in the NAIA or the NCAA.''
</P>
<P>
   The Heartland will sponsor two sports, men's golf and women's
tennis, its first year, although Wesleyan will continue to field
teams in men's and women's basketball, men's and women's soccer,
women's volleyball, men's tennis, men's baseball and women's
softball.
</P>
<P>
   In the second year, the conference plans to sponsor several
sports, including men's and women's basketball, and to seek an
automatic bid to the NCAA Division II men's basketball tournament.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
