<HEADLINE>
PORT WARNED THIRD SEA-TAC RUNWAY WILL COST MORE, TAKE LONGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JACK HOPKINS  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Port of Seattle commissioners will meet next week to
deal with the latest in a series of problems plaguing construction
of a third runway at Sea-Tac Airport _ word that the controversial
expansion will cost nearly one-third more than anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioners will be asked Tuesday to approve a $186 million
cost overrun that will boost the price tag of the project _
originally estimated at $587 million _ to $773 million.
</P>
<P>
   Also, port staffers now say work on the third runway won't be
done on schedule in 2004 and isn't expected to be completed until
the second half of 2006.
</P>
<P>
   Money for the increased cost would come from future airport
revenue bonds, grants from the Federal Aviation Administration and
fees imposed on passengers flying in and out of the airport, a port
official said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Davis, Port Commission president, said she expects the
five-member commission to approve the increased costs, although
they might do it through clenched teeth. The Port of Seattle
operates Sea-Tac airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we'll approve it, but unhappily because of the
delay,'' Davis said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Port commissioners have been expecting the bad news for some
time, she added.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were kind of waiting for this,'' Davis said. ``The fact of
the matter is there is nothing we can do. We just have to accept
this and go forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Environmental concerns _ raised by discovery of wetlands when
the port began acquiring property in the path of the project _ are
responsible for much of the increased cost, port spokesman Bob
Parker said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   But some of the increase occurred because of construction
delays, regional growth in construction and real estate costs, and
project changes, port officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The port halted construction in October after discovering
unexpected wetlands on some of the property being acquired for the
runway project.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would think that you could just do an aerial survey and
identify the wetlands, but some of these just did not look like
wetlands,'' Parker said. ``Some had swing sets and dog houses on
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Port officials realized some properties were wetlands only after
they were able to get onto the land and take core soil samples, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The port will have to pay more to address that problem by
providing compensatory wetlands in other nearby areas, improving
the quality of fill material used in the runway to minimize
erosion, and taking other actions to protect the environment, port
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The increased costs are unavoidable, Parker said. ``When you
come across wetlands, you have got to protect them.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the third runway have blasted the expansion plan on
numerous grounds, including noise, potential damage to the
environment and cost. Some opponents have projected the ultimate
cost of the runway at $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The new price tag and two-year delay in completion show the
opponents are right in fighting the project, said Bob Sheckler,
chairman of the Airport Communities Coalition. The coalition is a
group of airport-area cities and a school district opposed to the
runway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three years ago we were told that the region desperately
needed this third runway by 1998,'' Sheckler said in a written
statement Friday. ``Now, in 1999, nobody at the port seems to be
concerned about completing the third runway six years after we
absolutely had to have it built.''
</P>
<P>
   The coalition believes runway costs will rise above $773
million, Sheckler said. ``The most expensive runway ever built in
Puget Sound has not submitted a wetlands application yet; that will
continue to drive costs up,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Port staffers said they expect their new estimate of the cost of
the project _ $773,362,000 _ to remain firm. But they don't rule
out the possibility of another increase.
</P>
<P>
   Parker said the third runway makes sense even at the increased
cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``We estimate that not having the third runway costs airlines
and travelers $189 million a year. So a $773 million runway makes
financial sense in just under five years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While much of the cost ultimately will be borne by travelers
through user fees, port officials aren't able to say how much the
increased pricetag will cost each individual traveler.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many ways the money gets handled that it is
impossible to trace a path,'' Parker said. ``I just can't say how
much. But if air services cost more, travelers pay more.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis and Parker both say they're hopeful the third runway will
be in use before the new projected date of the third quarter of
2006. But that's largely out of the port's hands, they said.
</P>
<P>
   The new construction timetable estimates it could take a year to
get work permits from the state Ecology Department and the U.S.
Army Corps of Engineers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are hoping the Department of Ecology gets that permit
through more quickly than a year,'' Davis said. ``Then we can go to
the Corps of Engineers.''
</P>
<P>
   Parker said that would enable the port to move up its timetable
for using the new runway.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
