<HEADLINE>
DALY KNOWS VALUE OF SURVIVING CUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINEHURST, N.C. _ Despite ballooning to a 77 in Friday's second
round of the U.S. Open, John Daly found a ray of sunshine at
Pinehurst Resort and Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   At least he made the cut, which will break a string of four
consecutive tournaments without paychecks on the PGA Tour. The
weekend tee times are significant, said Daly, because he is still
feeling the effects of $9 million in gambling losses suffered
between 1993 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need the money,'' said Daly, a recovering alcoholic who
stands at 5-over par through 36 holes, eight strokes behind the
leaders. ``I have to make my money out here now. It's not like when
I had it coming in from other places.''
</P>
<P>
   Although his gambling debts have been retired, Daly said he
recently had to sell a Mercedes and a house in California to help
meet his $40,000 monthly obligation in alimony and child support
from three failed marriages. Daly said his home in Memphis, Tenn.,
may soon be put on the market to pay taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Daly put himself in financial peril between 1993-96 when he won
$42 million from casino gambling but offset that total with $51
million in losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``You name it, I bet on it,'' Daly said. ``I always liked the
fast action, but I haven't recovered from all those losses.''
</P>
<P>
   Daly said he has wagered as much as $220,000 on a single hand at
blackjack and $50,000 on a single football game. But he never bet
on golf. Since leaving an alcohol rehabilitation center in 1997,
however, Daly said he has not taken a drink or placed a wager.
</P>
<P>
   After leaving the rehabilitation center, Daly received an
endorsement deal from Callaway Golf products and company founder
Ely Callway agreed to retire $1.8 million of Daly's personal debt
to various casinos. Previous deals from Reebok and Wilson helped
cover $1.2 million and the remaining $6 million in debt came from
Daly's pocket or the sale of personal items.
</P>
<P>
   That has left him feeling a financial pinch throughout the 1999
season, which shows Daly ranked 125th on the money list, with
$158,021. Until making the cut at the Open, Daly had not earned a
PGA Tour paycheck since May 16 at the GTE Byron Nelson Classic,
where he finished 67th and received $6,090.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the way I've played the last eight weeks, I didn't even
expect to make the cut here. I expected to play two rounds, then go
home and watch on television,'' Daly said. ``This has been a nice
surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   As with public discussions about his battles with alcoholism,
Daly said he decided to share his tale of gambling woes because
``it helps me to talk about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Daly, however, said he has not been tempted to punch a hotel
room wall in anger, as Masters champ Jose Maria Olazabal did after
shooting a 75 in Thursday's opening round. Olazabal withdrew Friday
and Daly said he could empathize with Olazabal's frustrations.
</P>
<P>
   ``This life (on the PGA Tour), it's not all that glamorous the
way everybody thinks it is,'' Daly said. ``But if I'd just won the
Masters, I don't think I'd be punching any walls. I'm the only one
who has a reason to punch something, because I haven't done crap
all year. At least he's got a green jacket.''
</P>
<P>
   John Daly, on the other hand, has a financial crisis on his
hands. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
