<SLUG> BC-CALIF-SYNAGOGUE-FIRES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREE CALIFORNIA SYNAGOGUES HIT BY FIRES
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By TODD S. PURDUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A wave of apparently coordinated arsons struck
three of the five synagogues in the Sacramento area within 45
minutes early Friday morning, causing nearly $1 million in damages,
and the federal authorities opened a sweeping investigation into
what they described as deliberate hate crimes, in which anti-Jewish
fliers were found at two of the fires.
</P>
<P>
   More than 100 agents and officers of the FBI, the Bureau of
Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms and local police and fire departments
were assigned to the case, but officials said Friday afternoon that
they had no suspects so far and no clear motives for the attacks.
</P>
<P>
   The fires occurred hours before scheduled Sabbath services and,
in the worst case, gutted the temple library at Congregation B'nai
Israel in Sacramento, destroying a collection of videotapes on the
Holocaust and Jewish culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was deliberate arson, it was a deliberate hate crime, and
beyond that we really can't say,'' James M. Maddock, the FBI's
special agent in charge of the Sacramento office, said in a late
afternoon news conference monitored by telephone.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said they could not be sure whether the fires were
connected, but Maddock said, ``Obviously, that would be the most
common theory that we're working on.'' He said investigators had
not ruled out the possibility that a lone individual was
responsible for all three attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Maddock and other officials declined to give specifics of what
they described as anti-Semitic fliers found at the fires. But at
one fire, at the Kenesset Israel Torah Center in northeastern
Sacramento County, a local television crew found a flier that
blamed the ``international Jewsmedia'' for the war in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Temple B'nai Israel suffered by far the worst damage, about
$800,000, mostly to its library, officials said. A second
synagogue, Congregation Beth Shalom in suburban Carmichael, Calif.,
had about $100,000 in damage, most from smoke and water, while the
Knesset Israel Torah Center sustained about $30,000 in damage,
according to preliminary estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Officials would not say precisely how the fires were set, but
Maddock said investigators had ``recovered a number of evidentiary
items from the crime scenes'' that would be analyzed by forensics
experts.
</P>
<P>
   Two toll-free numbers have been set up to take tips from the
public at (800) 435-7883 for the FBI and (888) ATF-FIRE for the
Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second firebombing attack at B'nai Israel in six
years. In 1993, the temple was among the targets of firebombings
directed at several minorities; a 17-year-old white separatist was
later convicted in those attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Mayor Joseph Serna of Sacramento said such acts were
``not typical of our city,'' and added, ``This has been a very sad
day for us here.''
</P>
<P>
   The regional office of the Anti-Defamation League of B'nai
B'rith, issued a statement that it had monitored activities of the
Sacramento branch of an anti-Semitic group called the World Church
of the Creator.
</P>
<P>
   The women's auxiliary of the group has recently published
materials attributing the war in Kosovo to a ``Jew world order,''
but the Anti-Defamation League said there was no known link between
that auxiliary and the arsons.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Brad Bloom of Congregation B'nai Israel said his
congregation was ``devastated, shocked and numb,'' but he vowed to
``be positive and rebuild.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully,'' Bloom added, ``we will create a culture which
will not tolerate intolerance anymore.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
