<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-VERBEEK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS FIND INSTIGATOR IN `LITTLE BALL OF HATE'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAULA CABALLERO 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Pat Verbeek doesn't appear to be conspicuously
rabid when sitting at his locker in the Dallas Stars' dressing
room.
</P>
<P>
   No growling, no baring of his teeth, no foaming at the mouth.
</P>
<P>
   But the way coach Ken Hitchcock talks about his ``Little Ball of
Hate,'' you'd think they keep Verbeek shackled so nobody gets hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has two different personalities,'' Hitchcock said.
``There's the personality in the dressing room on an off day, and
then he has a personality you avoid at all cost on the day of the
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just don't go near him. He's not a nice person to be
around on the day of the game. For anybody. Coaches or players.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Little Ball of Hate'' is at his most hateful these days, and
that's how the Stars like him. Gritty, relentless, taking it right
at Buffalo goalie Dominik Hasek as he did to score in Game 5 of the
Stanley Cup Finals on Thursday is how Verbeek has helped the Stars
to the brink of the championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``We use him kind of as a catalyst,'' Hitchcock said. ``When we
need other people to get going, to get physically involved, we
would put Verbeek in and that's it. He would draw either the anger
from the other team or draw the anger from our own people, and it
was good for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Verbeek is a player with a nose for the net and making trouble
around it. He says he likes ``the dirty areas'' on the ice, and
when he's in those spots, he likes to make them dirtier.
</P>
<P>
   All this hate comes in a convenient travelsize package, too.
Verbeek has made a career of playing bigger than his very generous
listing of 5-foot-9.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say it could be what they call `Small Man's Disease,' ''
Verbeek said, analyzing the root of his hate. ``I'm not sure I have
it, but I'm close.''
</P>
<P>
   Verbeek said his ball of hate began rolling in his teen years in
Wyoming, Ontario. From age 14 through his first season in the NHL
in 1983, he had to prove he could overcome his small stature to
scouts, coaches and opponents.
</P>
<P>
   The struggle, Verbeek said, left him with a rather large chip on
his shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   And his opponents with an stick-wielding pest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've just always had the personality where I never liked to
take crap from anyone,'' Verbeek said. ``If they hand it out,
they're going to have to make sure they can take it, because
they're going to get it back.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all the hate was derived from the ice. Verbeek, the oldest
of five, endured some tough love growing up. Verbeek said he had
two parents who taught him the value of work ethic, but also liked
to keep him in line.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like good cop, bad cop, and they took turns at it,''
Verbeek said.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is the thumb episode. Verbeek had his thumb
severed in an auger-driven fertilizer at the family farm when he
was 21. He found his thumb and had it reattached. And he proceeded
to score 25 goals the next season for the New Jersey Devils.
</P>
<P>
   ``The team owner suggested we cut the other one off,'' Verbeek
said.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, through all of this, Verbeek manages to leave the hate
at work. Father of four girls and a boy, Verbeek has been known to
play Beanie Babies with his daughters.
</P>
<P>
   He draws the line at Barbies, of course.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny, because when they say that `Little Ball of Hate'
stuff, I just don't know where they get it from,'' said Dianne
Verbeek, Pat's wife. ``Around here, he's really happy-go-lucky and
agreeable.''
</P>
<P>
   As long as Verbeek's nastiness continues to lift the Stars, the
niceness can be kept quiet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Little Ball of Hate'' wants his first Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone interested in telling him no? nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
