<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-CAMPAIGN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILL BRADLEY AND WIFE SPEAK OUT ON BREAST CANCER DURING L.A. VISIT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY MARY LOU AURELIO  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Democratic presidential candidate Bill Bradley
joined his wife, Ernestine, at a YWCA forum to talk about her
breast cancer battle and his experience as the husband of a
survivor.
</P>
<P>
   ``When breast cancer hits, it hits an entire family, and all the
attention and care should go to the woman,'' Bill Bradley said.
``But men are traumatized too, and it's important to know other men
are out there like them.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a husband of a breast cancer survivor, I have tried to
reach others going through it with a kind word, or a story or a
letter,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The forum at the Glendale YWCA in Los Angeles' San Fernando
Valley was held to let women know about ENCOREplus, a program
sponsored by the Y that provides free pap smears, clinical breast
exams and mammograms. A mobile mammography center visits the Y
eight to 12 times a month. Women receive free screenings.
</P>
<P>
   The mobile Iris Cantor Center for Breast Imaging is part of the
UCLA Medical Center and one of the Y's partners. The George Slate
Mobile Pap Center, sponsored by Planned Parenthood, is another
center.
</P>
<P>
   The Bradleys urged women to take advantage of the service.
</P>
<P>
   ``The outreach programs are incredibly important,'' Ernestine
Bradley said. ``They reach those who would not normally have the
time or the resources. ``If found at an early stage, cancer is not
a fatal disease.''
</P>
<P>
   Ernestine Bradley said a brush with cancer is a very profound
and moving event.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life goes on but much better than before _ life is more
precious,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She said she was lucky to have her husband at her side, and it
brought them closer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a good marriage before, but cancer gave us a bond that
neither of us thought could be forged,'' she said. ``This is the
good side, if you have the strength to see it that way.''
</P>
<P>
   About 325 to 425 women a month are seen at the Glendale Y's
ENCOREplus program, said Laila Santos, program director. It is
aimed at women who have little or no medical coverage, but no one
is turned away.
</P>
<P>
   She said since 1994, the program has screened 9,000 woman and
found 78 breast cancer cases.
</P>
<P>
   During a question and answer forum, Bill Bradley said such
health services should be provided to the 44 million uninsured in
this country, many of them working poor.
</P>
<P>
   ``That can only happen when we have national leadership,'' he
said. ``Then any woman can get a pap smear, not just as a generous
gift, but because it is a right in America.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
