<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-19 01:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1832 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDIA-PAKISTAN-ART-NY     06-19 1102
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-PAKISTAN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KASHMIR MILITANTS SEEK ISLAMIC STATE
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By STEPHEN KINZER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  SRINAGAR, Kashmir _ The fierce combat raging along the
mountainous border between the parts of Kashmir controlled by India
and Pakistan is only the most visible face of an effort by Islamic
militants to turn Kashmir into a religious state.
</P>
<P>
   Militants from various countries appear to have chosen Kashmir
as a prime target in their campaign to bring the world's Muslim
regions under religious rule. The campaign is in part a legacy of
the proxy war that the U.S. waged against Soviet forces in
Afghanistan during the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   During those years the United States trained and armed thousands
of Muslim guerrillas who opposed the Soviet troops because they
viewed them as anti-Islamic infidels.
</P>
<P>
   Now, having succeeded in driving the Soviet forces from
Afghanistan and establishing a form of religious rule there, many
of the warriors are turning their attention to Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   The conflict dates to the establishment of predominantly Hindu
India and mainly Muslim Pakistan in 1947 by Britain, the departing
colonial power. Since then the countries have fought two wars over
Kashmir, where most of the population is Muslim. Pakistan controls
about a third of the region, with India holding most of the rest
and China a smaller area.
</P>
<P>
   In Srinagar, the summer capital of the Indian state of Jammu and
Kashmir, militants from countries as far apart as Indonesia, Sudan
and Bahrain have given interviews asserting that they learned the
art of war from Americans and are now using their skills to fight
the Indian Army.
</P>
<P>
   Many are evidently using not only tactics that Americans taught
them, but also weapons that Americans gave them. The most graphic
example came soon after the latest round of fighting began last
month, when an Indian helicopter was shot down by an Islamic
guerrilla using an American-made Stinger missile.
</P>
<P>
   Intelligence officers say about a dozen more Stingers are
unaccounted for in this region, each able to shoot down a plane or
helicopter.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of indication that former Afghan fighters from
the war against Russia are now fighting here,'' said Gen. Joszef
Bali, the U.N. envoy in Srinagar. ``Weapons provided for
Afghanistan with large help from the Americans and the CIA are now
in the hands of the militants.''
</P>
<P>
   Indian officers involved in the current fighting agree. ``The
militants are using not only small arms that they got from the
Americans, but also Stinger missiles and American anti-tank
weapons,'' said one officer, Col. Hemant Desai. ``It's not only
weapons, but also battle-hardened troops. It's a direct result of
the American policy in Afghanistan.''
</P>
<P>
   The most recent fighting in Kashmir broke out when Indian forces
sought to take up positions that they had abandoned during the
winter along the frigid border. They came under fire, and it soon
became clear that insurgents had crossed from the Pakistani side
and seized a sliver of Indian-held territory.
</P>
<P>
   India has charged that the insurgents are working closely with
the Pakistani Army and include many Pakistani regulars, but
Pakistan denies any involvement.
</P>
<P>
   Heavy-handed Indian tactics here have turned many people against
India. The Indian authorities have arrested an estimated 30,000
young Kashmiris in the last decade, releasing nearly all of them
after a year or two without charge.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands more have died in shootouts, ambushes and battles.
Soldiers with bulletproof vests and automatic weapons patrol the
streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``People here feel very happy when Indian soldiers are dead,''
said Surinder Oberoi, an Indian journalist who has lived in Kashmir
for nearly a decade. ``When three aircraft were downed, it was
literally like a celebration. People were congratulating each
other.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see another round of violence if the government of India
continues with this rigid policy. It's extremely dangerous in the
long run.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Kashmiris are also suspicious of Pakistan, where the tide
of religious militancy runs counter to their tradition of
tolerance. If allowed to vote in a plebiscite as their leaders
demand, many might choose independence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to be a free nation, but we are not ruling out any
option,'' said Shabir Shah, who has spent 22 of his 46 years in
Indian prisons for advocating separatism and who now heads a
pro-independence party. ``If India and Pakistan would negotiate
with legitimate Kashmiri leaders, maybe some other solution could
be found. But unless India gives some response to our nonviolent
struggle, the field will be left entirely to the men with guns.''
</P>
<P>
   The men with guns, aided by a spreading network of civilians,
are engaged in a social and cultural campaign to shake the
foundations of life here. Nearly every village in Kashmir now has
at least one mosque, many of them built in recent years with money
reportedly donated by people in Saudi Arabia and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Some religious leaders have condemned the use of zirayats,
Muslim houses of prayer that are symbols of tolerance and welcome
Hindus and other non-Muslims. Several zirayats have been burned.
</P>
<P>
   Hindus and Christians have fled some villages in Kashmir,
complaining of threats and intimidation. Koran courses are
sprouting in many schools. Religious workers have begun a campaign
of adopting orphans and street children, who are given intensive
religious education.
</P>
<P>
   Radicals have warned women to wear modest clothing. In at least
three cases in the last year, they have shot women in the feet who
refused to stop wearing jeans.
</P>
<P>
   The combination of Islamic fighters in the mountains and
fundamentalist pressures in towns and villages is not all that
makes the Kashmir crisis explosive. India and Pakistan are the
world's newest declared nuclear powers, and although both have
pledged not to use nuclear weapons in this dispute, the prospect
lends an apocalyptic air to the recent fighting.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the confrontation between NATO and the Warsaw Pact during
the Cold War, peace was maintained not only by the nuclear balance,
but also by a balance of conventional forces,'' said Bali, the U.N.
envoy. ``That meant that the nuclear threshold was very high.
</P>
<P>
   ``But here, where there is a great imbalance of conventional
forces, the nuclear threshold may be very low. The big powers can't
afford to sit back and let this situation play out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
