<SLUG> BC-SLEEP-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KILLER'S ACTIONS TOO COMPLEX FOR SLEEPWALKER, EXPERT SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY KAMMER  
 and RICHARD RUELAS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Scott Falater's actions after he stabbed his wife were
too purposeful and complex to have been done by a sleepwalker, an
expert witness for the prosecution testified Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very uncommon in sleepwalking to have a very neat, tidy
progression of events,'' said Dr. David M. Baratz, assistant
medical director of the Sleep Disorder Center at Good Samaritan
Medical Center in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Baratz provided perhaps the strongest testimony yet for
prosecutor Juan Martinez, who has clashed at times sarcastically
with expert defense witnesses who testified that Falater was
sleepwalking when he stabbed his wife, Yarmila, 44 times.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Friday, Falater, who on previous days sobbed
remorsefully and said he was devastated by the death of ``Yarm,''
finished his testimony by answering questions from the jurors.
</P>
<P>
   In one question, read aloud by Judge Ronald Reinstein, a juror
asked if Falater, 43, felt responsible for the death of his wife of
20 years and the mother of his two children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I'll have to leave that up to God to decide,'' he
said, then paused. ```Personally, it is something that is going to
haunt me forever. I don't know that I'll ever get over that.''
</P>
<P>
   Baratz based his opinion that Falater was not sleepwalking on
the eyewitness account of a neighbor who looked over a wall after
the stabbing.
</P>
<P>
   The neighbor, Greg Koons, saw Falater approach his wife's body
twice, first looking down at her for about 30 seconds before
fetching a pair of gloves from the garage. Koons continued to look
on as Falater dragged her to the pool, rolled her in and held her
head underwater.
</P>
<P>
   Then Koons summoned police and paramedics, who arrested Falater
inside the house and pulled Yarmila's body from the pool. Official
reports listed her cause of death as ``multiple stab wounds with
drowning.''
</P>
<P>
   The defense has characterized the pool incident as the sort of
bizarre behavior that is typical of sleepwalkers. They said it made
no sense for Falater to leave the body floating in the pool and
then return to the house.
</P>
<P>
   Baratz disagreed. ``I can't see how that would be an act of a
sleepwalker,'' he said. He said it appeared to him that Falater
used the pool to finish off Yarmila.
</P>
<P>
   Baratz also noted police reports that indicate Falater went into
the garage twice during the time he claims he was sleepwalking.
</P>
<P>
   First Falater removed his bloody clothes, then he returned to
stash his gloves _ along with the clothes and hunting knife _ in
the wheel well of his Volvo station wagon.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Martinez questioned Jacqueline Haek, a sleep
technician at St. Luke's Medical Center who administered four
nights of hospital sleep tests on Falater. The defense has used
test results to show that Falater's brain waves had characteristics
commonly found among sleepwalkers.
</P>
<P>
   Haek testified that one of the expert witnesses for Falater's
defense, Dr. Janet Tatman, asked her to alter the test results in
order to show Falater entered the deep sleep.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't feel comfortable changing the data. This is a legal
document going to court, and I told her (the doctor) I didn't feel
comfortable changing it in the middle of the study,'' Haek said.
</P>
<P>
   During Haek's cross examination, defense attorney Lori Voepel
sought to portray her as a headstrong technician who used outdated
methods as she evaluated the brain-wave tests.
</P>
<P>
   Voepel showed Haek medical journals and technical manuals
authorizing the use of different methods.
</P>
<P>
   But Haek held her ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``She asked me to change the data. That's what I considered
unethical,'' said Haek.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez is expected to finish his rebuttal case early next week
in the murder trial, which has drawn international attention to the
Maricopa County courthouse in downtown Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   That would set the stage for final arguments and for jury
deliberations that could begin as early as Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   As Martinez wraps up next week, he will not be able to present
testimony about a discussion Falater allegedly had three weeks
before Yarmila's death.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Reinstein ruled that Martinez had resorted to
impermissible hearsay to claim that Falater had talked about the
case of a Canadian man who used a sleepwalking defense to walk away
from charges that he had murdered his mother-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   Reinstein also blocked Martinez's effort to call a witness to
testify that Yarmila developed a venereal disease in 1990. Martinez
said before the trial that the witness would testify that she told
Yarmila that Scott had been ``messing around.'' But Reinstein ruled
that the seven-year gap between 1990 and Yarmila's death was too
great for the issue to be permissible material for the trial. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
