<HEADLINE>
KREIGER RANKS AMONG THE BEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEITH LAIR  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRWINDALE, Calif. _ Irwindale Speedway Super Stock points leader
Michael Price of San Pedro is the third-best race-car driver in the
Pacific Coast Region ShorTrack Series with Thousand Oaks' Larry
Kreiger ninth, according to the NASCAR Winston Racing Series.
</P>
<P>
   Price has a Competition Performance Index of .7778 to rank
third. Tim Clark of Watsonville Speedway is No. 1 with Robert
McCoun of Madera Speedway No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something new to shoot for,'' said Price. ``It's been
us and (T.K.) Karvasek battling for the lead. It's so much fun.''
</P>
<P>
   There are nine other ranked Irwindale drivers with Grand Am
driver Kreiger ninth on the first tier.
</P>
<P>
   On the second tier, Karvasek is No. 1 and Grand Am/Super Late
Model's Rod Johnson fourth. Whittier Super Stock driver Greg Benner
third in the third tier with Grand Am's Gerry Mielke seventh.
</P>
<P>
   On the fourth tier, Grand Am's Rip Michels is second with Tom
Siebuhr in Super Stock third. Kevin Wood in Super Stock is No. 1 in
the fifth tier and Grand Am's John Watkinson is eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Kreiger says the secret is that most of the drivers raced at
Saugus.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my opinion, it's all these Saugus guys,'' says Grand Am
points leader Kreiger. ``That was a hard track. The set-up was
tough. We can run anywhere _ Las Vegas, Mesa Marin _ and win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Winston Racing Series has contributed a $1.423 million fund
to be distributed among the 120 short tracks in the nation. Eight
California tracks make up the Pacific Coast Region.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being consistent is the key,'' Whittier's Brenner said.
``Being ranked is a pleasant surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday's race was the first time members of the Winston Racing
Series a main sponsor for the Winston West race had seen Irwindale.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the finest track in the nation and that includes more
than 100 tracks,'' assistant manager Terry Rutledge said. ``The
venue is the best, the tech building is unbelievable and the
tear-down area is unheard of.''
</P>
<P>
   The Winston Racing Series is based in Winston-Salem, N.C. The 10
regional champions will be recognized at the series banquet in
Orlando, Fla. in November.
</P>
<P>
   Track vice president Ray Wilkings says 3,000 of the 6,500
tickets have been sold for tonight's Winston West Irwindale 250.
</P>
<P>
   The West series qualifying will be at 5 p.m. with all drivers
available for an autograph session at 6 p.m. in the chalet area
between the grandstands and the pit area. Wilkings said that will
be a permanent track feature.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just making the area a good meeting area for families,''
Wilkings said.
</P>
<P>
   Winston West drivers Austin Cameron, Brendan Gaughan and Wayne
Jacks raced in Friday night's Super Late Model events.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a huge difference,'' said Gaughan, who has raced at
Irwindale thee times. ``This car is 3,100 pounds compared to 3,400
pounds. There two-barrelled with restrictor plates compared to wide
open.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacks will drive his NWWS car with a picture of Pasadena's Olga
Mendez on the hood. Mendez has been missing since being adbucted in
February 1998. Jacks will be racing for Race for the Missing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll do anything to help anybody,'' Jacks said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
