<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS BATS GO SILENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Time for a Los Angeles Dodgers quiz.
</P>
<P>
   How did the Dodgers lose this time? A) Poor starting pitching,
B) shoddy defense, or, C) failure to accomplish anything
offensively.
</P>
<P>
   On any given night this week, it could be all of the above, but
this time it was C. The Dodgers managed four hits and wasted a
bases-loaded opportunity in the eighth inning as they lost to the
Philadelphia Phillies 2-1 in front of 41,590 Friday at Dodger
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   It's the ninth time in 12 series the Dodgers lost the first game
of a series at home.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers (30-35) are also five games under .500 for the first
time since losing to Philadelphia May 31, 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't play the game right,'' said Dodgers third baseman
Adrian Beltre, who hit a solo homer. ``I don't know what's going on
with this team. We're supposed to be strong with starting pitching,
and (Ismael Valdes) throws a great game and we don't score. If it's
not one thing, it's the other. It's a lot of bad things. Everything
is negative for us. We're not playing the right way.''
</P>
<P>
   The lethargic Dodgers offense killed itself in the eighth
against reliever Steve Montgomery. First, pinch-hitter Dave Hansen
drew a four-pitch walk. Eric Young singled just over the head of
third baseman Scott Rolen and Jose Vizcaino sacrificed the runners
over a base. After a lengthy meeting at the mound, Raul Mondesi was
intentionally walked to bring Eric Karros to the plate with the
bases loaded.
</P>
<P>
   But, of course, the Dodgers found a way to get themselves out of
a big inning.
</P>
<P>
   Karros hit a sinking line drive to shortstop. Alex Arias caught
it a few inches off the ground and threw to second to easily double
off Young and end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I did a better job of getting back it would have been a
double play anyway,'' Young said. ``This is a tough drop for us.
You keep going at it and hope it turns, and you hope you don't get
too far behind before it turns.''
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Gomes pitched the ninth for his eighth save. The only
saving grace is Arizona lost and the Dodgers remain nine games
back.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had the right guys in the right spots and we just didn't do
it,'' Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said. ``You're not supposed to
get doubled up on a line drive. Maybe from his view he thought the
ball was going to go through.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Curt Schilling's first win since May 29 when he shut out
the Colorado Rockies, and also ended a miserable streak for one of
the best pitchers around. In his past three outings Schilling was
0-2 with a 6.97 ERA. During that span his ERA went from 2.57 to
3.39.
</P>
<P>
   The best thing the Dodgers did was take a few more pitches than
normal and get Schilling (9-4) out of the game after he threw, for
him, a relatively low 101 pitches. Schilling allowed three hits and
one run in seven innings. He struck out four and walked three.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers starter Ismael Valdes was nearly Schilling's equal. He
allowed five hits and two runs but lost. Valdes threw eight
innings, a windfall for the Dodgers starters, but left trailing
2-1. He struck out five and didn't walk a batter, but all that
meant was the Dodgers had a chance to win. Valdes threw 118
pitches, 81 of which were strikes.
</P>
<P>
   It's the fifth straight start Valdes has allowed three earned
runs or less, yet for the fourth straight time he lost.
</P>
<P>
   The one thing Valdes has been victimized by this season is the
long ball, and that's how the Phillies built their 2-1 lead. Valdes
entered the night having yielded 15 homers, one fewer than Chan Ho
Park's team-leading 16. By the time the night ended Valdes had the
dubious lead.
</P>
<P>
   Phillies catcher Mike Lieberthal, a Westlake High graduate, put
the Phillies ahead with his 15th homer of the season. His solo shot
in the second came with the count full.
</P>
<P>
   Beltre tied the score 1-1 in the bottom of the inning with a
solo homer to left with two outs.
</P>
<P>
   Valdes and Schilling remained locked in speedy duel until the
seventh when Rico Brogna led off with a homer to center field to
give the Phillies a 2-1 lead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-99 0146EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
