<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-SPURS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPURS TAKE COMMANDING 2-0 LEAD OVER KNICKS IN NBA FINALS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo of is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ It was early in the game, and Latrell Sprewell was
in full intimidation mode. With a menacing glare, he was going to
the basket hard and fast, like a rock from a slingshot.
</P>
<P>
   But out of nowhere, the eerily quiet Tim Duncan popped out of
the paint like a submarine breaking the surface and timed his leap
in sync with Sprewell's. And in one instant, Duncan turned a sure
dunk into a blocked shot and rejected all the intensity and
determination Sprewell had bubbling inside of him.
</P>
<P>
   The scenario that played itself out in the first quarter was
repeated Friday night, as Duncan joined his 7-foot partner, David
Robinson, to combine for nine blocked shots. Each was a dispiriting
slap to the Knicks' once unflappable confidence, which withered in
the end as New York was beaten, 80-67, by the San Antonio Spurs in
Game 2 of the NBA finals at the Alamodome.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't put my finger on the problem,'' Sprewell said before
having the shot-blocking numbers pointed out to him. ``You know
they are coming, both Tim and David. But you've got to go at them
and take it right to them. If they block it, they block it.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's time for a new plan. This was the Knicks' second
double-digit loss to the Spurs in two games. Once again, the Knicks
had no answer for Duncan, whose 25 points and 15 rebounds helped
give the Spurs a 2-0 lead in this best-of-7 series.
</P>
<P>
   The series now moves to New York, beginning with Game 3 at
Madison Square Garden on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, the Knicks' offense boiled down to whatever points
could be generated by the one-on-one style Sprewell and Allan
Houston were left to make up as they combined to shoot 17 of 42
from the field. They tried to drive and were stopped. They were
left to shoot jumpers and missed. Inside and out, the Spurs seemed
to be in the Knicks' heads as they held New York to 32.9 percent
shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were thinking about us when they were coming to the
hole,'' said Robinson, who finished with 16 points and 11 rebounds.
``They understand it's not going to be easy to get to the rim.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came in and talked about getting one or two games here.
This is a different challenge for them. But with all the stuff
they've been through this year, we don't expect them to quit.''
</P>
<P>
   They don't die easily. The Knicks led in the first quarter for
only one brief moment, but they were close for so long. They were
still scrambling and forcing turnovers and giving themselves a
chance deep into the third quarter. They were within three points
of the Spurs, trailing by 52-49 with 2 minutes 41 seconds left in
the third, and then they got outsmarted by their opponents.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks had three chances to pull even but failed, on a
shot-clock violation and two missed jumpers. The Spurs were missing
as well _ failing on jumpers from 3-point range _ but then Sean
Elliott drove past Sprewell to the basket for a layup and was
fouled on the way by Houston.
</P>
<P>
   With 2.5 seconds left in the third period, Elliott stood at the
free-throw line. At that moment, Duncan noticed Marcus Camby
talking and not paying attention. As Elliott missed his free throw,
Duncan slipped inside of Camby and put the rebound back for a layin
with 1.9 seconds on the clock. The 4-point swing gave the Spurs a
56-49 lead entering the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were talking, me and Latrell, and saying to each other to
move down,'' Camby said. ``He was able to sneak in there and grab
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell had to accept part of the blame, as well, for chatting
during such a pivotal moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a big moment for them,'' Sprewell said. ``If we stop
them, then it's a different game at that point. That allowed them
just to keep that little bit of extra cushion. So I mean, it was a
mental mistake on our part.''
</P>
<P>
   It cost them dearly. The Knicks were never so close again. They
closed to within six points with 8:22 left in the game. But at
almost the same moment as in Game 1, the Spurs went on a run to put
the game away, this one a 12-1 streak that capitalized on a
plethora of missed jumpers by the Knicks and four turnovers in a
six-minute span. This futility was not just pinned on Houston and
Sprewell, but on the teammates who were unable to make open jumpers
around them, as the Knicks went nearly seven minutes without a
field goal.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Larry Johnson finished 2 for 12 from the field and
scored five points on a sprained right knee, while a suddenly cold
Kurt Thomas was 1 for 6 and Chris Childs ended the night 2 for 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously I don't think we're playing well offensively,''
Knicks coach Jeff Van Gundy said. ``Tonight, I thought in stretches
we had good shots and missed point blank. Other times, I would
agree, we were trying to squeeze it ourselves instead of doing one
more thing, like an extra pass, one more drive and kick, whatever
it takes to create a better shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Usually, layups are high-percentage shots. But not with Robinson
and Duncan ready to pounce on anyone coming their way. With the
Knicks so predictable in their one-on-one approach, Robinson and
Duncan just waited until a defender turned Sprewell or Houston into
the paint, and then timed their leap.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to play better offensively,'' Sprewell said. ``We have
to keep positive.''
</P>
<P>
   They have to remain confident despite two bad nights in the
Alamodome.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want them thinking about being down, 2-0,'' Van Gundy
said. ``I don't want them thinking that we have to win four out of
the next five games. All we need to think about is Monday.''
</P>
<P>
   And put all the rejection of the past out of their minds.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
