<SLUG> BC-AUTOREVIEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIDENGINE ACURA NSX PUTS SPORT ON STREET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB GOLFEN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the talk turns to hot sports cars, it's not often that the
name Acura pops up. The upscale Honda division is best-known for
well-built luxury cars and some spunky compacts, but rarely
mentioned in the same breath as Corvette, Porsche, even Ferrari.
</P>
<P>
   But those in the know are well-aware of the exotic, midengine
Acura NSX. Here's a supercar by any standard, an exclusive fantasy
machine and streetable racer that provides all the sounds and
sensations of the top performance sports cars.
</P>
<P>
   The NSX is a thrilling car to drive. The powerful, tractable V-6
howls behind your ears, propelling the lightweight car like a
rocket and pinning you back in your seat. The firm, supple
suspension provides a solid sports-car ride without the punishing
harshness, but with the on-the-dime cornering. The Ferrari-esque
styling of the all-aluminum body turns every head, young or old.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, it's a real-world vehicle that can be driven every day,
docile and smooth in traffic and backed by Acura's reputation for
reliability. The interior is roomy, simple and handsome. The trunk
space is decent. And the stereo is fabulous.
</P>
<P>
   I'd order my NSX in a heartbeat if it didn't cost so darn much.
</P>
<P>
   One friend, a consummate vintage racer who collects Jaguar
sports cars and has the money to drive whatever he wants, traded in
his Porsche 911 for an NSX about a half-dozen years ago. And never
looked back. The NSX, he says, is the best street car he's ever
driven.
</P>
<P>
   I know I'm impressed. The NSX just aces the field in performance
and sheer driving fun. And before you start sneering at the
small-displacement V-6, consider that it's cranking out a solid 290
horsepower with only about a ton-and-a-half of aluminum sports car
to push around.
</P>
<P>
   The techy V-6, which uses Honda's pioneering VTEC
variable-valve-timing system, programmed fuel injection, variable
volume induction and exotic aluminum and titanium alloys, roars to
life at nearly any engine speed.
</P>
<P>
   VTEC is a complex system of camshafts and rocker arms that
actually change cam-lobe profile as engine revs climb. It provides
a mild profile for smooth low speeds, which switches at about 5,200
rpm to a profile that provides longer duration and higher lift to
boost high-end power. You can hear the engine roar turn more urgent
as the profile changes, and feel the power quickly build.
</P>
<P>
   This setup was first tried in the NSX when it appeared on the
scene in 1991, and since has spread to Acura's and Honda's more
mainstream cars. VTEC represents the performance wave of the
future, mainly on four-cylinder Honda engines that young gearheads
love to hot-rod.
</P>
<P>
   With its trick V-6, all-aluminum construction and exotic
midengine design, the NSX is the high-tech equivalent of big-block
supercars such as Chevy Corvette or Dodge Viper. And even at a
lofty $88,000 for the T-top version we drove (the coupe is a mere
$84,000), the NSX is a relative bargain compared with the big-time
exotics, such as Ferrari or Lamborghini.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the muscle-car acceleration is that wonderful,
balanced handling. Really, the midengine car takes the curves so
well it's almost humbling. A great driver could make this thing
jump through hoops. A not-so-great driver can push it as hard as he
or she dares, never really reaching its ragged limit or full
potential.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, if you tried to drive this car full-bore on the street,
they'd throw you in jail. The best place to appreciate the NSX
would be on a race track, if you had the good fortune to get it on
one.
</P>
<P>
   The NSX interior is attractive and accommodating, with decent
leg and shoulder room, but a bit sparse on headroom. I had the roof
panel removed when I rolled past a buddy, who yelled at me, ``Hey,
your big head's sticking out.'' So much for my Michael Andretti
impersonation.
</P>
<P>
   The T-top, by the way, stows in a cleverly designed compartment
built into the engine hood just behind the cockpit.
</P>
<P>
   For the driver, everything inside the NSX feels just right. The
steering is on the money in effort, feedback and precision. The
shifter moves with short, precise throws. All the switches, from
turn signals to radio dials, yield positive and solid movements.
It's a great place to do business.
</P>
<P>
   Oh yes, there is an automatic-transmission version with a
slightly detuned engine, but why anyone would buy an NSX so hobbled
is beyond me.
</P>
<P>
   The dashboard is moved far forward in the interior, creating a
sloping form that provides a spacious feeling. The seats are firm
and supportive.
</P>
<P>
   The NSX has never been a volume seller. They only make 500 of
them a year, completely by hand, one at a time. That compares with
about 10,000 Porsche Boxsters and 20,000 BMW Z3s sold last year in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But for any well-heeled soul looking for a high-end sport
machine, I'd say check out the NSX. It's the best seat in town to
enjoy that midlife crisis. &QL; 
Bob Golfen can be reached at 444-8106, or at bob.golfen(at)pni.com
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
