<HEADLINE>
CONFIDENT HALAMA CONTAINS CLEVELAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ The best team in basketball intimidates John Halama.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a diehard Knick fan,'' the Mariners left-hander said with
a sigh Friday night, as he watched New York struggle against the
San Antonio Spurs in the NBA Finals. ``But they don't have a
chance.''
</P>
<P>
   The best team in baseball doesn't faze him at all.
</P>
<P>
   Showing the measured self-assurance that is becoming a
trademark, Halama beat the Cleveland Indians, 9-4, with seven
strong innings at Jacobs Field. He was touched for two singles and
a three-run homer in the eighth, but mastered the Indians until
that inning, keeping them off balance with an assortment of
off-speed pitches and winning for the third time as a starter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sensed that from him in spring training, and that's one of
the best features that he has,'' catcher Dan Wilson said of
Halama's poise. ``He's so stone-faced out there and so focused at
the same time. It's really a great asset for him.''
</P>
<P>
   So is Halama's repertoire, especially against a team like the
Indians, which often devours fastball pitchers. Halama's fastball
averages about 87 miles per hour, so he relies on change-ups,
curveballs and, like veteran Jamie Moyer, variations on his
fastball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether he realizes it or not, he changes speeds with his
fastball a lot,'' Wilson said. ``But he really didn't throw that
many tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   No more than half of Halama's 106 pitches were fastballs, and
Wilson said it may have been as few as 40 percent. The effect on
the Indians was dramatic. Cleveland came into the game with a .302
batting average, best in the majors, but did not manage a hit until
Manny Ramirez's leadoff single in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Halama struck out five and did not walk a batter. He faced the
minimum number of hitters through four innings, and got double-play
ground outs to end the sixth and seventh. He improved to 5-2 on the
year, and is 3-0 with a 3.34 earned run average in five starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not much that's going to bother me,'' Halama said.
``Give up a hit, so what? I just want to get outs. I don't want to
sit out there and keep my defense out there for a long time.
There's going to be times where I don't have it and get my tail
kicked and I give up a five-spot or a six-spot. I don't want to
walk hitters. I think that'll frustrate me more, when I walk
hitters, knowing that I'm a control pitcher. I have such a fluid
motion that I shouldn't walk anybody to begin with.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners offense gave Halama a five-run lead with a
second-inning outburst that stemmed from, of all things, an error
by seven-time Gold Glove second baseman Roberto Alomar. David Bell
looped a single over Alomar to bring home Seattle's first run, but
with two outs and two on, Brian Hunter bounced a ball toward
Alomar.
</P>
<P>
   Alomar bobbled it, and by the time his throw reached first,
Hunter already had crossed the bag. One run scored, making it 2-0
Mariners, and Charles Nagy then had to face Alex Rodriguez and Ken
Griffey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Double to left, single to right, 5-0 Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ball just seemed to come up on Robbie,'' said Indians
manager Mike Hargrove. ``Give credit to Brian Hunter on the play.
He hustled all the way.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners added two runs in the sixth and two more in the
ninth, when left-hander Ricky Rincon _ whom Seattle had tried to
acquire from Pittsburgh last winter _ gave up his first runs in 18
games this year. Griffey belted his 25th homer to lead off the
inning, rocketing a high fastball 464 feet into the right-center
field bleachers for the third-longest homer in the six-year history
of the Jake.
</P>
<P>
   It also moved Griffey past Indians legend Rocky Colavito for
42nd place on the all-time home run list, with 375. Butch Huskey
followed with his 13th homer one batter later.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Fassero finished up for the M's _ who have now won four in
a row _ with his first relief outing since Sept. 11, 1993, a span
of 170 starts. Fassero sandwiched a strikeout between a pair of
ground outs for a one-two-three ninth.
</P>
<P>
   ``No problems,'' he said. ``It was a positive first step. And
it's pretty easy to go out there with a five-run lead in the
ninth.''
</P>
</TEXT>
