<HEADLINE>
FOR SLUMPING DAVIS, WALK A GOOD SIGN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ It did not help his batting average or produce a run
or affect the outcome of a game. But Russ Davis had a good at-bat
Wednesday night in Detroit, and the way things are going for him,
that was a start.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners third baseman worked the count full, fouled off
about five pitches and drew a walk. Few in Tiger Stadium may have
paid much attention, but the Mariners bench noticed.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he fouled those balls off, the entire dugout was roaring
for him,'' said hitting coach Jesse Barfield. ``You could see his
confidence building on each pitch. His swing was much shorter that
at-bat. As a hitter, you try to take something positive out of each
at-bat, and that was certainly something to build on.''
</P>
<P>
   In his last 11 games, Davis is 4-for-41 (.098) with one run
batted in and no extra-base hits. Manager Lou Piniella has started
John Mabry at third in four of the past seven games.
</P>
<P>
   ``In '96 I struggled my first 50 at-bats,'' Davis said. ``I've
always been kind of an up-and-down, streaky type hitter, but I
think this is as bad as it's been since that '96 season.''
</P>
<P>
   In the clubhouse after Wednesday's game, Davis watched a video
of his walk and also studied the ``ugly ones'' that preceded it.
But Thursday's game brought no better results, as Davis went
0-for-2 and was removed for a pinch hitter. He did not start Friday
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obvious,'' Davis said. ``Guys are going to continue to
pitch me away and throw sliders away until I show them I can go get
that ball and take it the opposite way, like I've done in the past.
There's nothing wrong with my mechanics. It's simple _ I'm pulling
off the ball. I'm getting myself out swinging at stuff off the
plate and over my head.''
</P>
<P>
   By pulling off the ball, instead of keeping his lead shoulder
closed, Davis is denying himself his best asset, Barfield said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he's on, he has some of the quickest hands in baseball,
and I try to continually remind him to trust his hands,'' Barfield
said. ``But when you're 2-for-20, your confidence level is down.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis agreed. Struggling for about a month, he felt he was
emerging from his slump two weeks ago. But then he got to Colorado,
where Rockies pitchers threw him nothing but sliders away, and he
went hitless in eight at-bats. He started tinkering with his stance
``instead of just going up there and hitting,'' and the problems
continued.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've just got to get my mindset right and believe in my
hands,'' Davis said. ``Let the ball just travel a little bit
further, let it get back in my zone.''
</P>
<P>
   Barfield isn't the only one helping Davis. Center fielder Ken
Griffey Jr. recently noticed that Davis was standing flat-footed in
the batter's box. Correcting that, Davis said, will help him get to
more outside pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's behind me and wants me to get out of this thing,''
Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   DEADLINE DOLLARS: Whenever the Mariners have been in a pennant
race the past several years, they've made deals near the July 31
trading deadline. With trade talk around the league increasing in
the next month, Mariners vice president for baseball operations
Woody Woodward would like to be active again.
</P>
<P>
   One snag, of course, is the budget. Ownership has yet to
authorize an increase in the team's $53 million payroll. When asked
if that could change if Seattle is still in contention in a month,
Woodward said, ``I don't know that right now. My directive from
(president) Chuck Armstrong is to be out there looking and keep him
informed of what's available.''
</P>
<P>
   That means approaching potential budget increases on a
case-by-case basis. ``It probably will depend on how strongly we
like what's available to us,'' Woodward said.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City's Kevin Appier and Toronto's David Wells are
front-line starting pitchers who are expensive but could become
available if their teams continue to struggle. Woodward appears to
be open to discussing anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking is free,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   EDGAR READY: Concerns about Edgar Martinez's sore left elbow
were so serious Friday afternoon that Martinez said he would have
X-rays on it during the game. But the M's designated hitter took
batting practice and felt only minor soreness, and told manager Lou
Piniella he's ready to go. No X-rays were taken on the elbow, which
was hit by a pitch last Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
