<SLUG> BC-BKN-FINALS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPURS PUT KNICKS IN 2-0 HOLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Say this much for San Antonio Spurs fans: They do
not hide the fact they're a spoiled and greedy bunch.
</P>
<P>
   Just how fat the Spurs have made their following became evident
midway through the fourth quarter at the Alamodome. At that time,
it was apparent San Antonio would polish off the New York Knicks
with Friday night's 80-67 victory in Game 2 of the NBA Finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sweep,'' the faithful roared. ``Sweep.''
</P>
<P>
   Nope. The Spurs did not get credit for three wins after going
ahead 2-0 in this best-of-seven series. No. The series is not over.
</P>
<P>
   But San Antonio has now won an NBA record 12 straight playoff
games, and it seems unlikely the Spurs' next loss is in sight.
Especially when the Knicks can't see straight.
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio's defense again forced a horrid shooting night by
the Knicks, who head home for Games 3 and 4, and Game 5 if
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   New York's hope is that Madison Square Garden will provide a
better backdrop after it shot just 32 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams combined to produce the second-lowest scoring game in
Finals history.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Spurs are playing the type of defense they used to
sweep the Los Angeles Lakers and Portland in the previous two
rounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last two series weren't that easy,'' said Spurs center
David Robinson, who is two victories away from winning his first
title in 10 seasons. ``Everybody said it looked easy but they were
not that easy. Our defense just took them out of what they wanted
to do. Playing the Knicks is not easy. They're explosive. They're
relentless. ... I don't know what it looks like but they're making
us work.''
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs' postseason run is better than that of the great
Showtime Lakers during the 1980s, and the Michael Jordan-led
Chicago Bulls who won six titles this decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still are very confident,'' New York forward Marcus Camby
said. ``Guys on this team have a lot of pride. ``We definitely
don't want to get swept. I don't think that's going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   New York is working much harder but to no avail. Robinson and
Twin Tower Tim Duncan made scoring inside against them a fruitless
chore. Robinson rejected five shots and Duncan swatted four to
account for all of San Antonio's blocks.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks were even intimidated into missing several
point-blank shot attempts.
</P>
<P>
   ``To a certain extent they're thinking about coming to the hole.
They understand it's not going to be easy getting to the rim,''
Robinson said. ``We've done a good job taking away the transition
buckets which they count on.''
</P>
<P>
   In Game 2, the Spurs disrupted the Knicks teamwork, too. New
York had just eight assists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our effort level and our mental state is fine,'' Knicks coach
Jeff Van Gundy said. ``We just need to score. ... The shot-blocking
presence really creates bad shot selection.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks reverted to one-on-one play, which allowed Duncan and
Robinson to stand in the paint like fly swatters.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a great defensive team, especially at the basket,''
Van Gundy said. ``But the game was decided at the free-throw line.
They could get their shots and we couldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio shot 35 free throws. The Knicks were 11-of-12 from
the stripe.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike in Game 1, New York stayed clear of foul trouble. Van
Gundy rotated Camby, Larry Johnson and Kurt Thomas and Marcus Camby
to defend Duncan. Camby was the only one to foul out late in the
fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson missed 10 of his 12 shots. Thomas was 1-for-6 and Camby
made just 3-of-9 field goals. Sprewell scored 26 points, but he was
8-for-22.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan finished with a modest 25 points and 15 rebounds after
taking 33 points and 16 boards in Game 1. It was Duncan who
provided the Spurs with the biggest momentum play.
</P>
<P>
   Ahead 56-59 with 2.5 seconds left in the third, Duncan slid in
the lane and rebounded Sean Elliott's free throw miss. Duncan
scored a putback that keep the Knicks at arm's length heading into
the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs led 39-34 at halftime and never allowed the Knicks to
get closer than five points in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``They changed it up a little bit. They double teamed a little
harder,'' Duncan said. ``I didn't get as many easy looks.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Duncan was plenty more effective than anyone the Knicks
had down low.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need our main three guys to be efficient offensively,'' Van
Gundy said.
</P>
<P>
   Or risk being swept?
</P>
<P>
   ``The talk will be there because of what happened in the last
rounds,'' Popovich said. ``But sweep was not in our minds against
the Lakers and Portland. We try to play with an appropriate amount
of fear.''
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs are evidently not afraid of playing on the road. They
San have yet to lose on the road in the playoffs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
