A1849 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDITORIAL-DEBT-BOS &LR;      06-19 0373
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-DEBT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SELFISH CHARITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Finance ministers meeting this weekend in Cologne, Germany, have
an opportunity to improve economic stability everywhere by helping
to ease the mountain of debt burying the world's poorest countries.
Reducing that burden is in the best interest of debtors and
creditors alike.
</P>
<P>
   The World Bank, the International Monetary Fund, and other
international lending institutions have identified about 40
countries with aggregate indebtedness of $170 billion that urgently
need relief. A sensible procedure has been established that
assesses the ratio between a country's annual cost for debt service
(interest and principal) and the income the country derives from
exports. If debt obligations exceed trade income by 2 1/2 times,
the country is deemed a candidate for assistance.
</P>
<P>
   The formula, first put to use three years ago, has produced only
modest gains so far. Only two countries _ Uganda and Bolivia _ are
fully engaged in a debt-clearing procedure, and four others are
approaching that goal out of a preliminary group of 12 nominated
for aid. Of the balance, some, like Sudan and Somalia, are in such
turmoil they are out of reach. Others haven't begun taking the
necessary political steps _ such as budget restraint and tax
collection _ to handle their debt.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing the debt problem of the poorest countries is
important not only for their interests but for those of wealthier
countries. In the struggle to cope with debt service, poor
countries sell their exports, often basic commodities like
minerals, at whatever price they can get, in the process driving
down not only their own income but that of other countries. While
lower prices benefit consumers, the benefits are achieved on the
backs of people at the bottom of the economic pile.
</P>
<P>
   The debt crisis also prevents poor countries from making
progress in basic development _ roads, education, medicine,
communications _ that would allow them to become better customers
for products from the industrialized world.
</P>
<P>
   Breaking this chain will not be easy or cheap. The alternative,
however, is in the long run far more costly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
