<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-ASTEROID-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PET ROCK? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Planetary Society's ``Name the Asteroid Contest'' is a nice
break for the earthbound. Even though the entry deadline has
passed, the winner is not expected for a few weeks, so a person can
still contemplate the possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   More than 400 entries came in for the naming of the space rock
known as ``1992 KD'' since its discovery seven years ago by Eleanor
Helin and Kenneth Lawrence at the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration's Jet Propulsion Laboratory. They had naming rights
but thought the public might enjoy doing the honors and turned the
project over to Carl Sagan's Planetary Society.
</P>
<P>
   Since the asteroid is a study target for NASA's Deep Space 1
mission, which is testing new technologies, the society asked
entrants to name the rock after an inventor.
</P>
<P>
   There were the expected nominees _ Albert Einstein, Galileo
Galilei, Thomas Edison, Sir Isaac Newton. But the not-so-obvious
suggestions are more interesting _ Philo T. Farnsworth, inventor of
television; Microsoft magnate Bill Gates; physicist Stephen
Hawking; naturalist John Muir; the fictional Merlin; a cat named
``Gertie''; the word ``necessity'' _ because it is ``the mother of
invention''; actress Hedy Lamarr.
</P>
<P>
   That last name is not as crazy as it sounds, for Lamarr did
invent an electronic guidance system for the military that is the
underlying technology for cellular phones. Putting a Hollywood star
among the real ones for her intellect might appeal to the judges'
imaginations, although the International Astronomical Union, which
must approve the name, could take a more conservative view.
</P>
<P>
   Naming what is beyond our control makes nature less scary. An
asteroid may be more than a mile wide, but with a first name it
would seem less likely to blast a hole in the earth. Man continues
to make pets of the wild things, ever seeking to temper his fear
while reaching out for a piece of immortality.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-99 0218EDT &QL; 
