<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SPURS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPURS SHOOT, MISS,   WIN EASILY ANYWAY
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Less than two minutes into Game 2, Sean Elliott
pulled up from 24 feet and launched an unsightly jump shot that
smashed against the rim with a bang.
</P>
<P>
   Two minutes later, his teammate, Mario Elie, stood alone behind
the 3-point line, waiting for the ball to arrive. When it did, he
set his feet, straightened his shoulders and released a misdirected
shot that ended up as a Chris Dudley rebound.
</P>
<P>
   For the Spurs, it was that kind of night. Midrange jumpers
clanged off the rim. Three-pointers fell short. And still San
Antonio defeated the Knicks by 80-67 to take a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good teams win ugly,'' said Jaren Jackson, who made one of
five 3-pointers after hitting five in Game 1. ``It was kind of
scary at moments, but we were able to finish it off and just grind
it out. It was ugly but it was effective.''
</P>
<P>
   You have to wonder how the game but overmatched Knicks will ever
defeat these Spurs if they did not do it Friday night. Jackson, who
scored 17 points in Game 1, was as cold as one of those late-night
bus rides he used to take while playing in the Continental
Basketball Association. He missed his first four 3-pointers before
making good on his last attempt with 10 seconds remaining and the
game already decided.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott, the miracle worker who won Game 2 of the Western
Conference finals against Portland by sinking an off-balance
3-pointer with 9.9 seconds left, was more effective on the drive
than the spot-up jumper, going 1 for 4 from 3-point range. All
told, the Spurs made just 2 of 12 3-pointers and just eight shots
outside the painted area.
</P>
<P>
   It is on nights such as these that the Spurs are vulnerable. Tim
Duncan (25 points, 15 rebounds, four blocks) and David Robinson (16
points, 11 rebounds, 5 blocks) will always do their damage,
especially against injury-depleted front lines like that of the
Knicks, so when one of the Spurs' perimeter players is hot, San
Antonio is all but unbeatable.
</P>
<P>
   But Friday night the Spurs, who did not hit their first jump
shot until Steve Kerr buried a 21-footer 4 minutes 17 seconds into
the second quarter, won with a sometimes overlooked aspect of their
excellence _ their defense.
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio, the league's best defensive team throughout the
regular season, overcame its shooting woes by holding the Knicks to
32.9 percent shooting. With the great shot blockers, Duncan and
Robinson, combining to swat nine shots, the Spurs had the Knicks
bewildered. Even when one of the agile seven-footers wasn't there
to contest a shot, the Knicks seemed to be thinking about them as
they missed numerous attempts near the rim.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a terrific defensive team,'' Elie said. ``Dave and
Tim are always talking, and if you get beat they're going to be
there and that's the trust we have in each other. We've been No. 1
in defense all year and there's a reason for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Elie's shot was as off as that of the rest of his teammates, as
he missed all three of his 3-point attempts, including one that
missed the rim and backboard entirely. But the New York City native
adjusted and, instead of settling for the jump shot, took the ball
to the hole to score 15 points, two of which came on a resounding
driving slam dunk.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's my game. I'm a city ball player,'' said Elie, who made
7 of 8 free throws. ``I put my head down and went to the rack. I
was a little frustrated that I missed two 3's from the corner, but
when your shots are not going, you have to put your head down and
try to get to the free-throw line and get a little rhythm.''
</P>
<P>
   All told, the Spurs' five key perimeter players _ Jackson, Elie,
Elliott, Kerr and Avery Johnson _ shot just 13 for 37 from the
field for 35.1 percent. Almost all the points they scored came from
the foul line and on drives to the basket.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, Spurs coach Gregg Popovich wondered aloud if
his team could win without a major contribution from outside
shooters.
</P>
<P>
   ``You certainly hope you're going to get something from the
perimeter,'' Popovich said. ``If we don't, we'll be in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Amazingly, that proved to be untrue. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
