<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-19 02:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1858 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDITORIAL-ESPIONAGE-B     06-19 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-ESPIONAGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COX'S CHINA SYNDROME 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, June 20, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a consequence of a House committee report marred by
unbalanced testimony and unfounded conclusions, Congress has been
in the throes of an old-fashioned Cold War fright about Chinese
espionage at the nation's nuclear weapons labs.
</P>
<P>
   It is crucial to retrace any actual theft of classified material
and rectify security violations that can be corrected, but the
shoddy work of the House Select Committee on US National Security
and Military/Commercial Concerns with the People's Republic of
China, chaired by Republican Christopher Cox of California, has
induced an unnecessary panic about Chinese espionage and the
specter of poor security at US labs.
</P>
<P>
   The danger is that measures taken against an overblown threat
can do as much harm to national security as the espionage they were
meant to thwart.
</P>
<P>
   At the Los Alamos weapons lab in New Mexico the damage has
already begun. Congressmen and government bureaucrats who show no
understanding of science or security have imposed Draconian secrecy
rules. The primary effect has been not to make nuclear secrets more
secure but to undermine the quality of science and prevent Los
Alamos scientists from fulfilling their mission _ competent
stewardship of the country's nuclear stockpile.
</P>
<P>
   Since the United States has ceased training enough top-level
pure scientists, Los Alamos is obliged to recruit 25 percent of its
pure scientists from abroad, and many of these exceptionally
qualified people come from so-called sensitive countries such as
Israel, India, and China. Rules imposed in the wake of the Cox
report prohibit non-US citizens from working on any pure science
project that might receive money from the ``X sector'' _ the
weapons sector _ at Los Alamos.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, the best postdoctoral fellows recruited for the
lab ``have turned us down because of this new climate of
suspicion,'' Fred Cooper, a senior scientist at Los Alamos, told
the Globe. Also, arbitrary restrictions on travel _ even by
scientists who do no work on sensitive projects _ have cast a chill
over a scientific community that depends on open conferences to
pursue its work.
</P>
<P>
   These rules and restrictions, although they do nothing to
improve security, are demoralizing and are driving away some of the
best scientists. ``This myopic view of the security problem really
jeopardizes our weapons program and the safety of the country more
than espionage can,'' said Cooper, stressing that he could speak
only as a concerned physicist and not for the Los Alamos
management.
</P>
<P>
   The director of the nonproliferation project at the Carnegie
Endowment for International Peace, Joseph Cirincione, concurred on
the harm done at US weapons labs. ``The best scientists will leave
or just will not come,'' Cirincione said. ``The only question is,
How big will our losses be and how long will the panic last?''
</P>
<P>
   Cirincione and Cooper are both adamant on the need for rigorous
enforcement of effective security rules at the labs. Both cite the
value of ending once and for all the insouciant habit some
scientists have had of downloading computer files from secure
machines at the lab to their computers at home. If researchers want
to do sensitive work at night, they will have to return to their
labs to work on secure computers.
</P>
<P>
   Although the FBI and the CIA conduct continual background checks
on lab staff, a useful improvement would be to make certain that
there are no gaps in this routine counterintelligence work.
</P>
<P>
   America's national security requires a delicate but achievable
balancing of espionage safeguards at the country's nuclear weapons
labs and the protection of a scientific culture that remains
hospitable to the best physicists from around the world. The false
conclusions and worst-case projections of the Cox committee must
not be allowed to subvert America's privileged status as the place
where the world's most accomplished scientists want to work.
</P>
<P>
   Cirincione recently said of the Cox report: ``I know
congressional reports. I have written congressional reports. This
is no congressional report. It is a propaganda piece.'' Propaganda
of this kind should not lead to fearful or confused politicians
casting away the irreplaceable scientific treasures that are unique
to this country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
