<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990619.0052 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-19 02:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1868 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDITORIAL-BIAS-BOS &LR;      06-19 0362
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-BIAS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FACING FACTS ABOUT CRIME
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Monday, June 21, 1999)  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's a grim, common fact: Young minorities are overrepresented
in the criminal justice system. But in 1988, rather than succumb to
what-do-you-expect ennui, Congress required states to act. Today 40
states have programs that analyze and respond to the
disproportionate numbers _ without quotas and without being soft on
crime.
</P>
<P>
   Now this progress is in danger. Senators Paul Wellstone of
Minnesota and Edward Kennedy presented an amendment to protect
these programs during last week's debate on the juvenile justice
bill, but it was tabled. Calling the amendment unconstitutional
because it ``makes an overt racial classification'' without having
any extraordinary justification for doing so, Utah's Senator Orrin
Hatch concluded that if more young minorities do the crime, they
should serve the time.
</P>
<P>
   This comfortable conclusion is flawed. Across all offense
categories from 1985 through 1994, black youths were more likely
than whites to be detained. Black males were four times more likely
to be admitted to a juvenile facility for property crimes and 30
times more likely for drug offenses.
</P>
<P>
   Black youths are 26 percent of those arrested but make up 32
percent of those sent to juvenile court, 41 percent of those
detained as delinquents, and 52 percent of those tried as adults.
</P>
<P>
   As Wellstone notes, looking at race is not inherently
unconstitutional. In a letter, more than 35 law professors at
schools ranging from the University of Alabama to Yale wrote that
constitutional questions arise only ``if there is some burden or
benefit allocated on the basis of race.'' Merely investigating
discrimination is not illegal, they said.
</P>
<P>
   A House bill would preserve these efforts. And the House has
passed an amendment to expand them. Now the issue must be hashed
out in conference committee.
</P>
<P>
   It would be outrageous to stop asking why the legal system is so
much harder on minority youth. Contrary to Hatch's argument, there
is an extraordinary justification for doing so.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-99 0226EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
