<DOCNO> NYT19990619.0057 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-19 02:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1876 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI     06-19 0908
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUP COULD BE WOMEN'S SPORTS BREAKTHROUGH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARTINSVILLE, N.J. _ Frankly, some soccer purists have been
offended that the 1999 Women's World Cup has been billed as the
world's largest women's sporting event, not as a world soccer
championship.
</P>
<P>
   There is a difference.
</P>
<P>
   Soccer is soccer. Advancing opportunities for women is something
else.
</P>
<P>
   Or, is it?
</P>
<P>
   With the '99 World Cup set to open Saturday, U.S. superstar Mia
Hamm did not chafe at the notion that she and her teammates are
still as much a symbol of women's athletic ability and achievement
as they are real, live, superb soccer players.
</P>
<P>
   Their game cannot exactly be separated from the movement to
advance women's sports. They do not believe the intertwining of
sport and symbol diminishes them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think in terms of having it sink in that we have been
pioneers, it's a continuing process. We're doing everything we can
to continue this ascension (of women's soccer),'' Hamm said.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a soccer perspective, we still want a professional league
started so those young girls can grow up dreaming of playing
professionally for a living. So there's still work that needs to be
done, but I think we're moving in the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   So what will these soccer players from 16 countries, who will
play in 32 games on the road to a July 10 championship match, be
like? That is the ultimate question on the eve of this
``breakthrough'' sporting event for women.
</P>
<P>
   Are they role models or soccer players?
</P>
<P>
   Are they pioneers or professional athletes?
</P>
<P>
   Or is it fine to be all those things at once?
</P>
<P>
   And when the TV cameras start rolling Saturday for the U.S.
opener at Giants Stadium, and the China match in Palo Alto, what
will this World Cup look like to whomever tunes in?
</P>
<P>
   My guess is that, at least in the case of games involving the
U.S., China, Sweden, Norway, Germany, Brazil and Italy, there will
be general surprise at the level of skill and competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, World Cup organizers are secretly hoping the Spurs
will sweep the Knicks and end the NBA Finals. That might open the
door for more cursory sports fans to channel surf to these World
Cup games, just to check it out.
</P>
<P>
   If that happens, this tournament has a chance to build some
momentum.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to understanding the athletic and star appeal of
some of the world's best players, there is a good chance that just
like during the 1996 Olympics _ when the women in softball,
basketball, swimming and soccer shined _ new names and faces will
become familiar.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Hamm, U.S. striker Tiffeny Milbrett is expected to have
a breakthrough tournament.
</P>
<P>
   For Canada, a former North Carolina State star named Charmaine
Hooper is the team's top scorer, capable of making Sportscenter
highlight goals.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese have a stellar goalie in Goa Hong, who is apparently
as media savvy and expressive as any Westerner.
</P>
<P>
   The Brazilians play the same balletic style as their male
counterparts, so look to Katia and Pretinha for fancy footwork.
</P>
<P>
   The Norwegians have Linda Medalen, a 33-year-old veteran who
lives to give the U.S. fits, and Ann Krisin Aarones, who scored the
goal in the 1995 World Cup that ousted the U.S. from the
semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   Women's basketball went over the top in the wake of the 1996
Olympics, when professional leagues arose, and so did a more
diverse landscape of athletic stars for fans of all genders, and
soccer has had to wait.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe now, with this World Cup, some of that waiting is over.
</P>
<P>
   There is little doubt that the announced crowd at Giants Stadium
for the opening matches of the 1999 Women's World Cup will exceed
76,481.
</P>
<P>
   That was the number of people who stood in Georgia's Sanford
Stadium to see the U.S. women win the gold medal in the '96
Olympics. That was the largest crowd ever to see a women's sporting
event.
</P>
<P>
   ``To walk out onto that field that day in front of all those
people screaming, that was a tremendous crowd. That was quite a
statement,'' U.S. coach Tony DiCicco said.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, as much as the quality of play is important, statements
are, too.
</P>
<P>
   That is why Giants Stadium must and will deliver a sellout. As
statements go, this opener must exceed the Olympic gold medal
match, just to put this tournament in motion, to get it rolling so
that this World Cup can set a new watermark.
</P>
<P>
   The players are more than ready for this.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always played this game with a high sense of
responsibility,'' Hamm said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been on this team a long time, but Michelle Akers and
April Heinrichs and the other veterans basically set the groundwork
for what this team is all about: working hard, no cutting corners.
There are no shortcuts. We treat the game and our opponent with
respect,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everywhere we play, in a lot of different cities, in big
venues and small venues ... it's amazing the support we've gotten.
And also if you look at the number of young girls who are playing
soccer in this country, there's a market.''
</P>
<P>
   For the heavily favored U.S. team, winning this World Cup is
every bit about demonstrating their utter dedication to
professionalism. And then it is more than that. It is a celebration
and a dare. There is still more to be done, and this is the stage.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-99 0231EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
