<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBA FINALS GIVE FANS LITTLE TO CELEBRATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Most discerning NBA followers knew that the Finals
between San Antonio and New York was not going to be epic.
</P>
<P>
   Not only was it an unbalanced matchup, owing at least in part to
all the Knicks' injuries, it followed the worst season in NBA
history, owing to the lockout and compressed calendar.
</P>
<P>
   But no one quick expected the championship series to calcify
right before the eyes of the sports world.
</P>
<P>
   I mean, good for the long-suffering basketball fans of San
Antonio, but the remaining witnesses need to petition the NBA to
call a halt to the proceedings before all hoops dignity is lost and
traditions forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night's 80-67 win by the Spurs at the Alamodome was
another slash across a once-handsome face. Compared to the great
Celtics-Lakers matchups of the 1980s, or even a little of the
Bulls-Jazz dramas of the last couple of seasons, the Knicks and
Spurs are going positively Flintstone on us.
</P>
<P>
   Only it's not yabba-dabba-do time.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Spurs are up two games _ the biggest 2-0 lead
since Sandy Koufax against anybody _ it's a little difficult to
celebrate anything about the second-lowest-scoring contest in
Finals history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't expect us to shoot this badly,'' said David Robinson,
cringing a little at the numbers. ``We shot the ball better in the
regular season and earlier in the playoffs. But that also gives us
confidence because we still can win without great scoring. We know
somebody is going to step up and hit big shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice because we don't have to think about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Fine for you, big guy. What about the rest of us who have to
watch?
</P>
<P>
   It's true that the Spurs have won a record 12 straight playoff
games and 44 of their last 50 overall. But 43 percent from the
field and 68 percent from the line against a crippled, intimidated
team? Expressions such as grandeur, majesty and whoopie do not
readily slip out the keyboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we outplayed them,'' admitted Spurs coach Gregg
Popovich. ``We just knocked down shots.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks had a better chance to knock down the building,
presuming they could be directed to a wall. They shot 33 percent,
including a stretch in the first half in which they missed an
incredible 18 of 19 field goal attempts.
</P>
<P>
   Witnessing the Knicks trying to score against the Spurs has all
the compelling allure of watching primitive man evolve from
hunter-gatherers to an agrarian culture. Decades can pass between
significant developments.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks' offense clearly has developed a magnum case of the
yips about hoisting a ball anywhere near Robinson and Tim Duncan,
the 7-footers who now have only to flick eyebrows at the visitors
to alter shots. Despite all the New York pregame rhetoric about
attacking the big men, San Antonio tied a Finals record for fewest
personal fouls with 13.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the reason they lead the league in field goal
defense,'' said Knick coach Jeff Van Gundy. ``They do it with great
lane intimdiation. I thought we had some good looks. But nothing
comes easy with those two guys.''
</P>
<P>
   The pair combined to block nine shots, and when it's considered
that the Knicks only attempted 67, that's a high failure rate
before the rocket even leaves the launching pad.
</P>
<P>
   But it would be wrong to attribute Knick failures strictly to
the imposing tandem. The Knicks also missed 12 of 14 shots beyond
the arc, where the giants never tread.
</P>
<P>
   The decimated Knicks are plain awful. There's a chance the U.S.
women's soccer team will score more goals today in its tournament
opener at the Meadowlands than the Knicks will muster in Game 3
Mondayin Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``We missed point-blank shots,'' Van Gundy said. ``At other
times, we were trying to squeeze it, instead of doing one more
drive, one more kick-out or one more pick-and-roll to create a
better shot.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't just the missed shots. It was the 24-second
violations, the dribbles off feet, the silly fouls, the 35-12
disparity in free throws. The whole evening was lame, right down to
the ``Go Spurs Go'' chant that the team actually paid an ad agency
to invent and promote.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of great contemporary literature doesn't come cheaply,
you know.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very ugly win, no way to hide that,'' said Duncan,
who again led the Spurs with 25 points and 16 rebounds. ``We win
best ugly. We never claimed to be pretty.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly it's nice to know somebody's happy. The rest of us
will have to find joy going into the 1950s archives for those
dreamy set-shooting classics between Fort Wayne and Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   Retro is so big in so many parts of American culture that by
Monday the Spurs need to break out the short shorts and thick black
glasses.
</P>
<P>
   Style points may be the only points available the rest of this
series.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-99 0233EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
