<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-19 02:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1878 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-IRWNDL2-LADN-(SLA     06-19 0422
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-IRWNDL2-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PURSLEY FEELS RIGHT AT HOME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEITH LAIR  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRWINDALE, Calif. _ The home-track advantage was all Greg
Pursley needed.
</P>
<P>
   Pursley, who has won at Irwindale Speedway five times, passed
Austin Cameron of the NASCAR Winston West series to win the Super
Late Model race before a crowd of 2,585 Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a pretty rough night,'' said Pursley, who has beaten
the best from the Featherlite Southwest Tour at Irwindale and now
three Winston West drivers. ``The competition was really good.''
</P>
<P>
   Cameron, fourth in the NWWS points race, led from lap 2 through
lap 30 of the 50-lap main event. Newhall's Pursley, running on
older tires, inched up on Cameron, from El Cajon, and drafted him
for two laps before making a pass on the backstretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to think tire strategy,'' he said. ``I knew that 112 car
(Cameron) would be hard to take because he had newer tires.''
</P>
<P>
   Cameron said he developed a push, which made it hard to maintain
the lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I had the better car. I began dialing in more back
brakes. I'm just glad I was able to put more laps on this track
before (tonight's race).''
</P>
<P>
   In the 30-lap Grand American main event, Rip Michels pulled away
from Mike Ayers on the final two laps for the win. In the 25-lap
Street Stock main event, Doug McComb held off T.K. Karvasek for his
first Irwindale victory.
</P>
<P>
   Pursley started seventh in the inverted field and didn't seem to
have a shot at moving near the leaders early on. Finishing off lap
7, he found a hole between two cars and shot between it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I closed my eyes,'' Pursley said. ``The car on the outside
started drifting in and my spotter told me someone was on my
quarter panel. It was scary.''
</P>
<P>
   In Grand Am, Michels, from Mission Hills, led by half a
straightaway and looked like an easy winner until Gerry Mielke and
Robert Rice hooked up and spun in turn 4 with the white flag to go.
On the restart, Michels slowed Ayers, from Las Vegas, and then took
off for the win. Canyon Country's John Watkinson _ who crashed
during the trophy dash _ started last and finished third.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt good,'' Michels said. ``I'm starting to build up for
the points race.''
</P>
<P>
   In Super Stocks, McComb, from Thousand Oaks, held off
hard-charging Karvasek, from North Hills. Karvasek got side-by-side
with three laps to go, but McComb managed to stay in front for the
win. Whittier's Greg Benner finished third.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
