<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-19 10:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1914 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOB-INTERVIEWS-TEXT-R     06-19 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOB-INTERVIEWS-TEXT-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT YOU DON'T WANT TO SEE IN A BOSS-TO-BE 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the economy booming, the future's so bright for this year's
crop of college grads that, as the song says, they gotta wear
shades.
</P>
<P>
   Yet of course, not every job interview goes swimmingly.
</P>
<P>
   Recently in this space, prospective employers shared their
recollections of the most clueless applicants to ever walk in the
door _ including one loser who had a pizza delivered in
mid-interview and another who showed up in her bathing suit.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's time to turn the tables _ with job seekers' critical
assessments of their corporate recruiters.
</P>
<P>
   The quotations below were collected in a written survey of
college seniors and post-graduates conducted this year by
WetFeet.com, an online job-market information service for students.
</P>
<P>
   _ By TOM KUNTZ
</P>
<P>
   _ ``During an interview, I was describing my work experience,
and the recruiter picked up his cell phone and checked his voice
mail while I was still talking.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``One of my interviewers ate an ice cream cone throughout the
entire 30-minute interview. He kept apologizing and said that it
was just too good to pass up.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``While interviewing with a Big Five (accounting firm) for a
management consulting position, the interviewer spoke about his
life and past jobs for 38 minutes of the 45-minute interview.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``I interviewed with two women from a company, one right after
the other, and they both spilled their coffee on themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``My future boss stood in the doorway and started scratching
his back on the door frame like a big bear.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``When asked where I want to work, I replied New York City.
And the interviewer responded, `How about I put St. Louis?'''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``I was so excited when I heard that there was a Fed Ex
waiting for me outside my dorm room. I figured it was details about
a `Super Saturday' of final round interviews, but in fact they
apparently thought I was so unqualified for the job that my
rejection letter required an overnight delivery.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``One of my third-round interviews started with the following
statement: ``Same questions as yesterday, but you must respond
differently.'''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``When I interviewed with Microsoft, the interviewer asked me
how I would design Bill Gates' bathroom.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``One guy started counting his money in the middle of our
interview.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Someone telling me I was getting old and needed to figure out
a definite career plan ASAP. (I am 30), followed immediately by the
next interviewer telling me I was quite young and could take my
time finding a career.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Being taken to a strip club in Los Angeles.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Rubbing my leg against the table leg only to eventually find
out it was the female recruiter's leg.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The chair I was sitting in broke and I fell down.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``When asked what the S with a star next to it meant on my
transcript, I replied that it meant that I was a superstar. (It
actually just indicates that the class I took was mandatory
pass/fail.)''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``One interviewer at a top investment bank asked me how
horseback riding was like investment banking.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Upon entering the room, one interviewer asked, `And who the
hell are you?'''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``When I arrived, a car had smashed into the fire hydrant at
the front of the building. The front lawn, driveway and street had
been torn up by the resulting geyser. I was hired and it turned out
the car had belonged to my new boss.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Flying down to Houston to interview for a position in
Chicago. (I live in Madison, Wis.)''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``A steel analyst in equity research at an investment bank
lamented the industry he was covering. He spoke thus: `If I was
covering technology, I would have a hotter wife, she would be
wearing bigger diamonds and I would drive a nicer car. I don't know
why anyone would want to do what I do.'''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The question, `Why are we here?'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-99 1057EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990619.0062 </DOCNO>
