</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DC-INTERNS-TEXT-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIPS ON SURVIVING A WASHINGTON INTERNSHIP WITHOUT A GRANT OF
IMMUNITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (editors: text that should be italicized is marked with (BEGIN
ITALICS HERE) and (END ITALICS HERE)  
 (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's been a year and a half since the word ``intern'' became a
punchline, time enough, perhaps, to purge the national
consciousness of tiresome jokes about fringe benefits and dry
cleaning. And time enough for interns to resume their rightful
place at the bottom of the office food chain, no matter how they
got their jobs or how much money their parents gave the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout history, interns have labored in obscurity, working
long hours for little or no pay, and without the prospect of a book
tour at the end. And so it will be this summer, as this year's
class of young achievers arrives in Washington. If all goes well,
it may once again be safe for them to note the internships on their
resumes.
</P>
<P>
   Both Congress and the White House have produced handbooks for
interns with advice about handling the difficulties that can arise
in Washington. Each was written well before the need for such
guidebooks became glaringly apparent. In that regard, the manuals
seem prescient, even wise, double entendres notwithstanding.
</P>
<P>
   _ By JANE FRITSCH
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) ``The Congressional Intern Handbook'' by
Sue Grabowski, published by the Congressional Management
Foundation, offers some thoughts for starting off on the right foot
with the boss.(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Once you start getting to know the Member, he starts asking you
to do things you'd rather not do (e.g., get shoes shined, buy
lunch), but these tasks are an avenue by which to build a stronger
relationship with the Member. . . .
</P>
<P>
   It can be an eye opener to learn that the boss has his/her
faults like anyone else and that nobody is perfect.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) The Member is a public servant.(END ITALICS
HERE)
</P>
<P>
   An intern should realize that there is only one public
personality in the place, and that is the one embodied in the boss.
Interns and the staff are parts of the woodwork when it comes to
presenting a face to the public _ the Member/Senator is the only
person who counts. . . .
</P>
<P>
   A constituent is an individual residing in the home district. .
. . They write and call a lot.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) In answering letters, remember, the Member
is sincerely sincere.(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   _ Member/Senator is understanding, sympathetic, friendly;
</P>
<P>
   _ Member/Senator is informed, knowledgeable about facts of
issue;
</P>
<P>
   _ Member/Senator is closely following legislation on the issue
(content/status);
</P>
<P>
   _ Member/Senator is active/participating in legislative action
or has been active on similar issue in past (voted/signed
letters/etc.);
</P>
<P>
   _ Member/Senator pays attention to constituent views and takes
them seriously; and
</P>
<P>
   _ Member/Senator is very glad to hear from them and hopes they
will keep in touch.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) Do you know who my father is?(END ITALICS
HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Don't mope or moan. . . . Ninety percent of interns are
over-qualified to be interns, but some don't realize this basic
fact of life. . . . You may end up salvaging a part of humanity,
but don't expect it as a matter of course.
</P>
<P>
   (END ITALICS HERE) He hasn't rolled in yet. (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   In general, don't volunteer specific information on why a person
isn't in. In particular, never admit the staff person hasn't come
in yet in the morning. . . . A good general phrase is, ``He is not
at his desk.'' . . . Short answer on speaking with the press:
don't. . . . What you may think is a joke or polite conversation,
or just plain old trying to be helpful, can end up in the morning
paper and cause much embarrassment to the Member or Senator. The
press is always out for a story _ and rightfully so. It's their
business. However, your Member's or Senator's perception of a story
and the press' perception might be worlds apart.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) I have some thoughts about education
reform.(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   An internship is a chance to occasionally run around and have
fun observing the spectacle without chafing against the confines of
a real job. . . . It can be the best of all worlds _ a share in the
action, but not an overwhelming stake in the future. This is not
advocacy of irresponsible conduct or unreliable behavior. . . .
Somewhere between laid-back and manic there lies the balanced
internship _ sensitive to one's contribution to any project, but
aware of one's place in the broader picture.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE)On observing a great deliberative body.(END
ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Once seated, a visitor cannot talk, read, write, eat, drink,
smoke, clap, wear a hat, lean over (or touch) the first-row railing
or do just about anything except watch, breathe and be very quiet.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) Above all, be subtle.(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Washington, D.C.'s fashion environment is considered
conservative with a small `c.' government is sober and serious
stuff where style tends toward traditional conventions. You're not
likely to see much of the splash and dash of Malibu, Miami or
Manhattan during working hours. . . . A man can get away with
having only khaki/gray pants. . . . Adjectives you don't want to
hear directed at your clothes: wrinkled, dirty, too baggy. A
women's wardrobe should be versatile. . . . Lean toward low-key in
the hem and neckline departments, and think about a slip for
anything sheer. . . . Adjectives you don't want to hear directed at
certain aspects of your outfit: too short; spiked; plunging,
low-cut, too tight, wrinkled, see-through.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) Should I retain counsel?(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Funny things can happen to us when we're taken out of our normal
surroundings. Often human nature rationalizes a different, and
sometimes dubious, behavior in a new environment _ it's like it
doesn't ``count'' because we're not at home and nobody's looking
who knows us. . . . It's a grown-up world with lots of
repercussions. Step lightly. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Test of propriety: if what you are about to do was to be
reported on the front page of the largest paper in your
district/state, would you still do it?
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
