Somewhere between laid-back and manic there lies the balanced
internship _ sensitive to one's contribution to any project, but
aware of one's place in the broader picture.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE)On observing a great deliberative body.(END
ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Once seated, a visitor cannot talk, read, write, eat, drink,
smoke, clap, wear a hat, lean over (or touch) the first-row railing
or do just about anything except watch, breathe and be very quiet.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) Above all, be subtle.(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Washington, D.C.'s fashion environment is considered
conservative with a small `c.' government is sober and serious
stuff where style tends toward traditional conventions. You're not
likely to see much of the splash and dash of Malibu, Miami or
Manhattan during working hours. . . . A man can get away with
having only khaki/gray pants. . . . Adjectives you don't want to
hear directed at your clothes: wrinkled, dirty, too baggy. A
women's wardrobe should be versatile. . . . Lean toward low-key in
the hem and neckline departments, and think about a slip for
anything sheer. . . . Adjectives you don't want to hear directed at
certain aspects of your outfit: too short; spiked; plunging,
low-cut, too tight, wrinkled, see-through.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) Should I retain counsel?(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Funny things can happen to us when we're taken out of our normal
surroundings. Often human nature rationalizes a different, and
sometimes dubious, behavior in a new environment _ it's like it
doesn't ``count'' because we're not at home and nobody's looking
who knows us. . . . It's a grown-up world with lots of
repercussions. Step lightly. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Test of propriety: if what you are about to do was to be
reported on the front page of the largest paper in your
district/state, would you still do it?
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE)I wish I had a best friend to talk to.(END
ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   There are very big ears in Washington. . . . Who you talk to is
not always apparent on its face.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE)How to get transferred to the Pentagon.(END
ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   What should you do if you observe what appears to be unethical
actions on the part of other interns or staff? In most cases the
best course of action is to take up your concern directly with the
individual involved. This can clear up misperceptions and set an
ethical ``tone.'' If the unethical activity persists, or it is of a
grave nature, it should be brought to the attention of your own
outside supervisor, the appropriate staffer within the office or
the Member/Senator. . . .
</P>
<P>
   If you believe you are being abused or otherwise being requested
to do something improper or unethical, talk to an appropriate
person within the office first and then, if not satisfied, talk to
your outside intern supervisor, if you have one. Example: An intern
was asked to dress in a mini-skirt and serve drinks at a fund
raiser. She did it, but when her supervisor learned about this
blatantly sexist and objectionable assignment, he ended his
program's relationship with that Senate office.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) ``The Unofficial Survival Guide for White
House Interns'' was written by Shawn Landres, a former intern, and
is distributed by the White House Intern Program. It offers
congratulatory comments about the high standards applied in the
intern selection procedure.(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   You were selected to participate in the Internship Program
because the members of the review committee believe that you will
bring intelligence, talent, ability and maturity to your job.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) Do you know who my father is?(END ITALICS
HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Dedication: Pursue your assignments with enthusiasm and be
prepared to come to work early and leave late. . . . Be prepared
for your job description to change every few hours, expect the
unexpected, and tackle your work promptly, professionally, without
complaint, and with dignity.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE)When he stops taking your calls.(END ITALICS
HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Don't . . . attend events without an invitation; take advantage
of your position for personal gain.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) Familiarize yourself with the Independent
Counsel Law.(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Honesty: 'Nuff said.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE)The congressional handbook sums things up
with a tip about hygiene.(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   One final note: make sure to locate a reputable dry cleaner in
your neighborhood. . . . Dry cleaning is expensive, but that suit
won't impress anyone if it sports a big salad oil spot on the
jacket _ at least not the way you want to impress anyone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
