<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded i)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO PACKAGE:
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Pristina) _ With the last Yugoslav forces streaming
out of Kosovo ahead of schedule, NATO commanders here have reached
a tentative agreement with Albanian rebel leaders to gradually
disband the Kosovo Liberation Army as an organized military force,
NATO officials said Saturday. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.S.-RUSSIA (Cologne, Germany) _ When the Clinton
administration invited Russia to help it out of the war in Kosovo,
the idea was that the involvement in big game diplomacy would help
maintain the ailing Washington-Moscow relationship, and even
improve it. But as Yeltsin prepares to make his first foreign trip
in four months on Sunday to attend the G7-plus-Russia summit
meeting here, and in particular to meet Clinton, as many questions
are hanging over the Russian-American dialogue as were before the
war. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SUMMIT-RDP (Cologne) _ The European Union on Saturday
announced plans to provide $1.5 billion over the next three years
for the reconstruction of Kosovo as the West tried to map out a
strategy that would channel money to the war-devastated area
without giving financial support to Slobodan Milosevic's Serbia. By
Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NOTEBOOK (Stimlje) _ The proud talk of NATO victory seems
hollow here, in this dank little cellar where Nesibe Gashi has been
hiding for months, with her memories and her nightmares and her
grief. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   OTHER INTERNATIONAL NEWS:
</P>
<P>
   ROYAL-WEDDING (London) _ England's Prince Edward gets married.
By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-UNREST (Mexico City) _ Riot police clash with municipal
workers, a harbinger of what's to come before Presidential
elections. By Sam Dillon.
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-COURTS (Bogota, Colombia) _ For a decade, terrorism and
drug trafficking cases in Colombia have routinely been sent to
special tribunals that allow judges, prosecutors, and witnesses to
remain anonymous. Now, despite complaints by the United Nations and
human rights groups that such practices violate international law
and should be abolished, the Colombian government is moving to
extend the life and scope of these so-called ``faceless courts.''
By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-BARAK (Washington) _ His coalition almost complete, Ehud
Barak, Israel's prime minister-elect, is expected to come to
Washington early next month to unveil his keenly awaited thoughts
on reviving peacemaking in the Middle East. It is a harbinger of
the style Barak brings to his new job that he has declined to
discuss his intentions with any American official since the
election _ not Dennis Ross, the American mediator, not even the
American ambassador in Tel Aviv. And he has asked that his first
meeting be a long and private one with Clinton. By Serge Schmemann.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-ISLAM (Jakarta) _ A restive but largely quiescent
political force for decades, Islam has suddenly emerged, in the
vacuum of the slow vote count, as a potentially divisive issue
here. There is no question of a rise of militant Islam or an
imposition of Islamic law. But all of Indonesian politics is in
flux now, one year after the forced resignation of former President
Suharto, and Islamic factions are shifting and roiling as they seek
a new place in a new political order.
</P>
<P>
   ARABS-CHASTITY (Resaifah, Jordan) _ More than pride, more than
honesty, more than anything a man might do, female chastity is seen
in the Arab world as an indelible line, the boundary between
respect and shame. An unchaste woman, it is sometimes said, is
worse than a murderer, affecting not just one victim, but her
family and her tribe. It is an unforgiving logic, and its product,
for centuries, has been murder _ the killings of girls and women by
their relatives, to cleanse honor that has been soiled. Across the
Arab world, in Jordan, Egypt, Syria, Lebanon, Yemen, the
Palestinian territories and among Israeli Arabs, a new generation
of activists has now quietly begun to battle these honor killings,
an enduring wave of crimes prompted by sexual conduct that is
sometimes only imagined. By Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   KOREAS-ENGAGE (Seoul, South Korea) _ The gun smoke over the high
seas may be gone, but there is growing apprehension here that as
relations with the North become more varied, they will also become
more vexing. As they watched a push-and-shove naval match in the
Yellow Sea erupt into a firefight this past week, many South
Koreans were renewed in their belief that even as relations thaw
across the Korean peninsula, North Korea remains an irascible,
secretive, terrorist neighbor. By Sheryl WuDunn.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded a)
</P>
<P>
   BAPTIST-CONVENTION (Atlanta) _ In its annual conference this
week, the Southern Baptist Convention avoided, for the most part,
its headline-grabbing rancor of years past. The most controversial
resolution it passed, calling on President Clinton to rescind his
ambassadorial appointment of James Hormel, a homosexual, to
Luxembourg called for no official action on the convention's part
and was more a public finger-wagging than anything. But the
convention's president announced something a little more
surprising: he wants to see a greater number of blacks becoming
Southern Baptists.
</P>
<P>
   SONOFSAM-MEMORIES (New York) _ David Berkowitz, the serial
killer known as the Son of Sam, wept in prison last week, grieving
over the coming release of a Spike Lee movie called ``Summer of
Sam.'' Although Walt Disney's Touchstone Pictures will not release
the movie until the first week of July, ``Summer of Sam'' is
already jarring loose memories _some of them extraordinarily
painful _ inside the circle of New Yorkers whose lives were
fundamentally changed by the Son of Sam.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-GANGS (Los Angeles) _ Incongruously close to some of this
city's most affluent neighborhoods and a shell's throw from
touristy Venice Beach and the azure Pacific, a gang war has played
out over a decade, in which dozens have been killed and scores
wounded. The conflict is driven in part by racial differences and
in part by the desire to control the drug trade in Venice Beach.
Now public nuisance laws are increasingly being used against the
rival gangs, since a series of court rulings have strengthened the
hand of law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Coded w)
</P>
<P>
   GUN-CONTROL-POLITICS (Washington) _ Democrats are moving to
capitalize immediately on the failure of the Republican-controlled
House to pass even modest gun-control legislation, and promising to
take the issue to the forefront of the 2000 presidential campaign.
By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-LEGALDRUGS (Washington) _ Congress seldom meets a
hearing that it doesn't like, but the one that Rep. John L. Mica, a
Florida Republican, convened on Wednesday raised quite a few
hackles. Its topic: ``The Pros and Cons of Drug Legalization,
Decriminalization and Harm Reduction.'' The hearing, the first on
the subject since 1988, was motivated by suspicions on Capitol Hill
that legalization of drugs is the ultimate goal of people who
actively promote marijuana as a medicinal palliative or advocate
giving sterile syringes to heroin addicts to prevent them from
contracting AIDS. The hearing illustrated Congress's reluctance to
rethink the war against drugs, on which the federal government
spends nearly $18 billion a year. And it presaged the sort of
discourse about drugs bound to surface in next year's election
campaign. By Christopher S. Wren.
</P>
<P>
   WIND-ENERGY (Washington) _ Energy Secretary Bill Richardson says
he will announce on Monday a plan to produce 5 percent of the
nation's electricity from wind by 2020, up from 0.1 percent now.
Under the plan, the federal government, the nation's largest
electricity customer, would rely on wind for 5 percent of its use
by 2010. By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   SPEECHES-POLITICS (Washington) _ To judge from the speeches
announcing their candidacies for president, Vice President Gore and
Gov. George W. Bush could be declaring the primary campaign over,
the general election begun and the battleground designated as the
moderate middle, with ideological extremes out of bounds. Yet even
though they did not engage over detail, Gore and Bush were fighting
over much of the same ground. Both opposed drugs in schools. Both
promised to involve religious organizations in social welfare
programs. Both supported foreign trade. By Adam Clymer.
</P>
<P>
   COLUMNS
</P>
<P>
   (Coded k)
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN (Dateline TK) _ Commentary by Maureen Dowd; details
later.
</P>
<P>
   HERBERT-COLUMN (Dateline TK) _ Commentary by Bob Herbert;
details later.
</P>
