<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-19 11:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1932 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTERNET-DANGERS-REVI     06-19 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-DANGERS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIRTUAL TRUST: IN EDEN, A SNAKE. ON THE INTERNET, A WORM. 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By JOHN MARKOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cyberspace, which not so long ago was heralded as the arrival of
Marshall McLuhan's long-awaited Global Village, has instead become
Milton's Paradise Lost.
</P>
<P>
   In early June an Internet worm, known as Explore.exe for the
file that launches it, emerged to cut a wide swath around the
globe, leaving in its wake gigabytes of erased files and hordes of
frantic computer system administrators. For many computer users,
the program marked the end of trust in the virtual world.
</P>
<P>
   Most people already knew that it was dangerous to trust
strangers in cyberspace, just as it is in the physical world. The
infectious Explore worm, however, masquerading as e-mail from a
friend, raised the specter that it might no longer be possible to
trust friends either.
</P>
<P>
   Cyberspace, once thought of as the world's most cozy community,
has quickly become a lonely, infinite expanse of electronic
hallways filled with endless queues of online shopping malls and
shadowy alleys where computer outlaws and their rogue programs
lurk.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the plight of the disk drive engineer in Silicon Valley
who made the mistake of clicking on the innocuous document titled
``zipped-files.exe'' that was sent as an e-mail attachment from a
close friend. That simple action launched the omnivorous worm,
which spread itself throughout his company, erasing his files from
his hard disk drive and more than 30 gigabytes of corporate
administrative data.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't open an executable file even if it came from my
mother,'' one of his company's vice president told him later.
Another colleague suggested that he ``go away for a while.'' The
engineer describes the incident as the most embarrassing incident
of his life.
</P>
<P>
   The worm was also a bitter lesson for Jim Walsh, the chairman of
the department of organizational behavior and resource management
at the University of Michigan Business School. Sitting with his
laptop at Starbucks a week ago Friday, he was reading a message
from a friend at a Seattle software company when he clicked on the
infected file.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like pushing the red button,'' Walsh said. ``I clicked
my mouse and boom!'' When he returned to his office, a phone
message from his friend was waiting to warn him not to open the
message.
</P>
<P>
   Although he lost 950 files, including a new course that he had
developed in January, Walsh is trying to stay in good spirits about
his misfortune ``It's kind of like spring cleaning,'' he said,
acknowledging that he has become the laughing stock of his school.
``I've had people stop me in the halls to offer their
condolences.''
</P>
<P>
   If the victims feel chastened, the program has served to
construct even thicker walls and stronger locks in cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those who are more guarded and measured about how they use
technology are going to be safer,'' said Andrew L. Shapiro, author
of ``The Control Revolution'' (Public Affairs, 1999), a book about
the Internet's impact on society. ``The idea that the Internet
lifts us above geography contributes to the kind of naivete that
places people in harm's way.''
</P>
<P>
   There are those who remember when the Net was a remarkably
convivial place. From its roots in the late 1960's as the ARPAnet,
the Pentagon-funded experiment that connected computers at computer
research laboratories and universities, the Net was once an
intimate virtual coffeehouse where software and opinions were
freely shared. Locks and passwords were unknown in a hacker's
community based almost entirely on trust.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the early days you could attach faces and personalities to
people on line,'' recalled Bill Duvall, who helped create the
original ARPAnet while working at SRI International, a research
center in Menlo Park, Calif. ``Now we've created a virtual society
and nothing is what it appears to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Some optimists believe that it will be possible to design
``synthetic'' trust and embed it in network software, using
encryption and other technologies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not worried,'' said Kevin Kelly, one of the co-founders of
The Well, an early online community that emerged in the mid-1980s.
``This is a fantastic time. Step by step, we're going to invent a
science of trust.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly argues that this is the power underlying the world of
computers and networks. ``You can take things that the philosophers
have talked about for centuries,'' he said, ``and wire them up in
virtual reality and see how they work.''
</P>
<P>
   From this point of view the rogue worm is simply a useful flaw
that can serve as a guideline for engineers who are building a more
workable system.
</P>
<P>
   But others argue that the reality of cyberspace is emerging as a
darker vision mirroring the world described by William Gibson in
his novel ``Neuromancer'' (Ace Books, 1984).
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a big, bad world out there in cyberspace,'' said
Shapiro. ``It's certainly not Kansas.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
