<DOCNO> NYT19990619.0083 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-19 11:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1934 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHIP-IMPLANTS-REVIEW-     06-19 1255
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHIP-IMPLANTS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEYOND THE TRAIL OF BREADCRUMBS: MICROCHIPS UNDER THE SKIN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ In an unusual case that unfolded in Worcester, Mass.,
last week, a reputed mobster by the name of Vincent ``Gigi
Portalla'' Marino went to court to find out whether the federal
Drug Enforcement Administration had secretly implanted a microchip
tracking device in his body two and a half years ago during surgery
to remove a bullet from his buttocks.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors first argued that the government was not required to
confirm whether it had done such a thing, but later, after a judge
ordered them to respond, they said the drug agency had not
implanted a microchip in Marino.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot speak, however, for any extraterrestrial beings,''
said U.S. Attorney Donald Stern.
</P>
<P>
   As strange as the case sounded, Marino was really not so far off
base in thinking that there is a gadget that could allow his
location to be pinpointed at all times, with the help of global
satellites. The intriguing question is whether a large market will
ever emerge for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get calls all the time: `Is this available for children?'''
said Paul McMahon, a spokesman for LoJack Corp., based in Dedham,
Mass., which markets a positioning device that has helped track
down 30,000 stolen cars.
</P>
<P>
   People also frequently ask about using LoJacks for an elderly
relative who might be suffering from Alzheimer's disease or other
disorienting ailments, said McMahon: ``Our answer is no, our
technology is not appropriate for that.''
</P>
<P>
   But why not, exactly? We're willing to put positioning devices
on cars and cell phones, and we already put microchips inside our
pets. In fact, more than 1.5 million American cats and dogs have
been surgically implanted with tiny chips the size of a grain of
rice, encoded with information about how to reunite them with their
owners. So why not put chips inside the people we love the most?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's inevitable,'' said Arthur Caplan, director of the Center
for Bioethics at the University of Pennsylvania. ``Why? Because
there's a level of concern, some based in fact, some based in fear,
about the loss of children, about kids being stolen in custody
disputes, about terrorism, about kidnapping, that leads people to
be frantic about wanting to know where other people they care about
are.''
</P>
<P>
   People are also likely to encode themselves with chips
containing medical information, Caplan said.
</P>
<P>
   The possibilities are both scary and humorous, and they are
endless _ especially if the devices could be implanted, as the
lower-tech pet chips are, painlessly and in seconds. (That may
still be an issue; The LoJack device is actually the size of a
chalkboard eraser.)
</P>
<P>
   As the technology advances, they could even be inserted
surreptitiously. Wary spouses could either confirm or allay
suspicions about their mates. Bosses could monitor their employees'
whereabouts or, to turn the tables, workers could monitor whether
the boss is nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it could all be done for more romantic reasons.
Consider Professor Kevin Warwick, a cybernetics expert at Britain's
Reading University, and his wife, Irena, who announced last year
that they both planned to be fitted with computer chip implants in
an experiment to see whether they could keep track of one another
and even transmit emotions over great distances.
</P>
<P>
   The chip technology could work in much the same way a mobile
phone takes spoken words and turns them into electronic signals,
Warwick said in a telephone interview last week. ``I think you
could really do the same thing with emotions some day _ you could
transmit them digitally.''
</P>
<P>
   The professor described the technology as extremely useful,
because he travels a lot and works long hours and ``sometimes we
just don't get enough quality time.'' Or, as Mrs. Warwick put it to
The Sunday Times of London last year, ``It would be so romantic to
know when he was thinking of me when we are apart.''
</P>
<P>
   There are certainly those who argue vigorously against any of
this technology, even in pets.
</P>
<P>
   The Whole Dog Journal, a newsletter for holistic dog care
published in Greenwich, Conn., says many dog owners refuse to
implant the identification chips because of the ``Big Brother''
aspects of the practice.
</P>
<P>
   And early last year, even as the Los Angeles Department of
Animal Services said it would like to see every pet dog and cat in
the city microchipped to cut down on forced euthanizing of stray
animals, officials acknowledged that many pet lovers would not buy
the chips.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is something spooky about it,'' a Los Angeles official
said at the time, ``and everyone realizes it.''
</P>
<P>
   In human beings, it would, of course, seem all the spookier,
though it's hard to say whether the practice might become more
acceptable in another generation or two: After all, in the computer
age, whether we like it or not, the amount of information that is
out there about each of us would have seemed unimaginable a few
decades ago. And some day-care sites already have ``Web cams''
through which parents can check in on their infants during the day
by logging onto the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course it's all a trade-off,'' said Peter Szolovits, a
professor of computer science at the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology and an expert on the privacy of medical records.
</P>
<P>
   ``If, in fact, you were ever getting kidnapped, you might be
delighted to have one of these things in you,'' Szolovits said. On
the other hand, he said: ``I'm not sure that I want to have my
children growing up in a society where they have the sense that
their every movement can be tracked at any time. This strikes me as
psychologically not a good thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Proponents like Warwick said people need to overcome such
old-fashioned objections. Even what seems like the best reason for
using the chips raises a frightening possibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very dangerous, because once kidnappers get to know
about these things, they will skin you alive to find them,'' Terry
Waite, the Church of England envoy who spent five years as a
hostage in Beirut, told the Sunday Times last year.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reservations about putting chips in children or
spouses, the feeling about criminals, convicted or even accused,
may be different. Many people agree to wear electronic monitoring
devices as an alternative to imprisonment: These devices enable the
authorities to make sure the subject does not leave home.
</P>
<P>
   But what about the next-generation tracking devices, the kind
that Marino said a drug agent told him had been implanted by the
government. (Prosecutors said the agent was only joking; Marino's
lawyer, Robert Sheketoff, said his client, now in prison, ``doesn't
trust the government'' and wants an MRI scan to check for a
microchip.)
</P>
<P>
   Intriguingly, the FBI would not say whether it ever uses such
tracking devices.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to fall into the no-comment category,'' said a
bureau spokesman, Paul Bresson. ``It's discussing investigative
techniques, and that's about akin to a journalist disclosing
confidential sources. It's very sensitive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-99 1154EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
