<DOCNO> NYT19990619.0086 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-19 11:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1937 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BAPTIST-CONVENTION-NY     06-19 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAPTIST-CONVENTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTHERN BAPTISTS SEEK MORE BLACKS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Ariz., Mass. Pa., Nev., Wash.)   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In its annual conference this past week, the Southern
Baptist Convention avoided, for the most part, its
headline-grabbing rancor of years past.
</P>
<P>
   The most controversial resolution it passed, calling on
President Clinton to rescind his ambassadorial appointment of James
Hormel, a homosexual, to Luxembourg called for no official action
on the convention's part and was more a public finger-wagging than
anything.
</P>
<P>
   But the convention's president announced something a little more
surprising: he wants to see a greater number of blacks becoming
Southern Baptists.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Paige Patterson, convention president, announced that
in the next three years the denomination will make a major move
outside of its rural, Southern base to spread the Gospel and
recruit more blacks.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing the convention, Patterson said that beginning in
Chicago and Phoenix next year, the convention would spend at least
$2.5 million in each city to establish a Southern Baptist presence
in areas it has usually avoided.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our convention is too white and too Anglo-Saxon,'' Patterson
said in an interview after his address to the denomination's annual
meeting, which ended on Wednesday. A similar statement by the
Southern Baptist Convention leadership would have been unthinkable
a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But Patterson said no one would be more disappointed than he if
the initiative did not result in a large increase in the number of
blacks joining Southern Baptist congregations. Of the convention's
40,870 churches, about 2,800 are predominantly black.
</P>
<P>
   The initiative, called Strategic Focus Cities, focuses on
creating 180 churches in six cities, with a concentration on
neighborhoods undergoing transitions in their racial makeup. After
Chicago and Phoenix, the cities to be focused on in 2001 are Boston
and Las Vegas, Nev., and Philadelphia and Seattle in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   The three-year initiative is an extension of a 1995 public
apology by the Southern Baptist leadership for the convention's
past policies, said the Rev. R. Phillip Roberts, vice president of
the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to show that while in the past Southern Baptists have
refused to minister to people because of their race, today we're
talking about sharing a Gospel that sees no color,'' Roberts said,
noting that during the civil rights movement in the 1950s and 60s
the denomination strongly opposed integration.
</P>
<P>
   The desire to reach out to urban centers was never far from the
eyes of the 12,000 delegates who attended the convention. Large
banners that depicted Jesus looking over a city skyline that
proclaimed, ``He beheld the city and wept,'' hung on the walls of
the the Georgia Dome, the home of the Atlanta Hawks, where the
convention was held. Videotapes describing the six cities and their
needs were given to the delegates.
</P>
<P>
   It will take more than good will and supplies for Southern
Baptists to make inroads among African-Americans, said the Rev.
Grant D. Perry, a black pastor who met strong resistance from other
black clergy last November when he founded a Southern Baptist
church in Winterhaven, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   There is a deep skepticism among many blacks about a
denomination that was founded on the principle of slave ownership,
Perry told the convention. When the fear of black clergy about an
``invasion'' of their neighborhood by a large, wealthy white
denomination is added, the result is often a tense environment
without enough communication between churches, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson acknowledged that Southern Baptists had an image
problem among minorities, particularly blacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were them, I wouldn't take that apology seriously unless
I saw some action behind it,'' he said. ``But in the end, my own
perception is black people are just like everybody else in the
world; they want to be loved and we're going to show them we love
them.''
</P>
<P>
   The effort by Southern Baptists to reach out to urban areas is
important not just for blacks, but for making the denomination a
more vital one, said Bill F. Sumners, director of the Southern
Baptist Historical Library and Archives. He maintained that the
success or failure of initiatives like Strategic Focus Cities could
determine whether the Southern Baptist Convention grew or began to
shrink.
</P>
<P>
   The convention, the largest Protestant denomination in the
United States, was formed in 1845 by Southern whites, based
primarily on their desire to further the practice of slave
ownership.
</P>
<P>
   This year marked the first time since 1926 that the convention
has had a decline in membership. Although the decline was put at
only 162,158 in a denomination of about 15.7 million, the drive to
add more members came up more than once in Patterson's speech.
</P>
<P>
   But Patterson said there was no connection between the six-city
initiative and a desire to increase membership.
</P>
<P>
   Sandy D. Martin, a professor at the University of Georgia who
studies the role of religion in America, said, ``Even if you look
at it in a less noble light, it's still quite something for them to
make an effort to say, `We want to become a more diverse body.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
