<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-19 11:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1940 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GREENSPAN-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      06-19 1004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GREENSPAN-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREENSPAN ON INFLATION: WAIT, DON'T WAIT. GO FIGURE. 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By MICHAEL M. WEINSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan strongly hinted last
week that the central bank will raise interest rates later this
month to prevent the galloping economy from setting off inflation _
even though, he conceded, inflation remains inconsequential.
``Pre-emptive action can obviate the need of more drastic actions
at a later date,'' he told Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Huh?
</P>
<P>
   Is this the same Alan Greenspan who has steered unemployment
rates to their lowest levels in 30 years precisely because he was
willing to let the economic party go on? Now he says growth,
averaging 4 percent a year, is on an ``unsustainable trend,'' even
though increases in hourly wages are falling and inflation in May
was zero.
</P>
<P>
   Has Greenspan reversed course, discarding his brilliantly
executed regime of watchful waiting in favor of pre-emptive strikes
against nonexistent inflation?
</P>
<P>
   Some students of the Fed say Greenspan has been more a pragmatic
opportunist than a watchful waiter, taking clever advantage of
special circumstances like falling oil prices and spikes in
productivity. Others say he has been more lucky than good.
</P>
<P>
   Lurking beneath this debate is a more important one about how
the economy works and how central bankers should control it.
</P>
<P>
   Conventional economic wisdom, circa 1990, came in three parts.
</P>
<P>
   First, there was thought to be a minimum long-term unemployment
rate, estimated to lie between 6 and 6.5 percent. If the Fed would
try to push unemployment any lower, the theory went, it would send
wages, then prices, spiraling upward.
</P>
<P>
   Second, inflation, once started, tended to accelerate out of
control. Breaking inflation would require the Fed to raise interest
rates so much that recession would follow.
</P>
<P>
   Third, it was thought that Fed policies to break inflation would
need a year or more to take hold. Conventional wisdom said, then,
that the Fed should strike pre-emptively against inflation.
</P>
<P>
   But something weird and wonderful happened on Greenspan's watch.
For reasons nobody really understands, unemployment fell steadily
from above 7 percent in 1992 to 4.2 percent today. Yet inflation
stayed quiet. Something was wrong with the Fed's models.
</P>
<P>
   Some economists, like Professor Frederic Mishkin of Columbia
University, chalk up Greenspan's success to subtle pragmatism. In
1992 and 1993, Mishkin cites as an example, banks were in poor
financial health, so Greenspan kept interest rates low; that way,
banks wouldn't have to pay as much to depositors. After the banks
recovered, he raised rates in 1994 to keep the economy from
overheating.
</P>
<P>
   Professor Benjamin Friedman of Harvard provides another example.
In 1998, the Fed reduced rates to keep the economy from slowing in
response to the financial crisis spreading from Asia. Now,
Greenspan indicated during his testimony last week, the Asian
crisis has dissolved and some of the rate cuts may no longer be
needed.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Stiglitz, the chief economist at the World Bank and
former head of the Council of Economic Advisors under President
Clinton, takes a dimmer view of the Greenspan record, suggesting
that the post-1993 recovery happened despite errors Greenspan made.
Stiglitz says the Fed misjudged the favorable economic impact of
the budget plan that Congress passed in 1993 to trim the deficit.
It therefore sat on the sidelines as the economy roared ahead,
pulling the unemployment down to levels the Fed had thought
dangerous. If Greenspan had correctly forecast the impact of the
budget plan, Stiglitz argues, he would have raised interest rates
to fight inflation _ and the country would have lost a roaring
recovery that has brought jobs to millions of low-paid workers.
</P>
<P>
   But whether Greenspan achieved spectacular economic results by
accident or mistake, Friedman gives him credit for letting
unemployment fall to levels the Fed considered unsafe _ thereby
discovering the economy could do a lot better than the Fed had
thought possible. Stiglitz draws some other lessons. Research by
the Council of Economic Advisers, he says, refutes most of the
conventional wisdom. Inflation is not the scourge it was only
recently thought to be.
</P>
<P>
   Professor James K. Galbraith of the University of Texas agrees.
``Research does not show that, once started, inflation
automatically spirals upward,'' he said. ``Nor is there evidence
that reversing modest increases in inflation is all that costly.''
</P>
<P>
   By this line of argument, there's no harm in waiting to attack
inflation until it actually appears. And waiting has the advantage
of letting the Fed learn how fast the economy can grow. So, it
might seem, the debate comes down to a dispute between economists
who think it is important to pre-empt inflation and those who think
fighting inflation can wait. It's not quite that simple. This is,
after all, the Delphic science of economics.
</P>
<P>
   Listen to Friedman. He agrees that the Fed can reverse modest
inflation with only modest recession as a result. In this, he
sounds like Stiglitz. But he also wants the Fed to raise interest
rates next week. That sounds like the strategy preferred by
Greenspan.
</P>
<P>
   Friedman has an explanation: ``I called for rate hikes five
years ago when I thought the economy was growing too fast. And I
was wrong. I called for rate hikes two years ago. Again, I was
wrong. But labor markets are tighter now than they were five years
ago or two years ago, and our economy is growing even faster. The
Fed cannot wait around for mistakes to happen when it thinks they
are in the works.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-99 1159EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990619.0088 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-19 11:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5676 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GREENSPAN-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      06-19 1004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GREENSPAN-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREENSPAN ON INFLATION: WAIT, DON'T WAIT. GO FIGURE. 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
