<DOCNO> NYT19990619.0090 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-19 12:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1949 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONSERVATIVES-REVIEW-     06-19 0946
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSERVATIVES-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS STALK A SLOGAN, HUNTING FOR THEMSELVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   W was the letter of the week _ as in the middle initial and
nickname of George W. Bush, the governor of Texas who announced his
candidacy for president in trips to Iowa and New Hampshire. But by
the time Bush had made his way home to Austin, another letter in
the alphabet was crowing for attention in this swift presidential
primary campaign: C, as in CC, the shorthand in the Bush campaign
for ``Compassionate Conservatism.'' It was on that rhetorical
ground, the son of the former president declared in the course of
10 speeches in three days, that his campaign for the White House
would rise or fall.
</P>
<P>
   And what ground was that? Bush devoted eight lines in his speech
to a discussion of compassionate conservatism, but at the end of
his announcement tour it was clear that the phrase was as open to
interpretation as the candidate himself.
</P>
<P>
   Was this alliterative call to arms a fundamental new variation
of conservative thought, a bold attempt to move the Republican
Party to the center, much the way Bill Clinton pulled the
Democratic Party away from the left in 1992? Or was it a narrower
political calculation designed to fit a new suit around the
conservative policies that Republicans have been advocating in
Washington in recent years, if not quite so kindly and gently as
Bush did last week.
</P>
<P>
   The phrase ``compassionate conservative'' has been the subject
of much discussion (and some confusion) in recent days, as
Republican leaders, watching Bush seek to dominate the presidential
field, consider exactly what it means, and how it applies to this
race. Is there, for example, a compassionate conservative view on
gun control or abortion rights or gay rights or China policy?
</P>
<P>
   In general, the Republicans acknowledge they aren't sure. But
that hasn't inhibited a lively and sometimes cranky debate within
the party over the meaning of compassion and the nature of
conservatism, a debate that reflects larger conflicts over who the
Republicans are and what they should stand for.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest with you, I can't give you a straight answer on
it,'' said California Republican Party chairman John McGraw when
asked his definition of compassionate conservatism. ``I've been
conservative my whole life, and I think I've been compassionate,
too. I just never hooked the two words together.''
</P>
<P>
   To some extent, the confusion was by design: It is not in the
interest of Bush, the front-runner by acclamation, to take too many
positions on too many issues. Compassionate conservatism can mean
different things to different people, depending on which word the
listener chooses to emphasize.
</P>
<P>
   As a result there appear to be as many interpretations as there
are factions in the Republican Party _ some intended to define what
Bush means before he gets around to it, others using it to
discredit the ideological credentials of the candidate most
Republicans view as the party's likely nominee.
</P>
<P>
   ``If George Bush talks more about teaching reading rather than
abolishing the Department of Education, that's the language of
compassionate conservatism,'' Nelson Warfield, the conservative
Republican who served as press secretary to Bob Dole's 1996
presidential campaign, said approvingly. ``That's more relevant to
voters than flaming rhetoric about burning down the government.''
</P>
<P>
   New York Gov. George Pataki applauded the slogan as a cogent
summary of Republican policies that had been unfairly criticized.
``The compassionate conservatism that Governor Bush speaks about is
exactly right and precisely what we are trying to do,'' he said.
``Our policies, our conservative policies, result, in fact, in
better lives, and recognize true compassion for people who are
striving for a better lives.''
</P>
<P>
   But former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander, a Bush rival, faulted
Bush for political gimmickry, describing the phrase as a sign of
disrespect for the party's conservative base. ``I don't know what
it means,'' Alexander said. ``I don't think anyone else does
either. I think it's a carefully tested way to confuse the voters
so they won't know what we stand for.''
</P>
<P>
   The slogan, agreed William Kristol, the editor of the
conservative Weekly Standard, is little more than ``a way of
distinguishing himself from the congressional conservatives.'' He
added, ``The opposite of compassionate conservative is angry white
male.''
</P>
<P>
   The variety of these responses suggests that Bush may have
created (or more precisely, adopted; the phrase has been around for
at least 15 years) one of those political slogans that is useful
because people can read into it whatever they want. If that is
true, it is evidence of the keen skills that Bush has brought to
this campaign; compassionate conservative is certainly more
memorable than the call for ``practical idealism'' offered by Vice
President Al Gore last week in announcing his own bid for the
Democratic presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   That said, the phrase, combined with Bush's promise to present
the details of his platform ``on my own timetable,'' would seem to
invite voters, along with Republican leaders, to fill in the
blanks, investing Bush with their own values and views.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-99 1223EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990619.0091 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-19 12:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5682 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONSERVATIVES-REVIEW-     06-19 0946
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSERVATIVES-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS STALK A SLOGAN, HUNTING FOR THEMSELVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   W was the letter of the week _ as in the middle initial and
nickname of George W. Bush, the governor of Texas who announced his
candidacy for president in trips to Iowa and New Hampshire. But by
the time Bush had made his way home to Austin, another letter in
the alphabet was crowing for attention in this swift presidential
primary campaign: C, as in CC, the shorthand in the Bush campaign
for ``Compassionate Conservatism.'' It was on that rhetorical
ground, the son of the former president declared in the course of
10 speeches in three days, that his campaign for the White House
would rise or fall.
</P>
<P>
   And what ground was that? Bush devoted eight lines in his speech
to a discussion of compassionate conservatism, but at the end of
his announcement tour it was clear that the phrase was as open to
interpretation as the candidate himself.
</P>
<P>
   Was this alliterative call to arms a fundamental new variation
of conservative thought, a bold attempt to move the Republican
Party to the center, much the way Bill Clinton pulled the
Democratic Party away from the left in 1992? Or was it a narrower
political calculation designed to fit a new suit around the
conservative policies that Republicans have been advocating in
Washington in recent years, if not quite so kindly and gently as
Bush did last week.
</P>
<P>
   The phrase ``compassionate conservative'' has been the subject
of much discussion (and some confusion) in recent days, as
Republican leaders, watching Bush seek to dominate the presidential
field, consider exactly what it means, and how it applies to this
race. Is there, for example, a compassionate conservative view on
gun control or abortion rights or gay rights or China policy?
</P>
<P>
   In general, the Republicans acknowledge they aren't sure. But
that hasn't inhibited a lively and sometimes cranky debate within
the party over the meaning of compassion and the nature of
conservatism, a debate that reflects larger conflicts over who the
Republicans are and what they should stand for.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest with you, I can't give you a straight answer on
it,'' said California Republican Party chairman John McGraw when
asked his definition of compassionate conservatism. ``I've been
conservative my whole life, and I think I've been compassionate,
too. I just never hooked the two words together.''
</P>
<P>
   To some extent, the confusion was by design: It is not in the
interest of Bush, the front-runner by acclamation, to take too many
positions on too many issues. Compassionate conservatism can mean
different things to different people, depending on which word the
listener chooses to emphasize.
</P>
<P>
   As a result there appear to be as many interpretations as there
are factions in the Republican Party _ some intended to define what
Bush means before he gets around to it, others using it to
discredit the ideological credentials of the candidate most
Republicans view as the party's likely nominee.
</P>
<P>
   ``If George Bush talks more about teaching reading rather than
abolishing the Department of Education, that's the language of
compassionate conservatism,'' Nelson Warfield, the conservative
Republican who served as press secretary to Bob Dole's 1996
presidential campaign, said approvingly. ``That's more relevant to
voters than flaming rhetoric about burning down the government.''
</P>
<P>
   New York Gov. George Pataki applauded the slogan as a cogent
summary of Republican policies that had been unfairly criticized.
``The compassionate conservatism that Governor Bush speaks about is
exactly right and precisely what we are trying to do,'' he said.
``Our policies, our conservative policies, result, in fact, in
better lives, and recognize true compassion for people who are
striving for a better lives.''
</P>
<P>
   But former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander, a Bush rival, faulted
Bush for political gimmickry, describing the phrase as a sign of
disrespect for the party's conservative base. ``I don't know what
it means,'' Alexander said. ``I don't think anyone else does
either. I think it's a carefully tested way to confuse the voters
so they won't know what we stand for.''
</P>
<P>
   The slogan, agreed William Kristol, the editor of the
conservative Weekly Standard, is little more than ``a way of
distinguishing himself from the congressional conservatives.'' He
added, ``The opposite of compassionate conservative is angry white
male.''
</P>
<P>
   The variety of these responses suggests that Bush may have
created (or more precisely, adopted; the phrase has been around for
at least 15 years) one of those political slogans that is useful
because people can read into it whatever they want. If that is
true, it is evidence of the keen skills that Bush has brought to
this campaign; compassionate conservative is certainly more
memorable than the call for ``practical idealism'' offered by Vice
President Al Gore last week in announcing his own bid for the
Democratic presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   That said, the phrase, combined with Bush's promise to present
the details of his platform ``on my own timetable,'' would seem to
invite voters, along with Republican leaders, to fill in the
blanks, investing Bush with their own values and views.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bush has offered a few hints of what compassionate conservatism
means to him. On taxes, for example, Bush said in his announcement
that he would propose changes to help families living on the edge
of poverty. By contrast, most Republicans tend to rely on cuts for
upper-income taxpayers to boost prosperity for all. ``It is
conservative to cut taxes,'' Bush said. ``It is compassionate to
help people save and give and build.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than simply impose stringent welfare reduction policies,
Bush said, he would propose ways to permit private charities to
help welfare recipients find their way. ``It is conservative to
reform welfare by insisting on work,'' Bush said. ``It is
compassionate to take the side of charities and churches that
confront the suffering which remains.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, demanding standards in public education _ such as
barring promotions of students who perform poorly _ would be
matched with programs to help children who might otherwise be left
behind. ``It is conservative to insist on education standards,
basics and local control,'' Bush said. ``It is compassionate to
make sure that not one single child gets left behind.'' Details are
left to future speeches.
</P>
<P>
   Bush might have been restrained in defining the term; other
Republicans were not, though, suggesting one of the risks Bush
faces in throwing out such a broad conceptual framework. ``I also
think it's compassionate to advocate campaign finance reform to
reduce the influence of special interests,'' said Sen. John McCain,
R-Ariz., the contender who has put himself at odds with many
Republicans by embracing tighter restrictions on contributions and
spending.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of abortion rights have also been quick to apply
Bush's formulation to their cause, notwithstanding the fact that
the governor of Texas, who is generally against abortion rights,
wants to avoid what he views as a no-win topic during this
campaign, his aides said. ``If compassionate conservatism means
anything, it has to mean, `Do anything we can to stop the loss of
1.5 million unborn children every year,''' said Gary Bauer, a
candidate favored by religious conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Murphy, one of the conservative Republicans who describes
Bush's slogan as ``slick marketing,'' sarcastically suggested that
there should be a compassionate conservative position on gun
control _ though he said he would not try to formulate it until
someone told him ``what the uncompassionate conservative position
is.'' (Bush said that he supports the right of citizens to bear
arms.)
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, Bush's course is reminiscent of the one Clinton
and the centrist Democratic Leadership Council, a group of moderate
Democrats, took in anticipation of the 1992 election.
</P>
<P>
   But the comparison only goes so far. Clinton was elected after
making a specific series of proposals that directly assaulted basic
Democratic positions: He advocated federal spending cuts, free
trade and anti-crime measures. Bush has yet to say anything that
might anger conservative voters, and there is no indication that he
feels any need to.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they haven't done yet is they haven't gone through the
agony and the tough, hard work that we did to really shape a
different agenda,'' said Al From, the executive director of the
Democratic Leadership Council.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it would seem that Bush has decided that the only thing
he needs is to ``put a smiling face on conservatism again,'' in the
words of Ralph Reed, the conservative consultant, and leave it to
others to figure out precisely what he means.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
