</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROYAL-WEDDING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A ROYAL PRINCE TAKES A COMMONER BRIDE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By WARREN HOGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINDSOR, England _ It is the marriage of a prince who prefers to
be called ``mister'' to a suburban girl turned downtown publicist
who brings a commoner's touch to the starchy British monarchy.
</P>
<P>
   This ancient castle town was the setting Saturday for the
wedding of Prince Edward, 35, the youngest child of Queen Elizabeth
and the last to wed, to Sophie Rhys-Jones, 34, the daughter of a
tire salesman from the village of Brenchley, Kent, and head of the
R-JH public relations firm in London.
</P>
<P>
   At their engagement in January, the couple had said they hoped
to have a low-key, family wedding, and Saturday's ceremony was that
only in contrast to the pageant-filled, high-profile marriages of
Prince' Edward's three royal siblings. It may have been the very
contrast he was seeking since his sister, Princess Anne, and two
brothers, Princes Charles and Andrew, all saw their grandly-feted
marriages end in divorce.
</P>
<P>
   In a television interview Friday night, Prince Edward said that
his love for his fiancee was ``the most important thing of all,''
and commentators promptly compared it to Prince Charles' dismissive
``whatever love is'' response after his engagement to Diana.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rhys-Jones decided she wanted the word ``obey'' included in
her vow ``to love, honor and obey,'' a stance that brought her some
critical comment but also served to set her off from Diana, who
insisted on dropping the word from her wedding. Ms. Rhys-Jones has
let it be known that, while she understands the comparisons her
passing resemblance to Diana prompts, she does not want to
encourage them.
</P>
<P>
   The couple chose Windsor, the weekend home of the queen, over
the more majestic Westminster Abbey and St. Paul's Cathedral in the
capital, sites of the other royal family weddings. They scheduled
the ceremony for the evening and said the dress code for women
would exclude the long ballroom dresses and hats that are standard
gear at royal events.
</P>
<P>
   The only military participating were the musicians of the Royal
Marine Band. The service was the standard marriage rite from the
Book of Common Prayer with the traditional three hymns and three
anthems.
</P>
<P>
   Their open carriage ride after the ceremony will be not along
the mall leading from Buckingham Palace but around the streets of
Windsor and through the castle grounds where 8,000 people, almost
all of them residents of this town 30 miles from London, have been
invited.
</P>
<P>
   The guest list of 550 to the wedding itself inside St. George's
Chapel included no politicians, only a handful of members from
Europe's other royal houses were invited, along with the few
celebrities the couple knows, like Andrew Lloyd Webber, who gave
the prince his first job with his theater production company.
</P>
<P>
   The Royal Mail stamp that has been issued to commemorate the day
appears to celebrate their informality, showing them both in
profile, dressed in matching turtle neck shirts.
</P>
<P>
   In an apparent plea that they be let alone, Andrew Motion, the
new poet laureate composing his first official verse, produced a
three stanza poem ending with a series of vows including the hope
``for privacy and what its secrets show.''
</P>
<P>
   In perhaps their most overt lunge at normality, the couple
decided that the reception dinner in the soaring 180-foot-long St.
George's Hall with its heraldic flags of the knights of the Order
of the Garter and its ornamental Gothic hammer-beam ceiling would
be beef stroganoff, served buffet style.
</P>
<P>
   Edward, who is seventh in line for the throne and the first
member of his family to hold down a nongovernment job, prefers to
be known as Edward Windsor in his role as co-owner of Ardent
Productions, a film company.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday he got two more titles from his mother that he can ask
people not to use when addressing him at work _ the Earl of Wessex
and Viscount Severn. Ms. Rhys-Jones becomes Her Royal Highness the
Countess of Wessex, sparing her the impersonal title of Princess
Edward that she would have assumed had the Queen not acted.
</P>
<P>
   Much as the young couple would like their union to be considered
just another June wedding, there were some striking differences.
</P>
<P>
   Their first home as newlyweds is the $16 million, 88-acre
Bagshot Park in Surrey, where 60 workmen have been laboring in
recent weeks to have the premises ready for them. Their gift
registry, with Thomas Goode of Mayfair, included matching $16,000
water and milk pitchers, a $14,000 silver teapot, a $10,000 sugar
sifter, a $5,000 hallmarked tea strainer and a 26-piece fine bone
china coffee and tea service for $22,000.
</P>
<P>
   Friends of Prince Edward say he had hoped to play down the
public nature of his marriage but did not anticipate the amount of
interest that there would be in a royal wedding. The BBC is
televising the event worldwide and says it expects an audience of
more than 20 million. Souvenir stores plates and mugs and postcards
with pictures of the couple, and a Regent Street shop announced
Saturday that it would have a copy of Ms. Rhys-Jones' wedding dress
designed over the weekend and in its showroom window by Monday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   In a pre-wedding interview with the BBC, Prince Edward was asked
if he feared for his own marriage, given the experiences of his
brothers and sister. Princess Anne, who divorced Capt. Mark
Phillips after 19 years of marriage in 1992, has since been married
again, to a former naval officer, Timothy Laurence.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't think about it,'' Prince Edward said. ``Anybody who
presumably decides to get married is doing it for the very best
intentions. They are going in there because they hope it is going
to last.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rhys-Jones is older than either Diana Spencer or Sarah
Ferguson were when they married into the Royal Family, and she has
had the advantage of acclimatizing herself to their famously cool
ways during the six years she has been Edward's steady companion.
</P>
<P>
   When The Sun published a decade-old picture of her with her
breast exposed on May 26, Buckingham Palace vigorously came to her
defense, attacking the tabloid paper for ``premeditated cruelty''
and successfully demanding a published apology.
</P>
<P>
   She should not present the kind of challenge that other spouses
have to the courtiers and the senior members of ``The Firm,'' as
the Windsors are known to call themselves. Asked how she saw her
future, she told a television interviewer: ``I certainly see it
more in a supporting role to Edward rather than rushing off and
forging my own path, going off and taking on the mantle of various
charities. We are very busy as it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Showing her practiced hand at public relations, she added: ``I
also think there is the queen and the rest of the royal family
doing an exceptionally wonderful job in a public role. I don't see
a massive need for me to go out there and do the same thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
