<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRONTPAGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(HLW)
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories that New York Times editors are planning
for the Page 1 of Sunday, June 20. The N.Y. Times News Service
supervisor is Henry Louis Warnken.
</P>
<P>
   For copy info: (212) 556-1927.
</P>
<P>
   For graphics, map, photo info: (212) 556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TOP: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Lead story: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Pristina) _ With the last Yugoslav forces streaming
out of Kosovo ahead of schedule, NATO commanders here have reached
a tentative agreement with Albanian rebel leaders to gradually
disband the Kosovo Liberation Army as an organized military force,
NATO officials said Saturday. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   1-column hed.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move this story by 3 p.m. ET in `i' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SUMMIT-RDP (Cologne) _ The European Union on Saturday
announced plans to provide $1.5 billion over the next three years
for the reconstruction of Kosovo as the West tried to map out a
strategy that would channel money to the war-devastated area
without giving financial support to Slobodan Milosevic's Serbia. By
Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   1-column hed.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move this story by 2 p.m. ET in `a' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Top center: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ARABS-CHASTITY (Resaifah, Jordan) _ More than pride, more than
honesty, more than anything a man might do, female chastity is seen
in the Arab world as an indelible line, the boundary between
respect and shame. An unchaste woman, it is sometimes said, is
worse than a murderer, affecting not just one victim, but her
family and her tribe. It is an unforgiving logic, and its product,
for centuries, has been murder _ the killings of girls and women by
their relatives, to cleanse honor that has been soiled. Across the
Arab world, in Jordan, Egypt, Syria, Lebanon, Yemen, the
Palestinian territories and among Israeli Arabs, a new generation
of activists has now quietly begun to battle these honor killings,
an enduring wave of crimes prompted by sexual conduct that is
sometimes only imagined. By Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   3-column hed.
</P>
<P>
   2-column photo with story.
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved; `i' category.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Off-lead: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GUN-CONTROL-POLITICS (Washington) _ Democrats are moving to
capitalize immediately on the failure of the Republican-controlled
House to pass even modest gun-control legislation, and promising to
take the issue to the forefront of the 2000 presidential campaign.
By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   1-column hed.
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved; `w' category.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FOLD: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SPEECHES-POLITICS (Washington) _ To judge from the speeches
announcing their candidacies for president, Vice President Gore and
Gov. George W. Bush could be declaring the primary campaign over,
the general election begun and the battleground designated as the
moderate middle, with ideological extremes out of bounds. Yet even
though they did not engage over detail, Gore and Bush were fighting
over much of the same ground. Both opposed drugs in schools. Both
promised to involve religious organizations in social welfare
programs. Both supported foreign trade. By Adam Clymer.
</P>
<P>
   3-column hed.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move this story by 3 p.m. ET in `w' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BOTTOM: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SONOFSAM-MEMORIES (New York) _ David Berkowitz, the serial
killer known as the Son of Sam, wept in prison last week, grieving
over the coming release of a Spike Lee movie called ``Summer of
Sam.'' Although Walt Disney's Touchstone Pictures will not release
the movie until the first week of July, ``Summer of Sam'' is
already jarring loose memories _ some of them extraordinarily
painful _ inside the circle of New Yorkers whose lives were
fundamentally changed by the Son of Sam case.
</P>
<P>
