<DOCNO> NYT19990619.0111 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-19 13:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1978 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-SUMMIT-RDP-785     06-19 1239
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-SUMMIT-RDP-785&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EUROPEAN UNION TO PROVIDE $1.5 BILLION FOR KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLOGNE, Germany _ The European Union on Saturday announced
plans to provide $1.5 billion over the next three years for the
reconstruction of Kosovo, as the West tried to map a strategy that
would channel money to the war-devastated area without giving
financial support to Slobodan Milosevic's Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   Guenter Burghardt, the director-general for Europe's Balkan
policy, said the 15-nation bloc would provide $500 million annually
over three years to Kosovo ``irrespective of whether Milosevic is
there or not.'' But he added that the Yugoslav president, who was
indicted by the international war crimes tribunal last month, was
``a cancer'' that had to be isolated.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to get rid of the source of the cancer that has been
spreading throughout the region over the past eight years,''
Burghardt said. ``That means we have to isolate Mr. Milosevic and
put democratic institutions in his place.''
</P>
<P>
   The European Union announced the aid on the second day of a
summit meeting of major countries that was on Saturday devoted
largely to Kosovo and possible financial support for the
debt-ridden Russian economy. Russia's prime minister, Sergei
Stepashin, is also attending the talks, and President Boris Yeltsin
is expected to arrive Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   A senior Clinton administration official pointedly avoided
Burghardt's forceful language on Milosevic, saying only, ``We
believe that a fully open and democratic process could easily have
a different result in terms of the kind of government we would see
in Serbia.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that he was ``not aware that there was specific
discussion about Milosevic remaining in power.''
</P>
<P>
   It was clear, however, that a sea change has occurred since the
1995 Dayton peace for Bosnia, reached with Milosevic's help. While
Serbian war crimes in Bosnia and Kosovo have scarcely differed,
NATO's ability to get to the scene of the crimes within weeks in
Kosovo has brought a decisively new level of outrage against the
Serbian leader.
</P>
<P>
   The exact direction of policy toward Milosevic still appeared
unclear Saturday as Western leaders reviewed the options. A plan of
aggressive financial aid for Kosovo, while largely isolating the
rest of Serbia as long as he remains in power, presents several
difficulties, Western officials said.
</P>
<P>
   These include the fact that Kosovo formally remains part of
Serbia, that it has no independent financial institutions capable
of negotiating for loans, that its long border with the rest of
Serbia is likely to be porous, and that it cannot indefinitely
survive on aid alone in what now amounts to an institutional limbo.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem is that the United States said Saturday that it
is ready to give a measure of emergency humanitarian aid to other
parts of Serbia. But the distinction between this and the kind of
support for reconstruction and development that Washington wants to
avoid as long as Milosevic is in power could easily become murky.
</P>
<P>
   It may also prove extremely difficult to help Montenegro, the
other surviving republic in today's truncated Yugoslavia, while
avoiding support for Milosevic. The West has indicated it wants to
accentuate the isolation of the Serbian leader by supporting
Montenegro's democratically inclined government.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether Stepashin had objected to the plans to isolate
Serbia from international aid for reconstruction, the senior
administration official said he did not know. But French officials
said the Russian prime minister, who took office last month, had
argued forcefully for extensive aid to Serbia, saying that the
conduct of Milosevic could not be allowed to prejudice millions of
Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's broad support for its traditional Orthodox Christian
Serbian allies has been strong, but tempered by the fact that
Yeltsin has no personal affection for Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Burghardt said that the European Union had decided to set up a
special agency to deal with aid for the Balkans and that a special
international donors' conference for Kosovo would be convened in
July, probably in the first half of the month. The countries
meeting in Cologne will play a central role in this conference.
</P>
<P>
   It will be devoted to emergency assistance _ essentially the
provision of shelter, medicine and food before the winter sets in.
Later in the year, a further conference will be held on the basis
of a detailed assessment of Kosovo's needs.
</P>
<P>
   Joly Dixon, a senior European Union financial official, said
Western financial support would be concentrated on Kosovo in a
first stage, to be followed by other countries affected by the war
and finally the Balkan region as a whole. The European Union has
already begun intensive consultations with the World Bank.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Clinton administration official said teams from the United
States were already in Kosovo assessing needs for the first
conference in July. Between July and the fall, he added, there
would be ``a more intensive effort involving the World Bank, the
European Union and others.''
</P>
<P>
   How much the United States will spend on Kosovo reconstruction
remains unclear, although Europe has indicated it will bear most of
the burden. In Bosnia, over $5 billion was pledged over four years,
with Europe paying more than half. But actual payments proved slow,
complicating and holding back reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
   It was clear in the leaders' discussions on Saturday that for
the first time since the wars of Yugoslavia's destruction began
eight years ago, the West has decided to approach the crisis in the
Balkans in a broad way, providing massive assistance to the region
in the hope of integrating the states there with one another and
with the rest of Europe.
</P>
<P>
   After a long period of hesitation, the specific prospect of
membership of the European Union has been held out to Croatia,
Bosnia, Macedonia, Albania and Yugoslavia itself, providing that
democracy and a market economy are convincingly installed.
</P>
<P>
   A Stability Pact for South Eastern Europe, agreed on earlier
this month by European Union leaders, said peace in the area
depended on ``democratic principles and values'' being firmly in
place.
</P>
<P>
   But how stability can be reached while Kosovo's status and
future remain so vague was an issue that none of the Western powers
appeared inclined to address on Saturday. In effect, the West has
decided to help the province as if it were independent, while
adhering to a policy that says such independence will not be
granted.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders devoted some of their time on Saturday to the
question of who should occupy the pivotal top civilian post in
Kosovo, without making a decision.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration official said the person had to be
someone who was a ``very strong leader who has management skills,
communication skills, the ability to deal with difficult political
challenges.''
</P>
<P>
   In effect, the official, to be known as the special
representative of the U.N. secretary-general, will be a kind of
proconsul in a province marked by an extraordinary administrative
void.
</P>
<P>
   Among the tasks facing the administrator will be coordination
and channeling of the various forms of assistance now being offered
by the West, and the delicate management of any relations with
Belgrade.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
