<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-19 13:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1979 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-BARAK-NYT &LR;      06-19 1233
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-BARAK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UPBEAT ISRAELI LEADER HAS U.S. GUESSING  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By SERGE SCHMEMANN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ His coalition almost complete, Ehud Barak, Israel's
prime minister-elect, is expected to come to Washington early next
month to unveil his keenly awaited thoughts on reviving peacemaking
in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   It is a harbinger of the style Barak brings to his new job that
he has declined to discuss his intentions with any American
official since the election _ not Dennis Ross, the seasoned
American mediator, not even the American ambassador in Tel Aviv. He
has asked that his first meeting be a long and private one with
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The delay, the directness and the air of mystery still
surrounding a leader who has spent far more of his life in the
secretive discipline of warfare than in the rowdy universe of
Israeli politics, have created a whirl of speculation and
anticipation.
</P>
<P>
   In the Clinton administration _ which has not concealed its
satisfaction with the demise of the outgoing prime minister,
Benjamin Netanyahu _ Barak is perceived as a virtual reincarnation
of Yitzhak Rabin, as a warrior-turned-peacemaker who will put
Rabin's peace effort back on the heady track it was on before
Netanyahu was elected three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe that I will have to take any steps to revive
the peace process,'' Clinton confidently declared this week in
Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Ross described Barak as a leader who ``intends to get the
country going.'' Speaking Thursday at a conference of the
Washington Institute for Near East Policy, Ross left little
question that it was Netanyahu he blamed for the stagnation of the
past three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did not have the kind of mutual confidence and trust that
we had before,'' he said. ``I am confident that we will restore
that relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   But at that same conference, Israeli hawks could be heard
pointing out that Barak's campaign statements on the Palestinians
were not so different from Netanyahu's, while a respected
Palestinian analyst, Mahdi F. Abdul Hadi, said many Palestinians
were apprehensive that Barak was coming to office as a former
general with an immediate surrounding of other former generals.
Rabin, he noted, had the dovish Shimon Peres at his side.
</P>
<P>
   However, Barak's policies take shape, analysts are virtually
unanimous in their conviction that he will be a leader
qualitatively different from Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barak has a different point of departure from Bibi,'' said a
senior American official, using Netanyahu's nickname. ``Bibi saw
enemies everywhere. He saw any meeting with us or the Palestinians
as a threat that he had to manage. He presumed the worst would
happen. Barak won't be like that. He knows Israel is strong.''
</P>
<P>
   He and other officials described Barak as a brilliant and
methodical planner who thought big but kept his cards close to his
chest. ``He's talking big bucks, big treaties, big concessions,''
said an analyst for a major Jewish lobbying group. ``Barak is
coming into this as a big-type guy. He's a genius, he disassembles
clocks for a hobby, he's a concert pianist, a meticulous planner.
He analyzes every aspect of a situation. He's not a dove; he's a
doer.''
</P>
<P>
   Above all, they said, he was a man who would carry out what he
pledged to do, in contrast to Netanyahu, whose intentions
invariably became mired in wrangles with his unwieldy coalition.
That alone, American officials argued, would help restore some of
the mutual trust that collapsed under Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that he has avoided meeting with Americans since the
election, officials said, demonstrated his determination to end the
situation under Netanyahu, in which the Americans moved from being
mediators to direct negotiators, severing any direct contact
between Israelis and Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Already, American officials noted, Barak has shown a readiness
to communicate with Arafat. ``The way to re-establish relations is
to talk,'' one official said. ``Engagement counts for a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Setting aside his intentions and style, analysts have identified
several advantages and disadvantages Barak will face in resuming
the negotiating process.
</P>
<P>
   His strongest suit is his landslide victory in the election, and
the fact that he will have a coalition that controls at least
two-thirds of the seats in the Parliament. He will also have the
support of an Israeli public far more supportive, as election
results demonstrated, of swapping land for peace than it was three
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Among the obstacles, one may be his own priorities. In his
election campaign, Barak pledged that he would make peace with
Syria, with a withdrawal in the Golan Heights, and would withdraw
Israeli troops from their self-proclaimed buffer zone in southern
Lebanon within a year.
</P>
<P>
   But it is the experience of Middle East peacemaking that Israel
cannot proceed on two fronts at once, and the question is whether
Barak will become focused on the more dramatic goal of concluding
peace with the last of Israel's neighbors still holding out, to the
detriment of the far more tangled Palestinian track.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a real fear among the Palestinian people that you
will have a peace treaty with Syria, but we will still be
nowhere,'' said Abdul Hadi. ``We are the small fish in the region.
But if it cannot swim, it will bite.''
</P>
<P>
   Another obstacle is that if Barak does pick up the Oslo process,
he will do so at a point where all the choices are brutally
difficult. The process was designed to create momentum and mutual
trust by resolving the easier issues first, and leaving the
difficult ones for the end _ the status of Jerusalem, the plight of
refugees, the fate of Jewish settlements, control over water.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under Oslo, the can was supposed to be kicked down the road,''
said David Makovsky, political writer for the Israeli daily
Haaretz. ``Well, now the can is down the road.''
</P>
<P>
   Right from the start, Barak will have to confront the spate of
settlements that right-wingers have launched in the West Bank, with
the blessing of Netanyahu, in anticipation of a change of
government. How he deals with these will have a major impact on his
standing with Palestinians, Americans and West Europeans.
</P>
<P>
   In general, the closer Israel approaches ``final status'' talks
with the Palestinians, the greater the gap. Though Barak has a far
greater consensus among his people than any of his predecessors, it
is still far from the expectations of the Palestinians, who still
anticipate getting a sovereign state in much of the West Bank and
Gaza with East Jerusalem as its capital.
</P>
<P>
   Barak will also face a Palestinian leader who is aging and
ailing. Should Arafat die, officials said, it would be a long time
before a leader took charge who would have anywhere near Arafat's
stature or control. ``We don't have very much time,'' Abdul Hadi
said. ``We cannot bring in a new leader in 24 hours.''
</P>
<P>
   But Barak will have one advantage. Under Netanyahu, Arafat
garnered considerable sympathy in Washington and Europe as the
maligned underdog, and the Americans often interceded for him in
Jerusalem. Now, should Arafat not like what Barak is offering, he
is not likely to be given a sympathetic ear, at least not so long
as talks are under way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to say we don't trust him,'' Abdul Hadi said, ``but we
would like very much to test him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
