<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-19 13:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1980 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-ALBANIANS-ART-     06-19 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ALBANIANS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A KOSOVO TOWN RETURNS TO LIFE WITH ALBANIANS ALONE
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By IAN FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRIZREN, Yugoslavia _ It is nearly impossible to find a Serb
here anymore, a state of affairs that is novel for the Albanians
and which the better side of Naim Spahiu, a 30-year-old driver,
said was not good for Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should stay here,'' Spahiu, an Albanian Kosovar, said
Saturday as he walked past Prizren's main mosque, filling with
worshipers. ``We've always lived together.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the next breath, all the anger and resentment felt on
both sides of the ethnic divide of Kosovo spilled out.
</P>
<P>
   ``They took our money,'' he said. ``They killed us. We couldn't
go anywhere freely. I'm a driver and I used to travel to Pristina.
You can drive there in an hour. But it would take me two or three
hours because I always got stopped by the police. They never
stopped the Serbs.''
</P>
<P>
   This lovely city in southern Kosovo, dotted with mosques and
churches alike, has been reborn in the last week under the watchful
eye of NATO peacekeeping troops. Stores are opening. The oldest
barbershop is back to normal hours. But Prizren has come alive
again without the city's perhaps 10,000 Serbs, most of whom have
fled north over the last week.
</P>
<P>
   While it is still possible to find a few people who believe in a
multiethnic Kosovo, most Albanians here seem frankly just as happy
to see the Serbs gone. Their anger underscores not only the
sufferings of the recent war but longstanding distrust between the
two groups, which foxy politicians, like the Serbian president,
Slobodan Milosevic, have been able to exploit.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs have long regarded themselves as the wall between
Christianity and Islam, and regarded the Albanians, many of whom
converted to Islam under the rule of the Ottoman Empire, as
traitors. The Albanians, with varying degrees of freedom under
different regimes, have regarded the Serbs as brutal oppressors.
Each side has inflicted horrors, the Serbs after the breakup of the
Ottoman Empire and the Albanians during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   ``This city seems like the kingdom of death,'' the Roman
Catholic archbishop of Skopje wrote about Prizren in 1913 when the
Ottoman Empire collapsed and Serbs massacred Albanians. ``They
knock on the doors of Albanian houses, take away the men and shoot
them immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As for plunder, looting and rape, all that goes without
saying,'' he continued. ``Henceforth the order of the day is:
Everything is permitted against the Albanians _ not merely
permitted but willed and commended.''
</P>
<P>
   But most people here _ Serbs and Albanians alike _ said that for
the most part ordinary people have largely gotten along. After
Milosevic came to power in 1989, though, stripping many Albanian
Kosovars of their jobs and their rights, the relationship changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all politics,'' said Dragica Spasic, 53, one of perhaps a
dozen Serbs who are left in the hillside neighborhood of Podkalaja.
``Milosevic did all this. Now the Serbs have all left. They went to
Serbia and they are all going to kill Milosevic.'' She is leaving
too, to be with her husband and children in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all lived here,'' said Leposava Sekulic, 74, a Serbian
woman who lives down the hill a few houses. ``We all worked here. I
have so much pity for the Albanians. We can't live without them.''
</P>
<P>
   But the distrust remains: As Mrs. Sekulic spoke, she and a few
others noticed three young men, apparently Albanians, and commented
that they might have come up the hillside to loot. It was certainly
possible: Houses around the neighborhood, several marked with
funeral notices for the Serbs who died in the war, have clearly
been ransacked.
</P>
<P>
   It is also true that Serbian forces looted Albanian homes, in a
pattern of atrocities against Albanians that is evident around
Kosovo. To have the Serbs gone, said Salajdim Ashikferki, 67, owner
of a barbershop that has been open since 1939, is simply
``better.''
</P>
<P>
   ``After 2 in the afternoon, there was nobody here, only the
police,'' he said Saturday between shaves at 60 cents apiece.
``They set fire to the houses. They stole.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not so good'' that all the Serbs are gone, he said. ``But
after what they did, it's better that they leave.''
</P>
<P>
   Another barber in the shop, Abdxlhadi Gjinali, 65, said he had
sympathy for ordinary Serbs, but not much.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all politics,'' he said. ``The politicians destroyed it
all. But almost all the Serbs listened to their politicians.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside, on the main square, Arlinda Mustafa, 23, said she hoped
that a Kosovo largely without Serbs would mean a new start for
Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother hasn't worked for 10 years,'' she said. ``Now that
they have left, we can go back to work, back to school. We
Albanians are hard-working. Now we can go back to work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
