<DOCNO> NYT19990619.0116 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-19 13:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1986 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-RUSSIA-2T     06-19 1016
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-RUSSIA-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNCERTAINTY PERSISTS IN U.S.-MOSCOW RELATIONSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLOGNE, Germany _ When the Clinton administration invited
Russia to help it out of the war in Kosovo, the idea was that the
involvement in big-game diplomacy would help maintain
Washington-Moscow ties, and even improve the ailing relationship.
</P>
<P>
   But now, as President Boris Yeltsin of Russia is about to make
his first foreign trip in four months on Sunday and to meet here
with President Clinton, as many _ if not more _ questions are
hanging over the dialogue as were before the war.
</P>
<P>
   The national security adviser, Sandy Berger, said here on Friday
that relations with Russia had been ``strained'' by NATO's
airstrikes against Yugoslavia but now were ``reinforced'' by
Russia's participation in the peace settlement.
</P>
<P>
   But as Berger left a briefing room after making those remarks,
he pretended not to hear a question about the likelihood of
Yeltsin's actually turning up in Cologne. The last time the Russian
leader was abroad, for the funeral of King Hussein of Jordan in
February, he cut his stay in Amman to about an hour, apparently
because of illness. ``No, I didn't hear it,'' Berger said of the
query.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, by declining to answer, Berger appeared to
summarize the uncertainties of the Washington-Moscow relationship,
which was most recently buffeted by three days of intense arguments
in Helsinki, Finland, over where and how Russian troops should
operate in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution of the Russian troop issue on Friday night was a
relief for the administration. But it remains to be seen how the
plan for the dispersal of Russian troops in Kosovo will be accepted
in Moscow, where politicians and the public alike felt humiliated
by the NATO airstrikes and where the Kosovo peace settlement
orchestrated by Victor Chernomyrdin was assailed as a sellout.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's foreign minister, Igor Ivanov, said at the signing
ceremony in Helsinki that the agreement on the troops would benefit
overall American-Russian relations. But the dispatch of Russian
troops from Bosnia to the Pristina airport in the dead of night
exactly a week earlier _ apparently without Ivanov's knowledge _
showed that the foreign minister does not always speak for all the
Russian government.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the Russians won concessions in the way their forces
will interact with NATO in Kosovo, including 16 Russian liaison
officers in the field and a Russian as commander of the Pristina
airport. A senior administration official said Saturday that the
agreement gave ``more broadly national Russian control'' over the
Russian troops than in Bosnia, where Russian forces also serve with
NATO. If broad disagreements develop beyond day-to-day tactics, the
Russians can dissent, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   The Helsinki agreement states that ``all command arrangements
will preserve the principle of unity of command.'' But unlike the
arrangement in Bosnia, the paragraph in the Helsinki accord on
unity of command adds: ``This presumes that the Russian side
exercises full political and military control over the Russian
contingent.''
</P>
<P>
   The administration was eager to have the peacekeeping dispute
resolved before Yeltsin's arrival here at the conference of the
seven major industrialized nations and Russia, thus giving what one
senior administration official described as a ``reasonable prospect
of getting the core parts of the relationship back on track.''
</P>
<P>
   But one inescapable issue for Washington is the flagging health
of Yeltsin, in whom the administration has vested much. Asked
several weeks ago whether Yeltsin would make it to the meeting in
Cologne, a Russian diplomat deadpanned: ``He's transportable.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision-making process in Russia, never crystal clear, has
also become even murkier of late.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are deep questions in Russia, now penetrating the
administration, about Yeltsin's mental as well as physical
health,'' said Thomas Graham, a senior associate at the Carnegie
Endowment for International Peace and a former American diplomat
who served in Moscow until 10 months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is more unreliable and erratic than he was three or four
months ago. There are a lot of doubts about whether he can make the
flight and then function effectively for three to four hours.''
</P>
<P>
   Assuming that Yeltsin does arrive in Cologne, administration
officials say they will be dealing with a leader whose attitude
toward the West is now pressed by increased anti-Western feelings
at home.
</P>
<P>
   A stark example of the anti-NATO sentiment from usually
pro-Western quarters came from Boris Fyodorov, the former chief of
the Federal Tax Service. Fyodorov, who helped organize a petition
to stop NATO's bombing of Yugoslavia, said of the alliance:
``Nobody can assume the role of a policeman to the universe, to
murder people in the name of human rights.''
</P>
<P>
   For reformist Russian politicians who favored Russia's becoming
a member of the Joint Permanent Council, an adjunct to NATO where
Russia is consulted on NATO issues, the war in Kosovo has been a
souring experience. Their argument for Russian participation in the
Permanent Council was based on the notion that NATO was a
defensive, not an offensive, alliance. ``Those Russians feel
burned,'' a senior administration official said.
</P>
<P>
   To try to re-energize the relationship with Moscow, Clinton met
Saturday afternoon with the new Russian prime minister, Sergei
Stepashin. Before doing so, in keeping with the administration's
disposition to lavish praise on new Russian leaders who may be open
to Washington, Clinton said through an aide that he was ``extremely
impressed'' by the prime minister. The two were to meet with other
leaders at dinner Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   With Yeltsin, Clinton plans to raise a longstanding menu of
standard issues, officials said. These are arms control, economic
reforms and nonproliferation, in particular what Washington argues
is Moscow's continued transfer of sensitive nuclear technology to
Iran.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   On arms control, Washington will continue to press for the
passage of the START II treaty and will explain again the rationale
for Clinton's announcement in the State of Union address that the
United States would pursue a national missile defense system.
Moscow has objected to Clinton's proposal on the ground that it
would violate the Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are difficult issues arising at a bad time in
American-Russian relations,'' Graham said of arms control. ``Russia
needs to do it for financial reasons, but Russia can't for domestic
reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   On economic progress in Russia, the picture is not so bleak,
administration officials said. Stepashin is moving on bank
restructuring, a key demand of the International Monetary Fund.
``There is a sense that Russia has played, overall, a constructive
role,'' one official said. ``People are going to want to be
forward-leaning and helpful, but in a responsible way.''
</P>
<P>
   In essence, this means that the IMF will probably be prepared to
release the first installment of a $4.5 billion loan next month,
the official said. The managing director of the fund, Michel
Camdessus, praised Russia last week for improved tax collections, a
slowing of inflation and an increase in business activity.
</P>
<P>
   If the first installment is released, there is a ``common
understanding'' among the seven industrialized nations here, the
official said, that scheduled Russian debt payments of $5.5 billion
should be deferred to the end of next year.
</P>
<P>
   But no decision was reached here about what to do in the longer
term with Russia's total debt of $155 billion, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   As for the continued transfer of nuclear technology, the United
States has placed sanctions on about a dozen institutes in Russia
that the administration contends have been involved in sending
scientists and selling nuclear know-how to Iran. These sanctions
prevent the institutions from doing business with the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   This issue is one of the most difficult, American officials
said, because Washington cannot understand why Moscow would want to
have nearby Iran become a nuclear power.
</P>
<P>
   It is also difficult, administration officials said, to
determine whether the sale of the technology to Iran is government
policy or is yet another example of the breakdown of government
control in Russia that allows economic fiefs left over from the
Communist era to do what they want.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-99 1326EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
