<DOCNO> NYT19990619.0118 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-19 13:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1989 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEST-SCORES-REVIEW-NY     06-19 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEST-SCORES-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW MATH: NO ONE IS BELOW AVERAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Minn., W.Va., Calif., N.Y., Colo., Mass.)   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By ANEMONA HARTOCOLLIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Lake Wobegon, Garrison Keillor's mythical Minnesota
community, the women are strong, the men are good looking and the
children are all above average. But who knew that those children
were pawns of standardized testing?
</P>
<P>
   Twelve years ago, a country doctor in West Virginia, John
Cannell, was treating teen-age patients with self-esteem problems.
Although their school test scores showed them performing above
average, they were depressed about not doing well in class. When
tested on different test, by independent psychologists, the
children scored below average.
</P>
<P>
   Enlisting his staff as detectives, Cannell surveyed school
districts across the country and found that most of them reported
their students scoring above the national average on standardized
tests _ something that any high-school math student would dismiss
as statistically impossible.
</P>
<P>
   Cannell's discovery, nicknamed the Lake Wobegon effect, set off
a furor over standardized testing as researchers confirmed what he
had discovered. Now an increasing number of states are adopting
high-stakes testing as a condition of high school graduation and to
reward or punish schools. Experts warn that the incentive to
massage test results is great, and that parents and children should
beware of the recurrence of Lake Wobegon effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be forgotten, but it is not gone,'' said Robert Linn, a
professor of education at the University of Colorado in Boulder,
who investigated Dr. Cannell's original findings.
</P>
<P>
   There are many ways for scores to be artificially inflated, from
companies marketing old tests to outright cheating. There have even
been treatises on the politics of testing; how changing tests can
lower scores when mayors are elected or school superintendents are
appointed and raise them over the next few years so those in charge
can take the credit.
</P>
<P>
   Take New York City, the nation's biggest school district.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani campaigned for re-election
touting a rise in reading scores of three percentage points, even
as his opponent, Ruth Messinger, scoffed that such a gain was
hardly cause to, as her press secretary put it, break out the
champagne. The mayor was celebrating results showing the school
system, with its high concentration of poor children and
immigrants, could produce results comparable to the national
average.
</P>
<P>
   That blissful picture was shattered recently when the Board of
Education announced the results of new tests, administered in
April. Last year, 49.6 percent of the city's elementary and middle
school students could read as well as the typical American student.
(By definition, 50 percent of all children should be reading better
than the typical student, and 50 percent worse.) This year, the
percentage of children reading at this level dropped suddenly, to
44.6. Math scores dropped 10 points, from well above the typical
level to a shade below.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me guess,'' said Walter Haney, a professor and senior
research associate in the Center for the Study of Testing at Boston
College. ``They changed the test.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, yes, they did.
</P>
<P>
   New York City changed from one major battery of standardized
tests, the California Achievement Test, to another, the
Comprehensive Tests of Basic Skills. The city also updated its
scoring, comparing schoolchildren to a national sample who took the
test in 1996, instead of 1991. The combination of new material and
a higher standard depressed the scores.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Board of Education argued that scores had risen one
percentage point in reading, not dropped, using a method called
equating _ a statistical calculation designed compare old and new
tests.
</P>
<P>
   Most statisticians, though, say equating is deeply flawed and
valid in only the most narrow circumstances. In New York City's
case, the test publisher, CTB/McGraw-Hill, refused to endorse the
equating done by the city's Board of Education.
</P>
<P>
   A national testing program, which President Clinton proposed in
his 1997 State of the Union message, would impose consistent
standards and dampen the Lake Wobegon effect. But many states have
balked, saying that a universal test would intrude on the tradition
of permitting school districts to set their own policy and
curriculum. As a compromise, Congress asked the National Academy of
Sciences to study whether the wide array of state and commercial
tests could be equated to one another _ or to the National
Assessment of Education Progress, which is the closest thing to a
nationwide test.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our conclusion was that it is really not feasible to develop a
common scale for those tests,'' said Dr. Michael Feuer, director of
the board on testing and assessment of the National Academy of
Sciences.
</P>
<P>
   Some equations are simple, Feuer said. Visiting a friend in
Germany, you may learn that the temperature there is 30 degrees
Centigrade and easily convert it to Fahrenheit. But what if you
wanted to convert temperature to rainfall? Reading, like the
weather, is not measured by only one factor. That is the equating
dilemma.
</P>
<P>
   As for New York City, Dr. Daniel Koretz, a senior social
scientist at Rand Education, a research group in Washington,
predicts that the latest results will soon be a distant memory.
Test scores will begin their inevitable rise again, he says, driven
by the growing familiarity of teachers with the test and an
outdated standard of grading.
</P>
<P>
   Cannell is now a forensic psychiatrist living in Los Osos,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a real time-consuming task,'' he said last week of his
crusade to end the manipulation of test scores, ``and one that
brings me enemies, not friends. Politicians, test publishers,
schools, they just have too much to gain by having test scores that
are going up every year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-99 1326EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990619.0119 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-19 13:27 </DATE_TIME>
