</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-FINAL-NYT </SLUG>
  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, June 20, 1999, moved Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE DRESS PAGE:
</P>
<P>
   CONSERVATIVES-REVIEW (Undated) _ The phrase `compassionate
conservative' has been the subject of much discussion (and some
confusion) in recent days, as Republican leaders, watching George
W. Bush seek to dominate the presidential field, consider exactly
it means, and how it applies to this race: is there, for example, a
compassionate conservative view on gun control or abortion rights
or gay rights or even the nation's China policy? By Adam Nagourney.
(`a' category)
</P>
<P>
   BALKANS-REBUILD-REVIEW (Undated) _ NATO's goal of rebuilding the
Balkans is questionable. That is because, barring the sudden
disappearance of Slobodan Milosevic, the West is proposing to
rebuild the area without rebuilding Serbia, the country at the
Balkans' heart. By Alison Smale. (`i' category)
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moved in the `a' category:
</P>
<P>
   TEST-SCORES-REVIEW (Undated) _ There are many ways for scores to
be artificially inflated, from companies marketing old tests to
outright cheating. There have even been treatises on the politics
of testing; how changing tests can lower scores when mayors are
elected or school superintendents are appointed and raise them over
the next few years so those in charge can take the credit. By
Anemona Hartocollis.
</P>
<P>
   SUPERGUN-SUBSIDY-REVIEW (Washington) _ The Pentagon is
subsidizing the civilian market for a long-range, semiautomatic
50-caliber rifle, a military weapon designed to destroy armored
vehicles and aircraft, according to Democrats on a House panel. The
Pentagon sells surplus ammunition at a discount to a West Virginia
company that markets the half-inch-thick bullets to the public via
retailers, some of whom offer the shells for sale on the Internet.
By David Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-DANGERS-REVIEW (Undated) _ For many computer users, the
infectious Explore worm marked the end of trust in the virtual
world. Most people already knew that it was dangerous to trust
strangers in cyberspace, just as it is in the physical world. The
worm, however, masquerading as e-mail from a friend, raised the
specter that it might no longer be possible to trust friends
either. Cyberspace, once thought of as the world's most cozy
community, has quickly become a lonely, infinite expanse where
computer outlaws programs lurk. By John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   CHIP-IMPLANTS-REVIEW (Seattle) _ In a bizarre case that unfolded
in Boston last week, reputed mobster Vincent Marino sued to find
out whether the DEA had secretly implanted him with a microchip
tracking device. But the case may not be as strange as it sounds. A
European company already claims to have implanted at least 45
people with such chips, all either willing adults or children of
millionaires who were worried about the possibility of kidnapping.
By Sam Howe Verhovek.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-VIOLENCE-REVIEW (Undated) _ The defeat in Congress of a
bill making it a felony to expose children to books, movies and
video games that contain explicit sex or violence has not quelled
the debate among public and school libraries. The American Library
Association is tracking complaints from adult readers who are are
scolding librarians for the violence in books like John Steinbeck's
`Of Mice and Men' or Alvin Schwartz's `More Scary Stories to Tell
in the Dark.' By Doreen Carvajal. WITH GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   GREENSPAN-REVIEW (Washington) _ Some Fed watchers say Chairman
Alan Greenspan has been more a pragmatic opportunist than a
watchful waiter, taking clever advantage of special circumstances
like falling oil prices and spikes in productivity. Others say he
was been more lucky than good. By Michael Weinstein.
</P>
<P>
   DC-INTERNS-TEXT-REVIEW (Undated) _ Congress and the White House
have produced handbooks for interns with advice about handling the
difficulties that can arise in Washington. Each was written well
before the need for such guidebooks became glaringly apparent. In
that regard, the manuals seem prescient, even wise, double
entendres notwithstanding.
</P>
<P>
   JOB-INTERVIEWS-TEXT-REVIEW (Undated) _ Job seekers' critical and
sometimes humorous assessments of their corporate recruiters:
quotations collected in a written survey of college seniors and
post-graduates.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week, leading
with Einstein's brain.
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moved in the `i' category:
</P>
<P>
   LATIN-MILITARY-REVIEW (Rio de Janeiro) _ Latin America's armies
are down but not out. But these are trying times for soldiers
throughout the region. Government spending is declining even faster
than the prestige of a military career. In virtually every country
the armed forces confront the question of what is their role now
that they are no longer the dominant force in their societies? By
Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-PAKISTAN-REVIEW (Srinigar, Kashmir) _ In the wake of the
Kosovo, awareness is growing in Washington and other capitals that
the world pays a high price for waiting too long to address
mounting crises. The India-Pakistan dispute over Kashmir is among
the most combustible, and the fact that both contending nations
have nuclear weapons lends it an apocalyptic urgency. It is now
drawing more serious attention than at any time since it started.
By Stephen Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   QUESTIONS OR RERUNS: (888) 346-9867
</P>
<P>
   PHOTOS AND GRAPHICS: (888) 603-1036
</P>
<P>
   TECHNICAL PROBLEMS: Peter Trigg
</P>
<P>
   Phone: (212) 499-3332.
