<HEADER>
A2007 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-MEXICO-UNREST-ART-N     06-19 1089
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-MEXICO-UNREST-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLASH WITH RIOT POLICE SPARKS ISSUE IN MEXICO CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating to add map note)  (ART ADV:  Locator map  is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By SAM DILLON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAUCALPAN, Mexico _ The fatal shooting of a young municipal
worker this week by a police officer here provoked a rampage of
partisan violence that could affect the outcome of closely watched
gubernatorial elections next month in Mexico's most populous state.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, union activists loyal to President Ernesto
Zedillo's governing party attacked municipal police in this
industrial suburb governed by the opposition, vowing to avenge the
killing by police the day before. The violence suggests that police
abuse is likely to be a potent campaign theme as Mexico moves
toward presidential balloting next year.
</P>
<P>
   Naucalpan is a city of 1 million residents in the state of
Mexico, a region of smoky factories and gritty slums adjoining
Mexico City. The state has for 70 years been governed by Zedillo's
Institutional Revolutionary Party.
</P>
<P>
   Gubernatorial elections are scheduled for July 4, and Jose Luis
Duran, who two years ago won election as Naucalpan's first
opposition mayor, has taken a leave of absence to run as the
candidate of the pro-business National Action Party, called PAN.
</P>
<P>
   Statewide opinion surveys show Duran to be closing a modest lead
held by Ricardo Montiel, the PRI candidate. Higinio Martinez, the
candidate of a leftist party, is running a distant third.
</P>
<P>
   All three candidates have sought to capitalize on public
distress over crime and police corruption, which are rampant all
across Mexico and which no party has battled with much success.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday afternoon, two Naucalpan police officers attempted
to detain Mauricio Martinez Hernandez, a 25-year-old city
waterworks employee, and one of the officers shot him dead when he
attempted to flee, in disputed circumstances. Naucalpan's acting
mayor said in an interview Saturday that the killing followed a
dispute between Martinez and the officer over a woman; local PRI
leaders insist the shooting occurred after Martinez resisted police
attempts to rob him.
</P>
<P>
   Angry residents gathered around Martinez's body, the officers
fled in their squad car, and local PRI leaders, shouting at the
crowd, immediately blamed the killing on Duran. Within hours of the
shooting, thousands of handbills headlined ``Killer Police, Duran's
Legacy!'' were being distributed across the state of Mexico. In one
city north of Naucalpan, state police officers were seen
distributing the leaflets, National Action officials said.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, during a public display of Martinez's coffin in the
Naucalpan plaza, leaders of his union, which is affiliated with the
PRI, urged about 1,000 municipal workers to take vengeance. Some
300 laid siege to the Naucalpan police headquarters and city hall,
shattering windows with rocks and engaging in hand-to-hand combat
with 500 helmeted riot police officers, some of whom appeared to
have fired their service revolvers. Several officers were dragged
away from police lines, disarmed and beaten. One officer's leg was
broken.
</P>
<P>
   At least 30 people, including seven officers, were injured and
at least one union worker was wounded by gunfire. Five police cars
were destroyed, city officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Naucalpan's police have arrested the officer accused of shooting
Martinez. The other is a fugitive. The investigation of the death,
however, appears most likely to be caught up in the partisan
warfare, because jurisdiction falls to state detectives who work
for the PRI governor.
</P>
<P>
   The Naucalpan violence took center stage in the campaign for the
governorship, Mexico's most important electoral contest before
presidential balloting next year. But it was not immediately clear
who would be hurt and who would benefit.
</P>
<P>
   Before the killing of Martinez, Montiel had been under fire from
human rights groups because, in positioning himself as a
law-and-order candidate who can crack down on crime, he recently
began airing ads that say, ``Human rights are for humans, not for
rats.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the killing has put Duran on the defensive by raising
questions about how much progress he has made in efforts to
professionalize the Naucalpan police, which have been a centerpiece
of his campaign. In an interview Saturday, he said he had purged
500 corrupt officers from the city's 1,800-officer force during his
two years in office, and had founded a police academy to train new
recruits. Naucalpan, he said, ``is the city in the state of Mexico
that has made the most strides in controlling crime.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a lamentable act, that a young man dies at the hands
of the police,'' he said. ``But the violence we've seen here is an
utterly irresponsible political manipulation by the PRI.''
</P>
<P>
   Jaime Vasquez Castillo, president of the PRI in the state of
Mexico, shot back, ``With their diatribes, Duran and the PAN are
just trying to divert attention from a homicide for which they're
responsible.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the desperate tactics of a candidate who's tried to
sell the image that he's created a pristine police force in
Naucalpan,'' Vasquez said.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, much of the Naucalpan plaza was still spattered with
blood, and dozens of police on horseback were patrolling the
streets. Curtains flapped in the empty window frames of the
shattered police headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Three dozen riot police officers were holding defensive
positions in the lobby of the city hall. Upstairs, Alejandro
Gutierrez Gutierrez, a National Action city councilman who in
Duran's absence is Naucalpan's acting mayor, was huddled in his
office, looking beleaguered.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no excuse for the PRI to call on people to commit
aggressions against authorities or to try to take over a police
station by force,'' he said. ``They've called out their
neighborhood organizations, the street vendors, the taxi drivers,
all to create tensions before the elections. I think they're
putting our political system at risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside in the plaza, David Parra Sanchez, a leader of the
PRI-affiliated municipal workers union, was addressing 200
municipal workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is that there's total insecurity in Naucalpan,''
he shouted. ``The police are murdering our young people, and when
we protest, they say we're politicizing the murder. Was Mauricio
Martinez's death political?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
