<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-19 14:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2009 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPEECHES-POLITICS-2TA     06-19 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPEECHES-POLITICS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS ANALYSIS: IN WORDS, GORE AND BUSH STAKE OUT MIDDLE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ADAM CLYMER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore and Gov. George W. Bush,
declaring their candidacies for president, sound as though they are
proclaiming the primary campaign over, the general election begun
and the battleground designated as the moderate middle, with
ideological extremes out of bounds.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who announced in Carthage, Tenn., on Wednesday, and Bush,
who did so in Cedar Rapids, Iowa, last Saturday, spoke as if they
were using the same pollsters and some of the same speechwriters.
</P>
<P>
   There were major structural differences, to be sure. In
Carthage, Gore had dozens of quite specific proposals, both because
that is the sort of person he is, and because he wanted to contrast
his experience with Bush's. Gore described himself as ``a leader
who has been tested.''
</P>
<P>
   In Cedar Rapids, Bush said that the time had not come for
``10-point plans'' and that he knew being governor of Texas ``isn't
the same as being president.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has one singular reason to avoid specifics early: There is
a large Republican field ready to pick his proposals apart.
</P>
<P>
   Even though they did not engage over detail, Gore and Bush were
fighting over much of the same ground. Both opposed drugs in
schools. Both promised to involve religious organizations in social
welfare programs. Both supported foreign trade.
</P>
<P>
   More generally, Gore boasted that ``America now has the
strongest economy in the history of the United States,'' but said
that was not enough, but merely a foundation from which to ``make
family life work in America, for the issue is not only our standard
of living, but our standards in life.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, while saying the Clinton administration ``did not invent
prosperity any more than they invented the Internet,'' said
American prosperity had to amount to more than ``simple
materialism.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Prosperity must have a greater purpose,'' he said. It has to
provide ``men and women who work hard, dream big, love their
family, serve their neighbor.''
</P>
<P>
   The announcement speech used to be the one occasion when a
would-be president could count on getting his message of why he
should be president out, relatively undiluted by analysis of his
motives or chances.
</P>
<P>
   That exposure is less certain today, in large part because
candidates seek to have so many bites of the political apple, from
announcing an intention to form an exploratory committee, to
announcing the committee, to announcing the plan to announce, to
the announcement itself. Indeed, Bush tried to reserve a later bite
last Saturday. Even though he said, ``I am running for president;
there is no turning back,'' he also maintained, ``I'll have a
formal announcement sometime in the fall.''
</P>
<P>
   But an announcement speech still offers an opportunity to define
a campaign, as Ronald Reagan did in 1979 when he quoted John
Winthrop's line in establishing the Massachusetts Bay Colony in
1630, ``We shall be as a city upon a hill,'' and promised to lead a
nation out of the pessimism he accused President Carter of
inflicting upon it. Or as George McGovern did in promising in 1971
to withdraw every American soldier from Vietnam, or as Bill Clinton
did in 1991 saying he would ``fight for the forgotten middle
class.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only each candidate, but each kind of candidacy, has a
formula.
</P>
<P>
   Announcing a challenge to an incumbent of one's own party, as
Reagan did in 1975 and Edward M. Kennedy did in 1979, requires
saying the president has failed his party's ideal. Running against
the other party's president if the economy is strong requires a
speech so good no one _ certainly not Walter Mondale in 1983 or Bob
Dole in 1995 _ has written it yet.
</P>
<P>
   But the demands of running when a vice president of an
administration with a successful economy seeks to succeed a
president whose popularity is wearing thin are special _ and both
speeches in the last few days owe a lot to the announcement speech
of the last vice president in such a situation, George H.W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   For example, though Gore used the word ``Clinton'' but twice,
Vice President Bush said ``Reagan'' only once. Both vice presidents
bragged on the economy. Just as Bush was running against ``an
economy buffeted by incompetence and intrusion'' he said Carter
left behind seven years before, Gore recalled ``deep recession and
high unemployment,'' and said, ``We remember what it was like seven
years ago and I never want to go back.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore tried to distance himself from the worst part of his
administration's image, his president's scandals, by promising to
use the nation's ``moral leadership to fight for America's
families.'' He said, ``I will take my own values of faith and
family to the presidency.''
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Bush confronted the worst of the Reagan
administration's image when he said: ``Where is it written that
Republicans must act as if they do not care, as if they are not
moved? I say to my fellow Republicans: We are the party of Lincoln.
Our whole history was protecting those who needed our protection
and making this a kinder nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's son played against the Republican image, too, when he
defended his own commitment to ``compassionate conservatism,'' and
asked: ``Is compassion beneath us? Is mercy below us? Should our
party be led by someone who boasts a hard heart? I know Republicans
_ across the country _ are generous of heart.''
</P>
<P>
   There were other, perhaps familial, similarities of phrasing.
Bush said ``prosperity must have a purpose.'' His father had said
``prosperity with a purpose means giving back to the country that
has given you so much.'' The younger Bush said, ``I'm running
hard''; the elder Bush said, ``I mean to run hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Bushes and Gore, too, to give a message of inclusiveness,
spoke a few words in Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Differences of approach will become clearer as Bush's policies
become clearer. The most precise promise he made in his
announcement speech was to see to it that Head Start, the
pre-school program for poor children, would ``teach our youngest
children phonics,'' the method of teaching reading that relies on
the sounds of letters.
</P>
<P>
   But there was a distinct difference in their attitudes toward
the role of government, though not the chasm that exists between
the caricatures each party sketches of the other.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said, ``government can help'' make schools safer and make
examples of bad behavior. He said, ``government should do a few
things and do them well.''
</P>
<P>
   And though Gore said no legislation and no president could
replace parents as moral guides to their children, he offered a
list of things government should do:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Making high-quality pre-school available to every child in
every community all across the United States of America.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Expanding ``community policing, with more cops walking the
beat.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Amending the family leave law so parents could leave work for
parent-teacher meetings and children's medical appointments.
</P>
<P>
   _ Enacting a patients' bill of rights.
</P>
<P>
   _ Helping ``seniors pay for the prescription drugs they need.''
</P>
<P>
   In all, Gore gave 15 specifics for government action in his
speech.
</P>
<P>
   Other Republican presidential contenders have struck more
combative, ideologically charged notes in their announcement
speeches. Patrick Buchanan, the conservative commentator, for
example, urged his followers to ``mount up and ride to the sound of
guns,'' while vowing to protect the rights ``of the innocent
unborn.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Bauer, another conservative, announced his candidacy
shortly after the school shootings in Littleton, Colo., and
criticized American culture, saying it ``glorifies death in a
thousand ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Vice President Dan Quayle also cited the culture wars in
his announcement. Referring to a famous speech he gave as vice
president, in which he lambasted the values of American popular
culture, Quayle noted, ``Murphy Brown is gone and I'm still here
fighting for the American family.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's only Democratic opponent, former Sen. Bill Bradley, has
not given a formal announcement speech but has tackled broad
subjects like race in his appearances. His stands on most issues do
not contrast sharply with Gore's.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-99 1402EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
