<SLUG> BC-BIKERS-BREAST-BAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TAMING OF A RALLY RANKLES THE BIKERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.H., Fla., S.D.)   (bl)  
 By CAREY GOLDBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LACONIA, N.H. _ Every summer, when several hundred thousand
motorcyclists roar into this lakeside town for the grand-daddy of
all biker bashes, Deborah Gagman, a k a the exotic dancer Autumn
Blaze, poses happily in the crowd with all who ask, positioning her
pasties for best photographic advantage.
</P>
<P>
   This year was different. When, on Thursday, Ms. Gagman pulled
forward the suspenders that were all that was covering the Harley
Davidson patches that were all that was covering her secondary
sexual characteristics (and primary professional assets), she found
herself facing a $250 citation for ``inciting the crowd,'' her
outraged manager, Lee Blais, said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Such strictness, declared Blais, is utterly out of place in the
rough-and-tumble atmosphere of this bacchanalian June motorcycle
week. ``These are  &UR; bikers &LR; '' he said. If town officials ``are
trying to make this Disneyland, they've got a long way to go. This
is never going to be Disneyland. Look around you!''
</P>
<P>
   Not Disneyland, certainly not; too many nipple rings. Still, for
all that this great gathering is the essence of subculture, replete
with enough black leather to jacket every soldier in the standing
U.S. armed forces and enough fringe to line the Brooklyn Bridge, it
is not so far removed from the cultural currents of mainstream
America, it turns out.
</P>
<P>
   To wit: This year, the small city of Laconia, population about
17,000, is enforcing a new woman-protecting,
quality-of-life-protecting ordinance that bars women from
displaying their breasts in public and anyone from encouraging them
to do so.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, it seems, is that Laconia's motorcycle week has
become known for a certain habit among beer-happy men to encourage
women to flash their upper bodies by shouting various rude
variations on ``Show us your breasts!'' Some women comply, which
fuels the problem for those who do not.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of my big issues is violence against women,'' said Laconia
Police Chief William Baker, who issued the first citation under the
new ordinance to Ms. Gagman. ``And I'm afraid with these sexual
contests in bars, these drunk men observe these things in a bar and
then they stumble out onto the street and assume every woman is
also a contestant. And there are a lot of women on the street being
treated in ways they're not happy about.''
</P>
<P>
   The other two major national motorcycle gatherings each year, in
Sturgis, S.D., and Daytona Beach, Fla., are not known as paragons
of decorum either, but Laconia's reputation, many bikers say, has
been the rowdiest. An image, say its organizers and hosts, that
needs to change.
</P>
<P>
   The Laconia rally, at 76, is the oldest of the major motorcycle
gatherings, but its name took on a tinge of infamy in 1965, when a
riot erupted that involved the National Guard. In general,
old-timers recall, those gatherings in the '60s were wild indeed.
``It was, like, serious party, like, insane stuff, but it's
mellowed, it's become a business for a lot of people,'' said Joseph
Delio, better known as Papa Joe, an ex-biker minister who offered
blessings to several dozen motorcyclists Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the bikers of that era are grandparents now, and the
country has changed, and so has motorcycling. It is a mass-market
sport, not the Hell's Angels specialty it used to seem _ though
Hell's Angels still show up at the gatherings.
</P>
<P>
   If Laconia is any indication, about as many women ride their own
motorcycles as are passengers. And bikers range from teens to
octogenarians, from gang members to lawyers, from walking tattoo
canvases to wholesome Tommy Hilfiger models.
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with the times, the Laconia gathering, for all its
intense racing, arm-wrestling, drinking, bike-inspecting, seeing
and being seen, has also clearly become a serious business: for the
corporate sponsors, for the hundreds of vendors, for the
townspeople of Laconia, even for New Hampshire Gov. Jeanne Shaheen,
who talks about insuring ``a safe family week'' in the event's
official bulletin. It is too big to be spoiled by what Charlie St.
Clair, its chief organizer, calls a few idiots, generally not even
bikers but locals, who harassed women.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the ordinance might not be construed as a stab at
political correctness in the most un-PC of crowds, he responded,
``How is that PC, when you're stopping a person from grabbing
somebody? From shouting at them? No one has the right to do that to
another person on a public street. It offends me as a human being
to see that happen.''
</P>
<P>
   St. Clair's sentiment does not seem to be shared among the
motorcycle multitudes gathered at Laconia's Weirs Beach. More than
a dozen interviews shouted over the engine racket and through the
exhaust failed to turn up any support for the new ordinance.
</P>
<P>
   Four members of the Yonkers, N.Y.-based Attiqua Motorcycle Club,
each contributing a sentence fragment where the last had left off,
said: ``Part of the fun of coming up here . . . is the freedom the
women have . . .to express themselves . . . and show their
well-sculpted bodies.''
</P>
<P>
   Several women said they expected the shouted comments and were
not offended by them _ sometimes, even flattered. Diane Ciampa of
Norwood, Mass., considers the shouts ``part of the whole thing,''
she said. Her husband, Wayne, added, ``I think it's cracking down
on your freedom'' at an event known as a time to ``let it all hang
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Town officials are well aware of such sentiments. When he was
citing Ms. Gagman, Baker said, ``A lot of men came by and said,
`Leave her alone, that's what this event is all about.' Well, we
disagree.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
