<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-19 14:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2024 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-GUN-CONTROL-NYT &LR;      06-19 0661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-GUN-CONTROL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: DELAY'S POWER PLAY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Sunday, June 20:
</P>
<P>
   That was one embarrassing week for Dennis Hastert. When the
House blocked tough gun control legislation and then could not
muster the votes for the pathetically weak measure that was left,
the speaker was nowhere to be found.
</P>
<P>
   It was bad enough to have to explain why his promise of ``common
sense'' gun control legislation flamed out as the House surrendered
to the gun lobby. Had he appeared in public, he also would have had
to explain why he surrendered control of the House to Tom DeLay.
George W. Bush and others, take note. DeLay _ fund-raiser, friend
of lobbyists and nasty culture warrior _ has become the main voice
of the GOP in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The gun control issue is instructive for those studying the
contours of politics in Washington as it approaches the most
competitive election year in a long time for both Congress and the
presidency. For all that, the Republican congressional leaders are
oddly passive. While the country yearns for centrist politics _
something that helps to explain the success of Bush in the
presidential field _ the top congressional Republicans have yielded
to the fire-breathing ideologues who drove the House to impeachment
last year and seem determined to make their hatred of the life
choices of many Americans the center of their strategy.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the skill that Trent Lott, the Senate majority
leader, brought to the impeachment trial earlier this year has
deserted him. Hastert is the accidental house speaker who owes his
job to DeLay and has all but handed over the speakership to him.
While Hastert sputters platitudes about inclusiveness, DeLay has
called the shots all year on campaign finance reform, Kosovo, the
budget and now guns.
</P>
<P>
   As a front man, Delay reached out to John Dingell, an old
Democratic bull who has served 44 years in the House, to do the
bidding of the National Rifle Association and gut the provision for
waiting periods on gun purchases at gun shows. That weakening
amendment passed early Friday morning, but by later in the day, the
House may have heard about the public's reaction to the tears of
Rep. Carolyn McCarthy, who made guns her cause after her husband
was murdered by a gunman on the Long Island Railroad. The House has
now defeated the entire watered-down bill that DeLay arrogantly
thought would fool the public into thinking something had been done
to curb guns.
</P>
<P>
   In the culture wars, you can credit DeLay for turning a major
political axiom upside down. It used to be an article of faith for
conservatives that Americans need to take more individual
responsibility for their actions. But now, thanks to DeLay, we
learn that violence perpetrated by gun owners is really the product
of larger forces. What might those be?
</P>
<P>
   According to the Republican whip from Texas, nothing less than
``broken homes,'' day care, television, video games, birth control,
abortion and, unbelievably, the teaching of the theory of
evolution.
</P>
<P>
   The gun vote revealed something else about Congress. In the
pivotal vote on gun shows, scores of Democrats defected to the
Republicans and scores of Republicans defected to the Democrats. It
was almost as if a third party had emerged from the other two. It
is made up of lawmakers from districts so competitive they actually
have to listen to their constituents.
</P>
<P>
   In the months ahead, the Party of Vulnerable Incumbents will be
emerging as a volatile swing vote. The debacle over gun control can
be reversed, but only with concerted lobbying in these swing
districts. Clinton must also make it clear that he will veto any
juvenile justice legislation that does not contain tough gun
control measures. A veto threat, and an appeal to the conscience of
the centrists, can bring sanity back to the House and provide the
ultimate rebuke to DeLay.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
