<HEADER>
A2025 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-FATHERS-NYT &LR;      06-19 0366
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-FATHERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: FATHERLY CONFUSIONS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Sunday, June 20:
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps those tickets to ``Death of a Salesman'' were the wrong
Father's Day present after all. Get him what he really wants, the
ads all say, but does he even know what that is, and if you gave it
to him could he open it over breakfast in front of the family?
Every possible present seems to carry the wrong message. Tie,
wallet, belt, after-shave _ the customary gifts _ imply that Dad is
something of an accessory. In fact, a strange obliquity often
emerges when dads open their Father's Day presents, as if Pandora's
box contained not a world of trouble but soap-on-a-rope.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, bewildered thanks is the leading sentiment on this
day of dadness, the bewilderment, as well as the thanks, flowing in
both directions. What makes the spirit of Father's Day hard to
internalize is the sound evolutionary intuition that fathers have a
smaller biological commitment to their offspring than mothers do _
that and the sense that this is a holiday dreamed up by shirt and
golf ball manufacturers. Just perceptible through the Father's Day
advertising blitz is the hint that there is also something
inherently comical about fatherhood itself, once the kids reach the
age of irony, that is, which comes much earlier now than the age of
reason ever did.
</P>
<P>
   No man is a hero to his valet, and most fathers manage to be an
unequal blend of all three _ man, hero and valet. That is one of
the things that infuse the official celebration of fatherhood with
its slightly awkward aura. The other thing, of course, is the
natural grace of mothers, who accept gratitude and love as their
simple due on Mother's Day and any other day of the year. They know
how, and who knows where they learn it, to make even the most
absurd gift, including no gift at all, seem like the very thing
they were hoping for.
</P>
<P>
   For men, it is all very different. Father's Day is the one day
when being a father feels odd, unless you can persuade your
children, as mothers so effortlessly do, that they are still and
will always be gift enough. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-99 1424EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
