<SLUG> BC-US-RUSSIA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON REACHES OUT TO RUSSIA AFTER DEAL TO JOINTLY PATROL KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLOGNE, Germany _ President Clinton and leaders of the world's
most powerful industrialized democracies moved Saturday to repair
strained relations with Russia over the Balkans by prying open
their checkbooks to reward Russia's cooperation with the West in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The proposals for financial aid were presented to Russian Prime
Minister Sergei Stepashin, just hours after American and Russian
negotiators ended a bitter week-long impasse to clear the way for
3,600 Russian soldiers to join the 50,000-member international
security force in Kosovo under the command of the U.S.-led
19-nation North Atlantic Treaty Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will meet Sunday with Russian President Boris Yeltsin
after the adjournment of the annual summit among the leaders of the
top seven industrialized democracies: Germany, France, Italy,
Britain, Canada, Japan and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's first face-to-face meeting with Stepashin came amid
reports from Moscow that the mercurial Yeltsin was in a ``fighting
mood'' as he prepared to meet Clinton but senior White House
officials said they were uncertain what Yeltsin had in mind.
</P>
<P>
   White House National Security Adviser Samuel ``Sandy'' Berger
said the allies were reaching out to Russia to ease strains caused
by NATO's 11-week bombing campaign that forced Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic to halt the murder or expulsion of ethnic
Albanian Muslims from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Russia is an ally of Milosevic's.
</P>
<P>
   Berger suggested that the allies were trying to stem the wave of
anti-western nationalism gripping Russia and threatens to influence
the outcome of Russia's presidential election next June.
</P>
<P>
   The allies have a ``strong interest in trying to help Russia
stay on the path of recovery, reform and democracy,'' Berger said.
``It makes a big difference whether Russia is able to strengthen
its economy, maintain its democracy, continue to head in the basic
direction of openness and reform _ or whether Russia reverts back
to some kind of nationalist or inward looking leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   The allied air campaign against Yugoslavia has frozen relations
with Russia in recent months, jeopardizing cooperation in a variety
of aras.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Stepashin agreed at their meeting that it was time
to end the chill in U.S.-Russian relations, according to Berger.
</P>
<P>
   ``There may be some desire to discuss, to go back and discuss
the events of the past 90 days,'' Berger said. ``But I think the
larger thrust here is to move forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the allied incentives outlined for Russia offered the
prospect of a fresh infusion of sorely needed western currency.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and his colleagues signaled greater flexibility on
Russia's repayment of $69 billion in Soviet-era debt in response to
Stepashin's promise that the Kremlin would complete economic
reforms demanded by the International Monetary Fund. Clinton
indicated that an IMF loan for $4.5 billion in emergency debt
assistance would be approved next month.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton promised Stepashin immediate satellite launch contracts
with American firms as Russia implements stiffer export controls on
missile-related technology to countries such as Iran. Clinton also
vowed to proceed with a $4.2 billion, five year U.S.-funded program
to help Russia improve nuclear weapons safety.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton discussed ways to reopen the U.S. market to greater
imports of Russian steel in the wake of a U.S. crackdown on Russian
``dumping'' of steel at prices below production costs.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration responded to Russian entreaties to
offer some flexibility on the definition of emergency
``humanitarian assistance'' that will be provided to Yugoslavia by
the 19-nation NATO alliance and the 15-nation European Union.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and some U.S. allies have stipulated that western
development aid will not be sent to Yugoslavia as long as
Milosevic, an indicted war criminal, remains in power.
</P>
<P>
   But Russia wants western humanitarian assistance to reach
Yugoslavia's Serbs. As Stepashin put it Friday night: ``The conduct
of one man must not penalize 10 million Serbs.''
</P>
<P>
   Berger said allies concur on providing ``humanitarian'' aid to
``the Serbian people'' while withholding broad ``reconstruction''
assistance until Milosevic steps down.
</P>
<P>
   But the distinction between the two types of assistance may be
blurred, Berger conceded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is getting the electric lights back on (in Serbia) for winter
humanitarian or is it reconstruction?'' Berger said. ``Where that
line is, is obviously something that is going to have to be
established.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States would participate in humanitarian relief to
the Serbian people ``if the need is great in Serbia, particularly
as winter comes on and there's need for food and medicine and basic
human needs,'' Berger said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another gesture to the Kremlin was the allies' readiness to deal
with Russia on security-related matters at the Group of Eight
summit where Russia enjoys equal footing with the industrialized
democracies, the G-7.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has refused to deal on security-related issues involving
Kosovo through NATO where Russia is merely a subordinate,
nonvoting, consultative partner to the 19-nation alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Stepashin told Clinton that the Kremlin is now prepared to
resume working-level contacts between the prime minister and Vice
President Al Gore. The twice-a-year meetings of the Cabinet level
commission had been suspended. Resumption of the sessions offers
Gore a prominent foreign policy stage in his 2000 presidential
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; -- &LR;  &QL;
</P>
