</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIOLENT-VIDEOGAMES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIOLENT VIDEO GAMES FACING NEW SCRUTINY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Wash., Mich.)   (ART ADV: Photo of Alfredo Labour playing a video game is being
sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Shortly after turning on his computer,
Alfredo Lambour, 15, shot and killed the same zombie six times, saw
countless gallons of blood splatter, and ran among the decapitated
heads and other body parts that littered a fortress floor in the
video game Quake II.
</P>
<P>
   Alfredo spends nearly two hours a day in his living room, here
in this Los Angeles suburb, looking down the barrel of a gun as he
roams dimly lit corridors in search of monsters. On a recent day,
Alfredo played the role of a marine, outfitted with body armor,
fatigues and a weapon called a blaster that he fired at anything
that moved, using his computer keyboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can just split people in half,'' he said of the blaster.
</P>
<P>
   Video games have come under increased scrutiny after the
shootings at Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo., that left
15 people dead. The students who carried out the attack, Eric
Harris and Dylan Klebold, have been described as playing Doom, a
violent video game released in 1993 that is not considered to be
realistic compared with newer games, but still includes ample
amounts of blood and numerous explosions.
</P>
<P>
   It is unknown whether the gory scenes in the game influenced the
minds of the Columbine shooters. But the issue of the violent
influence of video games has been seized upon by many politicians
and members of the public who believe that such entertainment is
inappropriate for minors and needs to be toned down.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton singled out video game advertising as being
particularly excessive when he announced the beginning of two
federal investigations June 1 into whether the entertainment
industry is marketing violence to children. A proposal by Rep.
Henry Hyde, R-Ill., to prohibit the sale of all violent
entertainment, including video games, to children under 17 failed
in a House vote Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   While video game enthusiasts generally concede that some of the
games sold in stores have violent content, they are adamant that
the games do not encourage players to imitate what they see on
screen. To them, fighting animated enemies is merely thrilling
competition and no more harmful than football, professional
wrestling and cartoons in which characters like Wile E. Coyote
battle the Roadrunner with anvils and dynamite.
</P>
<P>
   ``There wouldn't be a lot of people foaming at the mouth over
video games if Littleton didn't happen,'' said Jon Dempster, a
video game enthusiast from Grand Rapids, Mich., who sometimes plays
games like Quake II with his twin 11-year-old boys. ``As long as
children can separate fantasy from reality, they leave any
aggressive thoughts behind once they turn off the computer. It has
no effect.''
</P>
<P>
   For the past five years, video game boxes have been printed with
ratings as part of a voluntary program by software publishers.
However, even games that are rated as ``mature'' like Postal, which
says on the box that it is so realistic that ``your victims
actually beg for mercy and scream for their lives,'' can be legally
sold to children of any age.
</P>
<P>
   Yet most video games are actually bought by adults, according to
the Interactive Digital Software Association, the video game
industry's trade group. If parents are not already aware of the
contents, most soon learn, and judging from the widespread use by
children, do nothing to intervene.
</P>
<P>
   ``These ratings are completely neglected,'' said Dave Sparks,
owner of Interact, a computer video game store in Pasadena, Calif.
``Maybe one out of a hundred Moms pay any attention to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Many video game enthusiasts blamed the media and political
opportunists for the bad reputation their hobby has received
lately. The recent rash of school shootings, they said, was more a
consequence of action movies, news reports about crime, bad
parenting and children who were mentally disturbed.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Matulewicz, 15, from near San Jose, Calif., said that
reducing the violence in the games he plays would not diminish his
interest in them because he does not stop to admire the dead
bodies. But he added that the reduction is not necessary because
thousands of people play video games every day without hurting
others _ proof that some other factor must be responsible for the
violence like that at Columbine.
</P>
<P>
   That the federal government is focusing attention on the video
game industry is generally met with skepticism by video game
players. Steve Merz, a longtime video game enthusiast from Forest
City, N.C., who has two small children, said the content of video
games and the age of the people who play them is none of the
government's business.
</P>
<P>
   Merz said parents should be the ones to decide what children
play. Dismissing the violence in video games as inconsequential, he
allows his 7-year-old son, Danny, to play games like Quake, but not
ones with foul language, satanic imagery and nudity because those,
in contrast, he believes can be harmful.
</P>
<P>
   But some parents support strengthening video game ratings, which
are being reviewed by the industry trade group. They also want more
manufacturers to install switches in video games that would allow
parents to block parts of the game.
</P>
<P>
   David Lepore, a 30-year-old computer analyst in Tacoma, Wash.,
is among those parents who encourage the industry to adopt some
voluntary changes. For now, his two boys, ages 5 and 10, are not
even allowed to watch the screen when he, for example, assumes the
role of a horrific creature that has invaded a space colony in the
game Aliens Versus Predators.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some cases these games may lead to violence,'' he said,
``I'm not taking any chances.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
