<HEADER>
A2041 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-SAMPRAS-WIMBLEDON     06-19 1124
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-SAMPRAS-WIMBLEDON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAMPRAS BACK ON FIRM GRASS AGAIN  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ The ritual gets more momentous every year.
Each June Pete Sampras makes a private pilgrimage to Center Court,
the famed swatch of lawn that shines, on sunny days, like a
square-cut emerald and will, after a two-week trampling, come to
resemble a dust bowl. He pays his respects and prays that it will
be his sneakers, seven rounds hence, that grind Wimbledon's
best-loved lawn into oblivion.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is more than just a tennis tournament to me,'' Sampras
said last week, parked on the sofa of his customary rental manse on
the fringes of Wimbledon village. ``This is the granddaddy of them
all, and when you step onto that court, the world is watching.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not trying to get too deep here, but I feel a connection
to this place. When I look around Center Court and remember the
matches I've won there, it feels like a cathedral. It's almost
surreal.''
</P>
<P>
   Late Friday, alone in the stands of the abandoned Center Court,
Sampras conducted his solo seance, communing with the ghosts of
Wimbledons past. For the most part, they have been friendly to him;
his five championships in the last six years are proof. But he has
reasons for wanting to feel more simpatico than ever with the
doomed grasses of Center Court.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras, whose 11th and most recent Grand Slam event was won
here last year, would establish a glut of historic footnotes if he
captured a sixth Wimbledon. Not only would he equal Roy Emerson's
career record of 12 Grand Slam titles, but he would become the
first man in 110 years to conquer the world's most celebrated
tennis tournament six times, and he would surpass Ivan Lendl's
record of 270 weeks with the No. 1 ranking.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I sit there in the stands and soak it all in,'' Sampras
said. ``I think about how the court will look when I play on
Monday, new and green and untouched, and then I think how it looked
last year in the fifth set against Goran, like a battleground, with
no grass left at all, how that's what makes the tennis that much
more threatening. It's all part of the charm of the place. Of
course I would love to win again. That's rhetorical. But I don't
feel pressure to do it; pressure is the wrong word.''
</P>
<P>
   Pressure was the right word for the way Sampras concluded 1998,
on a frantic six-week tour through Europe designed to give him
sufficient match victories to finish the year at No. 1 for a sixth
consecutive season. Another record.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras went 14-4 during that stretch, which began with a title
in Vienna but included a first-round exit at Stockholm and a
final-round loss to Greg Rusedski in the Paris Indoor that almost
drove him into psychiatric care. ``I began asking myself how would
I ever recover if I didn't do this thing,'' he said. ``I was solely
consumed by the thought of winning matches, and by the end of the
year I felt like I was fighting for my life.
</P>
<P>
   ``This wasn't like failing at a Slam, where you at least have
the next one to look forward to,'' Sampras said. ``This was now or
never. I knew it was one record that won't be touched, and I had to
prove to myself that I could do it. Was it worth it? Yeah. It
was.''
</P>
<P>
   His success _ aided by the injuries that took Marcelo Rios and
Patrick Rafter, his rivals for the ranking, out of the year-end ATP
World Championships _ broke his tie with Jimmy Connors in the
record books, but it almost broke him, too. His hair fell out in
clumps, and eventually his relationship with the actress Kimberly
Williams was another casualty.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're two people with two demanding careers, and when it comes
right down to it, that opens itself to problems,'' he said. ``I
couldn't be there for her the way she needed me to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Call it selfishness, but Sampras found out he wasn't ready to
put romance ahead of records. ``It's not like we did anything
wrong, but neither one of us was going to make career sacrifices we
might end up regretting or resenting. Who knows what may happen in
the future, but for now, we're broken up.''
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of that break-up, Sampras _ who skipped the
Australian Open this year and spurned Davis Cup because the hunt
for No. 1 had left him ``at the end of my rope'' _ turned his
attention to winning the French Open, the only Grand Slam event he
has not won. He obsessed about Roland Garros from February on,
changing his diet from spontaneous to spartan and embarking on a
gladiator's training regimen. But, still, Sampras lost in the
second round, and lost ``badly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I put all this into it and I didn't even come close,'' he
said. ``I wanted it too much, which sounds like an irony. I play my
best tennis on instinct. Next time, I'm going into it like any
other tournament. If I don't ever win it, that won't totally
diminish my career _ but we all want to have a perfect career,
don't we?''
</P>
<P>
   Part of Sampras' new take on the perfect career includes Davis
Cup. During a spring of soul-searching after his monomaniacal chase
of the year-end top ranking, Sampras decided the final three or
four years of his career should consist of big events with tangible
outcomes.
</P>
<P>
   He is, he said, looking for ``the arena, and when I watched Jim
Courier and Todd Martin win the first round of Davis Cup against
England, for the first time I was kind of outside looking in.''
</P>
<P>
   He realized he wanted to be in on Davis Cup, especially in this
centennial year. ``So I swallowed my pride and offered to play just
doubles in the second round,'' he said. ``Really, I wanted Jim and
Todd to know I was serious about this commitment and wouldn't join
the team unless it was OK with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampras also felt a stab of recognition when Wayne Gretzky
retired this spring, sandwiched between the swan songs of Michael
Jordan and John Elway. ``I realized that it wasn't about the number
of Stanley Cups he won, it was about everything else he did and
meant to his sport,'' Sampras said. ``I don't want to sit here and
say that I'm tennis the way he is hockey, but it did make me think
of his role in his sport; it kind of opened up the big picture.''
</P>
<P>
   But the immediate picture is Wimbledon, the Grand Slam
tournament he reveres the most, and the achievements a title there
would bring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody's won it six times, not in modern times;
as for Emerson's record, to even be in the position to tie it is an
effort and achievement in itself,'' said Sampras, who for the
moment is confining his ambitions to beating Scott Draper in the
first round. ``It's ridiculous to put pressure on myself to get the
record here. But if and when I do tie it, then I'll start having
dreams about breaking it.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
