<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, June 20, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   High pressure will dominate the weather over the northeastern
quarter of the nation, bringing mainly dry conditions. Sunshine and
warmer air will cover eastern New England while clouds gather over
the northern Appalachian Mountains where isolated afternoon showers
may form. Onshore winds from the Middle Atlantic coast to the
Southeast will draw moisture from a stalled offshore front back
into the Piedmont plateau. As a result, thundershowers will dampen
the coast and a few storms should form over the southern
Appalachians.
</P>
<P>
   Tropical moisture will continue to interact with a stationary
front over Florida. Clusters of heavy thunderstorms will deposit
several inches of rain in the southern sections. A large
disturbance over the southeast Bahamas will drift toward the state
enhancing the wet weather.
</P>
<P>
   A surge of hot and humid air into the Plains will trigger
several areas of thunderstorms. Large thunderstorms will form in
the Dakotas and move into Minnesota and Iowa. Another cluster of
storms will generate over eastern Oklahoma or northeast Texas and
progress into Arkansas and Louisiana. A few thundershowers will
dissipate as they move into the Ohio Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Humid air circulating around high pressure at 15,000 feet over
the Rockies will trigger afternoon thundershowers mainly along the
southern and eastern peaks. A few storms will reach into Arizona.
Cooler, moist air from the North Pacific will sponsor clouds and a
few showers on the Northwest coast. Much of California will be
bright and hot over the interior.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: First Pacific Storm
</P>
<P>
   The first tropical storm of the season in the eastern Pacific
formed on Friday. It was named Adrian. With steady winds of nearly
60 mph, Adrian was situated very close to the west-central Mexican
coast. Conditions favor a strengthening to hurricane status by
Sunday morning. The hurricane season began more than a month ago in
the eastern Pacific. Indeed, it is unusual for the Atlantic to see
a named storm before the Pacific, but such is the case this year.
Usually about 15 storms form in the eastern Pacific each season;
there were a record 24 in 1992.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
