<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-ITALY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ITALIANS CELEBRATE AN UPSET, AS TURIN IS AWARDED 2006 WINTER
GAMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By SHERYL WuDUNN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea, June 19 _ Handing the Olympics to a city as
famed for its culture as for its ski slopes, the International
Olympic Committee on Saturday chose Turin, Italy, to host the 2006
Winter Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us, it was really a dream,'' Valentino Castellani, the
ebullient Mayor for the 1.3 million people of Turin, said in an
interview here after defeating the favored Swiss town of Sion, in a
59-36 vote. ``This is great for my city and for our country.''
</P>
<P>
   To the Swiss, who were shocked at the decision, it seemed the
realization of their worst fears. Even before the vote, Sion
officials had worried that their bid could fall prey to a backlash
targeted at Marc Hodler, a veteran Swiss IOC member who blew the
whistle on corruption at the IOC meeting last December. His
comments led to an investigation into Salt Lake City's bid for the
2002 Winter Olympics and the ensuing scandal left the IOC battling
a perception that it is a corrupt organization whose members sell
their votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sion wasn't the loser; Sion was a victim,'' Denis Oswald, a
member of the Swiss delegation, told reporters. ``Today, the IOC
was the loser.''
</P>
<P>
   Hodler also expressed frustration, telling reporters: ``It's
unfair. For Sion, it's really unfair.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, he took the podium at the end of the general
assembly meeting to congratulate Turin and pledge to help make the
2006 Winter Games a success.
</P>
<P>
   Turin, a baroque Italian city that is the home of the Fiat car
maker, had portrayed itself as an Olympic city of the future, a
metropolis near the Alps surrounded by churches and castles, by
museums and mountain peaks.
</P>
<P>
   A first-time bidder for an Olympics, Turin will become the first
Italian city in 46 years to be host to the Games. Cortina
d'Ampezzo, Italy, was the site of the 1956 Winter Olympics, and
Rome had the 1960 Summer Games.
</P>
<P>
   As the biggest city near the Alps, Turin and its surroundings
have been the home of many skiers, teachers and Olympic trainers,
and it had the added strength of having a relatively strong city
network of transportation, culture and cuisine.
</P>
<P>
   This was Sion's third attempt to be host of a Winter Olympics,
and each time, its bid had become stronger and better scripted.
This time, the image of the Swiss was similar to the concept
fashioned by the Winter Olympics in Lillehammer, Norway, in 1994,
and it won praise from the committee in the early stages of the
bidding process.
</P>
<P>
   Sion had also bid against Salt Lake City for the 2002 Winter
Olympics, but it had lost. At the time, Sion's group was told by
the committee that the ski slopes were too far from the Olympic
village, so it reworked its layout and in its bid this time, almost
all the sites would have been only about 30 minutes away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sion's concept was very good, but also very traditional,''
said Marco San Pietro, a spokesman for the Turin bid committee.
``Our bid was much more in the future, in the 21st century. This
was really the difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's selection vote was the first since the IOC expelled
six of its members and adopted new rules designed to prevent the
kind of gift-giving that had sometimes consumed the cities that had
campaigned in the past. In the past, cities wooed committee members
by sending them on tours, paying for golf outings, garden parties
and even tuition bills for members' children. Japanese sponsors of
the Nagano Winter Olympics in 1998, for instance, donated $10
million to help the IOC construct a new building in Lausanne,
Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, under the new rules this year, bidding cities were
not allowed to invite the IOC members to view the potential sites
of the Games. Nor were they allowed to throw dinner parties for
them or take them on expensive and entrancing tours in the host
countries.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Turin had prepared a budget of $5 million to $6 million
simply for entertaining 50 to 60 different Olympic Committee
members and other people who are part of the voting process. When
the rules were changed, Turin campaigners felt they were put at a
disadvantage, partly because few members knew anything about Turin,
much less visited the city. In contrast, many members were familiar
with Sion from its earlier bid.
</P>
<P>
   But using videos, compact disks and other materials, including
the 350-page bid book submitted to the committee, Turin was able to
convince the committee that a big city with a rich history and
culture could be part of a trend in future Olympics sites. In the
end, it spent about $10 million, according to San Pietro.
</P>
<P>
   Turin was the last city to join as a candidate in the Olympic
race, but it emerged as a relative underdog to beat the favorite,
the tiny and scenic Swiss hamlet of Sion, which has 28,000 people.
Even as delegates from six different cities gathered to hear Juan
Antonio Samaranch, the longtime president of the Olympic committee,
announce the winning city, there were whispers that Sion had won.
</P>
<P>
   But when Samaranch called out ``Turino!'' a surprised roar
erupted from the small band of supporters, and Champagne bottles
were uncorked.
</P>
<P>
   Hodler said he had no regrets about going public with his
allegations. Had he not, he said, ``It would have been
scandalous.''
</P>
<P>
   Some delegates to the meetings Saturday said that Sion's bid
could have been tainted slightly by its past participation in the
old-style selection process.
</P>
<P>
   The other bidding cities were Klagenfurt of Austria, Zakopane of
Poland, Helsinki of Finland and Poprad-Tatry of Slovakia.
</P>
<P>
   The committee is expected to finish work on the selection rules
for host cities perhaps at its next meeting next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will review everything from now until the end of the
year,'' said Chiharu Igaya, the Japanese delegate to the IOC and
the head of the committee evaluating the rules.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
