</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-HINGIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HINGIS BECOMES THE NEWEST `BRAT' IN TENNIS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ As an advertisement for herself, Martina
Hingis' petulant performance in the French Open final against
Steffi Graf two weeks ago gave cause for pause. Is the 18-year-old
Slovak-turned-Swiss-turned-Florida-resident trading in her
trademark precocity for pathology? Is she out to become the
brattiest No. 1 since John McEnroe made a habit, and a living, out
of on-court dysfunction?
</P>
<P>
   ``Her game may be mature beyond its years, but her behavior was
a very public temper tantrum, and her offenses were definitely
booable offenses,'' said Mary Carillo, a former French Open
mixed-doubles champion (alongside McEnroe), who now does television
commentary for CBS and HBO. ``She was the author of the atmosphere;
she turned a Grand Slam final into a Jerry Springer festival. She's
used to smiling her way out of anything; she's used to being the
one who jerks the chain.''
</P>
<P>
   But in Paris, at the only Grand Slam event she hasn't won,
Hingis' own Mount Everest of an ego sabotaged her. She didn't just
play at fever pitch, she pitched a fever fit.
</P>
<P>
   In the fifth game of the first set, she wrung her racquet like
the neck of a chicken, a bit of brutality that earned her a warning
and raised the hackles of the Roland Garros audience, which prefers
that its ladies' tennis finals be conducted in a ladylike fashion _
or at least with some facade of sportsmanship.
</P>
<P>
   OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   Had a handy shower come along and transformed the red clay to
red mud, Hingis might have challenged Graf to a wrestling match
before trophy time. As it was, she was misusing racquets when the
score was still 2-2.
</P>
<P>
   END OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   Later, she committed a rule-book taboo by invading Graf's turf
to argue a line call, a tantrum all the more ill-advised because
she held a 6-4, 2-0 lead at the time she chose to indulge herself
and denigrate the officials. Graf outwardly ignored the teen-ager's
histrionics and inwardly told herself: ``Hey, this kid is beating
me and she's cracking anyway. Better not count myself out just
yet.''
</P>
<P>
   The 16,000 fans just saw Hingis' hissy fit as further reason to
boo her and clamber aboard the bandwagon of the then 29-year-old
Graf as she soldiered through her ninth and last French Open final.
</P>
<P>
   After sulking through a third set comeback by Graf, the
frostiest rival to rise above an opponent's transgressions since
Bjorn Borg used to sit back at the baseline and watch McEnroe
detonate himself, Hingis produced the shot that drove the crowd to
a frenzy of condemnation. At match point for Graf, Hingis unfurled
an underhanded serve, and when it worked, she tried another on
Graf's second match point. That one didn't.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Chris Evert, Hingis' chosen mentor on the WTA Tour,
has decided that the underhand serve ``was just an act of total
desperation because she was trying at that point to do anything to
throw off Steffi's timing,'' Pam Shriver, another Grand Slam
champion turned television commentator, saw a darker side to the
shot selection.
</P>
<P>
   ``The underhand serve can be a tactic; I've seen people revert
to it before,'' said Shriver, noting that the most famous case was
the cramping Michael Chang during his improbable French Open
campaign of 1989. ``But in Hingis' case, it seemed like it was like
the parting shot of her breakdown; it's like she used that serve
out of spite because she didn't want to see Steffi win the title in
the normal way. She acted like a defiant teen-ager.''
</P>
<P>
   Or like a furious toddler who has been denied a coveted toy. In
defeat, Hingis did everything but lie on her back and kick and
scream and call for her mother _ wait a minute, she did that, too.
After slapping away the arm of the WTA Tour representative who
attempted to console her and remind her of her responsibilities on
the podium, Hingis raced from the court and into the arms of her
mother/coach, Melanie Molitor.
</P>
<P>
   Hingis later admitted she wouldn't have returned to absorb her
ultimate punishment _ the runner-up plate instead of the trophy _
if her mother hadn't reminded her that ``great champions'' have to
make consolation speeches just like any other loser in a Grand Slam
final.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting back on the loss, Hingis was dry-eyed and not in a
particularly redemptive mood. ``I don't think my behavior was too
bad,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   About the disputed forehand in the second set, she maintained
her shot was good and that Graf knew it but elected to steer clear
of the fray. As for her underhand serves, she termed them a
strategy wrought of frustration: ``I just used anything I could
use,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Bart McGuire, the chief executive officer of the women's tour,
said Hingis' French Open theatrics were her black eye to bear, not
the tour's, but he added, ``She's got some fence-mending to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Continued McGuire: ``There are things she's done and said that
don't present her in an attractive light, and certainly she
succeeded in creating a hostile crowd in the French final, but I
see it as more of a competitive judgment issue than a sportsmanship
issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I condone what she did? No. But I hope and believe she'll
learn from this, and as for it having an adverse effect on women's
tennis, I don't think so.''
</P>
<P>
   Hingis earned a $1,500 fine for the automatic point penalty she
received for crossing to Graf's territory, but worse than the fine
was the aftertaste of her tantrum. It suggested a champion who not
only believes she can beat everybody, but who also believes she's
better than everybody.
</P>
<P>
   But not better behaved. And not, when push came to shove on June
5 on center court at Roland Garros, better than Graf, who has spent
15 years working for her 22 Grand Slam crowns and definitely felt
slighted last year when Hingis dismissed her as over the hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being a professional athlete is a total learning curve,'' said
Billie Jean King. ``Right now Martina's anger is coming out
sideways. In time, things will change.''
</P>
<P>
   If they don't, the women's tennis tour has a built-in villain at
No.1. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
