<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-19 15:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2050 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRANDCANYON-RAIL-ART-     06-19 1209
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRANDCANYON-RAIL-ART-825&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAND CANYON BLAZING TRAIL WITH LIGHT RAIL LINE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND CANYON, Ariz. _ Mass tourism to the Grand Canyon started
in 1901 with the construction of a Santa Fe Railroad spur to the
south rim. Now, at the century's twilight, the canyon is returning
to its mass-transit roots, breaking ground recently for the first
light rail in a national park.
</P>
<P>
   Sandwiched in the decades between was the National Park
Service's love affair with the automobile _ scenic drives,
drive-through overlooks, acres of parking and, outside the south
entrance, the kind of development symbolized by a two-story statue
of Fred Flintstone calling out ``Yabba-dabba-doo'' to motorists
looking for a campground.
</P>
<P>
   While work starts this summer on the $100 million light rail
system, which is intended to cut vehicle traffic by 80 percent,
Grand Canyon National Park is innovating on a different front:
refurbishing its tacky commercial gateway.
</P>
<P>
   In a rare collaboration between developers and
environmentalists, nine environmental groups have endorsed a $330
million plan to build a gateway to the park that would include
1,220 hotel rooms and 250,000 square feet of commercial space. In
July, the Forest Service is expected to approve a land swap that
would allow the developer, Canyon Forest Village, to exchange 2,200
acres of private land scattered around the Kaibab National Forest
for 272 acres next to the terminus of the light rail line. There,
trains will leave every seven minutes for the south rim, 8.5 miles
away.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have seen what the marketplace has done around the Grand
Canyon _ junk, strip malls, sprawl. We are not interested in seeing
any more of that,'' said Brad Ack, program director of Grand Canyon
Trust, a regional environmental group. Noting that during five
years of negotiations, environmentalists and Indian tribes have won
major changes in the project, he said, ``It's a pretty interesting
approach to environmentalism. Instead of saying no, and losing, we
say yes and win.''
</P>
<P>
   Expected to draw nearly 5 million people this year, the Grand
Canyon is one of the nation's most visited parks. The turn to mass
transit here presages a larger shift in how Americans will visit
their most popular parks in the 21st century, park officials
predict. Over the last 30 years, the number of visitors to American
national parks has nearly doubled, hitting 287 million last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the big parks, our goal is not to limit people, but to
limit their cars,'' Jackie Lowey, a deputy director of the Park
Service, said recently from Maine, where she was preparing the June
21 inauguration of free shuttle-bus service from Bar Harbor to
sections of Acadia National Park.
</P>
<P>
   In southern Utah, Zion National Park is buying a fleet of buses
that run on clean-burning fuels. Next spring, park officials plan
to close Zion Canyon to cars, shuttling visitors in and out by bus.
</P>
<P>
   In Alaska, at Denali National Park and Preserve, almost all
motorized access is by van or bus. In Wyoming, at Yellowstone
National Park, and in California, at Yosemite National Park,
officials are studying ways of using buses to reduce traffic. In
announcing the Yosemite study last December, Interior Secretary
Bruce Babbitt said, ``At times, the valley reminds you very much of
being in Times Square in midsummer.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, about 40 of the nation's busiest parks, including the
Grand Canyon, have some form of mass-transit system. Here, a steam
railroad continues to take tourists to the canyon and shuttle buses
transport them down West Rim Drive.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors should ``have a park experience, not a parking
experience,'' Robert Arnberger, the Grand Canyon's superintendent,
said at the April 23 groundbreaking for the hub of the new light
rail system.
</P>
<P>
   Gazing down into the mile-deep depths of what some Indians call
the House Made of Dawn at times inspires mystical feelings. But a
one-hour search in 100-degree heat for a parking spot can inspire
fist fights. On a busy summer day, 6,000 vehicles dispute 2,400
parking space in the park's south side, the destination for 90
percent of the park's visitors. The roads and parking lots were
built in the 1960s, when the park had about 1 million visitors a
year.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than building six-lane freeways and multistory parking
garages, park officials have opted for a parking lot for 3,500
vehicles around the transit center at the park's southern entrance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to take time for people to embrace this new way of
seeing national parks,'' said Bradley Traver, the park's chief
planner.
</P>
<P>
   At the rim's edge, where tour bus drivers now idle engines to
keep air-conditioning running, a maximum of 4,200 people an hour
will arrive by train, then shift to bicycle and pedestrian trails
or to buses powered by electricity or natural gas.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we run diesel-belching monsters for buses, we are part of
the problem,'' Traver said. Air pollution has cut visibility at the
canyon to an average of 110 miles, from 140 miles at the start of
the century.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In another effort to reduce the mark of man, Interior Department
officials support the Canyon Forest Village development, which
would be built eight miles from the canyon in the Kaibab National
Forest.
</P>
<P>
   Under this plan, the Parks Service would demolish substandard
worker housing in the park and build up to 500 housing units in the
new development. Thomas De Paolo, the developer, believes that the
park's high school and medical center can also be moved into the
development.
</P>
<P>
   With a host of new hotel rooms at the park's edge, the Park
Service will demolish two boxy, 1960s lodges on the south rim.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental groups like the proposal because it calls for
importing water by train and pipeline from a section of the
Colorado River on the Arizona-California line. Hotels in the
gateway town of Tusayan now pump well water from an underground
aquifer, which environmentalists argue robs water that is vital to
the canyon's delicate ecology.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any project that relies on groundwater pumping is
unacceptable,'' said Dave Simon of Albuquerque, regional director
of one watchdog group, the National Parks and Conservation
Association. ``We are going to have one master-plan development in
one area that is already developed, instead of three or four
developments that will smear the problem over a big area,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Three Indian tribes of the Colorado Plateau have endorsed the
Canyon Forest plan, largely because the developers promise them
jobs, market space for their wares and a museum that gives weight
to Native American views of the Grand Canyon. Although tourism
injects nearly $1 billion a year into the canyon area, the
surrounding county, Coconino, ranks among the 10 poorest in the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   Ack, one of the environmentalists, said from Flagstaff, ``For
the first time, the tribes have been asked to be part of the
economic engine of the Grand Canyon, other than selling trinkets by
the roadside.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
