<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL BRIEFS: PHILADELPHIA MAYOR; HOUSE TERM-LIMITS ADVOCATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Philadelphia Star May Shine Wider  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After decades of being mired in urban doldrums, Philadelphia has
resurged and prospered under the guiding hand of Mayor Edward
Rendell. He is now ranked among the nation's best city leaders, one
seemingly with a bright political future should he choose to shoot
for higher office after he completes his present City Hall tour
this year.
</P>
<P>
   So what does Rendell, a moderate Democrat, have in mind?
</P>
<P>
   He has always said that if he seeks elective office again _ and
he insists he has not made up his mind _ his most likely target
will be the governor's office, which will be up for grabs in 2002
when the incumbent, Tom Ridge, a Republican, completes his second
term.
</P>
<P>
   But some national Democratic leaders think they have a better
idea. They want Rendell to run for the U.S. Senate next year when
Pennsylvania's junior senator, Rick Santorum, a conservative
Republican, comes up for re-election.
</P>
<P>
   Santorum, who squeaked into office in 1994 with just 49 percent
of the vote, is generally considered one of the most vulnerable
Republicans in the Senate. As Democratic election strategists
scheming ways to recapture the Senate see it, a strong Democrat
like Rendell might just be able to take Santorum in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, three leading Senate Democrats _ Robert Torricelli
of New Jersey, chairman of the Democratic Senatorial Campaign
Committee, along with Tom Daschle of South Dakota, the Senate
minority leader, and Edward M. Kennedy of Massachusetts _ are
urging the mayor to jump into the contest.
</P>
<P>
   Rendell has told them he will ``think about it.'' But in his
heart, he says, he would rather hold executive office than
legislative office.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, he adds, should he jump into the Senate contest, he
would have to jump very soon to guarantee he would have enough time
to raise the $10 million or so required to run a good race. Such a
fund-raising effort, he says, would not leave him much time to run
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   For that matter, should Rendell hold off and run instead for
Governor, he would by no means be assured victory. His first
hurdle, and maybe his highest, likely would be the Democratic
primary, in which his toughest opponent most probably would be
State Auditor General Robert Casey Jr., the son of former Gov.
Robert Casey, one of Pennsylvania's most popular and powerful
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Breaks Promise, Pays a Price  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After months of maybe-maybe not pondering, Rep. George
Nethercutt of Spokane, Wash., finally made up his mind last week.
He will seek a fourth term.
</P>
<P>
   But that decision did not mark the end of his struggle over
whether to renege on his 1994 campaign promise to serve no more
than three terms. Anything but.
</P>
<P>
   In a real sense, the real struggle for Nethercutt, a
conservative Republican, is just beginning.
</P>
<P>
   He does not have a Democratic opponent yet. But he has an
opponent nevertheless _ U.S. Term Limits, the leading term-limits
advocacy group and once his leading supporter.
</P>
<P>
   Of the half-dozen or so members of the House who so far this
year have broken or are thinking about breaking promises to
voluntarily limit their tours on Capitol Hill, Nethercutt is
perhaps the best known. When he initially made his promise back in
1994, U.S. Term Limits rushed to adopt him as its poster child and
worked mightily to insure his narrow, upset victory over House
Speaker Tom Foley, a 15-term veteran of Congress and a passionate
opponent of term limits.
</P>
<P>
   But when Nethercutt's resolve to stick with his promise began to
crumble earlier this year, U.S. Term Limits, embarrassed, had a
change of heart. It took to the Spokane airwaves with ads that
demanded, first humorously but eventually stridently, that he keep
his word.
</P>
<P>
   The failure of that campaign has strengthened the resolve of
U.S. Term Limits to stay on Nethercutt's case. Rather than cancel
the campaign now that the Nethercutt promise lies shattered in
pieces, the organization sees the ad effort as more crucial than
ever to the future of term limits and says that an extra $1 million
will be poured into spots.
</P>
<P>
   A number already are running, some on television, some on radio,
some in newspapers. All were designed, according to Term Limits
officials, to educate voters about term limits and politicians who
``cynically'' break promises to abide by them.
</P>
<P>
   In one television spot, a parent asks: ``When a politician
clearly gives his word, then breaks it, how do I explain that to my
children?''
</P>
<P>
   In a radio spot, a Term Limits official labels Nethercutt ``just
another career politician who'd say anything to get elected.''
</P>
<P>
   A newspaper ad says that the word ``Nethercutt'' can now serve
as a verb meaning ``to go back on one's word,'' or ``as an
adjective with its usage synonymous with `hypocrite,' `opportunist'
and `dishonest.'''
</P>
<P>
   Nethercutt is fighting back with his own ad campaign, telling
voters in his district, the Washington 5th, that he feels his work
on Capitol Hill is unfinished and that he made a ``mistake'' five
years ago by promising to limit his time in office.
</P>
<P>
   And he is not without an important ally in the coming fight.
</P>
<P>
   The National Republican Congressional Committee, deeply worried
about a possible Democratic takeover of the House in 2000, has
promised to do ``anything we can'' to help him hold his seat.
</P>
<P>
   Bush or Gore, But Who Cares?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It may seem like the presidential campaign of 2000 is in full
swing, given all the hoopla about Al Gore and George W. Bush
hitting the campaign trail. But consider what the Pew Research
Center, a major public policy study group, found when it sent its
polltakers out a few days ago to test the nation's political pulse:
</P>
<P>
   Two out of three voters said they were paying little or no
attention to Election 2000 at this point.
</P>
<P>
   Or to quote from the Center's analysis of its findings:
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all background noise to the average American voter. Just
1 in 10 Americans are following election stories very closely.
Fully one third are totally tuning campaign news out.''  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-99 1524EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990619.0152 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-19 15:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2054 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-EMERITUS-N     06-19 1040
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-EMERITUS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAST KNICKS PRAISE AND CRITICIZE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By IRA BERKOW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   He was home in New Jersey, in more or less 3-point range from
Manhattan, after recently having undergone back surgery, and so
could hardly have been in the New York Knicks' lineup. Then again,
he hasn't been in a Knicks' lineup since he retired from basketball
19 years ago, in 1980. But the memories of having been a part of a
championship Knick team for Earl (the Pearl) Monroe, as well as for
his teammates, remain vivid, and have been rekindled with the
appearance of the current Knick team in the National Basketball
Association finals.
</P>
<P>
   Walt Frazier and Monroe, who has been involved in business
ventures including the record industry since his retirement,
comprised one of the most exciting and effective backcourts ever.
</P>
<P>
   In 1973, Monroe and Frazier _ along with the other starters,
Bill Bradley, Dave DeBusschere and Willis Reed, and the bench of
Henry Bibby, Dean Meminger, Dick Barnett, Jerry Lucas, John
Gianelli and Phil Jackson, and coached by the late Red Holzman _
won the Knicks' second, and last, NBA title. Those '73 Knicks have
kept an eye on the '99 version.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not surprised that they've done so well, since I think
they have the talent to be where they are,'' Monroe said, ``but I'm
just surprised that after all that has gone on in the season that
they're still there.''
</P>
<P>
   Monroe cited the injuries to Patrick Ewing and, most recently,
Larry Johnson, and the organizational upheavals from the demotion
of General Manager Ernie Grunfeld to the controversies surrounding
the playing time of Marcus Camby and a starting role for Latrell
Sprewell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think once Patrick got hurt,'' Monroe said, ``the other
players no longer thought they'd have to defer to him in the
post-up game and guys were allowed to now play their game. They had
been in a system that was not suited to them. And Sprewell came in
and his speed opened up eyes. I thought Johnson started playing a
lot freer. But they also drew inspiration from Patrick's
determination to play when he was in such pain.''
</P>
<P>
   Can the Knicks beat San Antonio? ``The Spurs are a problem
because they are so big and so athletic,'' Monroe said. ``But the
biggest thing the Knicks have going for them is that Houston and
Sprewell can turn games around. If you have two good guards, you
can always be in a position to win.''
</P>
<P>
   In Los Angeles, Bibby, the third guard in 1973, and now the
coach at Southern California, observed that ``somebody, or
somebodies, has truly brought this Knick team together.''
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing that's happened is that Jeff Van Gundy has shown his
true colors as a leader and coach,'' Bibby said. ``And maybe it was
Van Gundy who has made this team go from that point. Or Patrick as
an inspirational leader. Or one of the players, Sprewell or Houston
or Camby. And yet it hasn't been just one guy who you can point to.
Everyone on a different night has come up with a big game. You
wonder, when did the light come on for them?''
</P>
<P>
   From Strawberry, Calif., a town of 150 in the Sierra Nevada
Mountains, Gianelli, a substitute center in 1973 who now works in
the family business of repairing farm equipment, was impressed with
the Knicks' defense. ``I like how they double-team and rotate,'' he
said. ``Looks to me like they're all on the same page.''
</P>
<P>
   Willis Reed, the center on the 1970 and 1973 championship teams,
and now an executive with the Nets, said: ``Earlier in the year, I
said that if this team could learn to play together, it could be
very successful. The addition of three new players _ Sprewell,
Camby and Kurt Thomas _ has made a huge difference, and Van Gundy
has learned to coach this team. This group of players has come to
believe in each other, and to accept their roles.''
</P>
<P>
   Frazier, the Knicks' television analyst, has marveled at the
team's resurgence. ``They remind me of the 1973 team in that we had
injuries to key players _ Willis was out for a while, Earl and Dave
were, too _ and we didn't have a great regular season, either. But
we came together in the playoffs. And guys started to step up, as
they have with the current team. Chris Childs is one of them. I
think he was the catalyst in the Indiana series, the way he held
down Mark Jackson, especially at the end.''
</P>
<P>
   How would the '73 team match up against the '99 group?
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd do very well,'' Monroe said. ``We'd be a much smarter
team than, say, Indiana. We wouldn't have let Camby jump over
people. We would have put a body on him. And we had a whole team of
shooters. And we had all veteran players. And we could be more
effective in the half-court offense. The half-court offense was our
forte.''
</P>
<P>
   Bibby said: ``Not to take anything away from the current bunch,
but we had five starters who were all-pro, plus Lucas and Barnett
who had been all-pro, and I think that Jackson and Gianelli and I
could have started for most other teams. In the finals, I think we
would have beaten them in five games.''
</P>
<P>
   Reed said: ``They are different eras. . . . But we always think
we're better than the other guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Holzman, who died last October at age 78, wrote an
autobiography, ``Red on Red,'' with Harvey Frommer, in 1997. In it,
Holzman said the 1973 team was better than the often more
celebrated 1970 championship Knicks because it ``had a little more
size, depth, dimension.''
</P>
<P>
   Holzman's players invariably had a high regard for him, and for
his approach, with its emphasis on defense, seeing the open man and
mutual respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``He expected everyone to act as a responsible adult,'' Bradley
has said, ``and he treated players accordingly.''
</P>
<P>
   After the team won its first title, in 1970, the owner Irving
Felt ended his remarks at a team party with, ``If Red Holzman
doesn't come to see me tomorrow about changing his contract, then
he's not as smart as I think he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Holzman wrote: ``Winning that championship was wonderful.
There's no feeling quite like it, but the way Felt acted was icing
on the cake. It showed his character, appreciation and generosity.
He really didn't have to make that gesture in public.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the way, I was in his office the next day.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-99 1527EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
