<DOCNO> NYT19990619.0154 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-19 15:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2056 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COX-KOSOVO-DIARY-0620     06-19 1477
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-KOSOVO-DIARY-0620 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A REFUGEE'S DIARY: ONE WOMAN'S JARRING RETURN TO KOSOVO
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    By MARCIA KUNSTEL 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ One week ago, Florie Topanica began the
jarring emotional passage that more than one million Kosovar
Albanians will make in coming weeks, returning to uncertainty,
sadness and a hard new beginning that will be too daunting for some
even to attempt.
</P>
<P>
   Flora, as she is called, is my translator and now my friend, a
brave young woman who came with me to Kosovo on the day NATO troops
opened the border from Macedonia. Not knowing what awaited beyond
that border, this slight, pretty 25-year-old managed to swallow her
fear of the menace she had left behind in Pristina, when her family
boarded a train on April 3 and became refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Now she was frantic to learn what happened to her home, to her
friends and _ we discovered later _ to her boyfriend, who had been
imprisoned since 1995 for belonging to an illegal political
organization, one agitating for Kosovo independence.
</P>
<P>
   Here is her story:
</P>
<P>
   SATURDAY, June 12 -- Flora called at 8 a.m. as arranged. I had a
surprise. ``Can you be ready at 8:45? We'll go to Pristina today.''
</P>
<P>
   Furious shopping for water, towels, food, a rack for the car,
and we were on the road. The Macedonian driver and another woman
journalist, an old friend from Moscow days, completed the team.
</P>
<P>
   Soon another surprise. The border guard was a Serb, not a NATO
soldier as expected.
</P>
<P>
   Serbian soldiers had hounded Flora's neighbors the day her
family left Pristina, giving them ten minutes to leave or face
death. They had taken her boyfriend Liburn four years earlier. They
had killed some friends and harassed others. Of course she was
scared.
</P>
<P>
   The border guard summoned her from the car.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, my God,'' said Flora. He started questioning her, but we
intervened. He had no right to stop a journalistic team in a NATO
military convoy with NATO credentials.
</P>
<P>
   He wilted, and we soon advanced into a surreal world of burned
and shattered villages, homes with no families, fields with no
farmers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, my God. Look at that. Look, there is no one,'' she said
again and again, pointing to roofless houses or gutted stores.
</P>
<P>
   Exhilarating moments when people finally appeared _ ethnic
Albanians joyously greeting our convoy of NATO tanks and trucks _
were followed by near panic once we hit Pristina. We lost the
convoy when we had stopped to talk to villagers, and now we were
alone in the twilight hours in a city thick with armed Serbian
soldiers and police. There was shooting. And no NATO presence in
sight.
</P>
<P>
   Journalists were at the Grand Hotel, we had heard, but it had
been a Serbian social spot where ethnic Albanians like Flora hadn't
dared go for years. We drove past, and luckily found a NATO tank
and armed soldiers guarding it. One intervened when a Serb driver
yelled at us for parking in a spot he was saving.
</P>
<P>
   Flora was shaken _ as were all of us _ by the time we walked
through the rain into the jammed lobby and up to a mezzanine media
center. Correspondents and hangers on were everywhere, mixed with
Serbian guys in uniforms just hanging out. I linked arms with Flora
and stayed close.
</P>
<P>
   No rooms available, so we slept on the mezzanine floor along
with dozens of other new arrivals. It seemed safe.
</P>
<P>
   SUNDAY, June 13 -- In daylight we drove around Pristina,
listening to Belgrade radio play patriotic songs, watching the
mostly Serbian pedestrians glower at us as we passed.
</P>
<P>
   Between news tasks, we went to Flora's place.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my house,'' she said, as we reached her apartment
building on the main Pristina drag. ``These are our flowers,'' she
said, pointing to the plants on the fourth floor stairs. ``This is
our door.'' It was number 15.
</P>
<P>
   But the key didn't work.
</P>
<P>
   Children could be heard somewhere. Was it behind her door, or
another? ``I think there are people inside,'' she whispered. But no
one answered either then or later when we returned.
</P>
<P>
   Then another bad sign. Flora went to the flat of a girlfriend,
and found the gypsy neighbors who had been left the key for
safekeeping had stolen valuables and trashed the place. It was so
filthy that Flora vomited.
</P>
<P>
   Yet a further troubling moment. ``Oh, I think that is my car,''
Flora said, pointing out a red four-door. Her family car, as most
others left behind by refugees, had been stolen. We followed and
watched four big guys get out after they parked by an apartment
building. Maybe it could be pursued later.
</P>
<P>
   A last stop at the International Committee of the Red Cross for
an interview, and Flora added her own question. Did they have lists
of prisoners, especially men transferred from Kosovo prisons into
Serbia as she believe Liburn had been. Sorry. They couldn't help
yet.
</P>
<P>
   MONDAY, June 14 -- A morning stop at a headquarters of the
Kosovo Liberation Army, the guerrillas who fought for independence,
turned up several old buddies, none of whom had news about Liburn.
</P>
<P>
   On the way out a young doctor told us about deep needs for
medical help in this neighborhood. He took us to patients who
included seven emaciated men in four different locations, some
badly injured, all of whom the Serbs suddenly had released from
prisons on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Flora did not have to explain her pale face or subsequent
silence after she translated their stories of prison life _ the
beatings, the filth, meager food, overcrowding.
</P>
<P>
   Liburn must be like these men, she said, if he is still alive.
</P>
<P>
   TUESDAY, June 15 -- With a Red Cross food convoy we drove to a
mountain town about an hour to the west, where Kosovar Albanians
were returning from hideouts higher up in the hills.
</P>
<P>
   The vexing problem Flora kept pondering: how to break into her
family's apartment without getting blown up, if it's boobytrapped,
or shot, if it's occupied by Serbian squatters.
</P>
<P>
   Later, we re-visited a returned refugee who had watched in
frustration on Monday the Serbian troops going in and out of his
house that they had taken over in April. Children who got into the
gated compound said the soldiers were filling their trucks with his
stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Serbs had pulled out, and he returned to find utter
devastation. Flora was so disturbed that she almost got sick again.
</P>
<P>
   WEDNESDAY, June 16 -- Suddenly a stellar day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wonderful news!'' Flora said. She had learned that her
brother, here as a translator for NATO troops, had broken the lock
on the family apartment. No one was inside, but all their
possessions were. Someone must have tampered with the lower lock,
perhaps trying to get in while the family was in refuge in
Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   She found the apartment exactly as her family had left it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my desk. These are my books,'' she said, touching them
as though they were treasures.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday was a double header.
</P>
<P>
   Later we drove up to the hillside neighborhood that was the site
of her father's small plastic bottle factory. He is an economist _
as Flora is studying to become _ but lost his job in a government
institute after Yugoslavia's Serb-dominated government withdrew
Kosovo's autonomy in 1989 and installed a Serbian provincial
administration. Without the factory, he worried, the family would
have no income.
</P>
<P>
   Their luck was phenomenal. The one-room factory also was intact,
the machinery we saw through a busted window seemed complete, the
building not grenaded or shelled as so many there had been.
</P>
<P>
   We needed to talk that day to Serbs who were becoming the next
round of refugees, but we didn't even ask Flora to translate for
us. She still felt the Serbs hated her, and she knew she held no
liking for them. She agreed with most Kosovar Albanians that Kosovo
would fare best without a Serbian population.
</P>
<P>
   THURSDAY, June 17 and beyond -- Devastation is everywhere.
Nothing much works. Thousands of people are missing or in prison.
Flora has a small, but whole apartment for her family. She has no
permanent job. And the man she loves is still in danger, if, as she
said, he is still alive.
</P>
<P>
   The numbing reports of atrocities by Serb forces are being
joined now by increasing numbers of stories about KLA fighters and
other angry ethnic Albanians exacting retribution through
kidnappings or shootings.
</P>
<P>
   One day we passed a wrecked car, whose Kosovar Albanian driver
had been shot as he traveled down the street. The next day we
passed ethnic Albanian men being detained by NATO troops on
suspicion of murdering a Serbian civilian.
</P>
<P>
   Flora is disturbed about what these acts portend, but she tries
to be positive.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are confused now. They only think, 'Oh, look what
happened to me,''' she said. ``Things will calm down. It will get
better.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
