<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990619.0157 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-19 15:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2060 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-IBF-3TAKES-ART-NY     06-19 1085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-IBF-3TAKES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEE AND THE IBF MAY FACE CHARGES BY U.S. GRAND JURY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mexico, Venezuela, N.J.)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1983, Robert W. Lee Sr. quietly formed the International
Boxing Federation. If the announcement lacked both drama and
publicity, Lee did not lack for ambition: the IBF, he pledged,
would be built from scratch with the idea that it would objectively
rank the world's top fighters and create its own set of legitimate
championship titles.
</P>
<P>
   As the leader of a new boxing organization, one that claimed it
wanted to clean up a sport rife with wrongdoing, Lee was a curious
candidate to play the part of maverick reformer.
</P>
<P>
   He had never been a serious boxer or trainer or promoter, having
spent most of his professional life as a homicide detective in
Hudson County, N.J. More odd, however, Lee, at the very moment he
was creating the IBF, was deputy commissioner of the New Jersey
Athletic Commission, a governmental agency charged with monitoring
boxing in the state. Federal agents investigating corruption in
boxing in the early 1980s had said they had evidence that Lee
accepted illegal payoffs in his job with the state commission.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, none of it _ a lack of experience, a possible
conflict of interest, a brush with the FBI _ mattered. Lee founded
the IBF (originally calling it the U.S. Boxing Association
International), and within months staged its first championship
fight. For the last 16 years, the IBF, along with the World Boxing
Council and the World Boxing Association, has functioned as one of
the sport's three sanctioning organizations, and thus as one of its
most powerful forces.
</P>
<P>
   The IBF has anointed champions, but it also has been sued by
fighters who have claimed, among other things, that its ranking
system was fixed. It has made millions of dollars, but has also
been at the center of some of the sport's great embarrassments _
most recently when the performance of a judge it appointed in the
Evander Holyfield-Lennox Lewis fight March 13 set off a New York
City criminal investigation into whether the bout was rigged.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Lee and the IBF, and with them another layer of boxing's
credibility, seem to be in additional peril.
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors in Newark, in a broad grand jury
investigation that predates the Holyfield-Lewis debacle, have been
submitting evidence of possible criminal conduct by the IBF, which
is based in East Orange, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   The grand jury is looking into whether the IBF accepted payoffs
in return for ranking certain fighters. Over the last year, the
organization's financial records have been seized; promoters,
managers and boxers have been questioned about a variety of
improper schemes, and the promoter Don King, who has worked closely
with the IBF over the years, has said he believes prosecutors have
targeted Lee and the IBF in an attempt to ultimately indict him.
</P>
<P>
   Lee has denied any wrongdoing, saying he believes he is being
investigated because prosecutors have failed in their attempts to
go after the WBC and the WBA, which are based in Mexico and
Venezuela, respectively. ``I'm an easy target because I'm in the
United States,'' Lee said a few weeks ago. ``I'm here, and I'm
accessible.''
</P>
<P>
   King, whose business offices in Florida were raided by federal
agents this month, said before the raid that he expected to be
indicted, but also predicted that he would be exonerated. According
to people who have testified before the grand jury, prosecutors
have focused on him because they are interested in seeing whether
he might have used his influence over Lee to turn the IBF and its
titles into his own fiefdom.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know they're trying to get Bob Lee,'' King said, ``but it
always ends up with me. I've been indicted all my life. But I'm not
going to deal with smokescreens and hypotheticals, and I'm not
going to give up my most basic right _ the presumption of
innocence.''
</P>
<P>
   Boxing's sanctioning organizations have long drawn criticism.
The WBC and the WBA operated as fringe groups in the sport until
the early 1960s, publishing rankings of fighters and designating
their own sets of champions, but being all but ignored by the most
powerful promoters and fighters. That changed in the late 1970s
when television networks, reacting to repeated scandals in boxing,
turned to the two organizations in an attempt to create a credible
mechanism for ranking fighters and staging legitimate championship
fights.
</P>
<P>
   Despite having been enlisted to help the networks and the sport,
the newly powerful organizations were soon criticized for their own
alleged misdeeds _ manipulating their rankings, extracting enormous
sums of money from fighters, establishing alliances with promoters
that called into question the integrity of both fights and
champions.
</P>
<P>
   When the committee on governmental affairs conducted the most
recent U.S. Senate investigation of boxing in 1992, it did not look
into the sanctioning organizations and their ranking systems, so
convinced was it of their illegitimacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was so universally accepted that they're arbitrary and
subject to manipulation that we didn't think it would serve any
purpose to spend six months looking into them,'' said Paul Feeney,
a legislative aide to Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz..
</P>
<P>
   As it happened, it was a scandal involving how boxers were
ranked that lifted the sanctioning organizations to positions of
real influence. In 1977, during a boxing tournament televised by
ABC Sports, it was revealed that the rankings of the boxers
involved, then set by The Ring magazine's experts, were flawed, and
that the records of some boxers were bogus.
</P>
<P>
   Embarrassed, ABC turned to the WBA and the WBC, which had been
formed decades before. The organizations took over the ranking of
the top boxers, deciding who would fight whom and when.
</P>
<P>
   The organizations, which made occasional nods toward the
interests of fighters _ establishing safety regulations such as
shortening the lengths of championship fights _ became the
beneficiary of television's effort to, in effect, purchase
credibility. Executives from ABC and other networks paid the
organizations for the right to broadcast a sanctioned fight, and
fighters gave up a piece of their purse for the privilege of having
a shot at a sanctioning organization's title.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Quickly, a dynamic of widespread coziness took hold.
</P>
<P>
   The interests at work in this dynamic were easy to see. One one
hand, television executives eager to offer the viewing public a
reliable product came to depend on at least the surface seriousness
of, say, a W.B.C.-sanctioned championship, one to be fought for by
boxers whose rankings said they were deserving. On the other hand,
the promoters ingratiated themselves with the sanctioning bodies,
recognizing that title fights meant more money. And the sanctioning
bodies set fees for their championships, often taking as much as
three percent of each fighter's purse.
</P>
<P>
   It did not take long, then, for people in boxing to conclude
that in using the sanctioning bodies to name champions, set
rankings and strip fighters of their titles if they did not box
designated opponents, one scandal had simply replaced another.
</P>
<P>
   In 1983, Bob Arum, a longtime promoter, claimed in a magazine
article that a WBA official, Pepe Cordero, had extorted $500,000
from him in order for Arum's fighter, Ray Mancini, to gain a
championship fight. Arum repeated the charge in a recent interview.
Cordero, who was never charged or disciplined as a result of the
allegation, died years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Others, though, made similar allegations. In the end, the FBI's
early-1980's study did not result in the prosecution of major fight
figures, but investigators nevertheless formed some conclusions
about the sanctioning organizations.
</P>
<P>
   ``They collect percentages of a fighter's purse in sanctioning
fees every time he fights,'' Joseph Spinelli, a former agent who
led the investigation, said. ``No one knows where it goes or who it
goes to. They're not accountable to anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Many promoters are quite frank about their efforts to get close
to the sanctioning organizations. It has been a ritual for years,
for example, for promoters to underwrite the costs of the
organizations' annual conventions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like everything else,'' said the promoter Butch Lewis,
whose records on his dealings with the IBF have been subpoenaed by
the FBI in the current investigation. ``You go to the conventions,
put on a cocktail party, you make donations to the conventions.
That's what you do to stay in business.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Marley, a former publicist for King who now manages a
number of boxers, agreed that the relationships between promoters
and sanctioning organizations could look suspect.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were always hints being dropped,'' Marley said of
rankings being put up for sale. ``If you're a discerning manager
you see them. I can't give you any evidence. I don't have any
receipts. I don't think guys are bringing bags of cash and handing
them out to these organizations. But they do things like buy
wedding presents for people.''
</P>
<P>
   Boxing always has attracted eclectic characters _ from the
heroic to the criminal, the comic to the sad. Thus the story of Bob
Lee and his rise within boxing is not entirely difficult to fathom.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, who at 67 is among the most powerful people in the game as
the head of the IBF, was not much of a boxer as a youth, a broken
finger cutting short his career after four fights. He served as a
detective with the Hudson County Police Department, later lost an
election for sheriff in Union County, and then took up a
bureaucrat's job in the New Jersey consumer affairs office.
</P>
<P>
   In 1978, though, Lee was assigned to assist Althea Gibson, the
former tennis great, in her job as the state's athletic
commissioner. Part of his job was helping attract boxing events to
Atlantic City.
</P>
<P>
   Almost from the start, questions were raised about Lee's
conduct. In 1980, the FBI, then conducting its initial
investigation into boxing, said an undercover agent had made an
audiotape that recorded Lee's acceptance of a bribe as payment for
granting a promoter's license. Though the investigation did not
result in indictments, the agents gave information on Lee to the
New Jersey authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Lee has maintained that the bribery claim is unfounded.
</P>
<P>
   State officials did not take action against Lee on the bribery
accusation, but four years later they did force his removal from
office. Lee, it turned out, had worked for the WBA, and later
formed the IBF, while he continued to work at his state job
overseeing boxing. In 1984, after an investigation by the state
attorney general's office, Lee was forced by the New Jersey
Investigation Commission to give up his state job because of what
were termed ethical misjudgments. Among the findings was that Lee
had solicited funds for the IBF from the very boxing people he was
regulating.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he saw his role as more boosterism than regulator,''
said James Morley, who headed the state investigation. ``Most of
those guys thought they were there to find ways to get more boxing
in New Jersey, not to regulate it.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Woodworth, the manager of Roberto Garcia, the IBF's junior
lightweight champion, said Lee's unusual route to becoming the head
of a sanctioning organization was a damning commentary on the
sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know there's something wrong with these organizations when
Bob Lee can go from being fired as a state commissioner to being
president of a sanctioning organization,'' Woodward said. ``But
this is the business of boxing.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   At least one boxing manager, Ron Weathers, said he had told the
grand jury in Newark that part of that business involved direct
payoffs to the IBF Weathers said in a recent interview that he had
told prosecutors of ``several occasions'' on which he had made
improper payments in order to get his fighters ranked.
</P>
<P>
   ``For years,'' Weathers said of the IBF and the other
sanctioning bodies, ``you could only do business with these
organizations if you paid them.''
</P>
<P>
   One fighter, William Guthrie, gave a sworn statement two years
ago claiming that the IBF's tactics could involve tools other than
money. Guthrie, a former IBF lightweight champion, sued King,
alleging that in using his influence with Lee, King had told Lee
not to grant Guthrie a title fight if Guthrie decided to sign with
a different promoter. Guthrie said Lee had told him that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no doubt what they were saying was true,'' Guthrie said
in an interview on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Lee said he has been singled out for criticism and punishment
because he is black.
</P>
<P>
   ``My two predecessors, Abe Greene and Joe Maloney, who were both
white, they had done the same thing I did,'' Lee said. ``I copied
what they did. Yet they never found them to be in ethical
violations.''
</P>
<P>
   After the state attorney general's investigation, Lee continued
to be haunted by his past. In 1992, he was called before the Senate
committee and was asked to answer questions about the FBI's claim
that he had taken a bribe in 1980. Lee repeatedly invoked his Fifth
Amendment privilege and declined to answer questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the stuff they were talking about,'' Lee said
recently, ``nothing ever happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Much, though, was happening with the IBF. Marvin Hagler fought
in its first championship event in 1983. Larry Holmes soon became
one of its champions. Its conventions attracted all the major
promoters. Lee's son, Robert W. Lee Jr., became a senior officer.
The organization's coffers filled with cash, as it took a greater
percentage of a fighter's purse than any other sanctioning body.
</P>
<P>
   ``The number of fighters who have come through here and have
been world champions, I'm happy about that,'' Lee said as he sat in
the IBF's offices. ``If you think about it, we've put a lot of
money in the pockets of these guys.''
</P>
<P>
   The IBF has only five full-time employees, and its finances are
not subject to any kind of independent oversight. According to
people who have testified before the grand jury in Newark,
prosecutors are looking into the question of whether improper
payments to IBF officials were made through the overcharging of
sanctioning fees.
</P>
<P>
   Suspicions about how the IBF has conducted its business have
certainly been widespread for years. Arum, the promoter who claimed
he was required to pay off a WBA official for a prize fight more
than a decade ago, said that his early optimism about the IBF
quickly dissipated, and that he has given testimony before the
Newark grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   ``These were American guys who weren't going to be corrupt,''
Arum said he once thought. But, he said, ``I began hearing rumors
as early as the end of the 1980s that guys were paying for
ratings.''
</P>
<P>
   The current federal investigation of the IBF, according to law
enforcement officials, grew directly out of a lawsuit brought
against the organization by Michael Moorer, a former heavyweight
champion. In his 1994 suit, Moorer argued that he had been wrongly
denied the IBF's No. 1 ranking, and had instead been leapfrogged by
two less-deserving boxers, including Francois Botha, a King fighter
who moved from No. 4 to No. 1. Moorer said he had been told by Lee
that he was not fighting frequently enough to merit the top slot.
</P>
<P>
   In making his case, Moorer and his lawyers obtained the
testimony of managers and television executives. The promoter Dan
Duva, then president of Main Events, said in an affidavit that the
IBF official in charge of rankings, Doug Beavers, had told him that
Lee ordered that Botha be ``unilaterally'' moved to No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the most provocative testimony came from Seth
Abraham, president of Time Warner-HBO Sports. He said in a sworn
statement that King had outlined for him how he would have Botha
moved ahead of Moorer.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that is indeed what happened,'' Abraham said in a recent
interview. ``There is no secret Don knows how to use the
organizations better than anyone I know. But quite frankly all the
promoters do what the organizations allow them to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit was settled, and, according to John Davimos,
Moorer's manager, the fighter received $3 million and a promise
that he could fight for the IBF title in the future. He fought for
the title in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   But according to lawyers involved in the suit, as well as a
number of people who have testified before the grand jury,
prosecutors were intrigued enough by the allegations in the case to
start their own investigation.
</P>
<P>
   A number of promoters, including Butch Lewis and Cedric Kushner,
have either testified before the grand jury or turned over many of
the financial records of their dealings with the IBF
</P>
<P>
   King and others have said that they believe the government's
case has been helped by the work of Beavers, the former IBF
rankings official, who they say worked as an informant for
prosecutors over the last year or more. Beavers, who has since left
the IBF, did not return repeated telephone calls seeking a
response.
</P>
<P>
   George Foreman, who once held the IBF's heavyweight title, also
testified before the grand jury. He said he was questioned
extensively about knowledge of kickbacks for rankings. Foreman said
he told prosecutors he had no direct knowledge of such payoffs, but
that he believed such schemes existed.
</P>
<P>
   He blamed the promoters as well as the sanctioning organization
officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you ever heard the old expression, `Can two walk together
unless they agree?''' Foreman said. ``I believe that's the way it
works.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
