</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-SENATE-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAUTENBERG REJECTS PARTY'S PLEA TO OPPOSE WHITMAN FOR SENATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAVID KOCIENIEWSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ Fearing that they don't have a candidate who can
defeat Christie Whitman and retain a Senate seat their party has
held for almost two decades, Democrats from President Clinton on
down urged Sen. Frank Lautenberg last month to cancel his plans to
retire and instead run for re-election, Democratic officials say.
</P>
<P>
   But Lautenberg, 75, said Friday that after considering the idea,
he told party officials he would not run again next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a decision that I plan to stick by,'' said Lautenberg,
who was reluctant to discuss the details of his talks. ``Frankly,
it's flattering to hear lots of these comments. I don't know where
they were before I had said I wasn't going to run.''
</P>
<P>
   In February, Lautenberg unexpectedly announced that he would not
seek a fourth term, prompting Whitman, a Republican, to declare her
candidacy and setting off a struggle among Democrats in New Jersey
to determine their nominee.
</P>
<P>
   The front-running Democrats are former Gov. Jim Florio, who lost
a re-election bid to Whitman in 1993, and Jon Corzine, the former
co-chairman of the investment banking firm Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co., a
political newcomer who is virtually unknown outside the financial
world but has a personal fortune estimated at $300 million.
</P>
<P>
   The party has been sharply divided between Florio's loyalists in
southern New Jersey and those who have banded together behind
Corzine because they fear a Whitman-Florio rematch would end
disastrously for Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   State Democratic Committee chairman Thomas Giblin has been
trying to minimize the differences between the Florio and Corzine
factions of the party and has scheduled a meeting for Monday at
which Florio, Corzine and the five other potential Senate
candidates will meet with the 21 county leaders. But Giblin
conceded that there are few signs that they will reach a consensus
on a candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Recent public opinion polls have shown Mrs. Whitman with a
substantial lead over Florio, who became widely unpopular after he
pushed through the largest tax increase in state history within six
months of taking office in 1990. The governor also leads Corzine,
who has no political track record and little name recognition. But
Lautenberg pointed out that with 17 months until Election Day,
there is still plenty of time for either of the leading Democratic
contenders to overtake Whitman.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one is writing off the candidacy of Jim Florio or Jon
Corzine,'' Lautenberg said. ``I think they are good people. But
it's a question of how secure they can be in a race against a
fairly popular governor. Folks have encouraged me because they
think it's possible to beat her. We'll have to wait to see.''
</P>
<P>
   Democratic leaders began lobbying Lautenberg in early May, when
Hillary Clinton, who was in New Jersey to visit the Kosovar
refugees who had just arrived at Fort Dix, asked him to reconsider.
The next day, according to a Democrat who is familiar with the
effort, a group of senior Democratic senators invited Lautenberg to
a more formal meeting, where he was again urged to run and was
promised financial support.
</P>
<P>
   In the 10 days that followed, Lautenberg was lobbied by
President Clinton, Vice President Al Gore and at least one member
of the Cabinet, said the official, who spoke on condition of
anonymity. Each of the Democratic leaders argued that, as an
incumbent, Lautenberg would stand the best chance of retaining the
seat for the Democrats and helping the party make inroads into the
Republicans' 55-45 majority in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said that Sen. Robert Torricelli of New Jersey, the
chairman of the Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee, was not
involved in the discussions.
</P>
<P>
   But before Congress adjourned for its Memorial Day recess,
Lautenberg told party leaders that he would not be persuaded to
enter the race.
</P>
<P>
   Giblin said he fears that a deep split over the Senate candidate
could damage the party's chances to retain the seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job,'' he said, ``is to make sure that if there is a
primary, it doesn't end up so heated that the person who loses''
refuses to back the winner in the general election.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have their own worries about the race. Despite
having run three statewide races _ including a 1990 loss to Sen.
Bill Bradley _ Whitman has never won more than 49 percent of the
vote and in 1997 was nearly defeated for re-election by Democrat
Jim McGreevey. The 2000 Senate race will also be run during a
presidential election, when voter turnout in heavily Democratic
urban areas is traditionally high.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
