u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-COL-GOOSE-ROUNDUP-     06-19 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-GOOSE-ROUNDUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.Y. COLUMN: LAST RESORT, AND ROUNDUP, FOR THE GEESE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By IVER PETERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LAKE CARMEL, N.Y. _ They are to the suburbs what pigeons are to
the city, only bigger, meaner, hungrier and dirtier. They are
Canada geese, and here in Putnam County, the turf war between folk
and fowl is about to get down to the pinfeathers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've tried everything else,'' said Annmarie Baisley,
supervisor of Kent, a town of 13,000 that includes Lake Carmel. A
former county auditor, she knows how to add the facts to reach the
truth, however distasteful. ``We've tried growing the buffer up and
we've tried mowing the buffer down and we've tried treating the
eggs. Now we're going to try this.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometime in the next two weeks or so (``Can't tell you when,''
Mrs. Baisley said. ``Secret.'') wildlife specialists will surround
the flock of about 150 geese that inhabit Lake Carmel, herd them
into pens and ship them off to a meatpacker as food for the poor.
</P>
<P>
   In the nearly unbroken chain of geese-flecked suburbs stretching
from Boston to the Outer Banks, it will be only the second time an
East Coast municipality has resorted to the ultimate step in goose
management: a federally authorized roundup and slaughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a comfortable decision,'' said Kathy Doherty, who has
been handling the details in Lake Carmel's goose wars. ``But it's
the only thing left for us to do.''
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, Clarkstown, in Rockland County, became the
first town in New York to get the state and federal permits to
catch and kill geese. It captured and slaughtered a total of 452
birds in 1996 and 1997, and the number of nests in the town's
parks, once about 200, declined to 168. But the outcry from
protesters was so fierce that the town gave up on future roundups.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't do it again because three members of our town board
caved to the pressure, and I think `caved' is the right word,''
said Clarkstown Supervisor Charles Holbrook. And now the number of
nests is up to 187.
</P>
<P>
   Undaunted, Lake Carmel's residents believe they have found the
right combination in Mrs. Baisley and Mrs. Doherty to make the case
for the goose roundup here. Mrs. Doherty, 44, who describes herself
as a housewife _ her husband is an electrical contractor _ is the
volunteer chairwoman of Lake Carmel's advisory committee. She has
worked the phones, the fax and the copying machine to sound out the
experts, weigh the alternatives and secure the necessary permits
for the roundup.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Baisley, the elected supervisor with a no-nonsense attitude
and an unflinching gunfighter's gaze, does not offer her age _ ``I
have a son in high school and I don't want his friends to find out
that I'm old enough to be his grandmother,'' she said. It has been
her job to muster the votes on the Town Board and to deflect the
accusations of murder and worse from animal rights advocates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the point guy; she's the brains,'' Mrs. Baisley said. What
the two have in common, besides each being the mother of four sons,
is the sense that the 200-acre, artificial lake they live by is
being choked by goose droppings, while the jogging paths, bathing
beaches and grassy borders of the lake are encrusted with guano.
</P>
<P>
   Five years of ``addling'' the goose eggs _ killing the embryos _
failed to limit the goose population, they said, and the
alternatives to the roundup have no appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Clarkstown, for example, is spending $36,000 a year to rent
border collies to chase the birds from its parks, but Lake Carmel
is a residential colony set around the water, where barking dogs
would be as much a nuisance as the geese.
</P>
<P>
   Shooting them, with the houses so close, would be illegal. So
now, in late spring, most of the Lake Carmel geese are so heavily
molted that they will soon become flightless. At the right moment,
the roundup crew will move in and Lake Carmel will find out what it
gets for the $8,000 it is paying to have the geese captured.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Mrs. Doherty continues to work as a kind of Mother
anti-Goose to municipalities up and down the Hudson River,
including Bronxville, Yonkers, Putnam Valley and East Fishkill,
that have called for her packet of how-tos on goose removal. ``The
protesters are saying we're going for the easy answers, but this
isn't easy,'' Mrs. Doherty said. ``All we're trying to do is
restore a little balance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
