<SLUG> BC-DC-TEEN-CURFEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASHINGTON'S TEEN-AGER CURFEW TO START SOON 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With school out for the summer, teen-agers
nationwide can look forward to two months of freedom and carefree
summer nights. But not here in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. appeals court ruled on Thursday that teen-agers do not
have an unrestricted right to roam the streets late at night and
that a youth curfew is constitutional. The law, an effort to reduce
crime, bars those under 17 from being in a public place
unaccompanied by a parent or guardian between 11 p.m. and 6 a.m.
Monday through Thursday, and midnight to 6 a.m. Friday to Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The District of Columbia U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled
that the Juvenile Curfew Act of 1995 does not infringe on the
rights of children or the rights of parents to raise their
children.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court's ruling lifts an injunction that has
prevented Washington police from enforcing the law since 1996.
Supporters of the curfew said enforcement was likely to begin soon.
</P>
<P>
   Breaking the curfew could result in 25 hours of community
service for young offenders. Parents could be ordered to pay fines
up to $500 for allowing children to disobey the curfew. There are
eight exceptions to the law, including errands sanctioned by
parents or guardians, emergencies and certain kinds of employment.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Lawrence Silberman wrote the opinion that was joined at
least in part by eight others on the 11-member court. It found that
although young people are generally afforded the same
constitutional guarantees as adults, the state must account for
their ``unique vulnerability and immaturity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel ecstatic, vindicated and pleased,'' said Harold Brazil,
a Democrat on the District Council, who sponsored the original law
four years ago. ``We have given police another tool to fight crime
and protect youngsters. It is very timely in the wake of all this
youth violence.''
</P>
<P>
   Other council members, however, did not share Brazil's
enthusiasm. ``I am a little bit disappointed,'' said Phil
Mendelson, another Democrat on the council. ``As a government, we
have to be circumspect about laws that curtail freedom. If we want
to cut crime we need to deal more with the problems associated with
crime, not people being out of their homes.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Henig of George Washington University, who specializes
in urban policy and directs the university's Washington Area
Studies Center, says that the success of the law lies in the
enforcement. ``If the police choose to use it as a tool, it could
have some positive effects,'' Henig said. ``But having a law on the
books with spotty and erratic enforcement could be worse than
nothing at all.''
</P>
<P>
   The American Civil Liberties Union is critical of the law,
viewing it as an infringement of free movement. In addition, the
ACLU contends that the law intrudes on parents' rights to raise
their children as they see fit.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as people are not acting illegally and irresponsibly
and they have their parents' permission, then they should be
allowed to move freely,'' said a former ACLU president, Robert
Plotkin. ``The curfew presumes that all parents are making bad
decisions and bad choices as a blanket rule.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
