<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-19 15:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2069 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-ART     06-19 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VAN GUNDY'S BIG-TIME COACHING WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   This was at one of those off-day news conferences in San Antonio
the other day, the coach of the Knicks being asked, once again, if
he felt personally vindicated by making it all the way to the NBA
finals after being one Miami bounce of the ball from the
unemployment line.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Van Gundy tried to say the right thing, to be the polished
diplomat, but the longer he went on, the more the victim lurking
inside him cried out to be heard.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing you get used to, if they can get you on results,
they get you on results,'' he said. ``If they can't get you on
results, they get you on relationships. So they're going to get you
on something.''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in the front row, without intending to, I found myself
blurting out, `Who is `they?'''
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy suddenly looked like the napping kid in the back of
the class, called on to explain the theory of relativity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just in general,'' he stammered. ``I mean, whoever _ just to
be _ whoever is being critical of you. We'll just leave it at
whoever. That sounds better.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it sounded absurd.
</P>
<P>
   With all this talk of people out to ``get'' Van Gundy, does he
not yet get what has happened here? Nobody got him and nobody
except Tim Duncan and David Robinson is going to. Whether or not
the Knicks can rally in this series against San Antonio after
losing Game 2, 80-67, Friday night, Van Gundy is walking out of
this season with the Life of Riley, with a huge financial score for
making the finals, with the highest of leaguewide profiles.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks, on the other hand, have no enviable coaching option
to turn to.
</P>
<P>
   While Van Gundy's band played on, Paul Silas was re-signing in
Charlotte, Doc Rivers was taking over in Orlando and Phil Jackson
was ditching O'Hare for O'Neal, Bradley for Bryant. The way this
tumultuous National Basketball Association season has unfolded is
reminiscent of a messy Bill Clinton script.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy has come out of the pileup of organization egos
looking clean and starched, like his former boss. Everyone else has
been indicted for something, except Ernie Grunfeld, who was fired.
</P>
<P>
   Months ago, Van Gundy was just an insecure coach with an
unfamiliar cast. Dave Checketts and Grunfeld might have saved
themselves big trouble by telling Van Gundy he was not going to be
judged on what he did with new players in a short season.
Nonetheless, the way it has worked out, Grunfeld is the only one
here with the right to say, ``If they can't get you on results,
they get you on relationships.''
</P>
<P>
   Playing the good corporate soldier, Checketts fired his ``close
friend'' over dinner and then publicly threw himself to the news
media wolves for not telling the truth about a meeting he had to
take with Jackson. Marcus Camby has convinced himself that Van
Gundy cost him millions on the contract he signed during his
too-soft exile, and maybe he's right. Even Patrick Ewing has lost
out while Van Gundy gained. Ewing was overworked early when he was
out of shape, because the coach wasn't about to let the general
manager ``get'' him for losing games with players he didn't trust,
or want.
</P>
<P>
   If he wasn't pushed in February, maybe Ewing is out on the floor
now, defending the low post, pump-faking Duncan into a few early
fouls and making this series a fairer fight. Through it all, Ewing
remained a Van Gundy man, forgetting that Checketts twice unloaded
bundles of cash into Ewing's account when he might have taken a
harder negotiating tact.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy has done a splendid job, steering his team through the
post-season. No argument there. He beat Pat Riley and Lenny
Wilkens, then coached the legend right out of Larry Bird. He was
right on using Latrell Sprewell off the bench, no matter how
reasonable Sprewell sounds promoting his point. But Van Gundy was
better cast last season as the underdog from the fast-food
drive-through, when Riley slandered him in a fruitless attempt to
fire up his troops. Now Van Gundy is a big-time coach. He has
confided to people that he isn't terribly proud of the political
games he has played this season, but he did play them, and played
them well.
</P>
<P>
   Grunfeld lost. Van Gundy should junk the conspiracy line.
Checketts is boxed in. Camby and Sprewell are under contract.
Whatever they are saying privately, at least they have been perfect
gentlemen when reporters have asked about the coach. Van Gundy
sounds more like a myopic player when he answers ``whoever'' to the
``who is they'' question.
</P>
<P>
   Players will admit they made the wrong defensive read, a foolish
pass, but when they look at the big picture, they mostly see what
they wish to. The coach should know better. Next season is not the
issue right now but it eventually will be, perhaps by the end of
the week. It wouldn't kill Van Gundy and wouldn't hurt his standing
with Camby, to name one Knick, if he just once came out and
admitted that he didn't cover himself with glory back in February
and March. Even if the Knicks go out in four or five against the
Spurs, Van Gundy has won. Now all he has to do is act like a
winner. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-99 1558EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
