<SLUG> BC-GLF-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE CLOWN'S NOSE AND THE TWO PAR 3S 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINEHURST, N.C. _ With a different look and a different finish,
this is a different U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   With the Open at Pinehurst No. 2 for the first time, the pros
need more touch than titanium. If their approach shots slide off
the sloping turtleback greens into grassy hollows, they must hit
delicate chip shots close to the hole if they are to save par. But
every so often their chip is too delicate.
</P>
<P>
   That's when this Open has a different look _ a pro watching his
chip shot roll back to his feet, if not beyond, as if he were
playing miniature golf and had missed the clown's nose.
</P>
<P>
   In other Opens, the look has usually been that of a pro slashing
his ball out of rough deep enough to hide his shoes. Or of his ball
plopping into a pond. Or a putt sliding 6 feet past. But whatever
the pros do or don't do in Sunday's final round, they will be
creating instant Open history here in the Sandhills where the pines
stand tall.
</P>
<P>
   In other years, the Open has usually been blessed with the
memory of what happened before at that year's course. How Jack
Nicklaus won at Baltusrol or Pebble Beach. How Ben Hogan won at
Merion or Oakland Hills. How Bobby Jones won at Winged Foot or
Interlachen. How Arnold Palmer won at Cherry Hills, or how he lost
at Olympic.
</P>
<P>
   But however the winner wins in Sunday's final round, it will be
unique to Pinehurst No. 2, no relation to any other Open anywhere
else.
</P>
<P>
   And with two par-3 holes among Pinehurst No. 2's last four
holes, the finish will be different from that on any of the usual
Open courses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is different,'' said Payne Stewart, the 1991 Open champion
at Hazeltine who finished second last year at Olympic, alluding to
the two short holes. ``Then you've got a par 5, I mean a par 4,
that you play in between those two par 3s.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, who shared the 36-hole lead with David Duval and Phil
Mickelson, was referring to the 489-yard 16th hole, the longest par
4 in Open history.
</P>
<P>
   ``You stand there on the tee at 15 and 17,'' Stewart said, ``and
you think, `I've got a par 3, it's going to be easy.' You've still
got to hit the shot.''
</P>
<P>
   And each tee shot must be precise. The 15th hole is 202 yards to
a severe turtleback green with two gaping bunkers on the right. The
17th is 191 yards with a somewhat flatter green but with swales
that funnel an imprecise tee shot into any of five surrounding
bunkers _ one to the left, one to the rear right and three on the
front right.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 15th is not easy,'' Tiger Woods said. ``Friday it was
gusty and I ripped a 5-iron and didn't get there. And the 17th is
probably the easiest of the par 3s here because at least you have
some room to hit to.''
</P>
<P>
   Then the dreaded 18th awaits: 446 yards slightly uphill, its
fairway left to right. For other PGA Tour and amateur events here
in the past, the traditional ``Sunday'' hole location on the par 4
has been rear left.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the first round on 18,'' said Stewart, ``I drove it in the
left rough and hit a really good 6-iron out of there and it ran up
on the front of the green and then it came back off the green, like
it's supposed to do. And then I just didn't hit my first putt hard
enough from the collar.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1976, the Atlanta Athletic Club had a similar 3-4-3-4 finish.
With a birdie 2 at the 15th and a birdie 3 at the 18th after a
fabled 5-iron to within 3 feet, Jerry Pate won that Open by 2
strokes over Tom Weiskopf and Al Geiberger. In 1909, the Englewood
Golf Club in New Jersey had a 3-4-4-3 finish as George Sargent won
by 4 strokes.
</P>
<P>
   But that was the Atlanta club's only Open (as a bicentennial
favor to the late Bobby Jones), and it's not likely to get another.
Englewood, dug up two decades ago for a condominium complex, never
had another Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes Sunday,'' said David Duval, ``a par on 15 is
going to be very valuable, as well as on 16. But you have more of
an opportunity to make birdie on 17. The 18th is a difficult hole,
but if you hit a good drive, you can access all the difficult pin
positions.''
</P>
<P>
   Phil Mickelson, the left-handed swami of the short game, thought
the two par 3s favored the leader going into the final four holes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you have an opportunity to put a 3 on your score
card, that's the goal,'' he said. ``It's going to be very difficult
to make up shots to par on those two holes. Par on those two short
holes will be a good score. If you have to make it up with the
leader, you're going to hope the leader falters rather than trying
to make something happen.''
</P>
<P>
   But whatever happens, it will be a different finish to a
different Open with a different look.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
