<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SPURS-DUNCAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON BASKETBALL COLUMN: DUNCAN A NO-FRILLS GUY BEYOND HIS YEARS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   On most road trips, Tim Duncan packs the toys of choice for the
Y2K pro athlete: a DVD movie player and a Sony PlayStation. He
likes current cinema and mindless video games, often killing time
on the team plane with young reserve point guard Antonio Daniels.
</P>
<P>
   Yet every so often, an elder teammate will test his 23-year-old
frame of reference.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, for example, veteran center Will Perdue recommended
that Duncan and Daniels check out a sappy basketball movie made in
the mid-1970s: ``One on One'' starring Robbie Benson.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were like, `What's `One on One' and who's Robbie
Benson?''' Perdue said. ``So we brought it on the plane flying to
Minnesota. And they were like, `Hey, that was pretty good.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, nobody got shot. Nobody got killed,'' Perdue said. ``And
they didn't wreck 50 cars.''
</P>
<P>
   They merely played basketball. What a concept.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan is dominating these NBA finals, playing the game that
time forgot. He uses power dribbles to move closer to the rim. He
faces up his defender from 18 feet away on the wing and uses the
glass to bank in shots. He uses his reach to pass to teammates
cutting through the lane. He has this pretty little jump hook that
is beginning to look Waltonesque.
</P>
<P>
   It is an interesting dichotomy: the old-school mind controlling
and nurturing a Generation X body. There are no frills to Duncan's
game, no death stares after a blocked shot and no scowls after a
monster dunk. In San Antonio's victories against the Knicks in the
first two games, and all throughout the playoffs, he has used an
economy of movement and emotion.
</P>
<P>
   Through circumstance and constant work, in two remarkable years
he has become the game's best player. It is the kind of achievement
that would usually establish a player as the example by which to
emulate: the lanky kid from the Virgin Islands who decided to stay
at Wake Forest for his senior year instead of entering the NBA
draft early.
</P>
<P>
   And yet at a time when Commissioner David Stern is considering
an age requirement for players entering the NBA _ and 19-year-old
Lamar Odom is confused about whether to stay or go _ Duncan is
still an anomaly.
</P>
<P>
   Teen-agers still want the money they have been told is owed to
them by their needy support groups and families. Simply, the chance
to be the Kevin Garnett of today outweighs the patience and reward
of being the Duncan of tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   The single largest problem in the NBA today is that young kids
enter the league with a sense of entitlement, the idea that they
are owed something because their university used their number on a
jersey at the campus bookstore and they were not compensated for
it.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan did not attend an Adidas or Nike camp for gifted
basketball players when he was 15 years old. He did not participate
in the cattle call that most American kids are in each summer for
the college and pro scouts that are salivating over their talent.
He was not treated better than most kids his age.
</P>
<P>
   He swam in high school, took up basketball late and decided to
enjoy the fruits of college rather than go to work right away. And
when he did finally enter the NBA, he worked harder on his game
than on his image.
</P>
<P>
   This is the player he has become.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether it's guard or forward or center, I have yet to see a
guy in this age of the game that's come into the league with such
fundamental soundness,'' Perdue said. ``A lot of teams, they draft
the best athlete and work on their games. In Tim's case, he was the
best player and the best athlete.''
</P>
<P>
   In this lockout-scarred season, some of the best reasons to
celebrate the game rather than denigrate it has been the
transformation of young, disconnected knuckleheads into fearless
competitors with passion and purpose. Whether it's Allen Iverson in
the East or Jason Williams and Chris Webber out West, their
scintillating play has forced Stern to view them as bona fide stars
for the millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan, standing taller than the rest, leads the contingent. As
Year 1 of the post-Michael era ends, Duncan is displaying all the
qualities that made people once pay incredible attention to the
game.
</P>
<P>
   There are, of course, marketing kinks to work out in the future.
Duncan is as quiet and introverted as he is good. Some of his
teammates have taken to calling him the silent assassin. At the
moment, he is not inducing any bidding war for his likeness on
Madison Avenue. Maybe another week in the national spotlight and a
title can change that.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, he is keeping amazing perspective during heady
times. According to Perdue, while Duncan has been helping save the
league with his old-school game, he has also managed to keep his
Gen-X priorities in order.
</P>
<P>
   ``He seems to be very grounded,'' Perdue said. ``I've been with
him for over two years now, and he never seems to get overjoyed
about anything _ except about maybe kicking somebody's behind in
Sony PlayStation. He does take a lot of pride in that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
