<HEADLINE>
DRAFTED BY THE CUBS, A SHORTSTOP CHASES HIS DREAM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)  (lb) 
 By ANDREW R. TRIPALDI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Jim Deschaine could not help thinking about the
possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Just the chance of being selected in the major-league baseball
draft on June 2 thrilled Deschaine, the Brandeis University
shortstop. He did not want to get his hopes up. Brandeis is, after
all, known more for its brains than its baseball. He was just
hoping for an opportunity to play professionally.
</P>
<P>
   When the call finally came _ the Chicago Cubs made the junior
infielder their 10th-round selection _ Deschaine became the first
player from Brandeis to be drafted since 1987.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really psyched about being drafted,'' he said. ``It is
definitely a special feeling. I knew that there was a possibility
that I would be selected, but I wasn't counting on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Deschaine, 21, led Brandeis in hitting with a .448 average this
season and set school records for home runs (18), RBIs (70), hits
(78), and runs (70). The Judges (33-10) qualified for the National
Collegiate Athletic Association Division III World Series, but were
eliminated when they lost to Cortland State, 12-5, on May 29.
</P>
<P>
   After signing with Chicago on June 5, Deschaine was immediately
assigned to the Cubs' practice facility in Mesa, Ariz., with the
other draftees and nondrafted free agents. Then, last Tuesday,
Deschaine reported to Chicago's Class A team in Eugene, Ore., in
the Northwest League.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jim is an extremely versatile player,'' Brandeis coach Pete
Varney said of the 6-foot, 180-pound Deschaine. ``That versatility
is going to help him make it to the big leagues.''
</P>
<P>
   For a period last season, however, it appeared that Deschaine
would not play ball again in college, let alone professionally.
During his sophomore year, on April 22, 1998, Deschaine was hit in
the face by a baseball on an attempted steal of third base. Five
minutes later, Deschaine regained consciousness to the news that
the left side of his face was shattered.
</P>
<P>
   At the Eye and Ear Institute, a division of Massachusetts
General Hospital in Boston, a team of three doctors _ an
ophthalmologist, a plastic surgeon and an ear, nose and throat
specialist _ performed surgery, inserting four plates into the left
side of his face.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having to play the waiting game was the worst for me,''
Deschaine said. ``I didn't know if I would ever play baseball
again. Watching my team go on and continue to play games without me
and knowing that I could not play with them was very tough for me
to deal with.''
</P>
<P>
   Deschaine was back on the field by the summer of 1998, playing
with the Hyannis Mets of the Cape Cod League. He says there are no
lingering mental or physical effects from the injury, and actually
claims to be stronger than he was previously.
</P>
<P>
   ``I appreciate the game a little more than I did before the
injury,'' he said. ``Now I feel blessed.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees were Deschaine's favorite team when he was growing
up in Bristol, Conn. And more recently he has made a habit of
watching the many talented young shortstops now in the major
leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is coincidental that I am starting off my career in an age
when the shortstop position is being revolutionized,'' Deschaine
said. ``Between Nomar, Rodriguez and Jeter,'' he said, referring to
Nomar Garciaparra of the Boston Red Sox, Alex Rodriguez of the
Seattle Mariners and Derek Jeter of the New York Yankees, ``there
are a lot of great shortstops in the majors right now that I can
learn from.''
</P>
<P>
   Varney, his college coach, who played professional baseball
himself from 1971 to 1978, including four years as a catcher with
Atlanta and the Chicago White Sox, believes that Deschaine's
biggest challenge will be adjusting to the mental aspects of
playing baseball on a daily basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Players going from college to the pros have to realize that it
doesn't matter whether you get four hits or strike out four times
in a game,'' Varney said, ``because you are going to have to play a
new game the next day. Jimmy will do well because he has something
you can't teach: a love for the game of baseball. When he is on the
baseball field, he always has a smile on his face.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Deschaine had another year of eligibility left at
Brandeis and says he will return at some point to complete his
bachelor's degree in American studies, he does not regret his
decision to leave school early and pursue his dream. ``I want to
make it to the major leagues,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
