<HEADLINE>
SPURS SAY LETDOWN IS UNLIKELY AT GARDEN
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ The San Antonio Spurs have three players with at
least two NBA championship rings, two players who spent years
moiling in the minor leagues before seizing the big stage, and
accomplished college graduates with degrees in finance,
mathematics, computer information systems and psychology.
</P>
<P>
   With a roster full of such experienced, persistent and
intelligent players, the Spurs' coach, Gregg Popovich, is not the
least bit worried about his team becoming overconfident and making
a misstep because of its 2-0 lead over the Knicks in the NBA
finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this group of guys, they don't need any speeches from
me,'' Popovich said after his club's 80-67 victory Friday in Game
2. ``They know what the deal is. You've got guys that have been
there before and some guys that haven't been and want it badly. So
they don't need me to give them a speech or talk about
distractions. They'll be ready to go on Monday.''
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs, who visit Madison Square Garden for Game 3 on Monday
night, have been in this position before, having swept the Los
Angeles Lakers and the Portland Trail Blazers en route to winning
the Western Conference title. After taking command of those series,
they stormed the opponents' home court and played better than they
had in the Alamodome.
</P>
<P>
   After edging the Lakers by three points in Game 2 in San
Antonio, they won by 12 and 11 points, respectively, in Games 3 and
4 at the Forum. Then, after needing a last-gasp 3-pointer by Sean
Elliott to defeat the Blazers at home, they whipped Portland by 22
points at the Rose Garden before clinching the series with a
14-point victory two nights later.
</P>
<P>
   These Spurs, who have won an NBA single-season record 12
consecutive playoff games, are indeed better away from the spacious
Alamodome. They are 6-0 in other teams' buildings, and their only
loss in 13 post-season games came at home.
</P>
<P>
   On the road, they have shot better from the field, from 3-point
range and from the foul line, outrebounded their opponents after
being beaten on the backboards at home, given out more assists,
made more steals and won by an average of 13.4 points, more than 10
points higher than their average victory margin in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, the hostile Garden crowd, with its
close-to-the-court seating and superstars in the front row, is not
likely to faze them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We relish being on the road,'' Spurs guard Mario Elie said.
``We seem to play better and our level of concentration seems to be
higher. Sometimes in this big, ole dome, it's hard to shoot because
the depth perception makes it hard to see the rim sometimes. But in
a regular arena, you get good looks at the basket and that's why we
seem to shoot better and play better on the road.''
</P>
<P>
   Elie, who grew up five minutes from the Garden, is more excited
than anyone. Though he played at the Garden in the 1995 finals with
the Houston Rockets, he was a bit player on that squad. But this
time, he will start and be responsible for holding one of the
Knicks' chief offensive threats, Allan Houston, in check.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nine o'clock Monday night's going to be exciting, hitting that
Garden floor, seeing Jerry Seinfeld and Spike Lee,'' Elie said.
``New York fans are the best fans in the world. The atmosphere at
the Garden is just terrific. We call it the Mecca. That's one of
the best places in the world to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite winning the first two games of this series by a combined
25 points, the Spurs feel there is room for improvement. They were
disappointed in their 43 percent shooting in Game 2 and said their
spacing on the perimeter was horrible at times.
</P>
<P>
   They also admitted to getting confused by the Knicks' sporadic
double-teaming of Tim Duncan and David Robinson in the post. And
for the second straight game, they were outrebounded by the smaller
Knicks, particularly on the offensive boards.
</P>
<P>
   With so much erroneous play to reflect on, the Spurs refuse to
contemplate sweeping their third straight opponent in the playoffs,
even though they could not help but hear the 39,554 fans at the
Alamodome chanting for that Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not worried about what people say,'' Duncan said.
``We're very focused on what we have to do. We haven't played real
well over these last two games and we want to play better. So we're
not thinking sweep. We never think sweep. We think one game at a
time, no matter how cliche that sounds. We're worried about the
next game.''
</P>
<P>
   Duncan, the most reserved young superstar in the league, is the
one with the degree in psychology.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
