<SLUG> BC-CHICAGO-MUSEUM-REAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: IN CHICAGO, 3 LAKEFRONT MUSEUM PROJECTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ROBERT SHAROFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ In a burst of energy that recalls another a century
ago that led to the building of elegant structures for many of the
city's premier cultural institutions, Chicago is once again seeing
a boom in new lakefront museum construction projects.
</P>
<P>
   One institution _ the Chicago Academy of Sciences, the city's
oldest museum _ is abandoning the landmark Beaux-Arts structure in
Lincoln Park it has occupied since 1893 and is moving to a new home
farther north in the park.
</P>
<P>
   Two others, the John G. Shedd Aquarium and the Adler Planetarium
and Astronomical Museum, both of which are part of a museum campus
the city has created in Burnham Park, are significantly expanding
and restoring their buildings.
</P>
<P>
   All three museums make the point that the idea of what a museum
should be has changed so dramatically over the course of the
century that the original buildings _ many of which are now beloved
landmarks _ are as much burdens as assets.
</P>
<P>
   ``As wonderful as it is, the old building is very constricting
in terms of what we can do with exhibits,'' said Paul Bluestone,
vice president of planning and design for the Aquarium.
</P>
<P>
   ``It became obvious that if we wanted to do something radical,
it was unlikely we could do it in that building,'' said Colin
Silvester, chief operating officer of the Academy of Sciences,
referring to deliberations that led to abandoning its longtime
home.
</P>
<P>
   The Academy has made the most dramatic change and, in the
process, has nearly tripled in size to 73,000 square feet. The new
building, which will be finished this fall, overlooks a pond at the
corner of Fullerton Parkway and Cannon Drive. The Academy's
previous home, which is known as the Laflin Building after a
benefactor of the museum, has been renovated and turned into
administrative offices for the nearby Lincoln Park Zoo.
</P>
<P>
   The new building was designed by Ralph Johnson, a principal with
the architectural firm of Perkins &AMP; Will. Johnson is also the
architect for the new Shedd Aquarium project.
</P>
<P>
   The Academy building, which is constructed of cream-colored
stone, is unusually shaped _ basically two trapezoidal wings
connected by a soaring glass and brick atrium. ``I don't think
there's a right angle in the entire building,'' said Silvester.
</P>
<P>
   According to Johnson, the building is meant to suggest a sand
dune, which is what was on the site until the park came into being
in the late 19th century. He added that he also wanted to strike a
blow for modernism in a park known for its many classically
inspired structures. ``I wanted to hit the right millennium,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The building is costing $33 million, $4 million of which is
coming from Richard Notebaert, chief executive of Ameritech Corp.,
a regional telephone company is based here. The donation is an
anniversary gift to his wife, Peggy, who is vice chairwoman of the
Academy's board of trustees. The building will be known as the
Peggy Notebaert Nature Museum.
</P>
<P>
   The Academy is using the building as an opportunity to both
raise its profile and redefine itself. ``We're not taking any of
the exhibits from the old building,'' said Silvester.
</P>
<P>
   The highlight of the new building will be a 4,300-square-foot
butterfly haven that will house several dozen indigenous butterfly
species. The haven, as well as the other exhibits, is being
designed by Lee H. Skolnik Architecture &AMP; Design Partnership, a New
York based firm that specializes in creating exhibits.
</P>
<P>
   The Shedd project is a similarly bold reimagining of the
nation's oldest and largest indoor aquarium.
</P>
<P>
   The Shedd consists of an elegant 1929 Beaux-Arts structure
designed by Graham, Anderson, Probst &AMP; White and a modern addition,
the Oceanarium, that was finished in 1990. The new project involves
both restoring and reconfiguring the original building and adding
two new partially underground wings.
</P>
<P>
   The first phase of the project, the restoration of the museum's
soaring entry hall and skylit central rotunda, opened in early May.
The rotunda contains one of the museum's most popular exhibits, a
90,000-gallon tank swarming with barracudas, stingrays, moray eels
and other life native to the Caribbean. The tank has been totally
rebuilt and reconfigured in a way that makes it possible to isolate
some of the smaller species. ``This way, the big fish don't eat
them,'' said Bluestone.
</P>
<P>
   The next phase, which involves connecting and partially gutting
two of the building's galleries and installing an elaborate
walk-through diorama of life along the banks of the Amazon River,
is currently under way and is expected to be finished next June.
</P>
<P>
   Ground will be broken shortly for the final phase, the two new
30,000-square-foot wings on the north and south sides of the
building. The south wing, which will contain a 350,000-gallon shark
tank and several smaller tanks that will approximate life in a
Philippine Islands coral reef, will be finished in 2002. The north
wing, which will consist of life indigenous to the Great Lakes
area, will follow at a date yet to be determined.
</P>
<P>
   The project _ minus the projected Great Lakes wing, which is at
an early stage of development _ will cost about $85 million and is
being driven by a fundamental shift in the way aquatic life is
displayed in modern aquariums.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, marine life was grouped by water temperature and
salinity. Thus, all animals that lived in warm, salty water
anywhere in the world were in the same gallery.
</P>
<P>
   The new approach is to focus on specific geographic regions and
replace rows of individual aquariums with spectacular, interactive
exhibits that usually involve large tanks and an expanded animal
population. The overall effect owes as much to Walt Disney as to
Jacques Cousteau.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the Amazon exhibit alone,'' said Bluestone, ``we're going
to have birds and monkeys, a marmoset, a sloth, a 30-foot anaconda
and other land animals. We're becoming a place that is part
aquarium, part botanical garden, part zoo and part museum of
natural history.''
</P>
<P>
   The Adler Planetarium also is doing a top-to-bottom renovation
of its original 1930 Art Deco building. The building, which has 12
sides adorned with astrological signs and is topped by a dome, was
designed by Ernest Grunsfeld Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Adler opened a new $20-million wing that curves
around the original building like a glass collar and contains a new
virtual reality theater, as well as several exhibits and a
restaurant. The current $10-million renovation, which will be
finished this fall, aims both to correct some past remodeling sins
and to update the museum's facilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Adler originally was a planetarium with a few exhibits
people could look at while they were waiting for the show to
start,'' said museum president Paul Knappenberger. ``What we're
doing now is creating a full-fledged astronomy museum with 45,000
square feet of exhibition space and state-of-the-art exhibits.''
</P>
<P>
   The two main exhibits being added are an introduction to the
universe and a history of mankind's view of the universe that will
include objects from the Adler's extensive collection of
astronomical instruments.
</P>
<P>
   The Adler also is restoring the building's original main
entrance, which has been closed since the '70s. It was replaced by
an odd glass box in front of the building that contained an
escalator and required visitors to enter through the building's
basement. The box has been dismantled and ``visitors will now be
able to enter through the original grand entrance,'' said
Knappenberger.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
