<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-19 16:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2096 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLA-ALA-CONNECTOR20-C     06-19 1359
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-ALA-CONNECTOR20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Florida, Alabama seek better roads to, from Gulf
 &HT;    (Map available.)
 &HT;    By Mike Williams
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox New Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLOMATON, Ala. _ It was a scene straight out of a Hollywood
disaster thriller, an emergency manager's worst nightmare: traffic
gridlock on a huge network of highways as a Category 5 hurricane
bore down on a heavily populated stretch of coast.
</P>
<P>
   Worried drivers fumed behind the wheel in bumper-to-bumper
traffic, their cars packed with kids, grandmas, pets and precious
possessions, unable to move as the skies darkened behind them. The
scene was all too real in dozens of small towns just north of the
Gulf Coast in October 1995 as Hurricane Opal blossomed overnight
into a killer storm, prompting a pell-mell, late-hour evacuation.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, the storm lost punch just as it roared ashore and
the thousands of evacuees stranded in their cars weren't thrown
about like toys facing nature's overpowering wrath.
</P>
<P>
   But the lesson wasn't lost on the towns of Flomaton, Brewton,
Century and Milton, where exhausted officials scrambled futilely to
unclog the roads and find a place to put frightened people.
</P>
<P>
   ``We opened every shelter we could and some we couldn't even get
permission for,'' said Brewton Mayor Ted Jennings. ``It was a bad
experience. As a mayor I don't guess I've ever had that tremendous
a responsibility, with so many lives depending on me.''
</P>
<P>
   The scare has prompted a flurry of proposals to improve the road
systems leading away from the booming Gulf Coast, where the
population of the Pensacola metro area alone is expected to double
to 750,000 by 2020.
</P>
<P>
   In neighboring Alabama, construction has already begun on a new
bridge and northward route from the Gulf beaches in Baldwin County.
In Florida, two unusual alliances have formed _ each spanning the
Alabama-Florida state line _ to lobby for better routes away from
northwest Florida beaches.
</P>
<P>
   Some Florida officials are so worried they are even proposing
their state pay to build roads in Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   ``Florida money is typically used on Florida roadways,'' said
Rep. Jeff Miller, a Florida Republican who lives in Escambia County
and supports one of the routes. ``But if you don't ask, you won't
know if there is an opportunity for funding.''
</P>
<P>
   Long road to improvements
</P>
<P>
   But it could be years before the routes from Florida connecting
to I-65 in Alabama are improved. Highway officials in both states
say the projects aren't yet on their work lists and the lead time
for such projects typically takes years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those plans are not in our five-year program,'' said Regina
Battles, a Florida Department of Transportation official who works
in the panhandle. ``First, local officials have to give us their
priorities and then the projects would have to work their way up
the list.''
</P>
<P>
   Local officials vow to lobby long and hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Opal really showed us the necessity,'' said Escambia County
Commissioner Tom Banjanin. ``We heard a lot of horror stories about
people trapped on the roads for 20 hours. It's a humanitarian
project.''
</P>
<P>
   A federal study in the early 1990s found there was a need for an
interstate highway spur to connect I-65 and I-10, the major,
controlled-access highways through the region. But the $500 million
price tag has been too steep and no federal funding has been
forthcoming.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves local officials scrambling to upgrade existing
routes.
</P>
<P>
   In Banjanin's county, four-lane U.S. 29 leads 40 miles north out
of Pensacola to the Alabama state line, but there it hits a
bottleneck in Flomaton. Drivers must work their way north to I-65
on two-lane Ala. 113, or go east or west on U.S. 31, which is part
two-lane, part three-lane and part four-lane. Banjanin has allied
with Flomaton officials calling for the four-laning of 14 miles of
113, the shortest, straightest route to I-65.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need it bad,'' said Flomaton Mayor Joe Brantley. ``That
storm in '95 came real close to being a big disaster. I'd feel a
whole lot better if we already had it.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Flomaton-Pensacola alliance isn't the only cross-state
effort under way.
</P>
<P>
   Just to the east in Santa Rosa County, Fla., mayors from Milton
and Gulf Breeze have joined their counterparts from Brewton and
East Brewton in a push to four-lane about 40 miles of Fla. 87 and
Ala. 41, which lead into Brewton. They also want to four-lane U.S.
31 north from Brewton to I-65.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would boost our economy and make hurricane evacuation
easier,'' said Milton Mayor Guy Thompson. ``We've been yelling
about this for years, but now with our growth, we need it badly.''
</P>
<P>
   Emergency management officials are aware of the problems and
also hope the roads will be built, but they have no say in
highway-building decisions. Instead, they have tried to learn from
the Opal near-disaster, hoping to be more precise and timely with
evacuation orders.
</P>
<P>
   States cooperate
</P>
<P>
   Florida officials now include Alabama emergency managers in the
conference telephone calls when evacuation decisions are made, and
also have traffic counters who estimate the cars headed north, said
Jim Loftis, a Florida Division of Emergency Management spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a continuing process of awareness and education,'' Loftis
said. ``But the bottom line is that every person needs to have a
plan for their family that is based on where they live and the
information they get from their local emergency managers.''
</P>
<P>
   While emergency officials once worried that not enough people
would heed evacuation orders, they now realize that a mass exodus
can be equally dangerous. In Florida, officials urge residents who
live in flood zones or mobile homes to evacuate to local shelters,
while those who live in sturdy, upland homes are urged to stay in
their homes except in catastrophic storms.
</P>
<P>
   While the Florida groups are just organizing, their neighbors in
Baldwin County, Ala., are already beginning construction, thanks in
part to another unusual partnership.
</P>
<P>
   A private bridge company run by the sons of former Alabama Gov.
Fob James is building a new toll bridge across the Intracoastal
Waterway from Orange Beach, a densely-packed stretch of beach 10
miles away from the only current waterway bridge, Ala. 59 in Gulf
Shores.
</P>
<P>
   The company will also build 6 miles of road to connect with a
7.5-mile section of four-lane the city of Foley is constructing to
help relieve traffic on Ala. 59, which in summer months is packed
with traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Baldwin County is also planning a 13-mile stretch that would
connect to the Foley road and carry travelers to I-10.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a real safety issue,'' said Foley Mayor Tim Russell,
whose city got a federal grant for its section of the new highway.
``We've just got tremendous growth here and we've got to have a way
to get these people out of here if there's a storm.''
</P>
<P>
   In Florida, officials insist the Escambia and Santa Rosa
projects aren't competing; instead, both groups pledge to support
the other because they believe both projects are needed.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Escambia project may have an advantage: 40 miles of
four-lane is already in place on U.S. 29 in Florida, and the
Alabama Department of Transportation already owns the right-of-way
for four-laning the 14 miles of 113, Banjanin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no major bridges to build, either,'' he said. ``The
estimate is about $28 million.''
</P>
<P>
   But Alabama officials say the project isn't in their plans,
although they are four-laning U.S. 31, which runs east-west between
Brewton and Atmore and could help ease the evacuation crunch. They
also have improvement projects under way farther east on roads
leading into Florida. But the 113 project may have trouble getting
funded.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a matter of prioritizing our resources,'' said Paul
Bowlin, assistant director of Alabama's DOT. ``Frankly, except
under an evacuation situation which might only come up once every
few years, the traffic on that road wouldn't justify it. We'll
certainly listen to any proposal, but it always comes down to
priorities.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
