<HEADER>
A2097 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SQUIRREL-SICKNESS-COX     06-19 0582
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SQUIRREL-SICKNESS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sad squirrel tale: Gray variety falling prey to potent pox
 &HT;    By Jenny Staletovich
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Mutant squirrels are popping up in
backyards, ravaged by a pox not seen in Florida since the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   So far, between 300 and 500 squirrels riddled with crusty brown
tumors _ some covering 90 percent of the body _ have been reported
in eight counties including Palm Beach County and the Treasure
Coast. Pathologists studying the epidemic at the University of
Florida suspect thousands more are infected with the disease. It is
specific to squirrels and cannot be contracted by other wildlife,
pets or humans.
</P>
<P>
   Still, this is a pox particularly potent.
</P>
<P>
   Transmitted by mosquitoes, the disease almost always attacks the
eyes, leaving its little victims blind and unable to plunder bird
feeders, their eyes swollen ``as big as marbles,'' said Florida
Game and Freshwater Fish Commission biologist Timothy Regan.
</P>
<P>
   As it progresses, it ravages the body with tumors so severe that
in some cases limbs have sloughed off. The critters eventually
starve to death or die from bacteria infecting tumors. There is no
treatment or preventive vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a hospital, it's difficult for us to watch something like
this and we understand it's difficult for some people. They're cute
and hop around in the yard and people put out peanuts,'' said Dan
Martinelli, director of the Treasure Coast Wildlife Hospital in
Hobe Sound, which has received about a dozen pox-infested
squirrels.
</P>
<P>
   (For those with a more culinary interest in the squirrel, the
Michigan Department of Natural Resources reports that the pocked
carcasses are safe for consumption: ``The tumors are confined to
the skin and are removed when the animal is skinned.'')
</P>
<P>
   Technically called squirrel fibromatosis, the pox first appeared
near Melbourne in the fall when the Florida Wildlife Hospital and
Sanctuary there started receiving calls about mutant squirrels.
Between November and March, 38 disfigured corpses were brought to
the center. In March, the University of Florida's veterinary
college began receiving calls from wildlife clinics and vets, said
pathologist Dr. Scott Terrell. The lab identified the disease as
squirrel pox, which has been documented in Florida only once
before, on Amelia Island in February 1974.
</P>
<P>
   The disease is commonly found in Northern states. However,
outbreaks usually occur with far less severity and in much smaller
numbers. Florida's 1974 outbreak involved only a few squirrels.
</P>
<P>
   ``For it to happen in such huge numbers is unusual. That's what
we're trying to figure out is if it's a new virus or if it was
introduced to a particularly susceptible population of squirrels,''
Terrell said. ``We're trying to survey the whole state.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, the pox has appeared in Palm Beach, Martin, St. Lucie,
Indian River, Okeechobee, Brevard, Osceola and Orange counties,
attacking gray squirrels, Florida's predominant species, Terrell
said. Nothing can be done but allow the disease to play itself out,
he said. A certain number of squirrels will die, some will develop
a resistance and some will be naturally immune.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an unfortunate instance of nature having to run its
course,'' Martinelli said. ``We tell people almost everyday this is
going to be a rough year for squirrels. That's the bottom line.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
