<HEADLINE>
RIVER GUARDIANS CONFER ON ENVIRONMENTAL SUITS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JOHN T. McQUISTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAG HARBOR, N.Y. _ Billy Joel took the helm of his new
65-foot-long boat, the Redhead, and with Robert F. Kennedy Jr., at
his side in the pilot's seat, led 50 environmentalists who keep
watch on the nation's waterways on a tour of Peconic Bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes when you're heading in from Block Island, you can
almost imagine how pristine it was here when the first explorers
arrived hundreds of years ago,'' Joel said as he maneuvered the
Redhead away from the dock at the Sag Harbor Yacht Club early
Friday, gave a warning blast on the boat's horn and headed out into
the bay.
</P>
<P>
   Joel, long an advocate for the dwindling number of commercial
fishermen and bay men on Long Island's East End, helped win
congressional approval of the bay as a national estuary in 1993,
providing it with protection from pollution under the Clean Water
Act.
</P>
<P>
   Adopted by Congress a quarter-century ago, the Clean Water Act
gave citizens broad powers to enforce environmental laws through
private lawsuits. It led to hundreds of suits filed by citizens
that produced millions of dollars in penalties paid to the
government and scores of court orders to stop pollution.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, however, more of the suits are being turned back by
rulings by the Supreme Court and lower federal courts, greatly
diminishing the power of environmentalists like the 50 members of
the Water Keeper Alliance aboard the Redhead.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the alliance, all grass-roots river and bay activists
from across North America, gathered Thursday at the Southampton
College of Long Island University for a four-day conference to
discuss their legal rights and to form a strategy to respond to the
legal challenges.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting was organized by Kennedy, a founder of the Water
Keeper Alliance, an umbrella group of 35 keeper programs in the
United States and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   The keepers, including Kevin McAllister, the Keeper of Peconic
Bay and a host aboard the Redhead, cast themselves among the most
aggressive and litigious members of the environmental movement.
</P>
<P>
   While there is no current legal action involving Peconic Bay,
groups like the San Francisco Baykeeper and the Hudson Riverkeeper
maintain more than 40 lawsuits against environmental polluters at
one time, according to Kennedy, who also is the supervising
attorney for the Pace Environmental Litigation Clinic at the Pace
University School of Law in White Plains.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that the Upper Chattahoochee Riverkeeper in Georgia
recently won a $1 billion judgment against the city of Atlanta for
violating clean-water laws at its sewage-treatment plants.
</P>
<P>
   But the recent losses in court, he said, were the primary
concern at last week's conference on Long Island, which included
Joel's boat tour, a clambake on the beach at Cow Neck on Friday
night and the South Fork annual dinner dance on Saturday night, and
is scheduled to end Sunday morning with a farewell breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the past decade, right-wing jurists have eroded or
dismantled many of the environmental protections and citizens'
rights that Congress wrote into the environmental statutes passed
after Earth Day in 1970,'' Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   ``These decisions are being written just as many of the nation's
rivers and beaches are recovering from decades of abuse and are
being reopened for fishing and swimming,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The first Keeper program was started on the Hudson River by a
coalition of commercial and recreational fishermen who came
together in 1996 to reclaim the river, Kennedy said. Since its
incorporation in 1984, Hudson Riverkeeper has brought more than 150
successful lawsuits against river polluters.
</P>
<P>
   The recovery of the Hudson inspired similar keeper groups from
Cook Inlet in Alaska to St. John's River in Florida, and from San
Diego Bay in California to Casco Bay in Maine. Kennedy said he
christened the 35th riverkeeper and the first Canadian keeper
program a week ago on the Petitcodiac River in New Brunswick.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday afternoon, the keepers, buoyed by encouragement from a
rock 'n' roll legend, were back at work at the Southampton campus
absorbing the finer points of gaining legal standing in a court of
law from a lecture by Karl Coplan, a lawyer with the Pace
Environmental Litigation Clinic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though the Congress has said in the Clean Water Act that
any person can sue, the courts are now saying there are
limitations,'' he said. ``The courts are now saying you have to
show an actual injury that you can point to and perceive. It may be
true that a plant may be putting pollution in water and breaking
the law, but when you get to court you have to point to something
tangible that proves the water has been affected,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As an example, he referred to a ruling June 2 by the 4th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals in Columbia, S.C., in a suit brought by
Friends of the Earth, a citizens environmental group, on behalf of
the operators of a canoe-trip company, against Gaston Copper
Recycling Corp., which sits aside Lake Watson in Gaston, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   The court ruled that the plaintiffs had no standing, as they
failed to prove that the canoe business had suffered because the
recycling plant had once discharged lead and copper into the lake.
The canoe company argued that it could sell more trips if the water
did not have a history of pollution. The court said this was not
good enough, Coplan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``To get standing, the courts are insisting that we get very
personal and specific about how we are affected by pollution, and
this can be tough to litigate,'' he told the keepers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
