<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-STARWARS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL OBSERVER: SHUFFLING THROUGH THE STAR WARS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BRENT STAPLES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial observer for Sunday,
June 20:
</P>
<P>
   White Americans make up about 80 percent of the population
today. But people who identify themselves as ``white'' are a
steadily shrinking majority, losing ground to Americans of Latin,
Asian and African descent. The inevitable ``browning'' of America
is happening fastest among school-aged children, where nonwhites
will become the majority by the year 2050.
</P>
<P>
   The entertainment industry as a whole was slow to recognize the
broadening market for black, Latin and Asian characters who
transcended the customary marginalism and stereotypes of Hollywood.
But futurists and science-fiction producers were another story.
They embraced multicultural themes more than 30 years ago and drew
heavily on the work of writers like Philip K. Dick, Ursula K. Le
Guin and especially the ``Star Trek'' developers, Gene Roddenberry
and D.C. Fontana.
</P>
<P>
   ``Star Trek'' televised one of the first interracial kisses _
between Capt. Kirk and Lt. Uhura _ in 1968, well before Hollywood
had the nerve. At a time when most black movie actors were confined
to roles as pimps, prostitutes and illiterates, ``Star Trek''
conceived a future where minority actors could play intellectuals,
military officers _ and eventually star ship captains and space
station commanders, like Benjamin Sisko on the ``Star Trek''
spinoff ``Deep Space Nine.''
</P>
<P>
   Most people think of futurism as a matter of gadgets. But in
``Star Trek,'' the most ``futuristic'' aspect was its depiction of
whites, blacks, Asians _ and Vulcans _ working with mutual respect
toward a common goal, unencumbered by the racial hostilities that
have poisoned the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   This ethos seems to have triumphed in science fiction _ except
in the mind of George Lucas, the ``Star Wars'' king. The first
``Star Wars'' film in 1977 had a great many white actors speaking
with British accents, but no black faces on the screen. The lone
black actor, James Earl Jones, was the voice of the villain, Darth
Vader. Stung by critics, Lucas drafted Billy Dee Williams into
``The Empire Strikes Back'' but made him a token with no real
substance.
</P>
<P>
   Most people would have proceeded cautiously after all the
grumbling. But Lucas has run into race-related controversy yet
again with ``The Phantom Menace.'' The characters who most resemble
Asians here are greedy, rapacious and disturbingly similar to Asian
hordes in the 1940s serials. But the main trouble centers on Jar
Jar Binks, a digitalized alien who speaks in an exaggerated West
Indian patois and lopes along in a combination shuffle and pimp
walk. Binks is by far the stupidest person in the film. His
simple-minded devotion to his (white) Jedi masters has reminded
people of Hollywood's most offensive racial stereotypes.
</P>
<P>
   David Ansen of Newsweek likened the character to Stepin Fetchit,
the grinning, shuffling character who defined the black presence in
film well into the 1940s. Writing in The Wall Street Journal, Joe
Morgenstern compared Binks to Butterfly McQueen, Miss Scarlett's
feather-brained maid in ``Gone With the Wind.'' The Rasta alien has
been torched on the Internet, primarily by a group calling itself
the Society for the Extermination of Jar Jar Binks.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesperson for Lucasfilm responded that nothing in ``Star
Wars'' was ``racially motivated'' and dismissed racial
interpretations as ``absurd,'' offering the lame excuse that Binks
was a fantasy. But so were the black characters in ``Birth of a
Nation'' whose eyeballs popped grotesquely from their heads when
they saw Klansmen clad in white sheets.
</P>
<P>
   Binks did not spring full blown from the forehead of the
universe. The filmmakers drafted a dancer from the show ``Stomp.''
Then they instructed him on how to speak and move in a way they
found amusing. Finally, they replaced the human dancer with a
digital version of an amphibian creature they had created from
scratch.
</P>
<P>
   To put it plainly, Lucasfilm built this fantasy plank by plank
and nail by nail. Instead of casting aspersions on Binks' critics,
Lucas and his friends need to examine the contents of their own
minds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-99 1646EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
