<SLUG> BC-COX-KOSOVO-COHEN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    COHEN TOURS KOSOVO, AND CLINTON MAY NOT BE FAR BEHIND
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By JOSEPH ALBRIGHT 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service (at)
<TEXT>
<P>
   UROSEVAC, Yugoslavia Defense Secretary William Cohen Saturday
led a coming parade of Western leaders eager to plant their foot on
the soil of Kosovo and thank the NATO occupation troops
</P>
<P>
   for a job well done.
</P>
<P>
   President Bill Clinton is expected to visit troops in the
American occupation zone of Kosovo on Tuesday or Wednesday, said
two staff officers who have been assigned to make arrangements for
a planned Clinton visit.
</P>
<P>
   There were also signs of a visit in the next few days to Kosovo
by British Prime Minister Tony Blair, following the weekend summit
meeting of G-8 industrialized nations in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are totally indebted to all of you for what you do day in
and day
</P>
<P>
   out,'' Cohen told Army paratroopers and tank crews gathered in
the city
</P>
<P>
   square. ``The courage, the discipline, the commitment, the
patriotism
</P>
<P>
   everything that you demonstrate day in and day out says why
America is
</P>
<P>
   Number One.''
</P>
<P>
   This was clearly intended as a pep talk for the troops from Fort
Bragg,
</P>
<P>
   N.C., and from Germany who landed in Albania in early April,
expecting to go to
</P>
<P>
   war, and have now been ordered here for a tour of peacekeeping
duty that
</P>
<P>
   could last into October.
</P>
<P>
   In the last week, Urosevac has been the scene of a panicky
exodus of
</P>
<P>
   more than 4,000 Serbian civilians who fled north to Serbia after
a wave of
</P>
<P>
   about a dozen kidnappings of Serbians, many from prominent
families.
</P>
<P>
   When asked how important it is for Western leaders to
</P>
<P>
   arrange for the departed Serbs to return to Kosovo, Cohen said:
``We are
</P>
<P>
   neutral on this subject. We are not taking favorites, we want
everyone to
</P>
<P>
   stay. What we want is a peaceful environment. To the extent that
the Serbs
</P>
<P>
   can be assured that they are going to be secure, we want that as
well.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House staff has disclosed plans for Clinton to greet
American
</P>
<P>
   troops across the border in Macedonia but has said nothing about
a possible trip to
</P>
<P>
   Kosovo. However, the two officers said that Clinton tentatively
plans to helicopter here from Macedonia to visit peacekeeping
troops of the Army's 82d Airborne Division and the Marines' 26th
Marine
</P>
<P>
   Expeditionary Unit.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen's visit to the city square of this largest Kosovar town
under
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Army control provided a preview of the kind of adulation
Clinton can
</P>
<P>
   expect should he tour the American zone.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen was serenaded by chants of ``USA, USA, USA'' from a
delirious
</P>
<P>
   cluster of Kosovar Albanian onlookers who happened to turn up in
the city
</P>
<P>
   square when Cohen and NATO commander Gen. Wesley Clark stepped
out of an
</P>
<P>
   Army Humvee. Army sharpshooters were stationed on rooftops, and
the square
</P>
<P>
   was sealed off by machine-gunners aboard Humvees.
</P>
<P>
   To the surprise of Cohen's security detail, one burly Kosovar
man
</P>
<P>
   enveloped Cohen in a bearhug, then kissed him on both cheeks.
</P>
<P>
   As Cohen and Clark were greeting troops, NATO negotiators were
in the
</P>
<P>
   last stages of working out an ``understanding'' with the general
staff of the
</P>
<P>
   Kosovo Liberation Army that is expected to result in an
agreement for the
</P>
<P>
   KLA to lay down its arms.
</P>
<P>
   In what could be a prelude to the broader agreement, the
commander of
</P>
<P>
   82d Airborne troops in Kosovo, Lt. Col. Joe Anderson, said he
had obtained
</P>
<P>
   an agreement from a KLA brigade commander to turn over a sizable
stockpile
</P>
<P>
   of KLA arms to American troops on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   This followed the KLA's release of five Serb hostages Saturday,
</P>
<P>
   as demanded by the 82d Airborne commander in a face-to-face
</P>
<P>
   meeting with KLA officials 24 hours earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
