<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-AL-NOTES20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    American League notes
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AL EAST
</P>
<P>
   Fans who stayed late last Sunday to see Cal Ripken finish his
6-for-6 night at Turner Field in Atlanta will never forget it, but
Ripken has been carrying on like that for a month. Emotionally
exhausted with back pain and forced on the DL April 19, Ripken in
his first 29 games back hit .375 with seven homers and 24 RBIs
while improving his season average 159 points to .338. ``I had a
little bit of a break from the baseball action, and I actually
distanced myself from the ballpark and gave myself a chance to heal
mentally,'' he said, referring to the death of his father. ``I came
back with a little bit sharper focus. Physically, I'm pretty sound,
and I'm enjoying the results.'' This is a ticklish time for the
O's, who have until the All-Star break to pick up the option year
for next season on Ripken's expiring contract. It is worth $6.3
million. Ripken turns 39 in August.... The Devil Rays are stocked
if the NFL ever buys them. The Rays just came to terms with
second-round pick Carl Crawford, who has signed with Nebraska to
play quarterback. He joins three other quarterbacks in the system,
including pitcher Jason Standridge, who turned down Auburn, and
pitcher Maquis Roberts, who turned down Fresno State. Kenny Kelly,
hitting .392 in Class A, is the starting quarterback at the
University of Miami.
</P>
<P>
   AL CENTRAL
</P>
<P>
   There is bad karma in the Twin Cities, where three Twins went
down within seven days after inopportune encounters with the
baseball. Right fielder Matt Lawton took aa fastball to the face
from Cincinnati's Dennys Reyes. Doctors haven't even let him jog,
because the broken bones around the socket of his right eye might
slip when jostled. Next up was pitcher LaTroy Hawkins, who took a
grounder off his kneecap against Milwaukee last Saturday. Three
nights later, it was pitcher Brad Radke's turn, taking a line drive
off the shin. The club is trying to blame outfielder Marty Cordova,
who one day asked Lawton if he had ever been on the disabled list.
Lawton went down a few nights later, triggering the sequence. ``I
left all kinds of nasty messages on his phone,'' Lawton said.
``That was my ticket to the disabled list.''... The Kansas City
bullpen is chasing history after blowing 13 of the club's first 24
save opportunities. No team has ever finished a full season with
more blown saves than saves, although the Dodgers managed it _ 20
saves, 21 blown saves _ in strike-shortened 1994.... On the average
weekday, the White Sox ticket office handles 1,000 orders for
future games. On the Monday after the Sox swept the Cubs, the
office handled 6,200.
</P>
<P>
   AL WEST
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim lost yet another Angel, this one after just seven
innings in the majors. Outfielder Mike Colangelo collided with
Reggie Williams and sustained a concussion and torn thumb
ligaments. Colangelo is the 12th Angel to land on the disabled
list, leaving embattled manager Terry Collins to wonder what he
might have done differently. ``You say to yourself, `What can you
change? What are we missing?''' Collins said. ``But when you look
back at all these injuries, they're not through a lack of training.
With the exception of (Gary) DiSarcina's, which was a fluke (he
broke a forearm bone when hit by coach George Hendrick's fungo
bat), they're because of aggressiveness. (Tim) Salmon and (Jim)
Edmonds dive for balls, and even if we had a railing up in front of
the dugout, Mo (Vaughn) would have crashed into it. I wouldn't want
those guys to change.''... When Oakland lost a two-run lead in the
ninth and fell to Cleveland on Wednesday night, the A's told
manager Art Howe to wait outside the clubhouse while the players
held a meeting. Howe's curiosity was answered the next night when
Cleveland staged a five-run seventh and won 10-6.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
