<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-NL-NOTES20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    National League notes
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NL EAST
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Benedict had managed just eight Class AAA games since
leaving the Braves organization in 1995 to work the New York Mets
system. He was so nervous Wednesday night when took over during
Bobby Valentine's suspension that Benedict forgot to wear a hat.
</P>
<P>
   When he finally found one, it was a nylon style the Mets use
only for batting practice, and it was the fourth inning before
someone fit him with the right one. The Mets beat Cincinnati 5-2,
and the whole night was a little calmer. New York starter Masato
Yoshii said, ``The only thing I noticed was that it was real quiet
in the dugout. That's when I noticed Bobby wasn't there.''... With
Craig Counsell dealt to Los Angeles, only three players remain with
the Florida Marlins from the 1997 title team _ Antonio Alfonseca,
Livan Hernandez and Cliff Floyd; Alex Fernandez was on the DL. The
Dodgers now have four players from that team: Counsell, Gary
Sheffield, Devon White and Kevin Brown.... Montreal right fielder
Vladimir Guerrero is on pace for a 38-homer, 126-RBI season, both
of which would be franchise records.
</P>
<P>
   NL CENTRAL
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs are getting an unwanted reputation for mishandling
their arms. Jeremi Gonzalez, a promising rookie two years ago now
recovering from elbow surgery, has quit throwing at Class AAA Iowa.
He charged that the club demoted him illegally and said his arm
still hurts. Gonzalez also says he was advised by one doctor to
have a complete ``Tommy John'' ligament transplant, although the
club opted for an ulnar-nerve tranposition. Gonzalez's complaints
could be characterized as the frustrations of one young pitcher,
except that Rod Beck charged last month that the team delayed in
approving his elbow surgery for elbow deposits. Although he was in
pain during spring training, surgery was finally done in mid-May.
And there is still some criticism about the way the club monitored
Kerry Wood's elbow, which began troubling him in mid-1998. So, what
was Cubs general Ed Lynch looking at during the eight years he
pitched in the majors?... Ray Lankford's knee, operated on during
the offseason, still hasn't stabilized so that he can play center
field every day. Manager Tony La Russa will keep him in left for
the duration.
</P>
<P>
   NL WEST
</P>
<P>
   No sooner did the Los Angeles Dodgers flop to fourth place last
week than every horn sounded in the front office. Within two days,
the team benched catcher Todd Hundley and sent him to ``catcher
school'' with bullpen coach Rick Dempsey; dropped former
first-rounder Darren Dreifort from the rotation for Braves
flunk-out Jamie Arnold; and acquired second baseman Craig Counsell
from Florida, although he walks into a deeper personnel jam than
the one that forced him away from the Marlins. The Dodgers lost 11
of 15 entering the weekend and haven't been in first since the
seventh day of the season. Asked how this mess gets straightened
out, left fielder Gary Sheffield said, ``I don't know. I'll let
Malone figure that out.'' That would be general manager Kevin
Malone, who said, ``I'm at my wit's end.''... Coors Field has
yielded 109 homers in the season's first 27 games. That's a
327-homer pace. The record is 276, set three years ago.... Barry
Bonds feels wanted. San Francisco's left fielder can tell a
difference, now that he's fighting back after elbow surgery. ``I
haven't gotten booed on the road,'' he said. ``In Seattle, they
were cheering and saying they're happy I'm back.... It's a change
for me. I didn't even know people liked me that much.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
