</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-FEATURE20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    All-Star Game streak ending for Atlanta
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The most charming aspect about the All-Star game is
how the public is invited to select the lineups, which of course is
also the worst possible thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``An ardent supporter of the hometown team,'' humorist Robert
Benchley wrote, ``should go to a game prepared to take offense, no
matter what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Fans play favorites, hold grudges, display incredible ignorance
and abuse their ballot just as much as the managers or the media
would, if it were up to them. But as popular voice is held so
dearly by this nation, the All-Star vote has become the best way to
judge how big a moron the guy next to you is when taking your seat
at the park.
</P>
<P>
   Yet baseball followers across the country are saying something
different this summer, different at least to a sentiment that has
reigned across the game during this decade. They are tired of the
Atlanta Braves, and they want them to go away.
</P>
<P>
   When the All-Star teams are announced this week, the Braves will
not have a starting player in the NL lineup for the first time
since 1991. The same franchise that in the last three years has had
12 players make 19 All-Star appearances might have a couple added
as reserves for the July 13 game in Boston, Brian Jordan and
Chipper Jones; Javy Lopez and John Rocker are long shots. But
that's it.
</P>
<P>
   Is this fair? Not particularly for Jordan, Atlanta's most
productive hitter, whose 55 RBIs entering the weekend ranked third
in the league. He was running eighth in the last voting update
released last week, behind Andruw Jones, of all people.
</P>
<P>
   Simply put, justice is being served. Chipper Jones had drawn
more votes than any Brave but still trailed Arizona third baseman
Matt Williams, who is having a better season a half-dozen different
ways. Lopez was third among catchers behind New York's Mike Piazza
and Pittsburgh's Jason Kendall, which sounds about right.
</P>
<P>
   What makes any of this suspicious is that the All-Star vote,
stripped to the core, is just a popularity contest, and all signals
say the Braves remain immensely popular. They were the first NL
team to crack the 1 million mark this season. On the road, their
hotels are mobbed as if Ricky Martin just checked in.
</P>
<P>
   A Harris Poll released last week found the Braves to be the
game's most popular team for the seventh year in a row, ahead of
the New York Yankees by a healthy margin. TBS has plenty to do with
it, but that's how the poll business works.
</P>
<P>
   So how can one of the game's best-drawing teams, one that was
just judged to be the most popular in the country, be banished from
the starting lineup? Is ballot-stuffing, the All-Star game's sweet
science, a lost art? What Chicago precinct boss is tabulating the
vote?
</P>
<P>
   All of that means two things. These 1999 Braves, even as they
flirted with the league's best first half, have overwhelmed no one,
and, as individuals, no one deserved to make the team.
</P>
<P>
   But secondly and more poignantly, as the All-Star team often has
little to do with statistical reality, America is also saying,
enough already. The Atlanta Braves have been calling the tune for
their decade. The fans just punched fast-forward.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
