<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ITEMS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Let's make a deal
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   With midseason just a couple of weeks away, clubs in need are
posturing for that one precise trade that will make all the
difference in the second half. Or so the thinking goes.
</P>
<P>
   The earliest interest is in Toronto's David Wells, who has drawn
considerable attention from Cincinnati. The Cleveland Indians also
have inquired, but the Reds, who fancy themselves one starter short
of a load, seem most anxious.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the team to win our division or the wild card if we
can add a starting pitcher or two,'' Reds general manager Jim
Bowden said. ``We're really more interested in young pitchers that
we can keep and build with, and Toronto has four or five of them.
I'd think because of the situation they are in, they have to try to
do something.''
</P>
<P>
   Other rumblings:
</P>
<P>
   _ St. Louis covets Chicago White Sox right-hander Jamie Navarro
but wants no part of the final season of his $20 million contract,
which expires next year.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ex-Braves player Michael Tucker fits Kansas City's need for a
first baseman, but getting him out of Cincinnati might be
impossible. Bowden wants pitching, and the Royals' fragile future
is based on their young pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Detroit is scouting Toronto first baseman Carlos Delgado, and
the Blue Jays, worried that talks over a long-term deal for their
captain have turned stale, are listening.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tampa Bay is pleading for someone to take DH-1B Paul Sorrento.
Please.
</P>
<P>
   Home sweet . . . oops
</P>
<P>
   A half-dozen Mariners were given a sneak peak at Seattle's
Safeco Field, the club's new $517 million home starting July 15.
The amenities were exquisite. The gaps were _ less so.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners, who hit have hit more homers than anyone the past
three seasons, including a major-league record 264 in 1997, found
during a quick batting practice that the ball does not carry as it
does in the Kingdome.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was difficult in the gaps,'' designated hitter Edgar
Martinez. ``In left center, it seems you really have to hit it
hard. On my last swing, I really hit it hard, and the ball just hit
the fence.''
</P>
<P>
   The dimensions are about the same at Safeco _ a foot deeper in
