<DOCNO> NYT19990619.0191 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-19 17:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2118 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FREE-MAN20-COX     06-19 1994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FREE-MAN20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wrongly convicted, free man rejoins life after 16 years
 &HT;    By Bill Torpy
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAPEVILLE, Ga. _ Two days out of prison, Calvin C. Johnson Jr.
found himself an instant celebrity. The 41-year-old sat on a
threadbare couch in his father's cramped suburban Atlanta
apartment, sparring on the telephone with irascible radio host Neal
Boortz and awaiting a call from Johnnie Cochran's TV talk show.
</P>
<P>
   Boortz tried to goad Johnson into saying something
controversial, but the soft-spoken ex-inmate demurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spent 16 years with con artists and crooks, people trying to
con you out of your locker box. I've dealt with worse than Neal,''
said Johnson, who made international news last week after being
released from a life prison sentence for a 1983 rape he did not
commit.
</P>
<P>
   DNA testing, performed on semen stains that were stored away in
evidence files, showed Johnson had been wrongly accused.
</P>
<P>
   The scene Tuesday in Clayton County Superior Court was a
tear-jerker: a black man, sent away for life after trial by a white
prosecutor, white cops and an all-white jury, was now getting the
apology he had dreamed about. He talked frequently about the Lord
and even shook District Attorney Bob Keller's hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``People make mistakes,'' Johnson said, simply.
</P>
<P>
   But a review of court records and interviews with law
enforcement officials show Johnson wasn't arrested merely because
he was a black man in the wrong place at the wrong time.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he became the target of a rape inquiry in 1983 at least
in part because he had pleaded guilty to a burglary charge two
years earlier after police caught him inside a College Park
apartment with a knife.
</P>
<P>
   That same arrest led to charges against him in connection with
sexual crimes in College Park in 1981. In addition to the burglary,
he was accused of rape, attempted rape, aggravated sodomy and armed
robbery. Johnson denies committing those crimes and the charges
were dropped. ``The only thing I ever did was the burglary,''
Johnson said. ``I take responsibility for what I've done.''
</P>
<P>
   But police and prosecutors suspected him of more. He understands
that himself. ``You know, police get upset when things don't go
their way,'' he said. ``I kept telling them I'm the wrong man. And
I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, handsome, college-educated and from a loving family,
grew up in the Cascade Heights neighborhood, an area where
Atlanta's black power structure was rooted. He played football at
Southwest High School and was well-liked by neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Southwest area was the creme de la creme of the black
community and the Johnson family fit right in,'' said Eric Wyatt, a
high school friend of Johnson's. ``His arrest was a rude awakening,
the same old things from Jim Crow. It showed us the past isn't
really the past.''
</P>
<P>
   After Johnson graduated from Clark College, now known as Clark
Atlanta University, he found work with Delta Air Lines and drove a
canary-yellow Trans Am. But his father said his son started to
change. ``I told him he was in the wrong crowd.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson himself said he committed the 1981 burglary to get
money. After he pleaded guilty to the burglary and possession of a
concealed weapon, the other charges were dropped. He was sentenced
to 12 years _ eight in prison, four on probation. Johnson
understood eight years was a stiff sentence for burglary. ``I
went,'' he said, ``with the advice of my lawyer. He said, `They're
acting funny. Take it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Fulton County District Attorney Paul Howard, the county's first
black D.A., was then an assistant D.A. and was the prosecutor who
made the plea bargain in Johnson's case. Howard said the sex
charges against Johnson were dropped because of problems with the
investigation. He declined to elaborate, but said prosecutors
demanded the relatively lengthy sentence ``because we knew, our
feeling was, that he was, in fact, responsible. We tried to embody
that responsibility in the burglary charge.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson served only 15 months in prison. In December 1982,
Johnson was released because he was a ``non-violent, first-time
incarcerate'' and prisons were overflowing, said Katherine
Browning, spokeswoman for Board of Pardons and Paroles.
</P>
<P>
   About 10 weeks later, in March 1983, two women were raped in
their College Park apartments. One lived on the Fulton County side
of the city and the other on the Clayton County side. Police
quickly zeroed in on Johnson, recognizing him from his 1981 arrest.
</P>
<P>
   College Park detective Lewis Harper got a search warrant on
March 14, 1983, for Johnson's home. ``This officer is personally
familiar with Calvin Johnson, having arrested Johnson in April 1981
for similar type crimes and that Johnson did enter a plea of guilty
to some of the charges as a result of this arrest,'' Harper wrote
in requesting the warrant.
</P>
<P>
   By then, police had shown both rape victims photo lineups that
included Johnson's picture. One pointed to Johnson's photo as that
of the man who had raped and sodomized her. The other didn't
recognize his photo, but identified him in a live lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't like we just snatched him off the street,'' Harper,
now College Park's acting police chief, said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's case in Clayton County went to trial that November.
Keller contended that Johnson slipped into the 30-year-old woman's
apartment, choked her with a belt as she slept, covered her with a
towel and then raped and sodomized her.
</P>
<P>
   The attacker turned on the light. She said she saw his face.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw everything,'' she testified. ``I know he was black and
didn't talk like a Southern black. And he didn't talk street jive.
(He) was smooth, smart and soft-spoken.''
</P>
<P>
   At the trial, under Georgia rules that allow prosecutors in some
circumstances to show jurors evidence of ``similar transactions''
in order to prove a defendant's pattern of conduct, another woman
testified that Johnson had walked into her home while she showered.
A third testified that Johnson had flashed her. Finally, the Fulton
County rape victim testified that Johnson had raped her.
</P>
<P>
   After leaving the witness stand, the Fulton County woman lunged
at Johnson as she walked by his table, either spitting at him or
throwing a punch at him, depending on the person remembering the
event.
</P>
<P>
   Akil Secret, Johnson's attorney, said the woman's emotional
attack put an exclamation point on an already one-sided contest. He
thought the incident warranted a mistrial. None was granted. Later,
Secret presented testimony from a GBI agent who said the pubic hair
found in the victim's bed did not come from Johnson, but jurors
weren't swayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clayton County (in 1983) was a redneck, racist county and had
a reputation as such,'' said Secret, who says the case convinced
him to keep his emotional distance from his clients. ``Everyone at
the prosecution table was white, the victim was white, the
witnesses against him were white. It was the opposite for Calvin.
He was black, I was black and his alibi witnesses were black.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said he feared the worst. ``I had a bad feeling; I just
saw it in the jury's eyes,'' he said. ``They looked at me like I
was some kind of monster.''
</P>
<P>
   The jurors deliberated a couple of hours before finding Johnson
guilty. Five jurors said this week that race played no part in
their decision. The victims, juror Keith Butts recalls, ``were very
convincing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The two or three girls they paraded in had no doubt in their
mind that Mr. Johnson raped them,'' he said. ``One girl basically
attacked him. There was no doubt in her mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Some legal experts call eyewitness identifications notoriously
unreliable and say interracial identifications are among the most
difficult to make. ``It is the case that people do worse in
identifying people from other races,'' said Irving Biederman, a
professor of cognitive neurology at the University of Southern
California in Los Angeles who has researched police line-ups and
eyewitness identifications. The next year, Johnson was brought to
trial in Fulton County on a rape charge involving the woman who had
identified him during the Clayton trial as a rapist. This time, a
racially mixed jury acquitted Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   But Johnson already was doing life.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne State Prison, one of five where he served his time, was
the toughest. Hard manual labor in unceasing heat was the norm.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were 200 men there, half were lifers,'' recalled
Johnson. ``You'd go out and cut bushes in water up to your knees
with snakes. We'd have a bossman who carried a shotgun and a pistol
and chewed a big wad of tobacco.''
</P>
<P>
   He called his family weekly and looked forward to their visits.
They usually came every other month. ``I never felt forgotten,'' he
said. ``My family was always there for me.''
</P>
<P>
   His faith deepened. ``I decided to put my life in God's hands,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's fiancee, Kaye Loney, stood by him through his 1981
incarceration, the 1983 trial and the start of his life sentence.
She always believed he was innocent. Johnson told her to move on
but she stayed with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``But finally, I couldn't hold out any longer,'' she said. ``I
was just so tired. I wanted to have kids and didn't know how long
it would be. I didn't see any light.''
</P>
<P>
   She married in 1987 and has two children, who once visited
Johnson in prison.
</P>
<P>
   A ray of light shone Johnson's way when a family friend told him
about the Innocence Project, a New York-based group founded by two
lawyers best known as members of O.J. Simpson's defense team. The
project, staffed by law students and volunteers, handles cases
where a defendant claims to have been wrongly convicted of rape or
murder and in which DNA tests can be done.
</P>
<P>
   The evidence in the Clayton County case was tested in November.
Johnson was transferred to Clayton County jail this year as
prosecutors decided what they would do. Johnson got a call from
Innocence Project lawyer Peter Neufeld.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `I got some news, they're not going to fight it.
You're going home,' '' said Johnson. ``I started telling all the
guys, But later I sat there wondering, `Is this real? Did I dream
that?'''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't. But the damage had been done. He had spent 16 years
in prison and friends and family members say the ordeal nearly
destroyed his family.
</P>
<P>
   About a year after his 1983 conviction, Johnson's mother, JoAnn,
suffered a stroke. She has had recurring heart problems since. Once
a prosperous couple living in a fine house, Calvin Sr. and his wife
now live in a cramped, ground-floor apartment. A wheelchair sits
empty in a corner of the living room. JoAnn Johnson has been
hospitalized for the last four months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their family resources, mentally and financially, have been
wrapped up by this case,'' said Charles Jones, Calvin Jr.'s cousin.
</P>
<P>
   The elder Johnson, once a state senator in Ohio, moved to
Atlanta to start a business that never took off. He boards MARTA
each day to visit his wife at Vencour Hospital in Midtown Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   As a free man, the younger Johnson has simple goals. ``Once I
get settled, get a job, spend some time with my family, then I'll
consider spending time with a lady. I'd like to have some
children.''
</P>
<P>
   He can seek compensation from the state, but hasn't decided
whether to do so.
</P>
<P>
   He's never used a personal computer and looks forward to
learning to surf the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   His father thinks of what's to come, when the celebrities stop
calling and the television trucks depart.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's still up there,'' his father said, motioning toward the
sky. ``I'm waiting to be holding his hand when you're all gone.
He's got to have his period of depression. That'll be the trying
time.''
</P>
<P>
   This article was reported by Atlanta Journal-Constitution
reporters Gabriella Boston, Robin McDonald, Bill Montgomery and
Bill Torpy and written by Torpy.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
