<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-19 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2122 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-CONDE-NAST-625&AMP;ADD     06-19 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CONDE-NAST-625&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONDE NAST MAGAZINES MOVE TO TIMES SQUARE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CHARLES V. BAGLI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With the coordination of an invading army, Conde Nast
has begun moving its glossy fashion magazines into a new home at 4
Times Square, the first skyscraper built in New York City since
1992.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, workers began trundling 50 truckloads of computers,
printers, files, photographs, fashion accessories and sports gear
for Bride's, House and Garden, and Women's Sports and Fitness from
their old office at 350 Madison Ave. to the 1.6 million-square-foot
tower on Broadway, between 42nd and 43rd streets.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 200 employees will sit down Monday in their new modular
offices. And over the next two months, they will be joined by 400
more truckloads of equipment and 1,800 colleagues from Vanity Fair,
Allure, Glamour, Self, GQ, The New Yorker and the other magazines
that make up the Conde Nast empire.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Conde Nast will inhabit floors four through 23 in
the 48-story office tower in a once-seedy district that is now home
to Viacom, Bertelsmann AG and Morgan Stanley. (Skadden, Arps,
Slate, Meagher &AMP; Flom, the largest law firm in the city, is
scheduled to take over the top half of the tower by Thanksgiving.)
For the first time in decades, S.I. Newhouse Jr., the chairman of
Conde Nast Publications, has brought together the 17 sleek and
sometimes fractious magazines that chronicle the culture and the
well-paid and carefully coiffed people of our times.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all preparing to live in harmony,'' said James Truman,
the Conde Nast editorial director, ``or at least under the same
roof.''
</P>
<P>
   Real estate and construction experts estimate that Conde Nast
spent $100 million on its new space. Investment banks usually set
the gold standard for lavish decor; for example, when Salomon
Brothers moved into 7 World Trade Center in the early '90s,
estimates of its spending ran to $250 a square foot. Newhouse
averaged half that figure, although he pulled out all the stops
when it came to the company's cafeteria, where, executives said,
spending exceeded $400 a square foot.
</P>
<P>
   Newhouse hired the architect Frank Gehry to design a highly
stylized cafeteria, with wavy walls of blue titanium and cloudlike
Venetian glass panels that enclose seating areas. Gehry and the
glassmakers spent a year figuring out how to bend and stretch the
glass in three dimensions. Four private dining rooms and an 85-seat
auditorium adjoin the cafeteria, which will not open until early
next year.
</P>
<P>
   Since Conde Nast signed a deal for the building nearly three
years ago, Times Square has become one of the most sought-after
commercial neighborhoods in the city. Reuters recently started work
on its new headquarters across from 4 Times Square, and Ernst &AMP;
Young, the accounting firm, is close to a deal to build its own
tower nearby. ABC's ``Good Morning America'' plans to open a
street-front studio in September at 1500 Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   Conde Nast will be moving from its old-money environs on the
East Side, within easy reach of Brooks Brothers, Paul Stuart and
Patroon, to the hurly-burly of Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a vital area that has the kind of energy we associate
with our magazines,'' Newhouse said. ``The ambiance of that
neighborhood suits us just fine.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Douglas Durst, the developer of 4 Times Square, who
persuaded Conde Nast to make the move. In 1996, Durst put together
the land for the project and gambled that if he built the first
office tower since the recession of the early 1990s, it would
quickly fill up.
</P>
<P>
   Truman, the editorial director, said Conde Nast had a choice of
either leaving its longtime home on Madison Avenue for a year while
the space there was renovated, or moving permanently to a new
building. The company chose to bring the magazines, scattered among
six buildings, into the same tower.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   He said he and the design firm of Mancini Duffy briefly
considered the kind of alternative office pioneered by accounting
firms in which each employee is assigned a personal locker, a
portable telephone and a computer on wheels. Instead, they decided
on what Truman described as a democratic approach to space that
would encourage teamwork and provide an element of privacy.
</P>
<P>
   The design might better be described as an architectural version
of George Orwell's ``Animal Farm,'' in which some people are more
equal than others. Instead of giving all the window space to
ranking executives, the company has decided to let many employees
labor at metallic blue workstations near the windows.
</P>
<P>
   At the next level up the ladder, most editors and writers who
were not relegated to workstations were consigned to interior
offices with glass doors.
</P>
<P>
   There are 21 conference rooms, wooden bookcases, Italian plaster
walls, perforated metallic blue office furniture from Italy, and an
open ceiling with exposed pipes that has a neoindustrial look.
Newhouse's office is in the middle of the Conde Nast space, on the
11th floor rather than the 23rd.
</P>
<P>
   But the publisher and editor in chief of each magazine still get
the trappings of rank: a spacious corner, or near-corner, office
with windows.
</P>
<P>
   Graydon Carter, the editor of Vanity Fair whose current offices
at 350 Madison Ave. are the envy of the company, brought in his own
architect, Basil Walter, to insure that his new space will look
exactly like his old office, which was renovated by the same
designer four years ago. He then insisted on a feng shui ceremony
to improve the spiritual environment.
</P>
<P>
   Some editors and writers complained about the corporate look of
the decor at 4 Times Square and the glass doors on their offices.
One top editor has refused to even visit 4 Times Square before
moving in. Another expressed trepidation about moving to a building
that has been plagued by construction accidents, including a
scaffolding collapse last summer in which an elderly woman was
killed.
</P>
<P>
   But many employees of the newer magazines embraced the
opportunity to join their colleagues under a single roof.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're thrilled,'' said Lucy Danziger, editor in chief of
Women's Sports and Fitness, which will be leaving cramped quarters
on Madison. ``There's a gorgeous art department and space for
kayaks, bikes and the other stuff we have.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
