A2123 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-MINOR-BASEBALL-NYT     06-19 1095
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MINOR-BASEBALL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACKIE, KING KONG KELLER AND NOW, THE STATEN ISLAND YANKS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio, N.J.)  (rk) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They will play minor league baseball Sunday on Staten
Island, something that may seem new or even quaint for a place like
New York City, the avowed capital of all things big league.
</P>
<P>
   It is true that the Yankees affiliate that opens its season on
Staten Island Sunday is the first recognized minor league team to
play in the city of New York this century. These Staten Island
Yankees will also become the only minor league team to currently
share its city limits with a Major League Baseball franchise.
</P>
<P>
   But minor league baseball in the metropolitan area is anything
but new and anything but uncelebrated. The Staten Island team
honors a long and rich tradition of minor league baseball in the
urban settings of the region. It's a story not exactly untold, but
perhaps a bit unseen.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is that New York's major league history is so big that
it has a way of blotting out quieter accomplishments, especially
those played out beyond the city's core and off its biggest stages.
Ruthian heroics, after all, cast a mighty shadow, like an Empire
State Building of sports landmarks.
</P>
<P>
   For example, one of the lesser known, though hardly minor,
baseball achievements in the metropolitan area occurred on April
18, 1946, in Jersey City. A small plaque beneath a wooden gazebo
next to what is now a condominium development graces the site on
Newark Bay. The plaque carries a simple, dignified sentence:
</P>
<P>
   ``Here, at the former Roosevelt Stadium, Jackie Robinson broke
`organized' baseball's color barrier.''
</P>
<P>
   It was in a minor league game. Robinson took the field with
eight white teammates, playing for the Brooklyn Dodgers'
International League team, the Montreal Royals, on opening day
against the Jersey City Giants.
</P>
<P>
   Newspaper accounts of the day estimate the attendance at 50,000,
twice the normal crowd. Robinson hit a three-run home run in his
second at-bat, but later unleashed a display of speed, skill and
basepath guile that would become a trademark of his Brooklyn days,
which began the following year.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson beat out a bunt, stole second base, then bluffed his
way to third base when a confused outfielder threw behind him.
Stalking home plate, Robinson then pestered the Jersey City
pitcher, Phil Oates, into a balk and scored.
</P>
<P>
   If Robinson's appearance in Jersey City was the single most
important minor league game in the metropolitan area, then the
season compiled by the 1937 Newark Bears was the most eventful.
</P>
<P>
   In 1931, the Yankees' owner, Jacob Ruppert, decided he was going
to build a minor league system for his major league team, and the
franchise in Newark was to be the showpiece of the farm system.
</P>
<P>
   The Bears won the International League championship in their
first season under the Yankees' wing. In 1937, the Bears, led by
Charlie ``King Kong'' Keller, finished their season with a 109-49
record, winning the league pennant by 25{ games. They batted .299
as a team.
</P>
<P>
   They swept through the International League playoffs, defeating
along the way Syracuse pitcher Johnny VanderMeer, who was less than
a year away from pitching back-to-back no-hitters in the major
leagues.
</P>
<P>
   In the Little World Series against the pride of the famed St.
Louis Cardinals' minor league system _ the Columbus Cardinals led
by Enos Slaughter _ the Bears lost the first three games of a
best-of-seven series at Newark's Ruppert Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining four games were in Columbus, Ohio. The Bears won
all four.
</P>
<P>
   Every player in Newark's 1937 regular lineup went on to play in
the major leagues, which was unheard in an era of just 16 major
league teams. Included in that group: Joe Gordon, who played second
base alongside Frank Crosetti and Phil Rizzuto; Babe Dahlgren, who
was best known as the man who replaced Lou Gehrig at first base in
1939; pitcher Spud Chandler, who still holds the Yankees' career
record for winning percentage with a 109-43 record; and Keller, who
led the Yankees in home runs four times and played on six World
Series champions.
</P>
<P>
   The Bears remained in Newark until 1950, with a host of future
Yankee stars passing through, most notably Yogi Berra. He now has a
minor league stadium named after him in nearby Montclair, one of
the many suburban or small municipalities throughout the country
that have attracted a second generation of minor league teams.
</P>
<P>
   A year before the Bears disbanded, another Newark team, though
hardly a minor league team _ the Newark Eagles of the Negro
National League _ had also dissolved. The Eagles, along with the
New York Black Yankees and other Negro National League franchises,
saw crowds dwindle as the number of young black players signed by
major league teams increased. Jackie Robinson had not only opened
the door, he had held it open.
</P>
<P>
   But like the Newark Bears, the Newark Eagles were a team of
legendary accomplishment. Monte Irvin, later a New York Giants
outfielder, was the shortstop, with Larry Doby, who would be the
first African-American to play in the American League, at second
base. Don Newcombe pitched for the Eagles, as did Leon Day. Willie
Wells, who hit .403 during the 1930 season, also played for the
Eagles, as did third baseman Ray Dandridge.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin, Doby, Day, Wells and Dandridge are in the Baseball Hall
of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, if baseball has flourished outside New York's major
league locales for more than a century, and appears to at least be
operating into the next century with the debut of Staten Island's
team, it's really not a surprise.
</P>
<P>
   It's instructive to remember how the game got its start.
Choosing a precise date for the first game played in America by the
appropriate rules is a sure way to start an argument, but most of
baseball's scholarly research puts the genesis of the game in the
New York area around 1845-46 (even if Cooperstown is deservedly
baseball's cosmic home).
</P>
<P>
   The teams that played then were the first semipro teams,
ancestors of the major leagues formed in 1876. They congregated in
Manhattan clubs but had little space for games on the already
crowded island. There was ample room in Hoboken and in Brooklyn,
and there was an easy way to get there: by ferry.
</P>
<P>
   Which is how America's first baseball players traveled to the
earliest games.
</P>
<P>
   So think of New York's latest baseball team in that context.
It's just another place New Yorkers can ferry to find their
baseball.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
