<SLUG> BC-SPORT-DANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEY COULD BE DANCING, AND THEY ARE
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Sport:Pucci, with no space after colon, cq) 
(rk) 
 By JERRY BREWER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Still sweaty from a day of practice, they gathered in
a semicircle beside Peter Pucci, focusing on him as if his last
name were Lombardi. But instead of blowing a whistle and barking
his final commands, Pucci hugged and kissed the men and women as
they left.
</P>
<P>
   The guess is that Vince Lombardi, the legendary coach of the
Green Bay Packers, never ended practice this way.
</P>
<P>
   The perception is that dance is as different from sport as is
the approach of its coaches. But Pucci, who used sport as a way to
leave the mean streets of Baltimore before being seduced by dance,
disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   This week, he plans to prove it. ``Pucci:Sport,'' the
choreographer's latest show, in which sports and dance collide,
premieres Tuesday at the Joyce Theater in Manhattan (through June
27; tickets cost $30).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very physical relationship in sports and dance,'' said
the 44-year-old Pucci, who, at 6 feet and 180 pounds, looks like a
point guard or a wide receiver. ``People have an inherent, innate
need to move. An instinctual need to move. Some people choose
athletics, others dance, others something else. But when you talk
about dance, the demands in the dance world are as high as in the
athletics world.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl Lewis, one of the dancers, added: ``It's like when
someone does a double play. They'll tag the bag, do a pirouette in
the air and throw the ball. Look at all that movement. It's total
dance. Those guys are flying in the air, spinning, just like we do
sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Pucci:Sport'' salutes badminton, basketball, baseball, boxing,
Frisbee, hockey, surfing and tennis. It is a show filled with wit
and cleverness, power and elegance.
</P>
<P>
   For example, during the hockey segment, one woman plays a puck
and dances with the hockey player who never gets the puck. A love
story. A sports story.
</P>
<P>
   During another part of the show, baseball players dive and slide
across the stage in a reckless physical display.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an interesting challenge to market something like this,''
said Noel Hayashi, a marketing consultant for ``Pucci:Sport.'' ``We
very much wanted to highlight the sports, de-emphasize the dance
and introduce this to people in sports and fitness. It's different
from what's thought of as American dance. It has the potential to
be quite popular.''
</P>
<P>
   Pucci spent six months auditioning dancers for the performance.
He needed versatile people who had experience in both dance and
athletics. He even took chances on athletes with limited dance
experience. Among the cast is Tony Gugliett, a former star hockey
player at New York University who is now an assistant coach for the
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more tiring quicker,'' Gugliett said of dancing. ``I
spend a half an hour here, and I'm as tired as I'll get in a
two-hour hockey practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Pucci, who has danced with the Joffrey Ballet and with the
Pilobolus Dance Theater in addition to composing works himself,
knew nothing about the arts while growing up, unless it was about
the art of avoiding conflict, or the art of staying focused amid a
swirl of negativity.
</P>
<P>
   At 8, Pucci began playing football. By high school, he had added
baseball, basketball and track to his athletic resume. He earned a
scholarship to run track at Towson State and was a member of its
all-America mile relay team.
</P>
<P>
   Then, at his girlfriend's urging, Pucci took a dance
improvisation class at the school. He loved it so much that he
changed majors _ from physical education to dance _ three weeks
before he was to get his degree.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in an umpire class, and we were learning how to say
you're safe and you're out,'' Pucci said. ``At that moment, I
realized that I wanted to do something else.''
</P>
<P>
   He wanted to dance. While he was on the baseball field that day,
Pucci looked up, and could see the Towson State dance department.
The sun glinted off its windows. It was beautiful. It was
intriguing. It was where he belonged.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took some flak for it at the beginning,'' Pucci said of his
change from athlete to artist 25 years ago. ``It was different
going from an almost all-male environment to all female. But it was
very natural for me to move and make up movement. It's called
choreography. I didn't know that then.''
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of the rehearsal, three ballet dancers who were
practicing at a studio across the hall peaked in on Pucci's
dancers. The hockey performance was being rehearsed. The girls
giggled.
</P>
<P>
   ``What sport is this?'' one girl whispered as she wiggled her
way into the doorway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hockey,'' two other girls whispered.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
