<DOCNO> NYT19990619.0196 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-19 17:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2138 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-SCHOOLS-SHAKEUP-NY     06-19 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SCHOOLS-SHAKEUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOOLS CHIEF WORKS OUT DETAILS OF MANAGEMENT OVERHAUL 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JODI WILGOREN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Schools Chancellor Rudy Crew is spending the weekend
making final decisions about the broadest housecleaning in the
history of the New York City school system, and neither school
superintendents nor Board of Education members have yet been
briefed on whose jobs are in jeopardy, officials said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Kovaly, the head of the city's superintendents'
association, said that he and his group's members were eager for
more specifics about who might be fired and why, while insisting
that students' poor test scores alone should not be grounds for
dismissal, particularly since new standardized tests were
introduced this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``To make conclusions on this test as to whether somebody went
up or went down, I don't think you can do that,'' Kovaly,
superintendent of District 11 in the Bronx, said Saturday. ``That's
like comparing how long it took me to run around the block this
year to how long it took you to run around the block last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Kovaly said that the right of superintendents to appeal their
ouster depends on when they signed their contract, but that ``if
someone chooses to challenge it, the association would likely
support them.'' But, he added, ``At this point, I haven't heard
names, I haven't heard what the reasons are, so it's purely
academic.''
</P>
<P>
   Crew said last week that more than five superintendents of local
districts will be ousted or urged to retire, and his spokeswoman
said Saturday that several dismissals will be part of a larger
restructuring likely to involve the creation of some new
administrative posts.
</P>
<P>
   Anticipating a more detailed announcement by Wednesday, members
of the Board of Education said the shake-up was the inevitable
other shoe dropping after state legislation expanded the
chancellor's authority over personnel matters in January 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I think it is larger than you've seen before?'' asked
William Thompson, president of the Board of Education.
``Absolutely. No one has ever had the authority to do it before.
All of us believe that this needs to be a very performance-driven
system. You try to reward people for good jobs. At the same time,
there are people who are not doing good jobs. There have to be
consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the new governance law expanding the chancellor's
authority went into effect, eight of the city's 32 districts have
had changes at the top based on performance, said Chiara Coletti,
Crew's director of public affairs. In two of those cases, the
chancellor and the superintendent came to a ``mutual agreement''
for early retirement; in others, Crew fired superintendents or
refused to continue their tenure.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the impending dismissals are significant because they
will be the broadest one-time change, and come at a critical time
for the city schools, as Crew faces pressure from City Hall to
boost performance and demand greater accountability from
administrators for poor test scores.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said Saturday that he had
not been told which superintendents were on the way out. And
Anthony Coles, the mayor's senior adviser on education, said in
statement: ``The mayor has urged the chancellor to present a plan
for radical reform of the education bureaucracy, including holding
administrators accountable, and we look forward to being briefed on
the chancellor's plans.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Coletti said that between now and Wednesday, when the school
board next meets, Crew would be talking to a variety of people,
including those likely to be fired or reassigned. ``There's a
certain amount of restructuring he wants to do,'' she said. Some
superintendents, she added, ``for a variety of reasons may be more
useful in other roles.''
</P>
<P>
   While she would not specify which superintendents are in danger,
Ms. Coletti said people who have been in their jobs for only a year
are unlikely to be let go, as they have not had time to prove
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   New superintendents are selected through a process in which
community school boards screen candidates, but Crew has the power
to reject their choices. Ms. Coletti said that her boss would seek
candidates both within the system and across the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he would be open to that approach, looking beyond New
York City,'' she said. ``It's happened before, but it hasn't
happened very often.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
