<HEADER>
A2139 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS-NOTES20-C     06-19 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-NOTES20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Anderson bonus can mark cap long-term
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ As talks aimed at extending the contract of Falcons
running back Jamal Anderson continue, it has become obvious that
the biggest hurdle is the signing bonus.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson wants more than the Saints gave draft pick Ricky
Williams and the Indianapolis Colts are expected to give Edgerrin
James. Anderson has $10 million in mind.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons are thinking around $6 million, which is what
quarterback Chris Chandler got with his extension last season.
</P>
<P>
   So what's the biggest problem with big signing bonuses?
</P>
<P>
   ``Like with any company, it's cash flow,'' Falcons general
manager Harold Richardson said.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a quick refresher on the workings of the cap:
</P>
<P>
   If Anderson signed a five-year contract with a $10 million
signing bonus, the NFL would divide the amount of that bonus
equally over the years of the contract. In each of those five
years, $2 million would count against the cap, before Anderson's
annual salaries or bonuses would be added.
</P>
<P>
   That method works well for the team in the first year, because
extensions with large bonuses usually come with minimum first-year
salaries.
</P>
<P>
   But once those annual salaries start accelerating, and they
almost always do, the salary cap takes another big hit.
</P>
<P>
   By the fourth year of Anderson's contract, he probably would
have a salary of more than $4 million, which, with the $2 million
annual charge for the bonus, would make the total cap charge more
than $6 million.
</P>
<P>
   For highly paid players, some teams pay much of the salary in
lump sums each year but call them signing bonuses, in order to
stretch out the effect on the cap.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons already have done it with Chandler by giving him $3
million of his $3.5 million salary and spreading the effect of the
$3 million over the next four seasons. That created $2.25 million
in cap room for this season.
</P>
<P>
   But when a player gets to the last couple of years of his
contract, retires or is cut, teams are on the hook for huge money.
Denver will carry several million dollars in cap charges for John
Elway this season and next, even though he retired.
</P>
<P>
   Big signing bonuses ``start the slide down the slippery slope,''
Richardson said. ``Cap charge jumps at a much greater percentage
than the cap limitation each year, which is why, if you do a bunch,
it's a never-ending deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, though, remains an optimist.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big contract, and teams never give up that kind of
money easily,'' he said. ``But it will get done.''
</P>
<P>
   What he said
</P>
<P>
   Richardson, when asked if the Falcons would trade a player on
the request of his agent: ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting busy
</P>
<P>
   Fullback Jeff Paulk, the team's third-round draft choice, became
the first Falcons draftee to sign a contract, a three-year deal
worth $1.09 million, including a $340,000 signing bonus.
</P>
<P>
   The other eight draft choices probably will begin signing next
week.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic jam
</P>
<P>
   Coach Dan Reeves said one of the questions in training camp will
be whether to keep four tight ends instead of the usual three.
</P>
<P>
   Tght end Rod Monroe, who was activated from the practice squad
last year for the final two games, has improved so much, Reeves
said, that he, O.J. Santiago, rookie Reggie Kelly and Brian
Kozlowski all possibly could make the active roster.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would mean more one-back sets,'' with two tight ends,
Reeves said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the team kept four running backs and a fullback. When
fullback Bob Christian got hurt and Kozlowski took his place it
hurt the offense.
</P>
<P>
   That's why the team drafted Paulk _ to back up Christian. But if
the Falcons carry two fullbacks, will they reduce by one the number
of running backs?
</P>
<P>
   Extra points
</P>
<P>
   Defensive end Chuck Smith has been slowed by a strained
hamstring, but it is not considered serious.... Reeves will visit
hospitals in Washington, Chicago and Nashville next week to speak
to heart patients.... Passing camp resumes Monday.... The Falcons
will scrimmage the Jaguars on Saturday, Aug. 8, at Furman
University in Greenville, S.C. The scrimmage will be open to the
public.... Third-year quarterback Tony Graziani has switched from
No. 13 to No. 7. He offered his old number to newcomer Danny
Kanell. ``It was for less than $10,'' Graziani said, ``but I can't
disclose what, because the IRS will get involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
