<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-19 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2140 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FATHERSDAY-SPIELM     06-19 1507
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FATHERSDAY-SPIELMAN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Linebacker father finds wife's cancer is also a defining moment
for him
 &HT;    By Tom Archdeacon
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   He quickly learned the value of paper plates over another sink
full of dirty dishes. He learned to play Pretty Pretty Princess
with his 5-year-old daughter, Maddie, and, after a few big-glass
spills, discovered Noah, now 3, drank best with his ``sippy cup.''
</P>
<P>
   He learned that Maddie won't eat the different foods on her
plate if they touch and that when it came to styling her hair, he
had the tonsorial touch of a ... well, a linebacker. As for Noah,
forget combing his hair, he didn't even like it washed. And neither
of the kids thought much of his scrambled eggs or the way he cut up
their apples. He just didn't do it like Mom.
</P>
<P>
   But he also was privy to the proud recountings of a daughter
learning to tumble in her gymnastics class and he marveled at each
new word mouthed by a son still learning to speak.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, there was the loving realization that his
31-year-old wife, Stefanie _ the girl he first got up the courage
to telephone for a date when he was 17 and she 15 _ had ``more
strength, more courage, more character'' than anyone he has known.
</P>
<P>
   All these lessons have come to Chris Spielman in the past year.
</P>
<P>
   And that's why today _ at a time when so many pro athletes show
themselves to be amateur parents _ the Cleveland Browns linebacker
gives us a Father's Day tale full of the same passion and intensity
that got him pictured on the Wheaties box as a high school player
in Massillon, Ohio, won All-America honors and the Lombardi Award
for him at Ohio State and four times has made him a Pro Bowl
defender in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   During the past decade, Spielman _ who at age 5 broke his
grandmother's nose with a hard tackle _ made his name as one of the
fiercest competitors in pro football. Now, he's also shown himself
to be one of the finest dads.
</P>
<P>
   This is the story of how Mr. Macho became Mr. Mom.
</P>
<P>
   It began last July, just as the 6-foot, 250-pound Spielman was
finishing nine months of rigorous rehab and preparing to return to
the Buffalo Bills after breaking his neck in an NFL game in late
October 1997. At the same time, Stefanie was three months pregnant
with their third child.
</P>
<P>
   During her pregnancy, Stefanie noticed a lump on her right
breast, though she dismissed it as a cyst. But after a miscarriage,
she mentioned the growth to a doctor. A biopsy determined the lump
was a non-spreading form of cancer.
</P>
<P>
   During surgery to rid the mass, another pea-sized malignant
tumor was discovered. Stefanie's right breast was removed, as were
21 lymph nodes on her right side. After that came six months of
chemotherapy.
</P>
<P>
   Late Thursday night _ after a day of individual workouts at the
Browns training camp in Berea _ Spielman recalled first trying to
cope with the cancer:
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember we were driving to the doctor's office to set up
some surgery and I said, `Man, I can't believe all this. I break my
freakin' neck and now you got cancer. What a raw deal.' That's when
my wife looked at me and said, `How can you talk like that? Look at
all the blessings in our life! Don't you ever say that again!' I
felt very small, very selfish. She made me realize what a weak
person I was. I saw her strength and I was in awe. Right then, her
words changed me.''
</P>
<P>
   Realizing what was most important in life, he decided last July
24 to sit out the NFL season so he could care for his wife and
their two small children.
</P>
<P>
   Stefanie was stunned and tearfully tried to convince him to
change his mind: ``He had trained so hard to get back to football I
didn't want to be the one who stopped his comeback. I knew just how
much football means to Chris.''
</P>
<P>
   To understand what she's talking about, consider:
</P>
<P>
   As a kid, Spielman trudged around football-frenzied Massillon in
the summer wearing combat boots and carrying old tires slung over
his shoulders to get in shape. When he married Stefanie, he showed
up for their honeymoon cruise with his weight-lifting gear. To prep
for the summer heat at preseason NFL camps, he's been known to
drive around in his truck with the windows up and the heater on. As
for Buffalo's brutal winters, he supposedly prepared by sleeping in
in the nude in front of an air conditioner.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, he played an entire game for Detroit with a torn right
pectoral muscle. He finished that fateful October 1997 game for
Buffalo _ making a game-high 13 tackles _ even though he was
experiencing numbness in his legs and later was found to have
damaged two vertebra in his neck.
</P>
<P>
   As for Grandma's broken beak, she had opened her arms to give
him a hug, but he thought she was getting ready to tackle him.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, while he'd spent a lifetime molding himself into an
unparalleled football player, he soon realized what he did away
from the game was most important:
</P>
<P>
   ``I always preached about being a husband and father first and
this was my defining moment. For 10 years, Stef had supported me _
without condition. It had all been about me and now I had to hold
up my end. I had to take my wedding vows literally. If I would have
played last year, I'd have been a fraud, a phoney. I wouldn't have
been a man. I had to be there to hold her hand when she was sick to
her stomach. I had to take her to her chemo, to care for her and
care for our kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Spielman tackled Stefanie's cancer with the same intensity he
uses in football. ``It's the only approach I know,'' he said.
``When there's adversity, you've got two choices_ fight or fold.
Just like in football, you learn everything about the enemy. You
learn the weaknesses and exploit them.''
</P>
<P>
   He set up a vitamin regimen for Stefanie, laying out 36 pills a
day. Discovering sugar and carbohydrates can feed cancer cells, he
rid the house of sweets. He administered the painful Neupogen shots
to bolster his wife's immunity and, when needed, he gave the pep
talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'd get down,'' Stefanie said, ``Chris would say, `It's
been proven that positive thinking can boost your immune system. So
no negatives.'''
</P>
<P>
   Spielman was at his best with the kids. ``We were pretty
up-front with them,'' he said. ``We explained Mommy had a boo-boo
inside her that had to be cut out.''
</P>
<P>
   As the chemotherapy took its toll, Stefanie decided to have her
head shaved during a backyard picnic. That afternoon, Chris had his
head shaved, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted it to seem normal to the kids that a parent had a
shaved head,'' he said. ``And I figured since I'm recognizable in
the area, if I showed up at 250 pounds with a shaved head, I'd draw
the attention away from my wife when we were out. But it was just
the reverse because Stef took a proactive approach and didn't try
to hide anything. She wanted women to know its OK to be yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   When Stefanie decided to wear a hat, she and Chris had a hat
party with the kids. As Dad played CDs, Mom and the two children
danced and tried on every hat they could find in the house. ``From
something awkward, we wanted to find a little fun,'' she said.
``It's all about finding the good in a situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Spielman said that while the next several months were tough _
and in private he often prayed his wife would not die _ he learned
some valuable lessons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned things a lot of fathers don't get to learn about
their families,'' he said. ``Before I just followed orders like
most husbands. For the kids, I was just there to play. But I
learned being a stay-at-home mom is the most important, the
toughest job on earth. With kids you can never be tired. You get no
breaks. I had no time to sit down and watch the ball game.''
</P>
<P>
   Stefanie's last chemo was in January, and two months ago she was
told she was ``cancer-free.'' She and Chris now give talks about
coping with breast cancer and they have started the Stefanie
Spielman Breast Cancer Research Fund (James Cancer Hospital, Office
of Development, 300 W. 10th Ave., Suite 519, Columbus, Ohio, 43210,
telephone (614) 293-3744). Spielman said all the money _ they've
raised $350,000 and hope to reach $1 million in a year _ is going
``purely for breast cancer research.''
</P>
<P>
   While this ordeal has driven him to help others, Spielman said
it's also helped him. In February, he was traded by Buffalo to
Cleveland and these days, as he drives from the family home in
Columbus to the Browns training camp, he can't help but notice the
changes:
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a different attitude. The grass seems greener this
year, the flowers seem brighter and everything seems to have more
sunshine on it.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why he couldn't wait to leave the Browns' camp for
Fathers Day: ``We're not doing anything extravagant. It's just that
I feel like I truly have my family back again. So we'll go to
church in the morning and then come home and have something to
eat.''
</P>
<P>
   And this time, by everyone's vote, Stefanie will be back cooking
the eggs.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
