<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-NOTES20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ravens poor, losing talent
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Desperate to upgrade the wideout spot, Baltimore coach Brian
Billick once dreamed of getting ``franchise'' free agents Carl
Pickens of Cincinnati or Terrell Owens of San Francisco, or trading
for Minnesota's Jake Reed. Instead the Ravens signed Webster
Slaughter, who has eight catches the last two seasons, Cowboys
reject Billy Davis and Qadry Ismail, who hasn't had a reception
since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The lackluster moves signaled that Art Modell again is the NFL's
most cash-strapped owner. A day after the Davis signing, that
circumstantial evidence was bolstered when Modell conceded he is
looking for a minority partner.
</P>
<P>
   There are rumblings that Modell is $190 million in debt and
asked league owners to forgive the $20 million relocation fee he
agreed to pay when he bolted from Cleveland. Word is Modell missed
one of his loan payments to Fleet Bank and had to hustle off to
Boston to make things right with his principal creditor. Modell
long has been one of the NFL's most accessible owners.
Unfortunately, he also has been the least fiscally responsible.
Even the Baltimore media, which chose to ignore Modell's financial
woes for a long time, concluded last week that the problems are
real.
</P>
<P>
   Despite denials by Modell, player agents around the league
insist that Ravens personnel director Ozzie Newsome lacked the
ready cash to sign high-profile vets. The Ravens lost guard Wally
Williams, offensive tackle Orlando Brown, defensive tackle James
Jones and tight end Eric Green in free-agency and swapped
quarterback Jim Harbaugh to San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   The Ravens have either signed or re-signed 14 unrestricted free
agents. But most of the signings _ running backs Steve Broussard
and Errict Rhett, tight ends Greg DeLong, Frank Wainwright and
Aaron Pierce, fullback Charles Evans, defensive end Fernando Smith
and safety James Trapp _ are not the kind to excite the fans.
</P>
<P>
   And it's clear that the franchise is operating on the cheap.
Eight of the 14 players signed contracts that included no signing
bonus. Only Evans and offensive tackle Harry Swayne got upfront
cash of more than $250,000. Swayne accounted for $5 million of the
$6.5 million that the Ravens spent on signing bonuses.
</P>
<P>
   Billick may be a great offensive mind, but with few standouts,
and the tandem of Scott Mitchell and Tony Banks at quarterback, he
had better be a miracle worker.
</P>
<P>
   The team managed to extend the contracts of two young stars,
linebacker Ray Lewis and wide receiver Jermaine Lewis, in 1998. But
in the long run, Modell probably won't be able to keep such
All-Pro-caliber performers as offensive tackle Jonathan Ogden and
defensive end Michael McCrary from exiting.
</P>
<P>
   Feuding
</P>
<P>
   It won't help the Ravens that new Washington owner Daniel Snyder
last week pirated away David Cope, who markets Baltimore's sale of
luxury suites, club seats and sponsorships. Modell has filed a
grievance, and league vice president Joe Browne said it will be
considered. But Cope was a noncontract employee. Modell, who said
there was, ``a sense of morality lacking'' in the hiring, might
have problems winning this battle with with new neighbor Snyder.
One Baltimore insider likened the loss of Cope to having a scout
switch teams on the eve of the draft.
</P>
<P>
   Means to an end
</P>
<P>
   New York Giants general manager Ernie Accorsi is discussing an
extension that would pay defensive end Michael Strahan $8 million a
year. It's good news for Falcons end Chuck Smith and bad news for
general manager Harold Richardson. If agent Tony Agnone lands that
deal for Strahan, the price for free-agent ends will escalate
leaguewide. Smith and fellow starter Lester Archambeau can become
unrestricted free agents in the spring. In an otherwise weak
free-agent market, there could be quality ends such as McCrary,
Robert Porcher (Lions), Tony Brackens (Jaguars), Simeon Rice
(Cardinals), Phillip Daniels (Seahawks), and Regan Upshaw
(Buccaneers).
</P>
<P>
   Tip sheet
</P>
<P>
   He lacks size, but Atlanta rookie wide receiver Rondel Menendez
isn't short on ego. A No. 7 pick and the 247th overall player in
this year's draft, Menendez last week fired Richard Katz, claiming
that the agent wasn't paying enough attention to him. Of course, it
might have been that $13,000 signing bonus the Falcons offered that
kept Katz from completing a deal. Maybe new agent Frank Myles will
heed Menendez's needs better.... Jacksonville coach Tom Coughlin
will serve as his own offensive coordinator in '99. But with two
former Jags coordinators, Steelers offensive coordinator Kevin
Gilbride and Browns head coach Chris Palmer, in the same division,
Coughlin has changed all the terminology in his playbook.... The
new six-year contract Philadelphia tailback Duce Staley signed
recently has been rejected by the league. Agent Brantley Evans and
Eagles vice president Joe Banner are shuffling the numbers to make
them comply with NFL guidelines.... With ABC televising Super Bowl
XXXIII, look for Disney execs to lobby Jim Steeg, league vice
president for special events, for major input into the halftime
show at the Georgia Dome.... Lions coach Bobby Ross is wasting
little time getting his pair of first-round picks into the lineup.
Chris Claiborne already is starting at weakside linebacker and
Aaron Gibson at offensive right tackle.... In the preseason
ratings, the National scouting combine lists the top quarterback
prospects in this order: Chris Redmon (Louisville), Chad Pennington
(Marshall), Tee Martin (Tennessee).... The days are numbered for
linebacker James Francis in Cincinnati. For the third year in a
row, he failed to get in enough offseason workouts to collect a
$250,000 bonus, and he's lost his starting job to Steve Foley....
The Jets are trying to extend the contract of standout linebacker
and former Georgia star Mo Lewis.... Rams offensive tackle Orlando
Pace has been a frequent no-show in the offseason and blew off a
workout bonus of $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   Carolina finer
</P>
<P>
   Credit Carolina coach George Seifert and director of personnel
Jack Bushofsky for making the most out of very little in this
year's draft. The 1998 signing of defensive tackle Sean Gilbert,
and this spring's trade for quarterback Jeff Lewis and signing of
restricted wide receiver Patrick Jeffers, left the Panthers without
first-, third- and fifth-round choices. Instead of making excuses,
the club made solid selections with its five picks. Former Georgia
standout Chris Terry (No. 2a) could win the starting job at
offensive left tackle. Mike Rucker (No. 2b) of Nebraska might get
significant playing as a pass-rusher. Tony Booth (No. 7), a former
James Madison safety being used at cornerback, looks like one of
the steals of the draft.
</P>
<P>
   Learning curve
</P>
<P>
   One reason Cleveland selected Tim Couch over Akili Smith was
that the Kentucky star had a one-month advantage reporting to camp.
Although he still trails Ty Detmer for the starting job, Couch has
benefitted from being with the club since May 16. Because Oregon
commencement exercises weren't until last Sunday, Smith couldn't
report to the Bengals until the next day. Cincy coordinator Ken
Anderson sent out daily Federal Express shipments to Smith with
video of every practice, but the rookie still looked lost in last
week's workouts and likely won't challenge starter Jeff Blake for
some time.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia freedom
</P>
<P>
   The Philadelphia Eagles might be no better in the first full
year together for director of operations Tom Modrak and coach Andy
Reid, but they will be different. Since the end of 1998, the team
has released, traded or decided not to re-sign eight former
starters: offensive guard Ian Beckles, offensive tackle Richard
Cooper, wide receiver Irving Fryar, running back Charlie Garner,
wide receiver Jeff Graham, quarterback Rodney Peete, linebacker
James Willis and strong safety Michael Zordich.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
