<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-19 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2142 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-DATELINE20-C0X     06-19 0643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-DATELINE20-C0X </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Emerging Kosovars enjoying the little freedoms
 &HT;    By Keith Graham
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FERIZAJ, Yugoslavia _ For several days now, Fatmir Demiri has
walked into the center of town and stood near a small outdoor
market selling peppers, lettuce and tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
   He comes, he says, for ``the joy of it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to go home,'' says Demiri, a 38-year-old grocery
wholesaler. ``I am enjoying this freedom very much.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a joy that, perhaps, only someone who has survived a
brutal war _ who has hidden in a cellar for many days and who has
seen his home firebombed, as Demiri has _ can share.
</P>
<P>
   If it were not so devastated, Demiri's town could pass for one
of those county seats in the American South with red brick
buildings around a square.
</P>
<P>
   But this town is in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs, who until recently controlled the government and
police, called the place Urosevac. The ethnic Albanians like
Demiri, who have long made up the vast majority of its people, call
it Ferizaj.
</P>
<P>
   Ferizaj will likely be its name in the future because only a few
Serbs, too old to leave, are still here. But those who departed
left a legacy of the hatred that spilled over between the Serb and
Albanian communities. A half block from where Demiri stands, a row
of a dozen shops were burned and bulldozed. Storefronts have been
smashed. Windows are broken in most buildings. Some entire blocks
have been burned.
</P>
<P>
   The Serb police and paramilitaries who, townspeople say, caused
all the damage, are gone. But NATO tanks manned by machinegunners,
survey the scene from street corners and uniformed Kosovo
Liberation Army guerrillas lounge in many doorways.
</P>
<P>
   The town is about 35 miles from Macedonia's capital of Skopje,
over green mountains covered with rocks and scrub. But to get here
from Macedonia is an ordeal that can take hours on roads jammed
with NATO convoys and masses of refugees either returning home or
leaving Kosovo to bring back loved ones who have fled.
</P>
<P>
   One of those convoys traveling Saturday was a team of CARE
International workers, part of the huge humanitarian contingent
pouring into Kosovo. Ferizaj, or Urosevac, and the surrounding
villages will be one of the principle areas in Kosovo where CARE
will operate, and it will have its work cut out for it.
</P>
<P>
   Homes will have to be made livable in time for the cold winters
in this region, and food is the most pressing need, townspeople
say. Prices are quadruple their rates before the Balkans conflict,
and 50 people were standing in line for bread at one store
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have flour for baking bread. We don't have oil for
cooking,'' says Esad Sabani, 63. ``Yes, there are plenty of hungry
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Isak Mehmeti, 62, a farmer from the village of Kastanievo, which
he says is ``four hours away by foot,'' says farmers' tools barns
and houses were destroyed by the Serbs and nothing has been
planted. ``No, we can do nothing this season,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Like many people, he is also fearful of landmines.
</P>
<P>
   Bob MacPherson, of Atlanta-based CARE U.S.A., is part of the
team that went into Kosovo from Macedonia on Saturday, and he will
be looking carefully at the mine problem. Marge Tsitouris, another
Atlanta-based CARE staffer, who is serving as CARE International's
interim Balkans coordinator, said others on the team, led by Marcus
Oxley of CARE Australia, will focus on the area's food and shelter
needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are waiting for your help,'' Mehmeti said. ``If the world
is not helping us, we cannot survive.''
</P>
<P>
   Demiri, who has been listening, nods in agreement, then puts his
hand on his friend's shoulder and adds: ``But the freedom is the
main thing. It doesn't matter if we don't eat for three days.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
