<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   G8-KOSOVO _ COLOGNE, Germany _ Second day of summit of the Group
of Eight industrialized nations. Welcoming statement by German
Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder. Developing. (Deans, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-DIARY _PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ One week ago, Florie
Topanica began the jarring emotional passage that more than one
million Kosovar Albanians will make in coming weeks, returning to
uncertainty, sadness and a hard new beginning that will be too
daunting for some even to attempt. Flora, as she is called, is my
translator and now my friend, a brave young woman of 25 who came
with me to Kosovo on the first day NATO troops got the border open
from Macedonia. Not knowing what awaited beyond that border, Flora
ate her fear of the menace she left behind in Pristina when her
family stepped on a train April 3 and became refugees. This is her
story. (Kunstel, Cox News Service) MOVED. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-DATELINE _ FERIZAJ, Yugoslavia _ For several days now,
Fatmir Demiri has walked into the center of town and stood near a
small outdoor market selling peppers, lettuce and tomatoes. He
comes, he says, for ``the joy of it.'' It is a joy that, perhaps,
only someone who has survived a brutal war _ who has hidden in a
cellar for many days and who has seen his home firebombed, as
Demiri has _ can share. (Graham, Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-BALKANS _ MOSCOW _ For Russia, winning isn't everything.
These days, with its economy in shambles and its president ailing,
winning isn't even possible. But being in the game is. Moscow's
diplomatic vexing of the United States and its Western allies
seldom prevails, but it cannot be ignored. Rushing troops into
Kosovo ahead of NATO's peacekeepers is the most recent and intense
example of an approach which, by design or default, has given
Moscow a prominent role in determining the future of the Balkans
province. It is an important achievement in Russia, where
nationalists are suspicious of NATO's expansion and distrustful of
America's intentions in a region once under the thumb of the Soviet
Union. (Holmes, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Thurs., June 17, in both International and Commentary
categories.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: An analysis.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-CHIAPAS _ SAN CRISTOBAL de las CASAS, Chiapas, Mexico _
Murder, rape, subjugation and emancipation _ this is the tough
stuff that infuses the drama of Mayan Women's Strength, an unusual
theater and social-service group in the southern Mexican city of
San Cristobal de las Casas. These are also the themes that sum up
the personal experiences of the two Mayan Indian women who founded
the group as a refuge for themselves and other women. As children,
both of these women were forced to become domestic servants and
they had to struggle long and hard to learn to read and write.
Today they write plays that reflect some of their experiences,
including the subjugation of women by men in their own Indian
communities. They also run a home that offers childcare and where
Indian women who have left or been expelled from their communities
can become literate, learn sewing and other skills. All become
involved in plays that are regularly performed in Indian villages
here. The group has also performed in the United States and
Australia. (Ferriss, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Wed., June 16, in both International and Lifestyle
categories.
</P>
<P>
   ANTIGUA-STANFORD _ ST. JOHN'S, Antigua _ This tiny island has
become a big battlefield in America's war to reshape the regulation
of offshore banks, which Washington says hides dirty money for
criminals and drug dealers. Caught in the middle is a wealthy
Houston businessman named Allen Stanford. Stanford has taken this
island by storm in recent years, opening up the nation's largest
offshore bank, as well as a daily newspaper and a development
company. He also has plans to build a hospital, a shopping mall,
and an airport. U.S. officials want to know why Stanford has such a
keen interest in this island of 64,000 people. In April, the U.S.
Treasury Department issued an advisory to U.S. banks, only the
second one in history, urging them to scrutinize all transactions
with Antigua. The advisory resulted, in part, because of U.S.
concern that Stanford was named to sit on a new board to supervise
the offshore sector, which seems a conflict of interest. Now
Stanford says he is helping Antigua to clean up i ts image. U.S.
officials aren't so sure. (Emling, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Wed., June 16, in both International and Financial
categories.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   TRICARE _ WASHINGTON _ In a year when concern for military
personnel has been trumpeted on Capitol Hill, defense spending
bills approved by the House and Senate reinforce a Pentagon policy
that lets military health care contractors refuse to pay for
skilled medical care for severely disabled spouses and children who
are cared for at home. Although two courts have disputed the
policy, the Pentagon says ``custodial care,'' which its Tricare
health benefits program doesn't cover, includes care by specially
trained nurses. That is driving some families to Medicaid to pay
the exhorbitant cost of providing essential care.
(Montgomery/Nesmith, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   Eds: MOVED Friday, June 18.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT _ WASHINGTON _ As the Microsoft antitrust trial enters
</P>
<P>
   its final week of testimony, all eyes are on a computer-savvy
federal judge who plans to issue his verdict by Labor Day. The
software giant, fearful of losing in the courts, turns to Capitol
Hill and public opinion for support. (Glass, Cox News Service). 25.
</P>
<P>
   Eds: MOVED Friday, June 18 in (w) Washington and (f) financial
categories.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   FLA-ALA-CONNECTOR _ Two groups are organizing with competing
proposals to build a connecting highway from Florida's beaches to
Interstate 65 in Alabama. Both groups say the four-lane road is
critical for hurricane evacuation, and point to 1995's Hurricane
Opal, which saw massive gridlock on all escape routes with some
motorists still stuck in traffic when the storm hit. Transportation
officials haven't given either route the OK, and officials in the
competing counties even say they hope both are built because both
are needed. Meanwhile, a new private bridge and a proposed toll
road are being pushed in neighboring coastal Alabama for the same
reasons. We examine the routes and their potential impact.
(Williams, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   FREE-MAN _ ATLANTA _ Calvin Johnson went from being a well-liked
high school football player and son of a former Ohio state senator
to the prime suspect in a series of rapes in and around an Atlanta
suburb. He was arrested in 1981, plea bargained his way out of
sexual assault charges and served 15 months in prison for burglary.
A few months after he was released, police started looking at him
in a series of rapes. He was arrested again, acquitted of one
attack and convicted of one. Now DNA evidence shows he didn't
commit that rape and he has been freed after 16 years in prison.
This week, he was an instant celebrity. (Torpy/Boston/McDonald,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   SQUIRREL-SICKNESS _ A weird strain of squirrel disease that has
not been seen in Florida since the 1970s is turning hundreds and
probably thousands of squirrels in Palm Beach County and five other
counties into mutant little freaks. The disease, squirrel
fibramotosis, covers their little bodies with hairless, bumpy
tumors, especially their eyes which leads to blindness.
(Staletovich, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
