<DOCNO> NYT19990619.0204 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-19 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2151 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-LOFT-LAW-REAL-3TAK     06-19 1239
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LOFT-LAW-REAL-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LOFT LAW'S PURSUIT OF LOFTY GOALS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DENNIS HEVESI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The old loft space _ not even all that extensive at
1,800 square feet _ is now worth a lot more than it was back in
'78; and, amid all his video equipment, Mike is wondering whether
there is a sizable chunk of profit to be made by selling now.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't live there any more; it's just his studio now _
really! Not like in the old days when the landlord looked the other
way while the couch was carried in and the freight elevator was an
adventure; when Asian women still bent over their sewing machines
next door and the streets downtown were plastered with those
``SoHo's Being Co-opted'' stickers. And certainly way before all
those chic boutiques dotted the block.
</P>
<P>
   Mike is a fictitious character, and his loft _ with its internal
Doric columns, sprinkler pipes, ersatz walls and raw-lumber loft
bed _ is, in reality, a walk-through exhibit currently at the New
Museum of Contemporary Art on Broadway, just south of Houston
Street.
</P>
<P>
   But while the exhibit is a product of the imaginings of two
installation artists, Joshua White and Michael Smith (down to the
created leak stain on the kitchen ceiling), it is certainly art
imitating life. And it is symbolic of the ongoing and, for some,
wrenching evolution of the loft market.
</P>
<P>
   It is an evolution that has seen some artists, like Kathy Arlt,
who lives in a former caviar warehouse on Greenwich Street in
TriBeCa, metamorphose from tenants to owners by way of arduous
financial and legal combat. And one in which many landlords, like
Diana Agostini of Greene Street in SoHo _ in the face of old,
demanding industrial buildings and reluctant lending institutions _
are joined in constant struggles to make the numbers add up.
</P>
<P>
   It was 17 years ago that the Loft Law _ more precisely Article
7c of the New York State Multiple Dwelling Law _ first legalized
what had been the clandestine tenancy of artists already occupying
commercial spaces downtown, while also mandating that landlords
bring their buildings into housing-code compliance.
</P>
<P>
   And with a five-year renewal of the Loft Law, which is to expire
at the end of the month, up for a vote in Albany (the Assembly has
already passed its version), partisans in the continuing
contentiousness between landlords and tenants are assessing the
effectiveness of legislation that, though directly affecting only a
sliver of the market, served as a wedge for the creation of a whole
new source of housing in a city long plagued by limited supply.
</P>
<P>
   The assessment is relevant, however, not just for the 835
buildings registered under the Loft Law _ 460 of which have, so
far, achieved code compliance or are in the process of doing so _
but for an estimated 2,600 other loft buildings scattered about the
city.
</P>
<P>
   For in recent years, artists, artisans and others priced out of
the increasingly gentrified co-op and condominium loft market
downtown have been illegally slipping into spaces in long-fallow
manufacturing areas in the Greenpoint and Williamsburg sections of
Brooklyn, in the South Bronx and in the Long Island City section of
Queens.
</P>
<P>
   And some tenant advocates, generally satisfied with a law that
has assured them legitimate occupancy and protection under rent
stabilization, argue that it should be extended to those
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   ``The law has worked insofar as protecting the tenancy of these
tenants,'' said William Hall, co-chairman of Lower Manhattan Loft
Tenants, a 700-member group. But there remains, Hall contends, a
core of landlords resistant to bringing buildings into compliance,
``and enforcement continues to be a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The New York City Loft Board, established in accordance with the
Loft Law, is charged with enforcing the statute's provisions and
deadlines, with writing the rules that govern the relationship
between landlords and tenants and with resolving disputes.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck DeLaney is the tenant representative on the nine-member
Loft Board. ``Everyone acknowledges that doing code-compliance work
in loft buildings with the tenants in place is a complicated and
delicate process,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, DeLaney said: ``There are now several thousand legal,
code-compliant housing units in the city thanks to the Loft Law,
and many more in the pipeline. To me, that's a success.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem,'' he said, ``is the real stubborn owner who
doesn't care about coming up to code, doesn't register and just
ignores the fines.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, ``illegal conversion has occurred in Brooklyn,
and a bit in Queens,'' DeLaney said. ``The city should enforce
against new illegal conversion, because if it turns its back, we're
going to see the same problems.''
</P>
<P>
   In the glass-half-full, glass-half-empty debate, however,
landlord representatives describe the law as ineffective, pointing
out that, after 17 years, 375 of the 835 registered buildings
remain out of compliance. The law is unfair, they argue, because it
fines them for failing to comply, but offers them little help in
finding financing to undertake the extensive renovations it
requires.
</P>
<P>
   It is a Catch-22, they say, that a building owner who cannot
obtain a loan for renovations because the banks are wary of a low
rent base is then punished by a law that allows tenants to stop
paying rents altogether because the renovations haven't been made.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Loft Law has sentenced owners to perpetual illegality and
made them owners of unsafe buildings,'' said Thomas Berger,
president of the Association of Commercial Property Owners, a
400-member loft-landlord group. ``They cannot get financing because
the banks see no sufficient rental to cover the mortgage.''
</P>
<P>
   The landlord representative on the Loft Board, John Lansden,
said the law ``should have taken into account that, for the most
part, these are small buildings where there is not a lot of income,
even after legalization.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These are not professional landlords,'' Lansden said. ``Many
have businesses in the building and bought the property to ensure
the survivability of the business. And as a matter of financing the
legalization, they're just not equipped to do it. That's the nuts
and bolts of it. What we have is a highly technical, confusing
series of regulations that are more penalty than incentive.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hall of the tenants group countered that the Loft Board has
a ``very liberal'' extension procedure. ``Any owner who can
demonstrate having made a good-faith effort to comply receives an
extension,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tenant leaders assert that the owners would simply rather see
their tenants leave, so they can go to market-rate rents or the
buildings can be converted to co-ops or condominiums _ even though,
in a blurring of the demarcation lines, some original loft tenants
have themselves banded together to partake of the conversion
possibilities. ``I would say that to whatever extent the
neighborhood has not become Disneyfied,'' Hall said, ``it's because
we are still there.''
</P>
<P>
   At stake is the survivability not only of the loft pioneers, but
of succeeding generations of artists who, in the estimation of Dr.
Elliot Sclar of the Columbia University Graduate School of
Architecture, Planning and Preservation, are vital to the city's
continuing economic growth.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
