<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-19 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2152 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COX-G8-KOSOVO-0620     06-19 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-G8-KOSOVO-0620 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SUMMIT TO TACKLE ANGRY YELTSIN
 &HT;    By Bob Deans
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox Newspapers
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLOGNE, Germany President Clinton joined the leaders of six
other major industrial powers in planning a high-stakes
fence-mending session on Sunday with Russian President Boris
Yeltsin in the wake of the Kosovo war.
</P>
<P>
   With the conflict shifting from peacekeeping operations after
the 78-day bombing campaign, the White House announced Clinton
would visit Macedonia and Italy Tuesday to meet with U.S. troops
and visit a refugee camp. The trip follows a weekend of summitry in
this 2,000-year-old city on the banks of the Rhine.
</P>
<P>
   First, though, the president hopes to turn the page after months
of troublesome dealings with Russia.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a kind of elephant in the room, which is hard
to ignore,'' Clinton's national security adviser, Samuel Berger,
told reporters here Saturday, referring to NATO's air war against
Serbia, a nation with whom the Russians have long been aligned.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the elephant gone,'' he said, ``it's possible to now deal
with a series of issues that are extraordinarily important.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's talks among the so-called Group of Eight, or G-8, were
to focus on ways the group could help Russia reduce its crippling
Soviet-era debt, safeguard its massive nuclear arsenal and prop up
its staggering economy all in an atmosphere of growing political
uncertainty in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting is also certain to highlight remaining differences
between Russia and its G-8 partners over the Balkans, however, and
the difficulty Yeltsin faces in pressing forward with painful
economic reforms back home.
</P>
<P>
   The partners were forced to table - for the second day in a row
- a planned statement on Balkan reconstruction because Russian
Prime Minister Sergei Stepashin balked at language that would rule
out rebuilding assistance for territory controlled by Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Even as White House aides stressed the need to restore
U.S.-Russian relations, Yeltsin was described as spoiling for a
tiff.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is in a fighting mood,'' Yeltsin's spokesman, Dmitry
Yakushkin told reporters in Moscow. ``A major aim by Russia is to
secure its place in the world arena.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cold War ended a decade ago, but the Kosovo campaign sent a
decidedly frosty breeze blasting through U.S.-Russian relations,
already chilled by two years of contention over economic and
security matters.
</P>
<P>
   The NATO campaign highlighted Russia's waning global influence.
Moscow bitterly opposed the air strikes but was unable, despite
months of trying, to prevent them or to pursuade Milosevic to
accept a compromise that would have averted the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   After the air war began, Yeltsin pulled Russia out of its
partnership arrangement with NATO, a move Clinton wants Yeltsin to
reverse.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin told the German magazine Der Spiegel in an interview the
NATO action had threatened ``to drag us back into the stone age''
and added: ``In our eyes, an extremely dangerous precedent for
solving conflicts has been set.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the continuing flap, Russia a fallen superpower with
more nuclear weapons than any other country except the United
States is both too dangerous and too important to be left out in
the cold by its G-8 partners: the United States, Britain, Canada,
France, Germany, Italy and Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's cooperation is deemed essential to furthering key G-8
aims ranging from the reduction of nuclear weapons to the expansion
of the global trading system; from countering global terrorism to
combating organized crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes a big difference whether Russia is able to strengthen
its econmy, maintain its democracy and continue to head in the
basice direction of opennes and reform,'' said Berger, ``or whether
it reverts back to some kind of nationalistic or inward-looking
leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   Stepashin, who took office only last month after the latest in a
series of unexpected shake-ups in the Russian government, presented
the G-8 leaders with Moscow's version of its economic outlook
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The presentation was expected to be the prelude to a
multi-billion-dollar debt reduction program the G-8 partners plan
to announce Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   In a private meeting, Clinton urged Stepashin to press for the
Duma, Russia's legislature, to finally ratify the SALT II treaty on
nuclear arms reductions. It was negotiated by President Bush,
signed six years ago and ratified by the U.S. Congress two years
ago, but has been held up by the Duma, which isn't expected to act
on the measure before elections set for December.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also asked his G-8 partners to put up more money to help
Russia safeguard its nuclear arsenal and to find civilian jobs for
Russia's nuclear scientists.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has spent $1.7 billion on the effort over the
past seven years; Clinton has asked Congress for an additional $4.2
billion over the next five years for the purpose.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
