<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-99 1822EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990619.0206 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-19 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2153 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-LOFT-LAW-REAL-2NDT     06-19 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LOFT-LAW-REAL-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: economic growth.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``It's not just paint on canvas,'' said Sclar, who with a team
of students wrote ``SoHo: A Community at a Crossroads,'' a 1996
study. ``It's important to remember that creative people develop
the software, the images, the movies, the lights _ the culture _
that attracts other industries and individuals to locate here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole new media industry growing up around Times Square
now,'' Sclar said, ``is built on the backs of this world-class arts
community centered in Lower Manhattan.''
</P>
<P>
   And, as ``Mike'' _ the archetypal loft resident of White and
Smith's exhibit at the New Museum _ seems to be asking: Can the
artist colony that begat the downtown residential boom survive its
own success, especially when it is so difficult for some of those
same artists to ignore the lucrative possibilities that their old
lofts now offer?
</P>
<P>
   ``Years ago, he considered himself a loft pioneer,'' said Smith,
who looks remarkably like Mike in the videos stationed around the
exhibit that serve as tour guide, and prospective seller.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back then he was trying to save SoHo for artists,'' Smith said
of his alter ego. ``He thought this neighborhood had integrity
beyond market value.'' But Mike also ``had to eat,'' Smith said,
and went into commercial art; most recently producing a
``point-of-purchase video'' for ``The Downtown Look'' _ a lip
definer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now 20 years have passed and Mike wants to test the market,''
Smith said. ``He's ambivalent about selling because the loft
represents a certain identity to him. But the market is so hot
right now that he wants to see what he can get for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Quite a bit, apparently, according a recent survey of the price
trajectory of 289 co-op or condominium lofts downtown. The report _
prepared by the Mitchell Maxwell &AMP; Jackson appraisal company for
the Corcoran Group residential brokerage _ found that in TriBeCa
between 1988 and 1998, the average price for 1,700- to
2,500-square-foot lofts increased from $495,000 to $800,000, or 62
percent; and from $855,000 to $1,440,000, or 68 percent, for lofts
of 3,500 square feet or more.
</P>
<P>
   In SoHo, the report said, the average price for lofts of 1,700
to 2,500 square feet rose from $495,000 in 1988 to $820,000 in
1998, or 66 percent, while lofts of 3,500 or more square feet
jumped 164 percent, from $700,000 to $1,850,000.
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Arlt, a longtime loft-dweller, and 23 neighbors bought
their six-story, 34-unit building _ an old caviar company's
warehouse at Greenwich and Watts streets in TriBeCa _ in 1993,
after a long and bitter dispute with the landlord. Told of the
museum exhibit and its protagonist's inner conflict about selling,
she said, ``Sounds like me.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Arlt, a writer who ran a typesetting business out of her
1,300-square-foot loft, moved in in 1978, when ``there was nothing
down here: no food store, no video store, no drug store, certainly
no doggy day-care like we now have.''
</P>
<P>
   Her initial rent was $350. ``But we all paid for everything
involved in operating the building,'' she said. ``If one of the
elevators broke, we would all pay a percentage; likewise taxes,
fuel bills.''
</P>
<P>
   The landlord bought the building in 1975 for $350,000. In 1981,
a year before the Loft Law was enacted, the leases expired and the
owner decided to raise Ms. Arlt's rent to $1,000 a month, twice
that for the larger units. ``But we would still pay all those
expenses,'' she said, ``so we went to court.''
</P>
<P>
   The landlord's position was that since the leases had expired,
he could go to market-rate rents before being channeled into rent
stabilization under the law. ``We prevailed,'' Ms. Arlt said,
``because we were still appealing before the law went into
effect.'' Rents were frozen. For years, claiming economic hardship,
the landlord did little to comply with the housing codes. And in
1990, the tenants went on rent strike.
</P>
<P>
   The difficulties in converting factory space to residential use
are hardly insubstantial. Any conversion must comply with laws on
access for people with disabilities _ most expensively, the
elevators.
</P>
<P>
   Many old factories do not have adequate rear yards to meet fire,
safety and air requirements, so it may be necessary to remove parts
of the building. Fire escapes must be installed; leftover
industrial contamination eliminated. Commonly, the buildings
require plumbing, electrical work, ventilation for kitchens and
bathrooms, sprinklers and smoke detectors.
</P>
<P>
   While the burden usually falls on the owner, in many cases the
original tenants paid for the renovations _ as well as improvements
like sanded floors, interior walls, appliances _ and then entered
legal combat over who was responsible for those modifications and
who would be compensated when the original tenant moved.
</P>
<P>
   In Ms. Arlt's building, the burden was eventually assumed by the
tenants.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-99 1822EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990619.0207 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-19 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2154 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-LOFT-LAW-REAL-3RDT     06-19 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LOFT-LAW-REAL-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: the tenants.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   By 1993, Ms. Arlt said, the landlord's widow ``decided she had
had enough, she wanted to sell.'' For $990,000, 24 tenants became
owners, ``and took out a loan for over $3 million,'' Ms. Arlt said,
to cover the renovation costs.
</P>
<P>
   These days, TriBeca ``is where everybody wants to live,'' she
said. ``It hasn't become SoHo yet, but it's getting there. And I'm
thinking of moving before the neighborhood gets to that point. In
two years, I think, it might be time to move.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Arlt paid $22,000 for her unit, not including her share of
the renovation costs, and believes she could now get ``somewhere in
the vicinity of $400,000.''
</P>
<P>
   Diana Agostini didn't really know what she was getting into when
she became a landlord. ``That's for sure,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Her father, Peter Agostini, a sculptor, had bought the
six-story, century-old clothing factory on Greene Street in SoHo,
along with a partner, for about $250,000 back in 1972. Each used
one floor, and they leased the other units _ two commercial spaces
on the ground floor and seven residential lofts.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Agostini's father died in 1993 and, because his partner
failed to pay real estate taxes for several years, the entire
burden of the building came down on her.
</P>
<P>
   ``The process of coming up to code had started even when my dad
was alive,'' Ms. Agostini said _ but was never completed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had an architect,'' she said. ``I have my blueprints, my
permits. Everything's been approved by the Loft Board. But I
haven't been able to secure a loan big enough to pay off the
$300,000 on the back taxes, plus the $200,000 to come up to code.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of Ms. Agostini's tenants were struggling artists when they
moved in. Now, she said, they seem to be doing quite well _ one
makes shoes for Broadway shows, one owns a recording studio and a
restaurant, another owns another building in SoHo.
</P>
<P>
   Three times the tenants went on rent strike between 1990 and '95
_ over issues like lack of heat, the front door not locking and,
more broadly, whether they were required to pay rent while the
building was in tax arrears. ``I'm out $80,000 that I will probably
never collect,'' Ms. Agostini said. Currently, there is relative
peace in the building _ only one tenant is withholding rent.
</P>
<P>
   The tenant on the top floor pays $1,004 for about 3,000 square
feet. Those on lower floors each pay about $770 for 1,700 square
feet. And there is an art gallery and a jewelry designer in the
ground-floor commercial spaces. ``Thank God I have them because
their rents are like $3,300 each and they are good tenants,'' Ms.
Agostini said.
</P>
<P>
   Total rental income is $12,000 a month and operating expenses
come to $10,000. ``That does give me an extra $2,000,'' Ms.
Agostini said, ``but I've been paying legal fees and architect
bills for the renovation plans. And right now I have a cornice that
I have to fix. That's $5,000 I have to borrow.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So that extra $2,000 goes pretty quickly,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Agostini would gladly complete the compliance process. ``I'm
not resisting coming up to code, I just don't have the money,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of me is emotionally attached to it,'' she said. ``It's a
dream of my dad's that I would like to fulfill. And when you've
given so much blood and sweat, you just don't want to walk away.''
</P>
<P>
   Not every loft building is a cauldron of contention.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Marks, creator of high-tech installations for museums
like the New York Hall of Science in Queens, has lived in his
1,600-square-foot loft in Chelsea for 30 years. When he sanded his
floors in the 1895 building on 28th Street, ``sewing-machine
needles came out of the cracks,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Loft Law, he said, ``has been a godsend, an imperfect
godsend, that has given me a legal standing and made for nice truce
conditions with the landlord.''
</P>
<P>
   The building's current owners _ the Chinese importers on the
ground floor _ ``are very close to complying,'' Marks said. And,
frankly, he is surprised it hasn't happened sooner.
</P>
<P>
   Marks, for one, is aware of contradictions at work in a
residential loft market where finger-pointing is often based on
stereotypes _ who is the victim, who is the money-grubber and on
whom does the building hang like an albatross _ that are about as
valid as a cliche: overused.
</P>
<P>
   Marks thinks that those landlords rigidly holding out against
compliance _ ``hoping, somehow, it will go away,'' he said _ have
done so ``not in their best interests.'' Even if a building were to
go to market-rate rent or conversion, ``we would still have our
rights,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Declining to state his rent, Marks pointed out that his landlord
would likely now be getting $2,000 a month from him had the
building achieved code compliance and, therefore, been granted a
residential certificate of occupancy. ``In a way, it works to my
benefit that he doesn't fully comply,'' Marks said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they had fully legalized under the Loft Law,'' he said,
``eliminated the violations and got the C of O, then we would be
channeled into rent stabilization and I would have been paying
increases compounded on increases for the last decade.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But the fact is I'd rather pay more,'' he said, ``and know
that everything is A-1 legitimate. It can really work beautifully
for both sides.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
