<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHOTO-WEEKEND-UPDATE-NYT </SLUG>
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Saturay, 06/19/99. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEWARK, N.J. -- June 19, 1999 -- BOX-IBF, 6-19 -- Robert
W. Lee Sr., founder and president of the International Boxing
Federation. For the last 16 years, the IBF, along with the World
Boxing Council and the World Boxing Association, has functioned as
one of the sport's three sanctioning organizations, and thus as one
of its most powerful forces. Now, Lee and the IBF, seem to be in
peril. Federal prosecutors in Newark, in a broad grand jury
investigation that predates the Holyfield-Lewis debacle, have been
submitting evidence of possible criminal conduct by the IBF, which
is based in East Orange, N.J. (Frank C. Dougherty/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- June 19, 1999 -- BKN-ARATON-COLUMN, 6-19 --
The New York Knicks' head coach Jeff Van Gundy, center, confers
with Marcus Camby, left, and Kurt Thomas during the first period of
Game 4 of the Eastern Conference Finals. His job in jeapordy
earlier in the season, Van Gundy has done a splendid job, steering
his team through the post-season. He beat Pat Riley and Lenny
Wilkens, then coached the legend right out of Larry Bird. Even if
the Knicks go out in four or five against the Spurs, Van Gundy has
won. (Barton Silverman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) GRAND CANYON, Ariz. -- June 19, 1999 --
GRANDCANYON-RAIL, 6-19 -- Motorists hoping to catch sunsets at
Grand Canyon National Park, top, are often forced to park along the
side of the road, after cars fill up the parking lot at Yavaipai
Point on the south rim, bottom. In a rare collaboration between
developers and environmentalists, nine environmental groups have
endorsed a $330 million plan to build a gateway to the park that
would include 1,220 hotel rooms and 250,000 square feet of
commercial space. The park is expected to draw some 5 million
tourists this year. (Jeff Topping/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) WASHINGTON -- June 19, 1999 -- GUN-CONTROL-POLITICS, 6-19
-- Following the defeat of the House Gun Control Ammendment on
Friday, Carolyn Maloney, D-N.Y., along with other Democratic House
female members gathered on Saturday to protest the passage of
viable gun control legislation. Democrats are moving to capitalize
immediately on the failure of the Republican-controlled House to
pass even modest gun-control legislation, and promising to take the
issue to the forefront of the 2000 presidential campaign. (Shana
Raab/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) PRIZREN, Yugoslavia -- June 19, 1999 --
KOSOVO-ALBANIANS-3, 6-19 -- Two barbers waiting for customers in
the oldest barbershop in the Kosovo city of Prizren, as life has
started returning to normal for many ethnic Albanians in southern
Kosovo. While it is still possible to find a few people who believe
in a multiethnic Kosovo, most Albanians here seem frankly just as
happy to see the Serbs gone, most of whom have fled north over the
last week. (Tyler Hicks/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) PRIZREN, Yugoslavia -- June 19, 1999 --
KOSOVO-ALBANIANS-2, 6-19 -- A Serbian woman walking in the deserted
Serbian quarter of Prizren on Saturday. While it is still possible
to find a few people who believe in a multiethnic Kosovo, most
Albanians here seem frankly just as happy to see the Serbs gone.
Prizren has come alive again without the city's perhaps 10,000
Serbs, most of whom have fled north over the last week. As one
Albanian put it: ``The politicians destroyed it all. But almost all
the Serbs listened to their politicians.'' (Tyler Hicks/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) PRIZREN, Yugoslavia -- June 19, 1999 --
KOSOVO-ALBANIANS-1, 6-19 -- Life has started returning to normal in
the Kosovo city of Prizren, as residents crowded into a food bank
on Saturday. Although very little food is available, this lovely
city in southern Kosovo, dotted with mosques and churches alike,
has been reborn in the last week under the watchful eye of NATO
peacekeeping troops. While it is still possible to find a few
people who believe in a multiethnic Kosovo, most Albanians here
seem very happy to see the Serbs gone. (Stephen Crowley/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) LOS ANGELES -- June 19, 1999 -- CALIF-GANGS, 6-19 --
Steve Wills, left, and Jason Wagner of the Los Angeles Police
Department, patrolling at a housing project near Venice Beach,
Calif., where a court injunction is in force. As a way to combat
street gangs, Los Angeles is increasingly turning to injunctions.
The injunctions give the police probable cause to stop and search
members named in the court order at any time. Gang members found
guilty of violating the injunctions can be ordered to pay fines or
serve time in jail, and probationers can be returned to prison to
serve the remainder of a sentence. (Monica Almeida/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- June 19, 1999 -- SONOFSAM-MEMORIES-3, 6-19 --
Joe Coffee, 61, a detective sergeant in charge of the weekend night
shift when David Berkowitz committed most of his murders, is among
those whose lives were altered by the Son of Sam killings 22
summers ago. ``I got a $5,000-a-year raise,'' says Coffee, who
retired from the police force in 1985. ``But I think the case has
taken at least 10 years off my life. I quit smoking three years
before I got called in on Son of Sam. But I started again after I
saw what he did to Virginia Voskerichian, and I never stopped
smoking since.'' (Librado Romero/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- June 19, 1999 -- SONOFSAM-MEMORIES-2, 6-19 --
Former Daily News columnist Jimmy Breslin, is among those whose
lives were altered by the Son of Sam killings 22 summers ago. Two
of the six murders occurred within a mile of where Breslin lived in
Forest Hills, Queens. His daughter, Rosemary, was the age of the
victims. Afraid that his daughter might be a target of David
Berkowitz, Breslin sent his family to live with relatives in East
Hampton and accepted police protection for himself. ``It was a
dreadful summer,'' says Breslin, now a columnist at Newsday. ``My
family was away. I was drinking too much.'' (Librado Romero/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) FALLSBURG, N.Y. -- June 19, 1999 -- SONOFSAM-MEMORIES-1,
6-19 -- David Berkowitz, the serial killer known as the Son of Sam,
serving six consecutive life sentences that total more than 300
years at the Sullivan Correctional Facility, a maximum-security
prison in Fallsburg. ``I am so sorry that, you know, this pain
doesn't seem to end,'' he says, referring to over the coming
release of a Spike Lee movie called ``Summer of Sam.'' Berkowitz
says that he monitors ``everything there is'' about Spike Lee and
his family. ``I pray for Spike Lee and his family, his wife, Tonya,
his two children, Jackson and Satchel,'' he says. (Librado
Romero/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) INGLEWOOD, Calif. -- June 19, 1999 -- VIOLENT-VIDEOGAMES,
6-19 --Alfredo Lambour, 15, at his home in Inglewood, playing the
violence-oriented computer video game Quake II. Lambour spends two
hours a day in his living room, in search of monsters. ``It can
just split people in half,'' he says of the game. Video games have
come under increased scrutiny after the shootings at Columbine High
School in Littleton, Colo., that left 15 people dead. (Gerard
Burkhart/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
