<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHASS-COLUMN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: for the franchise. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Homerless Race
</P>
<P>
   On successive days last week, the race for most times at bat
without a home run underwent a dramatic change. Last Monday, Tony
Womack of Arizona relinquished his lead in the race with a home run
against Ryan Dempster of Florida in his 227th at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   A day earlier Mike Caruso of the Chicago White Sox, in his 216th
at-bat, hit his first home run of the season against Rick Aguilera
of the Chicago Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   Their exit from the race left Luis Castillo of Florida all alone
at the top. Entering Saturday's games, he had batted 231 times
without hitting a home run. Rey Ordonez of the Mets was a distant
second with 189 at-bats, and Kevin Stocker of Tampa Bay was next at
183.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Karl probably cannot understand their power problem. The
Milwaukee pitcher has only 29 at-bats in his 14 starts this season,
and he has hit two home runs.
</P>
<P>
   It's a Blue Jay! It's Fernandez
</P>
<P>
   Some people might swear that Tony Fernandez stepped into a
telephone booth last Aug. 1, but all he did, really, was move from
second base to third base. Since that day, however, American League
pitchers have suffered from Fernandez's transformation.
</P>
<P>
   Not even balls made of kryptonite can get him out. ``This is not
a phenomenon this year,'' Gord Ash, the Toronto general manager,
said. ``You go back to last August, when we moved him from second
to third. He didn't have to worry about a lack of range. He seemed
to take off offensively.''
</P>
<P>
   A .282 career hitter for his first 14 years in the majors,
Fernandez was hitting .287 when the month of July ended last year.
The next day he began playing third, and he proceeded to hit .381
in his last 67 games, finishing with a .321 average, just one point
below the career-high .322 he batted in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's always been a fairly good hitter,'' Ash said, ``but he's
moved into another level.''
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez, before Saturday's game, was batting a league-leading
.407. When the first phase of interleague play began June 4, he was
hitting .383. In 14 games since, he amassed 25 hits in 51 at-bats.
Besides catapulting him beyond .400, his torrid stretch placed
Fernandez two career hits away from Julio Franco's 2,177, most ever
by a Dominican Republic native.
</P>
<P>
   ``His work ethic, his concentration and, I think, his comfort
level all play a role in it,'' Ash said of Fernandez's remarkable
late-life improvement as a hitter. ``I've never seen anybody, and I
underline anybody, work like this guy works. Pre- and post-game, he
conditions himself. He sets a work tone second to none.''
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez, who will turn 37 on June 30, is in his third tour of
duty with the Blue Jays, with whom he has spent nine years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony has always been a hard worker,'' Ash added, ``even when
we had him as a youngster. He always had dedication. Everybody
talks about the pressure that comes with hitting .400. He's a guy
who has the ability to shut it out. That doesn't seem to bother
him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
