<DOCNO> NYT19990619.0220 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-19 19:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2175 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LENDING-COMMERCIAL-RE     06-19 1180
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LENDING-COMMERCIAL-REAL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYERS SAY MARKET, WHILE NOT `FROTHY,' IS HEALTHY 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
 - 2TAKES-NYT   By JOHN HOLUSHA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ This time last year the real estate market was, in
the words of one executive, ``frothy.'' Aggressive Wall Street
firms were providing 90 percent financing for deals, reducing the
amount of equity a prospective purchaser had to provide. Deals were
plentiful and prices were climbing.
</P>
<P>
   Then the capital-market crunch hit in late August. Problems in
far-away places like Thailand and Russia shook the confidence of
bond market investors. Institutions that were backing investment
bankers' eagerness to lend by buying the loans packaged as
commercial mortgage-backed securities suddenly fled to the safety
of Treasury securities.
</P>
<P>
   Stuck with loans it could not resell at a profit, the Wall
Street companies stopped lending or sought to readjust the terms of
their agreements. With uncertainty prevailing, transactions came to
a halt. Declining stock prices for real estate investment trusts,
or REIT's, sharply limited their ability to make additional
investments.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the smoke has cleared, real estate finance executives
say that financing is available for property sales but that buyers
now need 25 to 30 percent equity. Several investment-banking firms
have left the real estate lending business or sharply scaled back.
The prices of publicly traded real estate companies, including the
REIT's, remain depressed, and the REIT's are no longer on a buying
spree.
</P>
<P>
   The experience left some veteran real estate executive amazed at
the pace of change in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the stock market crashed in 1987, it took three years for
our industry to adjust,'' said Peter Hauspurg, the chairman of
Eastern Consolidated Properties, a Manhattan-based sales brokerage
company. ``Last year it happened in one day.''
</P>
<P>
   He said his company sells on average two buildings a week. ``We
didn't do anything for two months'' after the credit market crunch,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Transactions have resumed and prices are at or above the level
of June 1998. But 90 percent loan-to-value financing has become
rare and both buyers and sellers are taking a more conservative
approach to structuring deals. Almost to a person, real estate
executives say this is a healthier state than the one that
prevailed a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Investments by REIT's have fallen sharply nationally. According
to figures compiled by Granite Partners, REIT's accounted for 53
percent of all investments in office buildings priced over $10
million in 1998. In the first quarter of this year the figure fell
to 30 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
   But the REIT's still like Manhattan. In 1998 they bought $900
million of property and accounted for 30 percent of office building
investment in Manhattan. So far this year, they have invested $700
million but account for 41 percent of investments, as buying by
institutional and offshore investors has dropped from 20 percent to
6 percent of the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``The demand for property in Manhattan is pretty strong, but
it's not what you would call frenzied,'' said Robert M. White Jr.,
a senior vice president at Granite. Overall, Granite anticipates
that investments in Manhattan office buildings in the first half of
this year will be two-thirds of the $3 billion that was invested in
the first half of last year. Pricing is up slightly from last year
to an average of $147 per square foot, compared to $142 a square
foot.
</P>
<P>
   ``REIT's reached their historical high in the fall of 1997,''
said Dennis Yeskey, managing director of Deloitte &AMP; Touche's real
estate services group. ``The problem is that they were hyped as
growth stocks when in fact they were a dividend play. So they
dropped about 20 percent on average, while the overall stock market
went up 30 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeskey said REIT stock prices have fallen so far that some
investors, notably Warren Buffett, are buying them as a value
investment. Yeskey said prices had gradually improved over the last
few months.
</P>
<P>
   New York office properties remain a solid investment, he said,
because of the good fundamentals of the market. ``Vacancy rates are
the lowest in the decade, at around 5 to 7 percent,'' he said. ``It
used to be when vacancy rates went below 15 percent everybody
started building like crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   He noted that most of the commercial buildings going up, such as
the Reuters headquarters in Times Square or the Bear Stearns
project on Madison Avenue between 46th and 47th Streets, are being
built to suit the needs of their major tenants, rather than on
speculation.
</P>
<P>
   Because liquidity has come back, although on a more conservative
basis, more owners are testing the water by offering their
buildings for sale. ``We did a survey and found that $25 billion of
office property was for sale in Manhattan,'' said Howard Michaels,
chairman of the Carleton Group, a company specializing in complex
financial transactions.
</P>
<P>
   Today's deals are likely to be more complex than in the past
because of the wary attitude of many lenders. ``Last year, you
could make one phone call and do the deal,'' Michaels said.
``That's a lot less likely this year.'' He said there were a lot
more of what he called ``A, B deals'' in which one lender makes the
larger, senior loan, while another provides the rest of the funds
to complete a transaction, to spread the risk.
</P>
<P>
   He said the weak market conditions of the early 1990's were
providing opportunities for investors to buy buildings in which
tenants are holding leases with rents well below current market
conditions. ``Today you can find properties that were substantially
leased in the early 1990's that are $10 to $20 a square foot below
the current market,'' he said. ``They are being purchased in the
anticipation that the return on investment will increase as the
leases roll over and are replaced at current rates.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the spreads on loans, the amount of interest above the
rates on Treasury securities with similar dates of maturity, have
not declined to last year's pre-crunch levels, the slower rate of
investment activity so far this year could be good news for buyers,
said Carol D. Nichols, senior managing director of Insignia/ESG's
capital advisory group. ``Some lenders have not filled out their
programs for the year, which may mean there will be more liquidity
as the year goes on,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Industry executives say one reason the credit crunch was so
severe toward the end of last year was that the first half was so
busy that many lenders had placed as much money as they had planned
for the year when events went awry in August. As a result, they
simply headed for the sidelines while the turmoil was being sorted
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, real estate learned that liquidity was more
important than location,'' said Dale A. Reiss, head of the E&AMP;Y
Kenneth Leventhal real estate group's New York office. She said the
nature of the commercial mortgage-backed securities market has
changed as a result of bond market turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
