<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-19 19:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2176 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LENDING-COMMERICAL-RE     06-19 0264
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LENDING-COMMERICAL-REAL-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
NEW YORK: market turmoil.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the commercial mortgage-backed securities market, mortgages
are pooled and divided into slices with different credit ratings,
with the lower rated parts _ those considered below investment
grade _ drawing the highest interest rates because of the greater
risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``The markets are not the way they were,'' she said. ``You need
buyers for the lowest-rated pieces, and most of those buyers have
disappeared. It's hard to do securitization when you don't have a
buyer for the below-grade piece.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not seeing as many games with A, B, and C pieces,''
said William Shanahan, a senior director of Cushman &AMP; Wakefield,
referring to the rating of the pieces of the commercial
mortgage-backed securities. ``Now we are seeing one big piece with
a small B piece.''
</P>
<P>
   He said some investment banks are still smarting from the
effects of some of the risky paper they bought while the market was
hot. ``Some of those shops are still holding B paper from last
year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Shanahan said borrowers are less able to leverage the income of
a piece of property. Last year, he said, if a property had $1
million in income, its owners could borrow as much as 11 times that
income. Today that multiple ratio is 8.5 to 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``The capital markets are not as much fun as they were last
year, but they are much healthier,'' he said. ``Most of the pundits
are saying that we are in an environment that can last for a while,
and people can count on their lenders being there for them.''(BBOX)
</P>
</TEXT>
