<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-19 19:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2177 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS &LR;      06-19 1526
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGER DIRECTED AT WITHDRAWING SERBS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MITROVICA, Yugoslavia _ The fires of revenge burned throughout
northern Kosovo as Serb forces sullenly made final troop
withdrawals before the NATO-imposed deadline of midnight Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   After enduring months of ``ethnic cleansing,'' of fleeing for
their lives, of seeing loved ones gunned down and homes burned to
the ground, some Kosovar Albanians gave their Serb neighbors a
taste of the same Saturday, looting and torching homes on the heels
of the Serb retreat.
</P>
<P>
   NATO forces face a daunting task trying to quell these flames of
vengeance, which first flared centuries ago near this green-brown
patchwork of lush farmland set amid craggy gray mountains.
Saturday, NATO peacekeepers seemed incapable of stopping many
ethnic Albanians from taking retribution on their Serb neighbors in
the rural pockets of Kosovo and back streets of towns.
</P>
<P>
   And despite the heavy presence of NATO troops in armored
vehicles and tanks, the soldiers also seemed unable to control
Kosovo Liberation Army guerrillas armed with pistols and grenades
who were telling Serbs to leave their homes and in some instances
overseeing the ransacking of Serb homes.
</P>
<P>
   Just off the main road that runs through Mitrovica, Yugoslav
Nasic, 64, and his wife were shaking in fear as a NATO armored
personnel carrier dropped them in front of their home.
</P>
<P>
   The Serb couple pleaded with NATO French peacekeeping forces,
which are responsible for the area, to protect them from KLA
soldiers, who they said had threatened to kill them if they
remained.
</P>
<P>
   Nasic said KLA soldiers burst into their home Saturday and
``seemed polite at first.'' Then he said one of the soldiers
wrenched his wife's left forefinger, apparently breaking it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am too afraid now. I have to go. NATO cannot sit and wait
here in front of our house all night. We are going to have to go,''
said Nasic, his hands trembling, his wife wincing in pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will kill us,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The French troops grew impatient and moved on. The Nasics then
left their home and walked away toward the Serbian forces on the
edge of town that were preparing to pull out. They took nothing
with them.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later, two KLA soldiers emerged from the elderly
couple's backyard. Sola Zahiti, a commander of KLA special forces
in the town, was dressed in full camouflage, armed with a pistol
and a grenade.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if he had forced the couple to leave their home,
Zahiti replied, ``Why not? Look what they did to their neighbors'
houses.''
</P>
<P>
   He pointed to the charred remains of ethnic Albanian homes that
dotted the neighborhood. Only those homes marked with a Serbian
Orthodox cross and symbol of Serb solidarity drawn in chalk were
left untouched.
</P>
<P>
   Ethnic Albanian children picked cherries from the trees in the
well-groomed yards of the Serb homes while Albanian men and
teenagers entered the Serb homes and filled burlap sacks with alarm
clocks, radios, eating utensils, and glassware.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did it to us,'' said one of the teenagers, looking
startled and ashamed that a reporter was watching him. ``Why
shouldn't we do it to them?''
</P>
<P>
   Zahiti led a reporter into several of the homes and pointed to
green uniforms worn by Serb paramilitaries who had been terrorizing
ethnic Albanians. One home, he said, was owned by Miki Vucinic,
whom he described as a local paramilitary leader who had
orchestrated the burning of ethnic Albanian homes and random
killings.
</P>
<P>
   Stepping over empty liquor bottles, scattered fishing tackle,
and several pornographic magazines, Zahiti held up a uniform with a
patch that depicted the insignia of a tiger which he said was worn
by the notorious and murderous paramilitary unit known as Arkan's
Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are murderers,'' Zahiti said.
</P>
<P>
   But he did not directly answer when asked about the elderly
couple who had lived here and the role they could have played. ``We
need the houses,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Similar attacks were reported near the village of Belo Polje,
where three Serbs were killed Saturday and a fourth badly wounded _
each with a shot to the forehead. Near Gnjilane, where US
peacekeepers have their headquarters, Marines arrested a Serb for
allegedly killing one man and wounding two others in a sniper
attack.
</P>
<P>
   Along the road from the Kosovo capital of Pristina to Mitrovica,
scores of Serb homes of stucco and red tile roofs were in flames.
Tractors and horse carts were seen on the road loaded with stolen
furnishings, beds, and appliances.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not stealing _ this is revenge,'' said Osman Majouni,
35, driving a tractor heaped with a washing machine, a hand-carved
cradle, an oak table, and bookshelves. He said he took the
possessions from a Serb neighbor in the village of Novo Sello.
</P>
<P>
   The neighbors said the house belonged to Miroloup Lazic, a local
farmer and military commander of Serb forces in the area. The home
was stripped clean, except for a picture of a Serbian Orthodox
saint in a smashed glass frame, a broken jar of pickles, and piles
of schoolbooks and papers from the man's teenage children. In the
yard, a dozen pigs grunted and picked through trash _ the only
livestock left behind by the Albanian Muslims, who do not eat pork.
</P>
<P>
   Feizullah Musa, 56, said that he and others in the village
always got along with their Serb neighbors until the fury of Serb
nationalism took hold about 10 years ago, building to a crescendo
of hate in the last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't always like this,'' he said, standing in an apple
orchard and watching as one of his Serb neighbor's homes crackled
in flames and charred roof beams collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   The Albanian revenge came fast on the heels of the Serb retreat.
In Mitrovica, a convoy of Serbian forces prepared its final retreat
from the northern edge of town in the long shadows of the
 &UR; afternoon &LR; . French forces were working out the final details of
the withdrawal, which is called for in the agreement between NATO
and Yugoslav Army leaders that ended the nearly three-month war in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   A 35-year-old major of the Serbian special police forces, with
an automatic pistol, a 10-inch knife and a grenade strapped to his
Kevlar vest, stood with his arms folded just moments before a
convoy of buses filled with soldiers and armored personnel carriers
prepared to exit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will see if they protect the Serbs. If they don't we will
come back. This is our country and we will protect our people,''
said the major, who declined to give his name.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about the systematic campaign exacted for months
againt ethnic Albanians, he shrugged his shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, and now they are doing the same thing to us in Pec, in
Jakovic, in Klina, and everywhere. NATO does nothing to protect the
Serbs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As he spoke he leered at the Globe's translator, an Albanian
woman. He smiled as his men made lewd gestures and shouted
obscenities at her.
</P>
<P>
   Then he studied the name on her press pass. ``We will have to
remember you,'' he said to her, ``when we come back.''
</P>
<P>
   Pressed again about the nearly 1 million civilians who were
forced from their homes by the Serbian forces, he said, ``We didn't
burn the houses of the innocent, only the terrorists. They are all
terrorists.''
</P>
<P>
   With the buses idling and the armored personnel carriers
sputtering to a start, the major climbed atop a jeep with a machine
gun mount at the head of the convoy and waved his arm as the convoy
headed north for the 40-mile drive to the Serbian border.
</P>
<P>
   As the line of vehicles passed, a soldier shouted to a group of
Albanian women and children who silently watched on the roadside,
``Kosovo is ours. We will be back.''
</P>
<P>
   At the corner of an avenue called Liberty, Shipi Koshie turned
to watch the convoy pass and the Serb soldiers making three-finger,
Serbian nationalist salutes. It was just after 5 p.m., and she was
walking home from her work at a technical engineering firm, a walk
that she made every day for 20 years with her co-worker and
neighbor Lila Borbaric.
</P>
<P>
   Even though she is ethnic Albanian and her neighbor is Serbian,
they walked together from work along Liberty Avenue every day, even
throughout the last three months of fighting.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, her friend, Lila Borbaric, pulled the shutters down on
her house and left for Serbia. The house with a neatly tended
garden of yellow lilies and pink roses was the only house not
blackened and bombed out on the street.
</P>
<P>
   Koshie turned the key in her gate and walked into what is left
of her home, which was firebombed and ransacked on April 25 by Serb
paramilitaries.
</P>
<P>
   In the weeks since the attack, Koshie said that there had been
long, awkward silences as the two colleagues walked home. She
didn't know what to say to her neighbor, who offered her little
help. The walk had become a silent ritual.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't blame Lila,'' she said, standing in the charred rubble
of her kitchen. ``She was not courageous. She was afraid like
everyone else. I blame the forces that make people act this way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
