u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2NDTA     06-19 0555
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDATED: LINDA GREENHOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Koreas Sparring, Again  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks after former Defense Secretary William Perry traveled
to North Korea with a letter from President Clinton proposing a
path to reconciliation between the two countries, the North
responded by getting its fishing fleet and navy into a fire fight
with South Korean ships along a disputed border. The North Koreans
lost a ship and more than 20 sailors. America, though, may have
lost a chance to convince Congress that sanctions on the North
should be lifted in return for commitments from Pyongyang to give
up their missile tests and other threatening programs.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DAVID E. SANGER
</P>
<P>
   Hold That Coke  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the biggest recall in Coke history, four European countries
ordered Coca-Cola products off store shelves after dozens of people
in Belgium fell ill after drinking Coke. By Friday, despite an
apology from Coca-Cola's chairman and an explanation that the
problem originated at two European bottling plants, a ban on Coke,
Sprite and Fanta remained in Belgium and Luxembourg. The
Netherlands banned products handled in Belgium, and France demanded
a recall of beverages from a plant in Dunkirk blamed for some of
the incidents.
</P>
<P>
   _ By CONSTANCE L. HAYS
</P>
<P>
   No Magic Bullet for Cancer
</P>
<P>
   In an international study that offered new hope for delaying the
onset of breast cancer, risk of the disease was lowered by 76
percent among postmenopausal women who took an osteoporosis drug,
raloxifene, for three years compared to a similar group that took a
placebo. But because the duration of benefit is unknown and
raloxifene can produce unwanted effects, experts cautioned against
recommending it as an anti-breast-cancer drug except in clinical
trials.
</P>
<P>
   _ By LAWRENCE K. ALTMAN
</P>
<P>
   A New Indian Museum  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Fine Arts Commission, the esthetic arbiter of the appearance
of what can be built in Washington's monument area, unanimously
approved the design of the Smithsonian Institution's new National
Museum of the American Indian. It will cost at least $110 million
and is to open in 2002 on the last available site on the Mall. The
museum's collection will include most of the holdings of the Heye
Foundation in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Indians played a major role in the design of the limestone
building. The land surrounding the museum will include forest and
wetland, and in the marshy area the cattails so essential to many
Indian rituals will be grown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's fabulous,'' said Emily Malino Scheuer, a member
of the Fine Arts Commission. ``It is a long overdue recognition of
native American culture.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By IRVIN MOLOTSKY
</P>
<P>
   GM and Ken Burns
</P>
<P>
   That Ken Burns would continue to make well-received
documentaries seems a safe bet. Still, General Motors took an
unusual flier on Burns when it committed to 10 years of
underwriting 35 percent of his future projects, sight unseen. GM
has been the sole corporate underwriter for ``The Civil War,''
``Baseball'' and Burns' newest, ``Not for Ourselves Alone: The
Story of Elizabeth Cady Stanton and Susan B. Anthony,'' to be seen
on PBS in November. Now Burns, and many freelancers who work with
him, have some security and the luxury to explore projects in
advance.
</P>
<P>
   _ By LAWRIE MIFFLIN
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
