<HEADLINE>
SERB, ALBANIAN FARMERS SQUARE OFF IN TRACTOR DISPUTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORALAVIC VALLEY, Yugoslavia _ Call it a tractor war.
</P>
<P>
   On one side of the road that weaves through the farmland north
of Pristina is the Serb village of Grac.
</P>
<P>
   And on the other side is the ethnic Albanian village of Stanovc
I Ult.
</P>
<P>
   Albanian Kosovars began returning to their homes Saturday after
hiding out in the mountains for months and claimed that their Serb
neighbors had stolen their tractors.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of Albanian farmers walked across the road armed with
shotguns and automatic rifles to get the tractors back, and soon
the crackle of gunfire echoed across fields of potatoes and
lettuce.
</P>
<P>
   NATO troops moved in.
</P>
<P>
   As the sun was going down, there was a tense standoff with
nearly a hundred farmers from each side squared off along the road,
separated by a NATO tank and an armored personnel carrier.
</P>
<P>
   The Albanians insisted they wanted their tractors, and the
Serbs, many of whom were Gypsies, insisted that the vehicles were
theirs.
</P>
<P>
   French peacekeepers did their best to sort things out, and
finally several of the tractors were returned to the Albanian side
of the road.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Serbs took the remaining tractors and loaded them with
their families and a few belongings and moved out of Kosovo. Many
said they knew they could no longer live with their Albanian
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   NATO forces escorted the Serbian tractor convoy out of town.
</P>
<P>
   ``They stole from us. They stole our tractors. And they are
getting away with it!'' complained Albanian farmer Imir Mendici,
34, who said he now has no vehicle to plow fields that have gone
untended for months during the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Danic Milovan, a Serb farmer, driving a red tractor with his
family loaded into a trailer in back, responded, ``We are leaving
and we will never come back.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't ever want you back!'' shouted an Albanian along the
road.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
