<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA WINS ROUND ON KOSOVO AID PACKAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLOGNE, Germany _ Russia, seeking to protect Slobodan
Milosevic's regime, blocked world leaders Saturday from completing
a multibillion-dollar Kosovo rebuilding plan that would have
excluded aid to a Serbia under Milosevic's control.
</P>
<P>
   A final declaration is expected Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and several of its allies had sought to
include in the document a statement that none of the reconstruction
money for states strained and damaged during NATO's 78-day bombing
campaign would go to Belgrade as long as Milosevic remains
president of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   With Russian President Boris N. Yeltsin due to arrive here
Sunday for talks with President Clinton, American officials
acknowledged that the Kosovo issue had ``frozen'' US-Moscow
relations but said the focus now was on thawing them. They said the
statement was a consensus document and without the approval of
Russia, an explicit denial of aid to Serbia could not be included.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of Yeltsin's visit, his spokesman Dmitry Yakushkin
quoted him as saying that he was coming to secure Russia's place in
the world, and was in ``a fighting mood.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's national security adviser, Samuel R. Berger, said,
``There may be some desire to discuss . . . the events of the past
90 days. But I think the larger thrust here is to move forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, White House officials confirmed that the president
and Hillary Rodham Clinton will travel to Macedonia and to a NATO
air base in Aviano, Italy, on Tuesday. The president will meet with
political leaders of Macedonia and Albania, visit a refugee camp
and speak to US military personnel supporting the peacekeeping
effort in Kosovo. At Aviano, Clinton will visit troops that were
involved in the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the timing of this year's summit of seven leading
industrial nations and Russia, known as the G-8, the Kosovo issue
has dominated the talks. Russian Prime Minister Sergei Stepashin,
who took Yeltsin's place for the first two days of the meeting, has
shuttled from one meeting to another with Western leaders.
</P>
<P>
   In a Friday night session with French President Jacques Chirac,
Stepashin said that ``the conduct of one man must not penalize 10
million Serbs.''
</P>
<P>
   However, he did not raise the aid issue for Serbia Saturday
during his meeting with Clinton, White House officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and Britian are resolutely opposed to economic
aid to Belgrade; the French also appear to be opposed, but US
officials Saturday said they were uncertain whether Germany and
Italy favored withholding aid to Belgrade as part of the aid
package to Kosovo and nations of southeast Europe which suffered
from the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   However, the United States and the other nations do favor
providing humanitarian assistance to the region through the Red
Cross or the United Nations or some other international agency,
officials said. But they are unclear, at the moment, whether
humanitarian aid would include, for example, restoring electrical
facilities in Serbia knocked out by NATO bombs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do believe that there should be a reconstruction program
for the Balkans, we would very much like it to include Serbia, but
not so long as Serbia is led by an indicted war criminal,'' Berger
said. ``And it's very difficult to imagine a major reconstruction
program in which the countries themselves didn't share the values
of democracy and tolerance and human rights, which were inherent in
the enterprise.''
</P>
<P>
   The conflict between the United States and Russia over Kosovo
has ``kind of frozen things,'' Berger said. He said it's been
``kind of an elephant in the room, which makes it difficult _ which
is hard to ignore.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As strongly as we felt about Kosovo, I think probably they
felt as strongly that what NATO was doing was wrong, for a whole
series of reasons,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While Russia may not have gotten its way on Kosovo, the leaders
here seem poised to reschedule $69 billion of debt run up under
communist governments. Moscow has balked at paying the Soviet-era
debt, which includes money once owed by now-independent republics,
in addition to the huge amounts of financial help it has received
since communism crumbled in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Russia also has been the center of talks here among leaders who
have grappled with issues ranging from arms control and
non-proliferation issues to the Moscow's economy, even as US
officials asserted that the positioning to replace Yeltsin in
upcoming elections has affected business with Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Steinberg, Clinton's deputy national security adviser, said:
``Looking back over Kosovo, the fact that Russia has stayed engaged
with its partners in the West both contributed to the achievement
of peace and now in the implementing of the peace as a result of
the agreement . . . they can go forward. They have a lot of
interests in common.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-99 1944EDT &QL; 
