<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of Sunday,
June 20, 1999. If you have any questions, please call Patricia
Hardin on The Star's News Desk at (816) 234-4753.
DISASTER-PLAN (KANSAS CITY) _ When Congress amended the Clean Air
Act in 1990, it created the new risk-management program, an attempt
to reduce chemical accidents in the wake of the 1984 Bhopal, India,
disaster, which killed almost 4,000 people. As a result, chemical
plants must envision the most devastating chemical accidents that
could occur and develop plans to deal with them. By MICHAEL MANSUR.
Story will move in the ``a'' category.
DADDY-LOVE (KANSAS CITY) _ The night didn't go well, Jesus
``Chucho'' Marquez says, as he prepares to leave the hospital. His
2-year-old son, Gabriel, born severely brain damaged and
quadriplegic, lies motionless. The day before, Gabriel's breathing,
always raspy, had been worrisomely strained, and he was running a
fever. Because of Gabriel's brain damage, the muscles in his throat
work poorly. In February and March, he was in the hospital for 24
days. In April, nine. In May, 10. Now it was June. Concerned,
Chucho and his wife, Elizabeth Uppman, admitted Gabriel to the
hospital for observation. As he always does and, Chucho says, as he
always will, he remained by his son's side. By ERIC ADLER. Two
takes. Story will move in the ``a'' category.
FREE-MAN (KANSAS CITY) _ Dennis Fritz was sentenced in 1988 to life
imprisonment in Oklahoma for a murder he did not commit. In April a
judge dismissed the charges. Now that Fritz is a out of prison, he
is striving to recapture the life he had as a free man. By MALCOLM
GARCIA. Story will move in the ``a'' category.
HEMINGWAY-CELEBRATION (KANSAS CITY) _ For Ernest Hemingway fans,
July will be a month of celebration. July 21 marks the 100th
anniversary of Hemingway's birth, and four events around Kansas
City will commemorate the writer throughout the month. By ERICA
THESING. Story will move in the ``a'' category.
PLANE-SHOW (ST. FRANCIS, Kan.) _ The old Stearman biplanes, almost
as if by magic, appeared out the clouds and washed over the crowd
at the Cheyenne County Airport. What arrived was history,
specifically a footnote to World War II. What people found here was
an old-fashioned county airshow, akin to those gatherings years ago
that brought in farmers from their fields, townsmen from behind
their counters and kids with their dreams. By JIM FISHER. Story
will move in the ``a'' category.
</P>
