<DOCNO> NYT19990619.0232 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-19 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2189 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DADDY-LOVE-2TAKES-KAN     06-19 1358
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DADDY-LOVE-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DADDY'S HERE: A BRAIN-DAMAGED CHILD DOES NOT LACK FOR LOVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ERIC ADLER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The night didn't go well,'' a bleary-eyed Jesus ``Chucho''
Marquez says at 9:20 a.m., as he prepares to leave the hospital and
loops the red backpack he uses as a diaper bag over his shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   He approaches the hospital bed.
</P>
<P>
   His 2-year-old son, Gabriel, born severely brain damaged and
quadriplegic, lies motionless on his back and in his diaper on a
crisp, white sheet. Except for his long lashes and soft,
llama-brown eyes, he is a miniature of his dad, hearty and strong,
25 pounds, with a tiny barrel chest, a square likable face and the
dense dark hair of his Mexican ancestry.
</P>
<P>
   The day before, Gabriel's breathing, always raspy, had been
worrisomely strained, and he was running a fever.
</P>
<P>
   Because of Gabriel's brain damage, the muscles in his throat,
like those of his arms, legs, neck, back and the rest of his body,
work poorly. His esophagus can't always stop mucus or other liquids
from his stomach from filling his lungs. So when a fever rises, the
fear is that he'll develop a dangerous pneumonia. In February and
March, he was in the hospital for 24 days. In April, nine. In May,
10. Now it was June.
</P>
<P>
   Concerned, Chucho and his wife, Elizabeth Uppman, admitted
Gabriel to the hospital for observation. As he always does and,
Chucho says, as he always will, he remained by his son's side.
</P>
<P>
   All night long, getting only three hours of sleep, the
38-year-old Overland Park dad remained near Gabriel's bed in the
pediatric unit at the University of Kansas Medical Center. All
night long, as Gabriel became restless, moaning, his arms, legs and
back stiffening into spastic arches, Chucho lifted him, cradled
him, kissed his temples and spoke to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's OK, Gabriel,'' he would say quieting him to sleep.
``Daddy's here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way it is,'' Chucho says.
</P>
<P>
   Chucho can't say that he doesn't wish it were different, that
Gabriel weren't so sick. You have children. A son. A daughter. You
want so much for them. Health. Happiness. And you have plans for
yourself and, until parenthood arrives, a notion of how it's going
to be.
</P>
<P>
   When Chucho first saw Elizabeth, he was living in St. Paul,
Minn., having come from Mexico to get his doctorate in plant
breeding at the University of Minnesota. Elizabeth, from Prairie
Village, settled in St. Paul after studying at Carleton College.
They sat near each other in a community choir. They began to chat,
date and, within two months, vowed to marry. In 1991, they did.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth learned Spanish. Chucho finished his degree and, in
1993, they moved to Torreon, Mexico, where Chucho's scientific
career began flourishing. When, in 1994, they had Julia Maria, a
blond-haired, brown-eyed baby so perfect and healthy, she just
confirmed their plan to have more. Three. That was the number.
</P>
<P>
   Then, on May 15, 1997, Gabriel was born.
9:25 a.m.: Chucho, cradling his son like an infant, makes his way
out of the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, Gabriel, time to go,'' Chucho says, relieved that whatever
was causing his boy's fever had passed. This time, no pneumonia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you,'' he calls to the KU nurses, stepping through
electronic doors that swish open and shut as he passes. If Chucho
hurries, he can get home, take a quick shower, change Gabriel and
get his son to a session of occupational therapy just after 10. He
kisses Gabriel again.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're outta here,'' he whispers.
</P>
<P>
   Chucho and Elizabeth are past casting blame or trying to discern
what caused their son's brain damage. Did it happen before birth?
During birth? Would it have been different had they been in an
American rather than a Mexican hospital?
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't matter now. Nothing can change the facts: During
Elizabeth's labor, Gabriel's heart rate unexpectedly plummeted. By
the time he was born, his entire body was blue and slack. By the
time doctors revived him, his brain had been deprived of oxygen for
20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You deal with it,'' Elizabeth said. ``You deal with it OK. You
deal with it badly; then you deal with it OK again.'' But you deal
with it.
</P>
<P>
   All they know, they say, is the only thing they need to know:
Gabriel is their son.
</P>
<P>
   The damage to his brain, they know, is profound. He has the
basic brain functions to survive, but it's unclear how much higher
functioning he possesses.
</P>
<P>
   Because he is unable to walk, his parents carry him. Unable to
eat, he is fed through a tiny tube in his stomach. Though he hears,
it's unclear whether he understands. Though he sees, he is thought
to be cortically blind, meaning the images that record in his mind
may make no sense.
</P>
<P>
   Yet when Chucho and Elizabeth stare into their son's brown eyes,
which glint hazel in the sunlight, ``He is in there,'' they insist.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows our voices,'' says Chucho who, with Elizabeth,
refuses to limit his son's possibilities with dire predictions of
the future. When Chucho talks, Gabriel stares. And even if Gabriel
doesn't completely understand who's speaking, what of it?
</P>
<P>
   Chucho knows. He's his father.
9:44 a.m.: Chucho and Gabriel arrive home.
</P>
<P>
   The house is a ranch-style rental that Elizabeth found and chose
because it's close to her parents' place in Prairie Village and
just blocks from the Lee Ann Britain Infant Development Center, the
place Gabriel receives some of his many therapies: occupational;
physical; music; sight; aquatic; early stimulation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing stuff all the time,'' Chucho says.
</P>
<P>
   At home, he strips down straight away and, with Gabriel held
naked in one arm, takes a shower. Out, dressed, - ``We're ready to
roll,'' Chucho says - and at the center by 10:14, occupational
therapist Linda O'Grady works with Gabriel, propped on his father's
lap.
</P>
<P>
   For an hour she massages and moves his joints and limbs to the
left, right, back, forth, side to side. She shows him lighted
objects to see whether he can follow. And, always, she talks to him
or _ as she did to the tune of ``Skip to My Lou' '' _ sings to him,
looking into his eyes for signs of a connection.
</P>
<P>
   Hello, Gabriel, how are you?
</P>
<P>
   Hello, Gabriel, how are you?
</P>
<P>
   Hello, Gabriel, how are you?
</P>
<P>
   I'm so glad you're here today.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he comes in here,'' Chucho says, ``he brightens up.''
</P>
<P>
   And, truth is, so does Chucho.
</P>
<P>
   Never did he think this is how his life would turn out. Never
did he think this would be his role. And never, for all the pain,
anxiety and tears that he and Elizabeth have shared, did he think
he would find it so rewarding.
</P>
<P>
   After Gabriel was born, the plan was never for Chucho to give up
his career, cook or clean, do the laundry and care for his son so
completely. In Mexico, where Chucho was raised the eldest of five
brothers, his mother did everything. He and Elizabeth planned that,
for the most part, that would be her role.
</P>
<P>
   The plan was to return to Kansas City, where there would be both
family and the kind of progressive therapy Mexico lacked. Chucho
would get a full-time job; Elizabeth might get a part-time job.
They would work it out.
</P>
<P>
   But, instead, Elizabeth got a terrific full-time job as a
technical writer for Tidestone Technologies, a software company in
Overland Park. Since any job Chucho might get in his speciality,
alfalfa breeding, would probably take him out of town and pay no
more than Elizabeth was now making, it made more sense for him to
stay home.
</P>
<P>
   So he did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw it as an opportunity not many fathers have. I was
willing to go for it,'' he says. Although he quickly points out
that what he's doing isn't any better or any different than what
Elizabeth would be doing were she at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it weren't me, it would be her,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   And he points out, too, that as much as he loves and cares for
his son, what he does is no more special than what thousands of
other parents do for their own special-need children. Although even
the therapists at the Infant Development Center, who see devoted
parents every day, say that in Chucho they see something more.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
