<HEADER>
A2190 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DADDY-LOVE-2NDTAKE-KA     06-19 0688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DADDY-LOVE-2ND </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DADDY'S HERE: A BRAIN-DAMAGED CHILD DOES NOT LACK FOR LOVE 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKE-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ERIC ADLER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Noon to 12:45 p.m.: Chucho's home, feeding Gabriel a liquid meal
through the tube in his stomach.
</P>
<P>
   1- 2:30 p.m.: Back to the Infant Development Center for infant
stimulation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's someone,'' therapist Jean Kubiak said of Chucho, ``who's
given up his family, his country and his job to come here and take
care of this little guy.''
</P>
<P>
   To which Chucho responds: What else is he supposed to do? Leave?
</P>
<P>
   ``The thought,'' he says, ``has never crossed my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   3 p.m.: Chucho and Gabriel drive to preschool to pick up
4-year-old Julia. Deadbeat dads. Fathers who bolt on their kids and
responsibilities. Sure, Chucho has known guys like that. His own
father was married three times. Yet, even then, he says, he always
knew where his father was and felt his commitment.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, when Chucho and Elizabeth struggled with the decision
to leave Mexico, it was Chucho's father who gave him advice:
</P>
<P>
   ``Put your kids in the front,'' he told him. ``You follow.''
</P>
<P>
   So he has, amazed at where Gabriel has led him, including, for a
man who once considered himself an atheist, back to God.
</P>
<P>
   3:30 p.m.: Chucho gives Gabriel his medicines. One to help keep
his muscles from tightening, another to regulate his heart rate, a
third to ward off infections.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say children bring you back to church,'' Chucho says.
``He dragged me back.''
</P>
<P>
   Chucho admits that when Gabriel was first born, he hoped and
prayed to God for a miracle. Mexico is a country with a long
history of magic and mysticism. At times, though he is a scientist,
Chucho even fantasized about taking Gabriel to a medicine man and
pleading with him with to cure his son. But in the last two years,
he says, he has developed a deeper faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the beginning it was like, can God do a miracle?'' he says.
``But now it's like I've got this big guy, God, behind me who loves
my son. That makes me stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   4 p.m.: Chucho begins dinner, hamburgers. He gives Gabriel
another feeding. They watch ``Arthur'' on PBS. Julia waters three
potted pea plants on the patio.
</P>
<P>
   Julia.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it's hard, when one child needs so much care, not to
forget, Chucho says, that ``at her age, she has a lot of needs,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We think she's a little bit jealous,'' he says. ``She used to
get more attention. But we try.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is why the weekend before, he and Julia went to the park
together, all by themselves, where they played, and looked at rocks
and slugs. Julia rode her bike. They gathered the rocks in a basket
to take home. ``Treasures,'' her mother said, ``that she
gathered.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We hadn't done that for a long time,'' Chucho says.
</P>
<P>
   5:30: Elizabeth arrives home. They eat dinner. For an hour it is
a bit easier, until once again, Chucho and Gabriel will head back
to the hospital for tests.
</P>
<P>
   Chucho and Elizabeth can't say what the future holds. It's
possible, they know, that they may forever be caring for Gabriel as
they do now, that he may never significantly improve. Every day,
every month, every year he is in therapy, however, they do believe
he makes tiny improvements: a stretch of the fingers; a smile of
recognition; a steady look of concentration that wordlessly says,
`I see.'
</P>
<P>
   In his dreamiest moments, Chucho looks at his boy with the hope
that one day he'll be healthy enough as an adult to decide, if he
chooses, to live assisted or in a group home.
</P>
<P>
   And should that day never come, Chucho says, that's OK, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to be learning his whole life,'' Chucho says. ``I'm
behind him.''
</P>
<P>
   7:15 p.m.: Gabriel and Chucho arrive at the KU Medical Center
sleep lab.
</P>
<P>
   When he was sleeping, Gabriel's breathing rate used to slow so
much doctors feared it could further rob him of oxygen, hastening
damage to his brain. They put him on medications that seem to help.
The sleep lab test is to determine how much.
</P>
<P>
   The test continues through the night.
</P>
<P>
   All night long, Daddy's there.
</P>
<P>
   (30)
</P>
</TEXT>
