<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY TO CELEBRATE HEMINGWAY'S 100TH BIRTHDAY ANNIVERSARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ERICA THESING  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ For Ernest Hemingway fans, July will be a
month of celebration.
</P>
<P>
   July 21 marks the 100th anniversary of Hemingway's birth, and
four events around Kansas City will commemorate the writer
throughout the month.
</P>
<P>
   Hemingway moved to Kansas City in the fall of 1917 and spent
seven months as a police reporter for The Kansas City Star. He
returned to the area several times in later years to visit
relatives. Two of his sons were born in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   A July 8 presentation by Michael Reynolds, Hemingway biographer
and National Book Award finalist, will begin the celebration.
Reynolds has written about Hemingway for 25 years and will have
copies of his latest book, Hemingway: The Final Years, at his
presentation.
</P>
<P>
   The lecture is part of the Kansas City Public Library's Sosland
Series. The Fine Arts Theatre will present a special showing of
movies made from Hemingway's work July 10 and 11. Each screening
will be followed by a discussion.
</P>
<P>
   On July 18, The Kansas City Star will offer a talk on Hemingway
by Mark Zieman, editor and vice president of The Star. The talk
will be followed by a guided tour of landmarks related to
Hemingway's life and work in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   The celebration will culminate in a panel discussion and
birthday party July 21. Area writers and educators will debate
Hemingway's influence and achievements.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-99 1949EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990619.0235 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-19 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2196 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PLANE-SHOW-KAN &LR;      06-19 1208
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLANE-SHOW-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD WAR II BIPLANES LEND THEMSELVES TO OLD-FASHIONED AIRSHOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM FISHER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. FRANCIS, Kan. _ The old Stearman biplanes, almost as if by
magic, appeared out of last weekend's threatening clouds, ethereal
forms until the grumble of their radial engines washed over the
crowd here at the Cheyenne County Airport.
</P>
<P>
   What descended from the low sky was more than metal tubing,
blackened cylinders and goggled aviators in open cockpits. What
arrived was history, specifically a footnote to World War II.
</P>
<P>
   For that, St. Francis and its airport just south of town were
ideal _ no concourses reaching to the horizon, no metal detectors
or any of the other annoyances of 1999 flight.
</P>
<P>
   Parking was wherever; 1,000 spectators sat on benches or
sprawled on the damp grass watching not only the Stearmans but also
dozens of other aircraft, hot-air balloons, sky divers and the tiny
ultralights with their shrieking engines.
</P>
<P>
   Even more unreal was that nobody had a hand out for money.
</P>
<P>
   In short, what people found here was an old-fashioned county
airshow, akin to those gatherings years ago that brought in farmers
from their fields, townsmen from behind their counters and kids
with their dreams.
</P>
<P>
   If even on a soggy day St. Francis was perfect, then the seven
Stearmans that came for the 17th annual Cheyenne County Stearman
Fly-In were sublime _ two wings, exposed spars and wires, fixed
landing gear, ugly engines, and garish paint schemes, most
chrome-yellow. The planes appeared closer to a Wright brothers
flying machine than to their sleeker cousins that went in harm's
way 55-plus years ago _ the Mustangs and Marauders, Hellcats and
Avengers.
</P>
<P>
   Outdated even during their production run as aerodynamic design
made a quantum leap forward just before and during the war,
Stearmans were an ugly duckling compared with that conflict's
snazzy fighters and bombers, planes that still draw crowds to big
airshows and attract millions to the endless aviation documentaries
on cable television.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Stearmans had a special claim to fame.
</P>
<P>
   Almost every World War II Army, Navy and Marine Corps pilot
learned to fly in one _ those who flew the P-51s that swept the sky
over Europe clean, the C-46 airmen who conquered the Hump, the
teen-agers who strapped themselves into B-17s for near-suicide
missions over Germany, and the young men who burned down Japan with
incendiary bombs dropped from their B-29s.
</P>
<P>
   All that flowed from a simple, Rube Goldberg-type aircraft with
a top speed of 124 miles an hour but with just enough bad habits to
initiate young pilots to the rigors of combat flying.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd have had more here, but just look at this weather
today,'' said Richard Grace of the Grace Flying Service, the fixed
base operator at the airport just south of this town in this far
northwestern corner of Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year 17 flew in, which was pretty good for us. Today
there're storms all around, so people have canceled.''
</P>
<P>
   The national Stearman fly-in is on Labor Day in Galesburg, Ill.,
attracting more than 100 of the estimated 2,000 survivors. Between
its introduction in 1934 and the end of production in 1945, 8,584
of the planes were built by the Stearman division of the Boeing Co.
in Wichita.
</P>
<P>
   Also manufactured then were enough spare parts to build 2,000
more. The average cost of each aircraft _ formally named Kaydet,
for the cadet pilots that would fly them _ was about $8,000.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, Kaydet never caught on. A Stearman is a Stearman.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, where Stearmans show up, stories abound.
</P>
<P>
   Take John Grace, Richard's dad, and founder of the flying
service. In World War II he learned to fly in a Stearman, graduated
into the rakish P-38 Lightning and spent the war flying in the
Aleutian Islands.
</P>
<P>
   When John came home, he needed a job. Farmers were beginning to
spray their fields with the host of chemicals developed during the
war. John decided on crop dusting.
</P>
<P>
   ``So he went to a banker and borrowed $1,500, an awful lot of
money then,'' said his son. ``He bought some equipment, some
chemicals and a war-surplus Stearman for $800. He was in the
spraying business. I think he got $1.95 an acre.''
</P>
<P>
   From that modest investment and an old plane still kept in
impeccable condition by another son, Robert, has emerged a thriving
business, a state-of-the-art flight operations center, several
other planes, hangars, and an annual airshow that draws pilots from
as far away as Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's free,'' said Richard Grace. ``We don't make a dime off
it. Fact is, we lose money. But that's OK. It's for the town.''
</P>
<P>
   John Grace died in 1997. At the 1998 airshow four Stearmans flew
over the field in formation. Then one peeled off to create the
``Missing Man Formation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a nice tribute to John,'' said Gloria Bracelin, who
runs the Chamber of Commerce in St. Francis. ``It was touching.''
</P>
<P>
   Bracelin said the annual show brings hundreds of visitors to St.
Francis, fills the local trailer park and motels, and means
business for the service stations and restaurants. That, she said,
is no small thing out in a remote part of Kansas that's closer to
Denver or Cheyenne, Wyo., than Topeka, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   The out-of-the-way location and its openness, said Mike Baldwin,
a Stearman owner and pilot here from Evergreen, Colo., make it
perfect for a fly-in.
</P>
<P>
   ``First, it's just visual flight rules to get over here,'' he
said. ``And it's a nice grass strip. How often do you get to do
that anymore? And it's fun. I think people flying now are the last
who are going to have fun with airplanes, you know _ enjoying
flying just for flying's sake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids these days don't seem really interested. They'll come out
for things like this _ they don't seem to have that fire in their
eyes. There's too much else to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Even at the bigger airshows with lots of fancy military hardware
around, such as F-15s and F-117s, Baldwin thinks the little
Stearmans somehow retain a magnetic appeal. Why? Because, he said,
the airplane looks as if anybody _ with a little instruction _
could fly it. Not so the newer aircraft, all computerized and with
a befuddling array of instruments.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Stearman's a pussycat once you get up,'' he said. ``But
it's an odd airplane. It's simple, but it handles like a much
bigger airplane. It can be unstable. It has its blind spots.
</P>
<P>
   ``But those things were designed into the plane. That's what few
people know. It was a primary trainer not that much different in
handling from a much bigger or higher performance airplane. So when
you got in a B-17 or a Corsair, there were no real surprises.''
</P>
<P>
   John Oshant, 70, formerly of Hays, Kan., but now a resident of
Tucson, Ariz., learned to crop-dust in a Stearman when he was 16
and had no problem becoming an Air Force pilot flying F-84s in
combat during the Korean War. He later flew F-86s and F-100s.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a great airplane,'' he said. ``But, you know, all of
us missed the boat. Right after the war, they were selling them for
$600 apiece in crates down in Oklahoma.''
</P>
<P>
   And the price of a Stearman now?
</P>
<P>
   ``Upper five figures easy, maybe more,'' said Oshant.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
