<SLUG> BC-GLF-USOPEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALONE UNDER PAR, STEWART IS ALONE ON LEADER BOARD
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINEHURST, N.C. _ After another torture test at the U.S. Open,
Payne Stewart was alone at the top Saturday and alone under par.
</P>
<P>
   Setting up a final round that will be a test of patience,
pressure and perseverance, Stewart shot a 72 to end the third round
at one-under-par 209 for the tournament, one stroke ahead of Phil
Mickelson and two ahead of Tiger Woods and Tim Herron. David Duval,
Vijay Singh and Steve Stricker were tied for fifth place at two
over par, still very much in contention, while Billy Mayfair (three
over) and Jeff Maggert (four over) still had legitimate hope as
well.
</P>
<P>
   Though it was an overcast day, with occasional rain, Pinehurst
Resort and Country Club's demanding No. 2 course continued to play
tougher than an overcooked steak, and shooting under par was almost
out of the question. Stricker was the only player who did, shooting
a one-under 69 that moved him from a 20th-place tie into striking
range of the lead. But many players sank faster than the Titanic,
unable to keep their approach shots on the sloping greens, unable
to save par and, in some cases, unable to save face.
</P>
<P>
   The last time the U.S. Open was won by someone above par was in
1978, when Andy North won with a one-over 285 at Cherry Hills
Country Club in Englewood, Colo. It would surprise no one if this
year's winner finished over par. After Saturday's round, many
players were just happy to have another round behind them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wind was blowing, and the pin placements were borderline
sadistic,'' said Scott Verplank (seven over), who shot a 72
Saturday. ``You knew it was going to be incredibly hard when you
got to the tee.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the contenders had their precarious moments. Woods began
his day with a double-bogey, while Duval shot a 75, including a 40
on the front nine. But good golfers have a way of rising to the
top. Both Duval and Woods, who shot a 72, recovered from early
struggles to shoot even par on the back nine, keeping alive their
chances and refusing to come unglued on a course that can unnerve
anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got off to a rough start, but I knew there were a lot of
holes left,'' said Woods, who is trying to win his third
consecutive start, his second major and his first U.S. Open. ``I'm
really proud of the way I hung in there today. It was windy, it was
rainy, it was gusty, it was calm _ we had everything today, very
similar to a British Open. I'm focused and I feel good. My game is
a little bit better than it ever has been. Above all, I just have
to stay patient.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart found himself in a familiar place. Sunday will be the
third time this decade that he will begin the final round of the
U.S. Open in the lead. In 1991, Stewart won, defeating Scott
Simpson in a playoff. But last year, Stewart took a four-stroke
lead into the final round and lost by one stroke to Lee Janzen.
</P>
<P>
   For Stewart, last year's Open was a potentially devastating
defeat, but he has shown his resiliency, winning this year's Pebble
Beach National Pro-Am and playing some of his best golf at age 42.
</P>
<P>
   Will Stewart win the Open again, as he did in 1991? Or will
another opportunity slip away at the national championship? He
looked ahead with no fear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have crawled away and hid after what happened last
year,'' said Stewart, who will play in Sunday's final group. ``Or I
could build on what happened and use it to strengthen myself.
That's the avenue I chose to take.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   How fitting would it be for Mickelson to win on Father's Day,
with his wife, Amy, expecting their first child on June 30?
Mickelson's caddie is carrying a beeper in his bag in case
Mickelson's wife goes into labor, and if she does, Mickelson has
vowed he will leave, no matter what. But Mickelson sounded
confident that he would be around Sunday, and confident about his
chances. At one point at No. 10, Mickelson held a three-stroke lead
over Stewart, but Mickelson bogeyed No. 11, No. 15, No. 16 and No.
17 before recovering to end the day with an 8-foot birdie putt at
No. 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I can make this my bad day and improve tomorrow, I should
be in good shape,'' said Mickelson, who shot a 73. ``I was sloppy
today and didn't play that well. But I don't think it's that far
away. I'm just a little off.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he was worried about his wife going into labor before
Sunday's final round, Mickelson said: ``I just spoke to her and
things are going well. I'm not all that concerned. All the experts
say it should be another week or two.''
</P>
<P>
   If Duval does not win, he will lament shooting 5-over on the
front nine Saturday. It was very unlike Duval, as he hit poor iron
shots and wedge shots, leaving him in places where only a magician
could have saved par.
</P>
<P>
   But Duval righted himself after his bogey at No. 8, ending the
day with 10 consecutive pars. On this course, 10 consecutive pars
was solid golf. And all the contenders knew they had an even more
challenging day ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't recall a whole lot of golf courses more difficult than
this,'' said Duval, the world's No. 1 ranked player, looking for
his first major championship. ``Whoever backs up the least amount
will win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
