<SLUG> BC-BBN-NLNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW DAY FOR NOMO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Hideo Nomo's victory this past week over Cleveland,
one of the teams to pass on him after a spring tryout, might be
proof he is back from all those 200-pitch games that ravaged his
arm in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Nomo, cut loose by the Mets and Cubs after his trade from the
Dodgers 13 months ago, has been successful with the Milwaukee
Brewers because he finally decided to stop trying to throw a
fastball that no longer exists.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's made an adjustment,'' Brewers manager Phil Garner said.
``He's lost a little on his fastball, so he's throwing more
breaking balls early in the count. That's been a successful formula
for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Nomo left the Cubs after they insisted he make two more
minor-league starts. Nomo was guaranteed $1 million with Chicago.
He received $250,000 from Milwaukee. As it turned out, the Cubs
would have brought Nomo to the big leagues quickly because Jon
Lieber went on the DL. Instead, rookie Kyle Farnsworth got the
call. &QL; 
MAKING A PITCH
</P>
<P>
   Giants right-hander Mark Gardner entered Wednesday's game
against Colorado 0-5 with an 8.31 ERA. All he did was allow six
hits and two runs in pitching just the 27th complete game at Coors
Field during a 15-2 win. It was his first victory in 11 starts this
season and his first win since Sept. 23 against Pittsburgh. It also
came at a time when the Giants need production from Gardner and
left-hander Shawn Estes to stay close to Arizona. &QL; 
STUNG AGAIN
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks' Randy Johnson, who pitched every fifth day
through his first 15 starts, left Monday's 2-0 victory after seven
innings with the stomach flu. The previous Friday he had an MRI
(negative) after reporting soreness in his lower back. He starts
tonight against the Braves on ESPN. With an off day Thursday,
manager Buck Showalter opted to keep his starters in rotation.
Despite their lead in the West, the Diamondbacks already have lost
No.2 starter Todd Stottlemyre to injury and have an unsettled
closer situation. ``I've been pitching a lot of innings. It will
give my back a chance to recoup a little,'' said Johnson, who had
back surgery that cost him most of the 1996 season. &QL; 
NOT SEEING STARS
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of right fielder Brian Jordan, there is not a
Braves position player deserving of All-Star selection. And
perennial All-Stars Tom Glavine and Greg Maddux, who have been
named to the past three teams, won't be making the trip to Boston
this year either. Third baseman Chipper Jones, a three-time
All-Star, may be voted a starter by fans, but if Matt Williams is
the top vote-getter at third, Jones may not be selected by Padres
manager Bruce Bochy. Jones hit .309 with 21 homers and 69 RBI in
the first half last season. With 25 games remaining until the
break, his numbers were .287, 14 homers and 40 RBI. &QL; 
CRUNCH TIME
</P>
<P>
   Lost in the Dodgers' messy week was the head injury Pirates
catcher Jason Kendall suffered in the fifth inning Wednesday on a
home plate collision with Gary Sheffield. Two innings and one
strikeout later, he left the game with what a CAT scan revealed as
a severe concussion. The Pirates knew something was wrong with
Kendall when he asked relief pitcher Greg Hansell the same question
three times. Kendall, who reluctantly went to the hospital, told
the Pirates trainer that he didn't remember the collision, who hit
him or whether the call was safe or out. &QL; 
FINALLY
</P>
<P>
   Mets starters are 8-0 with a 2.51 ERA since pitching coach Bob
Apodaca was fired and replaced by Dave Wallace.... The defending
NL-champion Padres are awful, but they have their memories. When
highlights of Kevin Brown's Tuesday-night drubbing by the Pirates
were shown on the right-field scoreboard Wednesday night, the crowd
roared louder than at any point during the Padres' game against the
Phillies.
</P>
</TEXT>
