<SLUG> BC-DISASTER-PLAN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHEMICAL PLANTS MUST GIVE GOVERNMENT THEIR DISASTER-CONTROL PLANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MANSUR  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Mike Wey doesn't like to imagine the worst.
But now he must.
</P>
<P>
   Wey is director of health, environment and safety at Bayer
Corp.'s large chemical plant in Kansas City's East Bottoms. The
plant is a complex web of pipes and vessels that produce herbicides
and other pesticides used on many food crops.
</P>
<P>
   The government now requires him to envision the most devastating
chemical accident that could occur at the plant.
</P>
<P>
   Wey places a transparency on an overhead projector, showing
Bayer's model of such a disaster. On a map of the metropolitan
area, a plume of chlorine vapor more than 14 miles long bubbles
along the Missouri River from the plant toward Missouri City like
an aneurysm ready to pop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Again, we don't think this is likely to occur,'' Wey says.
</P>
<P>
   But it's just this type of computer modeling that is attracting
attention around the nation. An estimated 40,000 chemical and other
private and government-owned plants must submit to the federal
government, beginning Monday, new plans on how to deal with
chemical accidents that could occur at their plants.
</P>
<P>
   In the metropolitan area, about 100 plants are expected to file
such plans, area emergency planners say. Bayer, which operates one
of the largest chemical plants in the region, is among them.
</P>
<P>
   When Congress amended the Clean Air Act in 1990, it created the
new risk- management program, an attempt to reduce chemical
accidents in the wake of the 1984 Bhopal, India, disaster, which
killed almost 4,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   The program was among a number of right-to-know laws that
required companies to disclose to the public the emissions of toxic
chemicals, storage of hazardous materials and plans for their safe
handling.
</P>
<P>
   The chemical industry generally has opposed such requirements,
saying they are an unnecessary intrusion. Industry leaders have
advocated voluntary guidelines for safer plant operations.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental activists want the information made public. They
believe such disclosure will pressure companies to reduce the use
of dangerous chemicals in communities.
</P>
<P>
   The latest of the requirements _ modeling of the worst possible
chemical accidents _ has stirred a debate that focuses on the
balance between the public's right to know and a threat of
terrorism. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last fall the Environmental Protection Agency, fearing that
terrorists with overly easy access to the worst-case scenarios
would be better able to plan destructive acts, decided not to make
those plans available on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the new risk-management plans will be available on
the Internet, probably this summer. In addition to the modeling of
chemical accidents, the plans include a company's five-year
accident history, any hazard prevention plans, its
emergency-response program and its management systems for
overseeing those programs.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Internet will not be used, the EPA still intends
to make public the worst-case accident plans. How they would be
released has not been decided, and environmental activists in
Washington warned last week that a new lobbying effort may
essentially deny public access to the information. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Environmental Protection Agency, under pressure from
chemical manufacturers, decided last fall not to make available to
the public on the Internet the worst-case accidents such as the one
Wey displayed for the Bayer plant. The agency cited concerns that a
terrorist surfing the Internet could use the worst-case scenarios
to better plan destructive acts.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the new risk-management plans will be available on
the Internet, probably this summer. In addition to the modeling of
chemical accidents, the plans include a company's five-year
accident history, any hazard prevention plans, its
emergency-response program and its management systems for
overseeing those programs.
</P>
<P>
   The part of the plans that disclose the worst-case incidents is
supposed to be available from the EPA, but that mechanism still is
unclear. And environmental activists in Washington warned this week
that a new lobbying effort may essentially deny access to the
worst-case information. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Paul Orum of the Working Group on Community Right to Know says
legislation has been circulating in Congress that would restrict
the public's access to the worst-case plans, even after federal
officials distribute them to local police and other emergency
officials. Although the Chemical Manufacturers Association stressed
in a public statement Wednesday that it did not want to deny public
access to the worst-case plans, one portion of the proposed
legislation would impose penalties on any officials who released
the information.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a last-ditch effort to restrict the ability of anyone
else from getting this information and disseminating it in any
convenient form,'' Orum said.
</P>
<P>
   This is an important point to activists such as Orum who long to
see reductions in the release and use of hazardous chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   They say that making companies disclose the amount and type of
chemicals they emit into the environment or store on site often
persuades them to reduce their emissions and uses of these
chemicals. Orum and others hope the risk- management program will
result in similar reductions.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Public Interest Research Group, the Sierra Club and the
Working Group on Community Right to Know released a report recently
that criticized chemical plants for not committing to reduce the
hazardous chemicals they're keeping on site.
</P>
<P>
   Only two of 175 chemical plants contacted by the environmental
groups had developed new goals and timetables for reducing their
use of hazardous chemicals, the groups said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We asked chemical companies what they plan to do to reduce
chemical disaster zones in our communities,'' said Allison LaPlante
of the Public Interest Research Group. ``Unfortunately the answer
is nothing, despite the fact that more than 250 Americans die every
year in chemical accidents.''
</P>
<P>
   The chemical industry has maintained that voluntary programs
have been successful in reducing toxic chemical emissions. It
opposes further reductions of chemical usage without some
scientific basis. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One upshot of the risk-management programs has been that Bayer
has been forced to make some new friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``Historically we haven't been as involved in our community as
we should,'' said Greg Coffey, the Bayer director of public
affairs.
</P>
<P>
   This year the company has been bringing in community members,
neighboring industry representatives and government officials to
show off their risk- management plans, including the worst-case
model.
</P>
<P>
   The company has also gone to community meetings and given
presentations on their emergency response plans and new efforts to
reduce the off-site effects of any future chemical accidents.
</P>
<P>
   Bayer has committed $4.6 million this year to build a new
chlorine containment building. All transfers of chemicals from rail
cars to Bayer pipelines will be done inside that building,
decreasing the possibility of an off-site release.
</P>
<P>
   Wey and Don Leming, Bayer's vice president for manufacturing,
say the actual chemical accident scenarios were ones that the
company already had considered.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a scientist and engineer, you can't help but wonder: Why do
I have to do this?'' said Wey, explaining the many reasons that a
worst-case accident like the one modeled in Bayer's plan could
never happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's also given us the opportunity to go out and show
people that this is a safe plant.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
