<HEADLINE>
IS RAMON MARTINEZ STILL OF VALUE?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Ramon Martinez, whose long Los Angeles Dodgers career
ended last July when he underwent reconstructive surgery on his
right shoulder, begins a minor- league rehabilitation assignment
Monday night for the Boston Red Sox Class-A affiliate.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, who topped out at 87 mph on the radar gun during a
recent simulated game at Fenway Park, hopes to join the depleted
Sox rotation around the All-Star break. Already this year, Boston
has lost right-handers Mark Portugal and Bret Saberhagen to
injuries and had to move Tim Wakefield to the bullpen when closer
Tom Gordon hurt his right shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez signed with the Red Sox in the spring after the Dodgers
failed to offer enough guaranteed money. The Dodgers' starting
rotation was set and even had a surplus with Dave Mlicki. Martinez
had torn his rotator cuff in each of the past two seasons and with
the overhaul at the top there was no one to recognize his clubhouse
value with Latin players.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Dodgers' staff is ineffective, except for Kevin Brown.
It's almost time to see if Martinez still has value as a pitcher. &QL; 
GOING DEEP
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay's Jose Canseco entered the weekend needing five home
runs to become the first player in major-league history to hit 30
or more home runs in a single season for four different teams
(Oakland, Texas and Toronto are the others). Teammate Fred McGriff,
who has 16 homers this season, could become the second.
</P>
<P>
   Canseco is the third-fastest AL player this decade to reach 25
homers. It took Canseco 63 games, while Ken Griffey needed only 55
games in 1994 and 56 in 1997. &QL; 
CHANGING SOX
</P>
<P>
   With their recent stretch of good play (winning 11 of 17 through
Tuesday) and a down stretch for the Red Sox, the Chicago White Sox
are thinking playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not concerned about catching Cleveland,'' said
right-hander Jaime Navarro, 3-0 with a 3.64 ERA and a consistent
95-96 mph fastball in his past five starts. ``I'm concerned about
getting the wild card. I think that's our goal. We can't worry
about what Cleveland is doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than trading veterans to contenders, as the Sox did in
1997 and '98, GM Ron Schueler foresees a scenario where he might
trade minor-leaguers for some stretch-run help. Schueler has been
shopping Navarro for at least a year, but now says he's off the
market. &QL; 
MORE STREAKS
</P>
<P>
   When Cal Ripken ended his consecutive game streak last September
at 2,632 games, teammate Albert Belle became baseball's new iron
man. So what happened? Orioles manager Ray Miller became angry at
Belle and benched him last weekend after their dugout blowup. End
of streak, which had reached 392 games.
</P>
<P>
   The longest active streak then fell to Colorado's Vinny
Castilla, who held the distinction for exactly four days before
sitting out Tuesday night's game. The active record came back to
Baltimore and outfielder B.J. Surhoff with 228. At this rate
Surhoff needs to play only every game until 2014 to challenge
Ripken's all-time record. &QL; 
TRADE WINDS
</P>
<P>
   Given his status as one of the game's top players, the team's
chance to reach the playoffs and GM Woody Woodward's general
inability to pull the trigger on trades, Seattle shortstop Alex
Rodriguez is not headed to the Detroit Tigers for Tony Clark,
Justin Thompson and Deivi Cruz. That rumor was burning up the
Internet and talk shows in Detroit this past week....
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers would love to bring back Cardinals left-hander
Darren Oliver _ a free agent after the season.... Wilson Alvarez
and Scott Erickson are also available.... The Royals would love to
trade Kevin Appier, but at the steep price of two premium
prospects.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
