<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRASS-ROOTS APPEAL, TAILGATERS AND TRAFFIC
</HEADLINE>
   (With SOC-U.S.-DENMARK, SOC-CHINA-SWEDEN) 
(nk) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ They drove in on the shoulder of the
turnpike, past a traffic jam worthy of a Giants game or a Jets
game. Their chartered bus roared past the soccer moms, the soccer
dads, the orange-cone soccer players, the soccer freaks, which was
only right. There would be no game without the talent.
</P>
<P>
   The American players in the bus knew the numbers, the number of
tickets that had been sold, but still that did not prepare them for
the sight of tailgaters filling up the parking lots, hours before a
soccer game.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a major stadium in the United States,'' said Brandi
Chastain, herself a major soccer player in that country. ``It is
known for its name. People know what happens here. Now soccer will
be remembered here, also.''
</P>
<P>
   They were part of a happening, part of a spectacle, part of an
only-in-America example of marketing. They were part of the largest
crowd ever to see a women's soccer game in history, 78,972, fans,
surpassing the 76,489 who attended the Summer Games final in
Athens, Ga., in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a soccer-only crowd,'' Chastain said. ``It wasn't a
corporate, let's-go-to-the-Olympics crowd. These were soccer
fans.''
</P>
<P>
   The fans would see the home team wear down Denmark, 3-0, in the
opening game of the 1999 World Cup, after which Brazil would run it
up over Mexico, 7-1.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd was a tribute to the sales skills of Yank
entrepreneurs, but it was also a sign that something is happening,
that there is an audience for good international soccer, male or
female. Flags sell tickets. National colors sell tickets.
</P>
<P>
   The American players were here to do business. They have been
waiting for this World Cup since that day in Sweden in June of 1995
_ in front of exactly 2,893 spectators in the Swedish town of
Vasteras _ when they lost to their archrivals, Norway, by 1-0 in
the semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   Some Americans prefer to forget that loss, bury it in the back
yard of their memories, but they all admit it festers there,
something to be avenged, something to be avoided, this time around.
</P>
<P>
   But they know how to ease into the big game. Chastain reported
that the day began with a dance party in the hallway of their
hotel, ``like 12-year-olds at camp,'' and painting their
fingernails in patriotic colors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds goofy, but that's what we did,'' Chastain said.
</P>
<P>
   When they got to the stadium, they did not hide behind
sunglasses and a professional game face. They were human enough to
take snapshots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked up and I saw little clusters of Brazilians,'' said
Briana Scurry, the goalkeeper, talking about the emotional center
of this sport. ``I saw another cluster from Denmark. The rest of
them were for us.''
</P>
<P>
   So they were, all these sport-utility vehicle families from the
Middle Atlantic and northeast states, with their soccer jerseys
displaying American players' names or their own names. (There was
one green jersey with ``Chrebet'' on it; do you think the poor fan
has been stuck in Giants Stadium since Jan. 10?)
</P>
<P>
   Chastain, known to her teammates as Hollywood for her
histrionics and pratfalls on the field, took the time to look up
into this crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``I actually saw two people I know from California,'' Chastain
said. ``Our eyes locked. Just weird.''
</P>
<P>
   She was glad she had made the eye contact because she knew these
people were for her, that most of the 78,972 fans had paid good
money to root for the home team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes your heart beat faster,'' Chastain said. ``You stand
a little taller.''
</P>
<P>
   Mia Hamm, who actually lived up to television's craving for one
star, one focus, was raving about the crowd afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we played in China, there were big crowds,'' Hamm said,
referring to the 65,000 for the World Cup finals in 1991. ``But I
can't tell you how proud I am of this crowd.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans who played in China and Sweden knew the 1999 World
Cup would be a different breed from either of the first two
tournaments. They knew that American marketing would fill up the
stadiums where the professional and college football players
normally cavort.
</P>
<P>
   Ticket sales were at 460,000 before Saturday's opener, perhaps
heading toward half a million. But when it happened, it was a joy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw a lot of painted faces, heard a lot of drums,'' said
Marla Messing, the president of the organizing committee. ``To me,
this was a soccer crowd. This is what we were struggling to
achieve. To me, the 1994 World Cup aimed at ethnic groups and men,
but we aimed more for families.''
</P>
<P>
   Messing recalled the grass-roots program, sending mailings to
registered soccer players, ``literally setting up pop-up tents on
soccer fields.''
</P>
<P>
   The hard work paid off Saturday, and will continue as the
talented teams like the Americans and the Brazilians work their way
toward the quarterfinals. The final at the Rose Bowl should draw
close to its 92,000 capacity. Saturday's record for a female soccer
match will probably last only three weeks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
