<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-19 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2202 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-DRAFT-QNA20-COX     06-19 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DRAFT-QNA20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Previewing NHL entry, expansion picks
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The expansion Atlanta Thrashers don't have a coach
yet, but they'll have a lot of players soon. Staff writer Jeff
Schultz offers some answers to a few of the most-asked questions by
Thrashers fans eager for the return of the NHL to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where will the Thrashers get their players?
</P>
<P>
   A: Players will come from four sources: deals such as Friday's
trade with Ottawa, for ``future considerations''; this Friday's
expansion draft; the entry draft Saturday; and free-agent signings,
with players allowed to sign with new teams after July 1.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the expansion draft?
</P>
<P>
   A: The format of the expansion draft has changed since the NHL's
first expanded from six to 12 teams in 1967, but the objective is
the same: to help stock new teams with players from existing teams.
Twenty-six of the exisiting 27 are allowed to protect its core
players. Nashville, as a one-year-old franchise, is exempt from the
expansion draft.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How many players can teams protect?
</P>
<P>
   A: Teams can pick from one of two formulas: one goalie, five
defensemen and nine forwards, or two goalies, three defensemen and
seven forwards. At least one defensemen and two forwards exposed
must have played a minimum of 40 games _ regular season and
playoffs _ this season or 70 over the last two. Teams protecting
two goalies must expose a goalie who has played at least 10 games
this year or 25 over the last two. Most teams will pick the
one-goalie formula, preferring not to lose a front-line defenseman
or forward. However, the teams that have two strong goaltenders
must risk losing one in the expansion draft. But teams can lose
only one player each. Also, first- and second-year players and
unsigned draft picks are exempt from the draft. Five teams are
exempt from losing a goaltender because they had one chosen by
Nashville in last year's expansion draft: Rangers, New Jersey,
Montreal, Anaheim and Los Angeles. Therefore, the Thrashers will
pick their goal-
</P>
<P>
   tenders from the other 21 teams.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How many goaltenders will the Thrashers draft?
</P>
<P>
   A: General manager Don Waddell must take at least three goalies,
eight defensemen and 13 forwards. But he said he will take the
maximum of five goal-tenders.
</P>
<P>
   Q: So the Thrashers will get 26 players from the expansion
draft?
</P>
<P>
   A: Not necessarily. Some teams might not have players fitting
the Thrashers' needs. Waddell has several options, including
``drafting'' an unrestricted free agent from a team's unprotected
list. If the player then signs with another team, even his original
club, Atlanta will receive a compensatory draft pick from the NHL.
For example, Nashville drafted Rangers free-agent goalie Mike
Richter, who then re-signed with New York. The Predators never had
any intention of signing Richter, who had expressed an interest in
remaining in New York. Signed players acquired in the expansion
draft also can be traded. The Predators stockpiled several draft
picks with trades.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the entry draft?
</P>
<P>
   A: It is the NHL's equivalent of the college or amateur drafts
in football, basketball and baseball. But it's a large pool of
players, including Canadian junior leagues, U.S. colleges and
European leagues. The draft is nine rounds.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When will the Thrashers pick?
</P>
<P>
   A: They will pick second in every round, behind Tampa Bay, which
finished last in the overall standings.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who are the best players in the draft?
</P>
<P>
   A: The consensus top players this year are forwards, and all are
European natives, which is unusual: Patrik Stefan and Pavel Brendl
of the Czech Republic and twins Daniel and Henrik Sedin of Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Will the Thrashers' first draft pick play for them next year?
</P>
<P>
   A: Maybe not. Hockey's draft is similar to baseball's in that
the players are young _ usually 18 or 19 _ and not yet ready
physically or mentally to compete in the NHL. The lone exception in
this draft might be Stefan, who has been competing as an amateur
for the IHL's Long Beach Ice Dogs against older, stronger players.
Scouts believe Stefan can step right in.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Will the Thrashers draft him?
</P>
<P>
   A: Possibly. Stefan suffered at least two concussions last
season, and there is uncertainty about any lingering effects. Also,
Tampa Bay might take Stefan first. Brendl probably is a year away
from playing in the NHL and the Sedins two years.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
