<SLUG> BC-HKN-HOCKEY-NOTES20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Isles trade machinations nixed
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _As Gary Bettman was attempting to enjoy the
Stanley Cup finals this past week, the NHL's second-most
embarrassing franchise (it's hard to top a team in bankruptcy)
continued to stick to the NHL commissioner like a fungus.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Islanders, who have been attempting to slash their
team payroll to roughly the cost equivalent of a Happy Meal, put
star forward Ziggy Palffy on the market. The crosstown Rangers, not
the Isles' usual trade partner, responded with a strong offer of
Niklas Sundstrom, Todd Harvey, the 11th pick in the draft, a
prospect and $2.5 million for Palffy and Rich Pilon.
</P>
<P>
   The teams agreed on the deal. Then Islanders owners Howard
Milstein and Steve Gluckstern decided to get cute.
</P>
<P>
   After agreeing to the deal, the Islanders tried to squeeze
Cablevision _ which has financial ties to both New York teams _
into juicing up its television deal with the team. They also
wouldn't mind if the company lent a hand (or a wallet) in the
team's quest for a new arena. Cablevision's motivation for
agreeing: Palffy in Manhattan would be a hot property.
</P>
<P>
   But Cablevision balked, the Islanders started holding trade
talks with Los Angeles, the Rangers fumed and now Bettman has
stepped in and demanded that no deal involve any cash, for fear of
it looking like the Isles are merely selling off players.
</P>
<P>
   NHL vice president Colin Campbell, a former Rangers executive,
has been watching over the mess for Bettman. ``All I'm doing for
Gary is giving my humble analysis of the hockey aspects of the
trade,'' Campbell said. ``A couple of times we've had some
discussions, but Gary is wrestling with the bigger picture. There's
responsibility and accountability for the league.''
</P>
<P>
   Surprise, surprise
</P>
<P>
   The only thing more unexpected than the Phoenix Coyotes' hiring
of Bobby Francis as coach was the Los Angeles Kings' selection of
Andy Murray. Murray has been an assistant for three NHL teams but
is known mostly for his coaching internationally and for the
Canadian national team _ at least, for those who know him at all.
Kings defenseman Rob Blake, who played for Murray in Canada, gave
him a strong recommendation to general manager Dave Taylor.
``Nobody should be surprised,'' Taylor said when asked about being
criticized for the hiring. ``In L.A. a lot of people aren't aware
of who the good coaches are. It's not a traditional hockey market.
A lot of people might say, `Andy Murray, who's that?' But if you
look at his resume and talk to people about him, you can't help but
be impressed.''... Coyotes general manager Bobby Smith said he was
impressed with Francis, a Boston assistant, in interviews ``and I'm
not an easy guy to impress. Any time you hire a new coach, it's a
risk. But I like his approach, his intellect and his understanding
of the game.'' Francis is the son of former long-time NHL coach and
general manager Emile Francis.
</P>
<P>
   The candidate (Part III)
</P>
<P>
   Orlando International Hockey League coach Curt Fraser, who
interviewed in Atlanta with Thrashers general manager Don Waddell
last week, doesn't believe his lack of coaching experience in the
NHL should be a handicap. Fraser played 12 years in the league,
then coached four years with Milwaukee of the IHL (two as an
assistant, two as a head coach), one in Syracuse and four in
Orlando (where was hired by Waddell). ``This has been a great
training ground,'' Fraser said. ``We've been an independent team so
we've covered the spectrum with players, from 20-year-olds to
35-year-olds. We've had winning teams every year. Atlanta is
starting with a clean slate. I feel I can grow with the
organization. I've already gone through a lot of growing pains.''
</P>
<P>
   Penguins bailout
</P>
<P>
   Mario Lemieux has enlisted singer Celine Dion among his
potential investors in the bankrupt Pittsburgh Penguins. Dion is
not from Pittsburgh but she speaks French and is wealthy, like
Lemieux.... The Washington Capitals may leave defenseman Dmitri
Mironov exposed in the Thrashers' expansion draft. But Mironov has
three years left on a deal that averages $2.875 million per
year.... Colorado general manager Pierre Lacroix said he will speak
with Theo Fleury's agent before the free agency period begins July
1 but he would not say how interested he was in keeping the player.
Fleury went scoreless in the Western Conference finals loss to
Dallas.... Detroit defenseman Niklas Lidstrom said it will be at
least three weeks before he decides whether to re-sign with the Red
Wings or return to his native Sweden. Meanwhile, Wings general
manager Ken Holland has other problems. His offers of one-year
extensions have not been embraced by assistant coaches Dave Lewis
and Barry Smith, who want more security in case Scotty Bowman calls
it quits after next season. Holland is exploring the possibility of
two-year offers.... Bobby Carpenter, who has had an 18-year career
but never quite matched the expectations set up by a Sports
Illustrated cover story proclaiming him hockey's next great player,
might retire and go into coaching. New Jersey already has told him
he won't be invited back.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
