<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-19 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2204 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-THRASHERS20-COX     06-19 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-THRASHERS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For Thrashers, drafts a whirl of deal-making
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ Nashville Predators general manager David Poile
watched with amusement as Don Waddell moved from one area of a
hotel meeting room to another, wading through a sea of NHL
executives and media members.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just follow Don around _ he can't go 10 feet without somebody
wanting to talk to him,'' Poile said after a recent general
managers meeting. ``That's the way it was for me last year. Now
nobody wants to talk to me; I can't help anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   As general manager of the expansion Thrashers, Waddell is
holding all the cards these days. ``Let's see what we're holding
when we're all done,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   With the NHL expansion draft coming up Friday and the entry
draft a day after, Waddell's decisions on how best to shape this
franchise will be linked to deals or nondeals with 26 other clubs.
The only general manager on the outside is Poile, whose Predators
went through this process last year and are exempt from this year's
expansion draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody wants to talk to you for whatever reason,'' Poile
said, ``either to ask who you're going to take from them, or to
tell you who'd they like you to take, or to tell you they don't
want to lose a certain player. Then it becomes, `Can we entice you
to take somebody else?'''
</P>
<P>
   Each team is allowed to submit a list of protected players,
choosing one of two options _ either one goalie, five defensemen
and nine forwards or two goalies, three defensemen and seven
forwards. The Thrashers will pick from the leftovers. But
sometimes, teams will persuade expansion teams to stay away from a
top young player, particularly a goalie, by making side deals with
them.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the Predators secured extra draft picks and players
from Los Angeles for not drafting goalie Jamie Storr and from St.
Louis for not taking goalie Jamie McLennan. Overall, they made
eight transactions on the day of the expansion draft. Some deals
are announced as involving ``future considerations,'' when in fact
they are ``past.'' Poile used his leverage to stockpile picks and
will have eight in the first three rounds of Saturday's entry
draft.
</P>
<P>
   The Thrashers' strategy will differ slightly, but the process
has been every bit as crazy for Waddell as it was for Poile. He
receives approximately 30 telephone calls a day about trades or
coaching prospects.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm having conversations with 17 or 18 teams that are looking
to do things,'' Waddell said. ``We'll look at everything. Chances
are we're going to do things a little different from Nashville.
We're not looking to stockpile draft picks. But we are looking to
build the franchise the best way possible. . . . I anticipate
(this) week to be very, very busy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stanley Cup finals have been bad for the Thrashers because
protected lists do not have to be confirmed until 48 hours after
the final game. If the series had ended earlier, Waddell would have
had more time to study the available players.
</P>
<P>
   But going into the weekend, this is what Waddell was looking at:
If Dallas and Buffalo played six games, all teams had until 5 p.m.
today to complete trades and until noon Monday to submit protected
lists. On a seven-game series, the trade deadline would be 2 p.m.
Wednesday, with the lists due at 4 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't do anything until we get the lists and we see who's
available,'' Waddell said. ``I can't tell a team, `Don't worry, I
won't take your goalie,' if I can't be sure the goalie I want from
another team isn't there. Once we get the list, then I'll have
something to work with. I'll know what my leverage is.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that Waddell would have committed to early deals, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``It only makes sense for me to wait as long as possible,'' he
said. ``The price will only go up.''
</P>
<P>
   The Thrashers' scouting department already has done 12 mock
drafts, Waddell said, ``and I've probably done 50, because every
time I get on a plane I do another one. I haven't gotten to 100
(total) goals yet (among potential picks), though. Ninety-seven is
the record so far. My guess is our goal-scorers will have to come
from the entry draft or potentially some European players,'' signed
as free agents.
</P>
<P>
   The key to the expansion draft is goaltending. The Thrashers
have gotten a jump in that area by trading for Ottawa's Damian
Rhodes, who probably will be their starter. But Waddell still is
likely to spend the maximum of five expansion picks on goalies.
Detroit's touted backup, Norm Maracle, is among those likely to be
taken.
</P>
<P>
   The expansion draft will take only about 10 minutes, because the
Thrashers are the only team in the expansion draft. All that
happens is that Waddell submits his list of players.
</P>
<P>
   The amateur draft, involving 27 teams for nine rounds, is an
all-day affair. Atlanta will pick second in each round, and Waddell
said it's extremely doubtful he will move up to the top spot --
occupied by Tampa Bay -- or down, although he has received several
offers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I wanted to start giving away draft picks and making
trades, that could make us really competitive right now,'' Waddell
said. ``But what's that do for us four or five years from now? If
we keep our draft picks, make good picks and build through it,
there's no reason we can't get good and keep it going for a long
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Poile said there was only one thing he didn't enjoy about
Nashville's starting point: ``I wish there were better players
available in the expansion draft.''
</P>
<P>
   But he also said, ``It was a neat thing. The one thing I've
talked to Don about is, you're starting something brand new. It's
your design. It's your team.''
</P>
<P>
   NHL DRAFTS
</P>
<P>
   Where: FleetCenter in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   When: Expansion draft is 3 p.m. Friday; entry draft is noon
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Expansion format: Atlanta Thrashers will select 26 players, one
from each existing NHL team except Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   Entry draft: Thrashers pick second behind Tampa Bay in each of
the nine rounds.
</P>
<P>
   TV: None for expansion draft; ESPN2 for entry draft.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
