<SLUG> BC-SOC-US-DENMARK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    78,972 join U.S. party in 3-0 win over Danes
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Pardon the U.S. women's soccer team for
indulging in an unusual post-match celebration after their
convincing 3-0 win over Denmark Saturday to open the Women's World
Cup.
</P>
<P>
   For a no-nonsense team focused solidly on the bottom line _
nothing less than the championship on July 10 at the Rose Bowl _
the American players weren't above rejoicing on this historic
occasion.
</P>
<P>
   As they took laps around the Giants Stadium field, they
applauded and waved to a world-record women's soccer crowd of
78,972, a number that almost certainly will be surpassed _ as long
as they're in the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what we dreamed a World Cup should be,'' said forward
Mia Hamm, who had a goal and an assist before coming out with
cramps late in the game. ``We could hear each other but we couldn't
hear from one side of the field to the other. That's the kind of
noise we wanted to have.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the U.S. admitted to having butterflies in the opening
minutes, when the gritty Danes got their best scoring chances and
hammered them with a physical game plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were a little bit nervous the first 20 minutes,'' said U.S.
goalkeeper Briana Scurry, who had the wind knocked out of her in a
mid-air collision with Denmark's Lene Jensen in the first half.
``They came at us with all they had. We knew it was going to be
that kind of match.''
</P>
<P>
   But like the Americans have done plenty of times before, they
simply wore down Denmark, which was outshot 24-9 and 15-4 in the
second half.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. team, which plays Nigeria Thursday at Chicago's Soldier
Field, still showed some defensive lapses that have been a concern
in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're delighted with the win, but can't get too overjoyed
here,'' said U.S. coach Tony DiCicco, who was trying to calm
himself down afterward. ``It's going to be a long road for us.''
</P>
<P>
   In the second minute of play, Lene Jensen found Gitte Krogh up
the middle with plenty of space, and she pulled out wide to unfurl
a cross that bounced through the goal mouth before a U.S. defender
could get to it.
</P>
<P>
   With 15 minutes gone, Jensen jumped for a long ball in the box,
her shoulder spearing Scurry in the stomach, but Denmark could not
reorganize to get a clear shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ball was loose and I was still down,'' Scurry said. ``I
don't even know if they had the ball or not.''
</P>
<P>
   While Scurry was gaining her equilibrium, Hamm soon found
operating room down the flank, and when Brandi Chastain served up a
high diagonal pass from the back in the 18th minute, the crowd rose
in anticipation. Hamm neatly brought down the deflected ball with
her right leg, and in a singluar motion whipped it high into the
net for a 1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept saying to myself, `are you freaking kidding me?' ''
Hamm said. ``I never score goals like that. That's something that
Michelle Akers does.''
</P>
<P>
   In the second half, Hamm set up the goal that signaled the
demise of the Danes by lacing a cross across the box to Julie
Foudy, who knocked home the shot with her left foot in the 74th
minute.
</P>
<P>
   At halftime, DiCicco had pulled Kristine Lilly up front and
dropped Cindy Parlow back into midfield to turn up the pressure
even more. And the creative, left-footed Lilly quickly began
wreaking havoc. She uncorked an open shot that hit the crossbar and
then took a touch pass from Parlow and was all alone with only
Larsen to beat before sliding it wide of the net.
</P>
<P>
   Her Danish marker derisively whispered in her ear, ``Nice try,''
but Lilly exacted some sweet revenge. With a minute remaining, she
worked the right edge of the box, took a couple of dribbles to her
left and curled a hummer into the far corner of the net. And she
pointed toward the beaten Jeanne Axelsen while dancing
triumphantly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted that one to be for her,'' Lilly said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
