<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Amazing' atmosphere for opener
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Briana Scurry was sprawling at the edge
of the penalty box, feeling the full force of a Danish shoulder in
her upper torso.
</P>
<P>
   It was bad enough that the U.S. goalkeeper was feeling the same
nerves as her teammates in the early moments of their World Cup
opening match with Denmark that drew a women's soccer world record
attendance of 78,972.
</P>
<P>
   But with no score in the game and the Danes exerting strong
early pressure, Scurry didn't hesitate to challenge forward Lene
Jensen, who was nowhere near the ball when they collided.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her entire body just went into me. I felt everything,'' Scurry
said. ``But especially I felt her shoulder going into my chest.''
</P>
<P>
   Denmark wasn't able to put together even two passes amid that
choas, and three minutes later the U.S. team got on the board first
with a Mia Hamm goal that seemed to loosen up the Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Playing in front of big crowds is not unusual for the U.S. team,
but the hype that has accompanied the World Cup has been
unprecedented.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole environment was just amazing,'' said midfielder
Kristine Lilly, who capped the 3-0 win with a goal in the final
minute of the game. ``I hope this game is going to have a snowball
effect throughout the World Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   But the kind of battering Scurry took is indicative of what the
U.S. team can expect the rest of the way, especially as they get
ready to face Nigeria and North Korea next week in their final two
group matches. Both are opponents the U.S. team has never met
before, and the Americans say they're taking no one for granted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a tough tournament, we know that,'' Scurry
said. ``Teams that usually roll over when we play them aren't going
to roll over in this tournament. They're very proud to be playing
on this big stage.''
</P>
<P>
   Glad to be invited
</P>
<P>
   All week long, Denmark coach Jorgen Hvidemose and his players
were good sports about being put in the role of playing the U.S. in
the opener. Even after being dominated on Saturday, he couldn't be
disappointed with being part of the spectacle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm satisfied,'' he said. ``We were a part of the party. We
created some chances and should have scored a goal or two. But it's
important for us to get some progress out of this match.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a really big game for everybody. Even Mia Hamm had
admitted she was nervous in front of this crowd.''
</P>
<P>
   Teeny-bopper crowd
</P>
<P>
   In case there was any question about the main target audience
for this World Cup, the entertainment acts in the pre-game
ceremonies were known mainly to teenagers: Bwitched, Billie and
N'Sync.
</P>
<P>
   The youthful audience fidgeted afterward while bigwigs with
suits took the microphones, ranging from FIFA president Sepp
Blatter to United Nations General Secretary Kofi Annan.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
