<SLUG> BC-SOC-U.S.-DENMARK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAMM HANDLES HYPE AND AMERICANS' HIGH HOPES
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J._ She is the face of women's soccer, the
player the young girls squeal for, the one personality who has
pushed through the glass ceiling of invisibility in a sport still
trying to broaden its appeal beyond the weekend fields of suburbia.
</P>
<P>
   For the Women's World Cup to succeed, in many ways, Mia Hamm has
to succeed. She is the one person anybody knows, if they know
anything about women's soccer. The largest audience ever to watch a
women's sporting event in the United States came to see Hamm
Saturday and she did not disappoint them, scoring a goal and
assisting on another as the Americans defeated Denmark, 3-0, in the
opener before a crowd of 78,972 at Giants Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Hamm is the poster girl for this World Cup, the one featured in
the television commercials, the newspaper and magazine stories, the
broadcast profiles. It is her No. 9 jersey that is sold at the
concession stands. In truth, she had not played at her best in
previous important tournaments, but Saturday she turned the hype
into an accurate forecast.
</P>
<P>
   While her teammates seemed tight and nervous at the beginning,
Hamm attacked immediately and threatened to score, or put someone
else in position to score, nearly every time she touched the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was important for her to get off quickly, because our team
didn't get off quickly,'' coach Tony DiCicco said. ``She looked
dangerous every time she got the ball, and it had a soothing effect
on our team. She wanted the responsibility, she wanted the ball.
Mia was awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   Denmark drilled a shot across the goal mouth in the second
minute and American goalkeeper Briana Scurry, still woozy from a
freight-train collision in front of the net, smothered another ball
in the 15th minute.
</P>
<P>
   The Danes were winning balls in the air at midfield and the
American defense found itself in unaccustomed retreat. On attack,
passes were being made too soon or were erratically placed. The
United States needed a play, a goal, a galvanizing moment, to
settle itself, and Hamm provided it.
</P>
<P>
   Her first meaningful touch came in the 17th minute, and she did
not waste the chance.
</P>
<P>
   Taking a long diagonal pass from Brandi Chastain with her right
foot in the penalty area, Hamm slashed to her left and tried to
chip the ball over Katrine Pedersen, the Danish defender. The ball
hit Pedersen in the chest, but Hamm pounced on it and blasted a
left-footed shot from 13 yards over the head of goalkeeper Dorthe
Larsen. With this bit of brilliant improvisation, the Americans had
a 1-0 lead and the confidence that more goals would follow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you kidding me?'' Hamm kept telling herself as she
sprinted upfield in celebration. ``I don't score goals like that.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a burden on Hamm, but also unprecedented opportunity,
in this World Cup. While she has scored more international goals _
110 _ than any man or woman ever to play the sport, the beauty of
her game is its completeness.
</P>
<P>
   Hamm is a selfless passer and a willing defender. She kept
sending balls into the penalty area for Kristine Lilly and Cindy
Parlow, and even when they could not catch up to them, or place
them in the back of the net, Hamm kept serving them up again as if
this were Wimbledon instead of the World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, in the 73rd minute, Hamm punched a hard cross from the
right flank and midfielder Julie Foudy connected. Gathering the
ball with her left foot, Foudy clipped the underside of the
crossbar, and the Americans pulled ahead by 2-0. The team's comic
relief, Foudy then tossed up her arm and leg, striking a pose out
of ``Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Danish defense could not stop Hamm Saturday, cramping
hamstring muscles finally forced her to leave the game in the 88th
minute. A minute later, Lilly, who moved from midfield to forward
in the second half, drilled a shot from the top of the penalty area
to give the United States its final margin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Goals help your confidence,'' Hamm said of the expectations
placed on her for the tournament. ``As a front-runner, that's one
of your responsibilities. To be able to do it in the first game
helps.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Hamm's presence, there were long dull stretches in the
game, and in the end, it may have served a greater purpose as a
cultural experience than an attractive athletic event. Only one
previous match _ the gold-medal soccer game at the 1996 Summer
Olympics, which drew 76,489 for the American victory over China _
rivaled Saturday's game in terms of attendance for a women's
sporting event in this country.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd was largely composed of soccer moms and dads, and
teen-age and pre-teen girls, a number of whom had their faces
painted red, white and blue and who wore a replica of Hamm's
jersey. One teen-ager was spotted reading Hamm's autobiography in
the parking lot before the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``She reminds us of what we can be if we keep our heads on
straight,'' said another of her fans, Kim Johnston, 18, of
Edmeston, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   The American players got into the star-spangled spirit by
painting their fingernails and toenails alternately red and blue,
and they had an impromptu dance party before leaving the team
hotel. ``This is what happens when you have a lot of time on your
hands,'' Hamm said. It took her calm assertiveness to channel this
nervous excitement into useful soccer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crowd was unbelievable,'' said Hamm, who was too fatigued
to join her teammates in a victory lap. ``It was a very proud
moment. We could hear each other, but we couldn't hear side to
side. This is what we always dreamed a World Cup should be.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
