<SLUG> BC-GLF-BISHER-USOPEN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Love affair with No. 2 ends badly
 &HT;    By Furman Bisher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINEHURST, N.C. _ Well, so much for that romance. A rift has
come between the golf pros of the world and Pinehurst No. 2, the
course once beloved, now reviled. It was ``the greatest U.S. Open
course'' he had ever seen, Greg Norman had said. He shot 151,
11-over par and was gone. Davis Love III loved it, professed his
undying devotion to it. Colin Montgomerie, the fleshy one, said
that this was the kind of course that just might be right for the
Europeans to break their long losing streak in the U.S. Open.
Donald Ross, who created it, would have been taking bows, had he
not been dead since 1948.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the cut at 36 holes. Jason Tyska, Spike McRoy, David
Lebeck, Geoffrey Sisk, Esteban Toledo and Kaname Yokoo made it.
Jack Nicklaus, Curtis Strange, Fuzzy Zoeller, Ernie Els and Steve
Jones didn't. What they have in common is, they are all former
champions. Lebeck has never played in an official tournament
before. Yokoo is the mystery player from Japan. McRoy has collected
$6,120 on the Nike Tour this year. The others are of equal
anonymity. That's the treachery of U.S. Open courses, seldom ever
praised before the 99th event reached this revered, storied old
course, with its shorn greens.
</P>
<P>
   As play began Saturday, there wasn't a European name on the
leaderboard. As twilight fell across the Sandhills, only one name
was in red numbers, and Phil Mickelson's reign was numbered. The
mourners' band was back in fine tune, as is usual at such places as
Olympic, Oakmont, Oakland Hills, Baltusrol, where the grass grows
high.
</P>
<P>
   One player, reflecting the frustration of the day, said,
``Personally, I prefer high rough.'' Tom Lehman said it after a
round of 73, his best of the week. Now he tells them.
</P>
<P>
   The horror stories coming in off the course sounded like reports
from a war zone. The wind had puffed up. The sun had taken the day
off. The skies spit a mist of rain, but the greens were still as
slick as glacial ice. Pin placements came in for the most damning
tirade, this reflecting the annual common displeasure with the
blue-jacketed gentlemen sportsmen of the USGA.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pin placements were borderline sadistic,'' Scott Verplank
said, though he had just come in at 72, his best round of the week,
with four birdies. This contradicted John Cook (77) who said, ``A
birdie today is out of the question.''
</P>
<P>
   Then came Lehman again, who will not be in the final pairing for
a fifth year. ``This makes Augusta look tame.''
</P>
<P>
   Then John Cook. ``If anyone shoots even par today, it will be
the round of the year.'' There were two, and Steve Stricker had to
hole a fairway bunker shot for eagle on the third hole to check in
with a 69. Tim Herron had an even 70.
</P>
<P>
   Players were wild-eyed and shaken. They cursed the USGA under
their breath, but all in all, it sounded like just another third
day at another U.S. Open. When there's no one else to blame,
there's always the financiers, the industrialists, the tycoons, the
elderly officials of the USGA. But can they be blamed for missed
three-foot putts, for sprayed tee shots that startle the squirrels?
And have you ever seen as many putts left short by men who should
be good at this game?
</P>
<P>
   We check in now with Lee Janzen, 13-over-par and no threat to
defend the title he won in San Francisco last year. ``I've been
asked many times what was the hardest golf course I ever played,''
he said. ``Now I have the answer.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a dreadful day for all concerned, except Pinehurst No. 2.
It defended its honor righteously. By end of the day, Payne Stewart
had the one red figure left on the board, 1-under-par. ``These guys
are good,'' the TV promo, was in serious jeopardy. The three who
began the day in the lead, Mickelson, David Duval and Stewart had
been separated and spread about the board. It had been, as the most
outspoken had said, a pretty horrid day on No. 2, except for
Stewart, who once again had the lead going into the final 18 holes,
as in San Francisco a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
