<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stricker's 1-under 69 gives him a title shot
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINEHURST, N.C. _ Steve Stricker's 1-under-par 69 was nothing
short of a masterpiece Saturday at Pinehurst No. 2, but look at the
necessary ingredients. Stricker jumped from 3 over par to even-par
in two holes by draining a 45-foot putt for birdie at No. 2 and
then holing out from a fairway bunker at No. 3 for eagle.
</P>
<P>
   Using the rare scoring flurry to move into contention in the
U.S. Open, Sticker, the only golfer under par, finished the third
round at 2-over 212.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel OK,'' said Stricker, runner-up to Vijay Singh in last
year's PGA Championship. ``I've been in this position a few times.
I learned a lot from last year. ... I'm in good position. I need to
come out and put up another one of those (69's) or better
tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Stricker's bunker shot came from 137 yards with an 8-iron,
erasing the irritation of a badly pulled drive at the 335-yard par
4.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a perfect yardage for me,'' Stricker said. ``I
wasn't able to see it go in the hole, but the crowd just kept
getting louder and louder and I knew it was in.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the day was less celebratory for Stricker, who tied for
fifth last year at the Olympic Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very difficult,'' he said. ``You have to be careful not
to chip it or putt it off the green.''
</P>
<P>
   Just ripping it
</P>
<P>
   Never much for practice range time, John Daly usually at least
makes an appearance. Not so prior to Saturday's third round. Daly
hit no practice balls prior to his 11:45 a.m. pairing with Steve
Pate. Unfazed, he boomed a huge draw off the first tee, but maybe
it caught up with him later as Daly shot an 81. ... When Tom
Watson, who turns 50 on Sept. 4, made the cut Friday, it created
his first weekend appearance in a major in his last seven tries.
... Greg Norman, after missing the cut Friday with rounds of 73-78:
``It's a bit of a horror story for me right now. I'm in a video
store picking out all of the bad movies instead of the good ones.''
Asked how many greens hit, Norman said, ``I probably hit 12, but I
only stayed on two.''... A kid ran up to Curtis Strange after the
first round and said: ``Mr. Nicklaus, may I have your
autograph?''... Ernie Els, with wins in 1994 and 1997, had missed
only one cut prior to Friday, in 1995 at Shinnecock.
</P>
<P>
   Angry young men
</P>
<P>
   When Jose Maria Olazabal punched his hotel wall Thursday night,
breaking a bone in his right hand and knocking him out of the
tournament, it prompted inquiries to other players about things
they've done when angry about their games. Said Phil Mickelson, ``I
used to have to buy my clubs if I ever broke them, so I learned not
to break them. I can't imagine trying to break a bone over it, it
doesn't make sense, let alone a club.'' David Duval said, ``I had a
putter about three years ago where I grabbed one end and grabbed
the other and just broke it. It was the putter; it just wasn't
working.''
</P>
<P>
   Pinehurst again?
</P>
<P>
   There is talk of a return to Pinehurst No. 2 for the 2004 U.S.
Open, but Saturday wasn't the ideal day to bring up the subject
after windy conditions made hitting the hardening, crowned greens
even more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be 41 then,'' said Scotland's Colin Montgomerie, who
cherished the 74 he shot Saturday. ``I might have retired.'' Of his
quest to win a major, Montgomerie immediately began looking forward
to the the British Open at Carnoustie next month (he holds the
course record there with a 64) and the PGA Championship at Medinah
in August. ``I'm getting on a bit,'' he said. ``I'll take any of
them now. I'm 36 next week. I'm running out of time. I'm not proud.
I'll take any of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
