<SLUG> BC-GLF-USOPEN20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stewart leads by 1, but pack chasing
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINEHURST, N.C. _ If this sounds familiar, it's understandable.
Payne Stewart has the 54-hole lead in the U.S. Open for the second
straight year.
</P>
<P>
   Sinking a 15-foot birdie putt at the 18th hole Saturday, the
42-year-old Stewart shot a 2-over-par 72 to grab a one-stroke lead
at 1-under-par 209 over Phil Mickelson entering today's final round
at treasured but treacherous Pinehurst No. 2
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson stroked in a 6-foot birdie putt at the 18th hole to
crawl even with Stewart, then watched the 1991 champion sink his
for the sole lead.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, who shot a final-round 74 last year and lost to Lee
Janzen, is the only player under par for the tournament. No. 2
became a nightmarish test Saturday when winds kicked up, making par
not just a good score, but a great one. With greens hardening, it
was commonplace to see chip shots rolling back to one's feet or
approach shots tumbling off the back of the putting surface.
</P>
<P>
   Two strokes back at 1-over 211 are Tiger Woods, who recovered
nicely after a double bogey at the first hole, for a 72; and Tim
Herron, who managed an enviable par 70.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a 75, second-round co-leader David Duval is still in
prime shape, just three shots back at 2-over 212 and tied with
Steve Stricker, whose 69 was the only sub-par round recorded; and
PGA champion Vijay Singh (73).
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been asked many times what the hardest golf course is
that I ever played,'' said Janzen. ``Now I have the answer.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
