<SLUG> BC-GLF-ANDERSON-COLUMN-1STLD-WRITEHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: A COURSE WITH A DIFFERENT FINISH 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: SUBS to update with Saturday's third round.) 
 (lb) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pinehurst, N.C. _ After Lee Janzen trudged off the 18th green
Saturday with a 76 for a 13-over-par total of 223, he put Pinehurst
No. 2 in perspective as well as on a pedestal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been asked many times what's the hardest course I've ever
played,'' Janzen, a two-time U.S. Open champion, said. ``Now I have
an answer.''
</P>
<P>
   So might all the other golfers in this U.S. Open with a
different look. Approach shots scooting off the sloping turtleback
greens into grassy hollows, then the world's best golfers trying to
hit delicate chip shots close to the hole if they are to save par.
</P>
<P>
   But every so often the chip is too delicate or too firm, and the
ball slides back or skids away as if the golfer were playing
miniature golf and had missed the clown's nose.
</P>
<P>
   In most Opens, the look has usually been that of a pro slashing
his ball out of rough deep enough to hide his shoes. Or his ball
plopping into a pond. Or a putt sliding past. But whatever the pros
do or don't do in Sunday's final round, they will create instant
Open lore here in the Sandhills where the pines stand tall.
</P>
<P>
   In other years the Open has usually been blessed with the memory
of what happened before at that year's course. How Jack Nicklaus
won at Baltusrol or Pebble Beach. How Ben Hogan won at Merion or
Oakland Hills. How Bobby Jones won at Winged Foot or Interlachen.
How Arnold Palmer won at Cherry Hills, or how he lost at Olympic.
</P>
<P>
   But however the winner wins in Sunday's final round, it will be
unique to Pinehurst No. 2, no relation to any other Open anywhere
else.
</P>
<P>
   And with two par-3 holes among Pinehurst No. 2's final four
holes, the finish will be different from that on any of the usual
Open courses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is different,'' said Payne Stewart, the 1991 Open champion
at Hazeltine and the runner-up last year at Olympic, referring to
the two short holes. ``Then you've got a par-5, I mean a par-4,
that you play in between those two par-3's.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, who birdied the 18th Saturday for a 72 and 209 to
snatch a one-stroke lead going into Sunday's final round, was
referring to the 489-yard 16th, the longest par-4 in Open history.
</P>
<P>
   ``You stand there on the tee at 15 and 17,'' said Stewart, who
parred both of the par-3's Saturday, ``and you think, `I've got a
par-3, it's going to be easy.' You've still got to hit the shot.''
</P>
<P>
   And each tee shot must be precise. The 15th hole is 202 yards to
a severe turtleback green with two gaping bunkers on the right. The
17th is 191 yards with a somewhat flatter green but with swales
that funnel an imprecise tee shot into any of five surrounding
bunkers _ one to the left, one to the rear right and three on the
front right.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 15th is not easy,'' Tiger Woods said. ``Friday it was
gusty and I ripped a 5-iron and didn't get there. And the 17th is
probably the easiest of the par-3's here because at least you have
some room to hit to.''
</P>
<P>
   Then the dreaded 18th awaits: 446 yards slightly uphill, its
fairway left to right. For other PGA Tour and amateur events here
in the past, the traditional Sunday hole location on the par-4 has
been rear left.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the first round on 18,'' said Stewart, ``I drove it in the
left rough and hit a really good 6-iron out of there and it ran up
on the front of the green and then it came back off the green, like
it's supposed to do. And then I just didn't hit my first putt hard
enough from the collar.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1976 the Atlanta Athletic Club had a similar 3-4-3-4 finish.
With a birdie 2 at the 15th and a birdie 3 at the 18th after a
fabled 5-iron to within 3 feet, Jerry Pate won that Open by two
strokes over Tom Weiskopf and Al Geiberger. In 1909 the Englewood
(N.J.) Golf Club had a 3-4-4-3 finish as George Sargent won by four
strokes.
</P>
<P>
   But that was the Atlanta A.C.'s only Open (as a Bicentennial
favor to the late Bobby Jones) and it's not likely to get another.
Englewood, dug up two decades ago for a condominium complex, never
had another Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to Sunday,'' said David Duval, ``a par on 15 is
going to be very valuable, as well as on 16. But you have more of
an opportunity to make birdie on 17. The 18th is a difficult hole,
but if you hit a good drive, you can access all the difficult pin
positions.''
</P>
<P>
   In Saturday's finish, Mickelson, the left-handed swami of the
short game, bogeyed the 15th, 16th and 17th holes and birdied the
18th, but he thought the two par-3's would favor the leader in
Sunday's finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you have an opportunity to put a 3 on your scorecard,
that's the goal,'' Mickelson said. ``It's going to be very
difficult to make up shots to par on those two holes. Par on those
two short holes will be a good score. If you have to make it up
with the leader, you're going to hope the leader falters rather
than trying to make something happen.''
</P>
<P>
   But whatever happens, it will be a different finish to a
different Open with a different look at Pinehurst No. 2.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
