<HEADLINE>
DESPITE DOUBLE-BOGEY, PAK LEADS GOING INTO FINAL ROUND  
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By   ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABSECON, N.J._ Se Ri Pak has a simple mission for Sunday, the
final day of the ShopRite LPGA Classic. The native of South Korea,
who sprang into prominence in women's golf last season, wants to
win the tournament so she can present her father and coach, Joon
Chul, the trophy as a gift for Father's Day.
</P>
<P>
   The chances of Pak, 21, capturing the $1 million tournament are
fairly good. At 10-under 132, Pak has a two-shot lead after
shooting 69 Saturday afternoon to go with the course and tournament
record of 63 on opening day. Juli Inkster, who won the U.S. Open
two weeks ago, is eight under.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a bad day, and I thought second or third would have been
fine going into the last day,'' Pak said after her round. ``This
was not as easy as yesterday, but I'm hanging in.''
</P>
<P>
   Pak's only blemish Saturday was a double-bogey on the 384-yard
fourth, where she hit three shots off line to the left. It was the
kind of double-bogey that could have devastated her, but she held
herself together and finished the day with four birdies.
</P>
<P>
   Pak, who has no victories this season after winning four times
in her rookie season last year, came very close to making bogey on
the 337-yard 17th, but she saved par by sinking a 25-footer after
she missed the green to the left.
</P>
<P>
   ``That felt like a birdie, if not an eagle,'' Pak said of the
save that gave gave her enough encouragement to finish with a
birdie 4 on the 508-yard 18th.
</P>
<P>
   Inkster shot 68 with birdies on the last three holes. The winner
of three tournaments this season, Inkster's 68 was one of her less
stellar rounds, with seven birdies and four bogeys. ``It was very
sloppy,'' Inkster said after going to the driving range right after
her round. ``I was very fortunate to hit 3-under. If I can make
this my sloppy day, hopefully I'll come out fine tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Trish Johnson (71), Wendy Doolan (66) and Leta Lidley (68) were
tied for third at 135, a stroke behind Inkster. Johnson's round
included two birdies and two bogeys, while Lindley had five birdies
and two bogeys. Doolan had eight birdies and three bogeys.
</P>
<P>
   Annika Sorenstam, last year's winner with a remarkable 17-under
196, was five behind Pak at 137 after shooting a 6-under 65 with
seven birdies for the day's best round.
</P>
<P>
   Sorenstam's 65 came after a 72 on Friday. She said she didn't
know the difference between the two rounds. ``It's golf,'' she
said. ``It's weird. Today, I put the ball on the right side of
things.''
</P>
<P>
   Erica Wicoff had the only ace of the day for her first career
hole-in-one. She used a 4-iron to ace the 177-yard 14th, earning a
Mercury Cougar.
</P>
</TEXT>
