<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-CARDINALS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAY BALL! 4 HOURS AND 372 PITCHES LATER, METS LOSE
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ ``Titanic,'' the movie, seemed like a trailer
compared to this.
</P>
<P>
   It took the Mets and Cardinals 3 hours 56 minutes to finish nine
innings Saturday afternoon, with the Cardinals holding on for a 7-6
victory in the longest nine-inning game the Mets have ever played.
</P>
<P>
   There were 372 pitches thrown, 201 by the Cardinals and 171 by
the Mets. Jason Isringhuasen threw 70 pitches in just two and
two-thirds innings (35 balls and 35 strikes). Darren Oliver, the
St. Louis starter, labored even harder: he threw 121 pitches in
four-plus innings (58 balls, 63 strikes).
</P>
<P>
   There were eight pitchers in the game. There were 25 full
counts.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals took a 3-0 lead in the first inning on Mark
McGwire's 20th home run off Isringhausen (1-2). But even though
they nearly blew leads of 6-1 and 7-2, the Cardinals did not have
to bat in the bottom of the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   And still the game lasted nearly four hours. And the tempo
actually picked up from the sixth inning on.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of like a walk across the desert,'' said Mets
catcher Mike Piazza, who extended his career-best hitting streak to
22 games with a fifth-inning home run. His streak is two games
short of Hubie Brooks's 1984 club record. ``As soon as you see some
water,'' Piazza said, ``it's not there. It's a mirage.''
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the Mets could empathize. They were sure they had
seen the tying run score in the top of the fifth, only to have the
home plate umpire, Charlie Williams, rule Bobby Bonilla out.
Replays seemed to show he was safe.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, many of the Mets privately grumbled about
Williams' inconsistent strike zone, which both helped them and hurt
them, saying it helped lengthen the time of the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets had already scored four runs in the top of the fifth to
pull within 7-6 on Piazza's two-run homer, his 15th of the season,
and Rickey Henderson's bases-loaded, two-run single with two out.
</P>
<P>
   Three batters earlier, Bonilla had worked a walk as a
pinch-hitter to load the bases. With Bonilla now on third and
Henderson on first, St. Louis reliever Manny Aybar quickly got
ahead of Edgardo Alfonzo, one ball and two strikes. Before he threw
another pitch, Aybar faked a move to third, wheeled toward first
and turned to see he had Henderson picked off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was going to go on that pitch,'' said Henderson, who had
homered off Oliver for the Mets' first run.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Henderson had no choice. But Henderson also wanted to get
in a rundown to give Bonilla, who does not run well, a chance to
score. Bonilla waited for Mark McGwire to throw to second baseman
Joe McEwing. And then Bonilla broke for home.
</P>
<P>
   Alberto Castillo, Piazza's former backup with the Mets, was
waiting for the throw. He was also preparing to block the plate.
Castillo is listed at 6 feet and 180 pounds; Bonilla at 6-3 and
240. Castillo, in other words, was giving away at least 60 pounds,
giving new meaning to his nickname, Bambi.
</P>
<P>
   ``Castillo can't stop me, trust me,'' Bonilla said later. ``He
can be standing on a barricade and he's not going to stop me. I
just hope I didn't hurt him.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonilla made his slide left leg first. McEwing's throw beat him.
But Castillo could not block the bigger man from the plate.
Bonilla's leg appeared to reach home well ahead of Castillo's tag.
But Williams ruled him out. And not another run scored the rest of
the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Bobby was safe,'' Henderson said.
</P>
<P>
   So did the rest of the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bobby broke right on time,'' Manager Bobby Valentine said.
``If Bambi was blocking the plate, it looked like Bobby went
through him easily. But it's tough to tell from where I was
sitting.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonilla had a much better view. He exchanged words with Williams
after the call, but would not reveal what he said after the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll say one thing,'' said Bonilla. ``I know I got a good
jump.''
</P>
<P>
   The play would have been less significant had the Mets been more
productive with runners on base. Henderson's hit was the Mets'
first of the game with runners in scoring position in 10 at-bats.
They would only have one more base-runner the rest of the game:
Henderson _ whose two-out double in the eighth gave him four hits
for the day. But Aybar (3-1) induced Alfonzo into a pop-up to first
on a full-count pitch to end the threat. And the Mets went down in
order against Scott Radinsky and Ricky Bottalico in the top of the
ninth.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to say who had a tougher day, Alfonzo, who went 0 for
5 and failed with runners in scoring position three times; or
Isringhausen, who grew up in nearby Brighton, Ill., and allowed six
runs in front of his family. One thing was sure. Isrinhausen's
afternoon was definitely shorter. Alfonzo had to play the whole
thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guarantee you, it seemed like a four-hour game,'' Cardinals
Manager Tony La Russa said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
