u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOREAS-TALKS-BOS &LR;      06-19 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOREAS-TALKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE CLASH, NORTH   AND SOUTH KOREA TO RESUME TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL _ North Korea said Sunday that planned talks on
humanitarian issues with South Korea, their first contact in 14
months, will go forward Monday in Beijing despite last week's naval
gunbattle, the first high seas firefight between the two sides
since the Korean War.
</P>
<P>
   But in a sign of the North's schizophrenic attitude toward the
South, Pyongyang also accused Seoul Saturday of inciting war, and
vowed to retaliate for the 10-minute battle that sank a North
Korean torpedo boat, killing an estimated 30 North Korean sailors
aboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``The exchange of fire was an adventurous act for provocation of
war which the South Korean puppets had planned, prepared in secrecy
and promoted,'' Pyongyang's official Korea Central News Agency
quoted a Navy Command spokesman as saying.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is our quality to answer . . . an all-out war with all-out
war,'' the news agency added. ``There is no limit to our
retaliatory strike at the enemy, and it is merciless.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite that rhetoric, Seoul downgraded its military alert
status Saturday, because Northern ships have kept out of the
disputed waters for four days.
</P>
<P>
   Seoul claims several Northern warships intruded on Southern
waters for nine days straight and finally fired Tuesday. The
standoff apparently began with both sides guarding their fishing
boats in the Yellow Sea's crab-rich waters. South Korea's Ministry
of Defense says its boats tried to bump Northern ships back into
their waters before the Northern side fired.
</P>
<P>
   It was the most serious incident since South Korea sank a
Northern spy vessel last December. That crew was found dead,
apparently of a mass suicide.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides are technically at war, since the 1950-53 Korean
War ended in an armistice. Since 1945, the peninsula has been
divided into Communist North, backed by China, and the South,
supported by the United States. The border is the world's most
militarized, with 2 million troops deployed on the two sides.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, ordinary South Korean seem unfazed by last
Tuesday's clash. Life continued as normal in the capital, and
numerous citizens said they believed their government was inflating
the incident for domestic political and economic reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of us think it's just a big show to divert people's
attention from domestic scandals,'' such as a recent brouhaha
surrouding a couple of Cabinet ministers' wives who each supposedly
accepted $10,000 worth of clothing and furs, said Pyun Ju Hyun, 26,
a customer service representative. ``When I look at CNN,'' the
clash ``looks really serious and deadly, but I think they try to
make it more serious than it is. We here know it's nothing much.''
</P>
<P>
   Park Hyun Jeong, a marketing executive, agreed that ``foreigners
have a tendency to exaggerate the situation here, so some little
struggle which we think is natural at sea, especially among
neighbors . . . gets sensationalized.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Political scandals happen everywhere, including the USA and
England,'' and politicians there have mastered the art of
exploiting foreign policy issues like Iraq or Kosovo to take the
heat of themselves at home, Park asserted. ``Like that, many Korean
politicians utilize the North-South situation at times when they
are weak.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone was so cynical about their government's motives,
but many seemed unconcerned about an escalation of tensions. Mun
Sung Jun, 26, a security guard, said he is relaxed because he
believes the South's military is superior to the North's. ``South
Korea has been victorious in the past, and this time we were again.
North Korea is frightened of South Korea. And we are not afraid of
war.''
</P>
<P>
   If war were to erupt, Mun said he would be proud to fight.
</P>
<P>
   Some older Koreans who lived through the Korean War view the
recent conflict as provocation by the North to force concessions
connected to military deployment or aid. Jack Kim, 60, a defense
contractor who survived General Douglas MacArthur's landing in
Inchon and now lives in Michigan, suggested that ``North Korea is
trying to push the US to the negotiating table'' at the talks in
Beijing or elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's North-South talks were planned to discuss food aid to
the famine-stricken North and the reunification of countless
families separated since the war. The naval clash may shift
attention to security issues, which may be Pyongyang's intention.
The North wants 37,000 US troops out of South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   The United States sent two guided-missile cruisers to Korean
waters from Japan after Tuesday's clash. Pyongyang Saturday
denounced ``the invariable, aggressive nature of the US warhawks
seeking to ignite a war in Korea at any cost,'' according to the
official news agency.
</P>
<P>
   Also Saturday, three North Koreans defected to the South,
government officials said. The Ministry of Foreign Affairs and
Trade said Kim Woo Suk, 38, his wife, Song Ki Sun, 25, and Kim Suk
Hoon, 29, were seeking asylum.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
