<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BASEBALL-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLINS' ANGELS FUTURE BECOMING MORE PRECARIOUS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On the one-year anniversary of the Los Angeles
Dodgers' Sunday Night Massacre, the Anaheim Angels are faced with
how long they can stay with manager Terry Collins.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Dodgers' unfulfilled expectation cost manager
Bill Russell and GM Fred Claire their jobs. Fox hadn't even spent
the big money on Kevin Brown yet, but they knew what they didn't
like. That night, they whacked two 30-year employees and began
reinventing the wheel.
</P>
<P>
   Now it is the Angels' turn.
</P>
<P>
   The owners at Disney went against their frugal nature by signing
Mo Vaughn last winter and expected nothing less than an American
League West title in return.
</P>
<P>
   What they didn't know was that Collins' hyper personality
already had worn out much of the team after just two seasons. When
Gary DiSarcina and Tim Salmon went down with injuries, everyone had
an excuse.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the large egos in baseball, players rarely look in the
mirror.
</P>
<P>
   Collins was an easy target. Citing the aggressiveness that makes
him the player he is, Randy Velarde ripped the manager two weeks
ago for taking away his green light to run with Vaughn at the
plate.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers used to get locked up on the bases for fear of
taking the bat out of Mike Piazza's hands, but this is much
different.
</P>
<P>
   This was a mutiny by players who couldn't get motivated by some
career minor- leaguer who liked to yell. When they heard the Angels
were negotiating to extend Collins' contract they used the only
leverage they have outside the jurisdiction of the Major League
Players Association. The front office doesn't fire the players.
</P>
<P>
   A lot can change in two weeks, but since then the message from
the players has gotten even louder. They've dropped five straight
and 10 of 12. They are 10 games behind Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we keep this up for a week or two, we're going to take on a
spoiler role,'' said Angels left-hander Chuck Finley, after losing
Friday to the Yankees. ``Fifteen games out by the All-Star break?
I've done that too many times.''
</P>
<P>
   Disney made a critical blunder when it allowed Collins' contract
to become a distraction in a season of such high expectation. They
went after Vaughn but allowed Collins' $400,000 salary to become a
bigger issue. Disney had so much hope but didn't understand the
terrain. Collins should have been given the extension well before
the season started. If it worked out they would be in the playoffs.
If it didn't, Collins would get a $400,000 going-away present.
</P>
<P>
   Collins is one of the most decent guys in baseball, but his ilk
appears to be a vanishing breed.
</P>
<P>
   All the years traveling by bus in the Texas League taught him
lessons that would benefit any organization. But players don't want
to know about that night in Midland when he owned the world. They
want to know what it's like batting in the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers are just as pathetic as the Angels right now; maybe
worse because they spent more money to put together an indifferent
team. Their purge a year ago did nothing to improve the situation.
But no one is questioning Davey Johnson. He has a World Series ring
with the Mets and averaged 96 wins a season. He took messy
situations in Cincinnati and Baltimore and made them into playoff
teams.
</P>
<P>
   Collins' lack of major-league experience hurt him in Houston,
where players said he was too uptight. They just didn't want a guy
in their face who hadn't been in their shoes. He was replaced by
low-key Larry Dierker and the Astros took off.
</P>
<P>
   The same was true in New York, where manager Buck Showalter, a
career minor- leaguer, was replaced by the fatherly Joe Torre. Two
World Series titles later, the Yankees are Showalter's team but
Torre's legacy.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, that will be true of Collins, too. Although he never
has finished lower than second as a major-league manager, he never
got the Double-A dirt out of his uniform.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
