</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAIL-RAMPAGE-3600(2ndTake)_TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAIL-RIDING SERIAL KILLER LEAVES TRAIL OF TERROR
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEIMER, Texas:false identification documents. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Presumably riding the rails, he has surfaced in Michigan,
Florida, Vermont, Oklahoma, Missouri, New Mexico and California.
</P>
<P>
   He has been deported at least twice.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what makes me so angry,'' Nancy Strickland, whose
husband, Tom, teaches English at Weimar High School, said in an
interview at her Weimar home. ``They had him so many times and kept
turning him loose.''
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, his travel portfolio includes McAllen, Laredo,
Kountze, Groom, Denton, San Antonio and, of course, tiny Weimar and
metropolitan Houston. It was Houston where the suspect may have
launched his Texas killing spree, investigators say.
</P>
<P>
   XXX &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SHORTLY BEFORE CHRISTMAS 1998, police received a routine
telephone call from employees at Baylor College of Medicine in
Houston. Dr. Claudia Gabriella Benton, 39, had not shown up at
work, and her colleagues were concerned.
</P>
<P>
   Police drove to her home in West University Place, an upscale
municipality surrounded by Houston.
</P>
<P>
   About 4:30 p.m. on Dec. 17, they discovered Benton's body on the
floor of an upstairs bedroom. Her head and upper body were covered
by a blanket.
</P>
<P>
   A bloody butcher knife lay nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Medical examiners determined that the physician had been
sexually assaulted and stabbed but that death apparently occurred
from a blow to the head with a blunt instrument.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband and young twin daughters were out of the state at
the time.
</P>
<P>
   In those grim early hours, nobody noted that the slaying scene
was near the railroad tracks. That would come later, after Benton's
stolen 1996 Jeep Cherokee Sport turned up in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   And after fingerprints linked the brutal slaying of Claudia
Benton to Rafael Resendez-Ramirez.
</P>
<P>
   XXX &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ON MOTHER'S DAY, a week after the bodies of Skip and Karen
Sirnic were discovered, the Rev. Mark Miller of Austin conducted
the Sunday services at Weimar's United Church of Christ as a guest
minister.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dear God, we come to worship in great need,'' Miller said in
an opening prayer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been wounded deeply by the deaths of Skip and Karen.
We hurt. We grieve. We suffer. ... Help us light candles and not
curse the darkness. Oh God, we need you to be with us. Amen.''
</P>
<P>
   The children's sermon that morning was dedicated to Karen
Sirnic. An insert in the church bulletin contained a personal and
poignant message to the slain secretary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Karen,'' it said, ``your love certainly is unending and no one
can take that away from us!''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, investigators had found no trace of the Sirnics'
missing red pickup. But, like Claudia Benton's Jeep, it too would
turn up abandoned in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   And all the while, the people of Weimar coped as best they could
with a mix of fear and grief.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're paranoid and scared to death, and they don't know what
to do anymore,'' Weimar police officer Douglas Blaha said. ``A
preacher and his wife. How could they kill someone with the Lord?
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something that shouldn't be happening in our town.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Weimar Country Grocery, owner Sam Mordence mourned the
community's loss of innocence.
</P>
<P>
   Once open and trusting, often gathering outside in the evenings
to visit, the people of Weimar are too frightened to go out at
night, Mordence said with a trace of anger.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're leery of strangers. They're leery of leaving their
doors open. They're leery of the darkness,'' he said. ``You didn't
see that before.''
</P>
<P>
   A 17-year-old high school senior said his family has put extra
latches on screen doors, changed door locks and, like others in
town, keeps lights turned on all night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's scary,'' he said. ``In a small town like this, you never
expect something like that to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The young man, a starter on the Wildcats football team, quickly
realized that he was being interviewed. Concerned about retaliation
by the killer, he pleaded with the reporter not to use his name.
</P>
<P>
   In Weimar, the level of fear itself was frightening. And it was
about to get worse.
</P>
<P>
   XXX &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ON JUNE 4, Linda Vacek drove out to visit her mother at her
small white farmhouse in Fayette County between Weimar and
Schulenburg, just off I-10 and about three miles from the Sirnics'
home.
</P>
<P>
   Railroad tracks run nearby, but not as close as they were to the
homes of other victims.
</P>
<P>
   There was no reason for alarm. The night before, Vacek had
spoken with her mother, Josephine Konvicka, 73, who had lived alone
since the death of her husband in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   A small dog guarded the home, but it was old and deaf and
couldn't even muster a bark.
</P>
<P>
   Vacek found a scene so gory that neither the family nor
authorities will discuss it in detail.
</P>
<P>
   Fayette County Sheriff Rick Vandel said Konvicka, like the
Sirnics, was attacked in her bedroom and killed by a blow to the
head. Some speculated that the weapon was left embedded in her
head.
</P>
<P>
   She was not sexually assaulted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he had a clue who was in the home when he broke
in,'' Vandel said, theorizing that the intruder expected to find a
younger woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``He killed her for no reason. She was just lying there sleeping
in bed. He could have left without waking her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why did he have to kill her?'' he wondered rhetorically.
</P>
<P>
   The intruder ransacked the house, apparently looking
unsuccessfully for his victim's car keys. Evidence suggests that he
tried to start the car without them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would assume he came off the train,'' the sheriff theorized
in explaining the suspect's frantic efforts to find the keys and
use the car for his getaway.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could not see the victim's house from the tracks. He just
walked through the woods until he came to the house. There were no
barking dogs. No lights. No sounds from the house.''
</P>
<P>
   As before, the killer gained entry through the rear.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just took the screen off and raised the window,'' Vandel
said. ``He used a weapon he got from the location. I think it was
outside the house. It's not the type of thing you'd have in the
house.''
</P>
<P>
   The sheriff, who spent 24 years with the Houston Police
Department, 20 of them as a solo motorcycle cop, does not
camouflage his distaste for the man known as Rafael
Resendez-Ramirez.
</P>
<P>
   ``This county is filled with good, honest, hard-working,
God-fearing German and Czech folks who live a law-abiding
lifestyle,'' Vandel said. ``We're a rural area. We don't lock our
doors. We don't look over our shoulders. We leave our keys in the
car. He's changed all that.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only are people fearful in Weimar, but also in Schulenburg
and Flatonia, both of which lie in his county. MORE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
