<HEADER>
A2232 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAIL-RAMPAGE-3600(3ed     06-19 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAIL-RAMPAGE-3600(3edTake)_TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAIL-RIDING SERIAL KILLER LEAVES TRAIL OF TERROR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEIMAR, Texas: in his county. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``There's the same fear and mood there also,'' he said.
``Actually, there are more trains going through Flatonia, because
they break off going north and south.''
</P>
<P>
   What really worries him, the sheriff says, is that the killer is
getting more aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's terribly scary that he might jump on a train and come
back to my county and do another crime,'' he said. But Vandel says
authorities will eventually catch Resendez-Ramirez and kill him _
legally.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a textbook case for the death penalty,'' he growled.
``This individual does not deserve to live.''
</P>
<P>
   XXX &QL;
</P>
<P>
   IN ANOTHER STRANGE and cruel twist, a Houston woman named Noemi
Dominguez may have been raped and killed because the killer could
not find Josephine Konvicka's car keys.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI says the body of the 26-year-old was found by her
brother in the bedroom of her home when she did not show up for a
family function in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Her 1993 white Honda Civic was missing.
</P>
<P>
   Although the time of death is uncertain, her body was discovered
June 5, a Saturday, one day after investigators learned of the
Konvicka slaying near Weimar.
</P>
<P>
   Officers speculated that the killer, without transportation,
abandoned his routine of using a victim's stolen car to return to
San Antonio. Instead, he hopped an eastbound freight train near
Weimar, got off in Houston and resumed his predatory search.
</P>
<P>
   Like the others, Dominguez lived and died near a rail line.
</P>
<P>
   And although she was sexually assaulted and killed by a blow to
the head, her slaying was not tied at once to the elusive
Resendez-Ramirez. But her car turned up days later in Del Rio near
the International Bridge leading into Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   And fingerprints found in the car matched those of the suspect.
</P>
<P>
   By the weekend, the FBI had forensic evidence linking
Resendez-Ramirez to the Sirnic and Konvicka killings and both
Houston slayings. But the case had taken a new and even more
ominous turn. The bodies of George Morber, 80, and his daughter,
Carolyn Frederick, 52, were discovered Tuesday in their home in
Gorham, Ill., about 100 yards from a rail line. What's more, a
truck missing from the scene was found the next day in Cairo, about
60 miles south of Gorham.
</P>
<P>
   Details of the deaths in southern Illinois were sketchy, but
because of similarities to the Texas cases, Illinois authorities
requested the fingerprints of the prime Texas suspect.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Rangers and FBI agents headed to Illinois at once with
their data on Resendez-Ramirez. Mike Cox, a Department of Public
Safety spokesman in Austin, said Rangers have also been in Mexico
to gather information about Resendez-Ramirez, The Associated Press
reported.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's everywhere and nowhere _ he has no roots,'' Tom Vinger,
another spokesman for the Department of Public Safety, told the AP.
``But he knows we're looking for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game is on.''
</P>
<P>
   WELL, NOT EXACTLY.
</P>
<P>
   In Weimar, Mayor Bennie Kosler says that about 20 trains roll
through town every 24 hours and that people can't help but wonder,
after the second episode: ``Is he on this train?''
</P>
<P>
   Police have doubled their nighttime patrols, and Kosler says
that overtime is not a concern until they ``catch this maniac.''
</P>
<P>
   As bad as it is, he said, it was ``kind of a relief to know it
wasn't someone from our area. I hoped we didn't have someone that
sick and that mean.''
</P>
<P>
   In a coffee shop that bears his name, but which he recently
sold, the mayor revealed a facet of the case that police have not
confirmed or discussed. He says that ``30-some-odd dollars was
lying on top of the dresser'' in the bedroom where the Sirnics were
slain.
</P>
<P>
   The implication is that the intruder is so obsessed with killing
and sexual gratification that he ignores money at his fingertips.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what's so weird,'' Kosler says. ``I guess he just
wanted to kill.''
</P>
<P>
   No one in Weimar, including law enforcement officers, appears
convinced that the killer crossed over into Mexico because the
Dominguez car was found in Del Rio.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until they catch him, we're going to think he's around,
because he is,'' says Larry Wick, owner of M-G Farm Service Center.
</P>
<P>
   Despite stories to the contrary, Wick says that the run on
handguns continues, but that they've never run out.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a normal week, we'll sell one or two handguns,'' he said.
``We've sold 40 or 50. We've sold some shotguns and some rifles.
And I've got some more coming.''
</P>
<P>
   Sales are also swift for Mace and pepper gas.
</P>
<P>
   At the United Church of Christ, Ralph Ludwig, the interim
pastor, suggests that the deaths of the Sirnics and others have
taken a tremendous emotional toll.
</P>
<P>
   ``What it's done to the community is chilling,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   For people like Larry Wick, there is no end in sight. Or sound.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hear a train whistle blow,'' he says with a sad smile,
``and you start thinking about it all over again.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
