<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-19 21:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2233 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAIL-RAMPAGE-3600(3Ta     06-19 1124
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAIL-RAMPAGE-3600(3Takes)_TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAIL-RIDING SERIAL KILLER LEAVES TRAIL OF TERROR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE COCHRAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEIMAR, Texas _ In the dead of night, police believe, he
scrambled from a passing freight train and slipped alone and unseen
into this peaceful little ranching community in the coastal savanna
of Southeast Texas.
</P>
<P>
   He came to rape and kill, and, as before, he chose his victims
randomly.
</P>
<P>
   Creeping through a darkened carport, he removed a weapon from a
tool cabinet. He pried open a window, unlocked a rear door, found
the bedroom where his targets lay sleeping and attacked with
horrendous fury.
</P>
<P>
   It is unlikely that the couple saw the snake tattooed on his
left forearm.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday morning, May 2, a parishioner at Weimar's United
Church of Christ discovered the bodies of the minister and the
church secretary, Norman ``Skip'' Sirnic and his wife, Karen.
</P>
<P>
   The popular couple had been bludgeoned to death with a hammer.
</P>
<P>
   In an attempt to restore calm to the terrified town,
investigators assured heartbroken residents that the killer was
most likely an outsider and that he probably would not return.
</P>
<P>
   They were half right.
</P>
<P>
   The slayings of Skip and Karen Sirnic and the subsequent
revelations about a maniacal serial killer sent residents scurrying
for guns, ammunition, dogs and a wide range of security devices.
</P>
<P>
   Weeks passed. Then, in early June, the unthinkable occurred.
</P>
<P>
   Again under cover of darkness, the killer returned. He broke
into the small farmhouse of a 73-year-old widow and killed her with
a blow to the head as she slept.
</P>
<P>
   Her home was three miles from the Sirnics' and, like the Sirnic
house, near railroad tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Even as Weimar residents recoiled from the latest violence, the
body of a young woman was discovered June 5 in her Houston home.
She had been sexually assaulted and beaten to death.
</P>
<P>
   The crime was not immediately linked to the Weimar killings. But
it did fit the chilling pattern and emerging profile of a suspect
in earlier sex slayings in Houston and Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   A common thread: Each crime occurred not far from railroad
tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Within days, the FBI formed a multiagency task force to share
the fruits of their investigative efforts and track down a suspect
as elusive and deranged as he is cunning and vicious.
</P>
<P>
   They identified him as a 39-year-old Mexican national and
branded him a rail-hopping, ``thrill-killing'' drifter motivated
more by sexual deviancy than money.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no idea what he might do, and we cannot project where
he might go. ... But I think his free time is limited,'' Weimar
Police Chief Bill Livingston told a Star-Telegram reporter at
midweek. ``There are too many good cops looking for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Barely 24 hours later, officers stopped a freight train in
Central Texas and arrested five men, one considered a suspect
because of a snake tattooed on his forearm.
</P>
<P>
   It was on the wrong arm.
</P>
<P>
   XXX &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WEIMAR EMBRACES a population of 2,050 in Colorado County and
lies along Interstate 10 and U.S. 90 between San Antonio and
Houston in Southeast Texas. The Texas capital, Austin, is little
more than an hour's drive northwest.
</P>
<P>
   One of the state's top 10 calf producers, Colorado County
derives its name from the river that winds down from Austin en
route to Matagorda Bay on the Texas Gulf Coast.
</P>
<P>
   It is a lush green expanse dotted with small, private lakes and
wooded areas that provide food and shelter for deer, doves, ducks,
geese and turkeys.
</P>
<P>
   Weimar is home to large families of Czech and German ancestry,
and its agriculture and light industry are enhanced by a booming
sausage business.
</P>
<P>
   It is a place for Special Living, proclaims the town's slogan.
</P>
<P>
   That changed overnight with the grisly discovery in the
parsonage of United Church of Christ on May 2, a Sunday. That was
also Skip Sirnic's 47th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   XXX &QL;
</P>
<P>
   IT WAS PAST midnight on a summer evening in 1997 when a
20-year-old woman, covered in blood, staggered to a student's house
near the University of Kentucky campus in Lexington. Her face was
swollen, her jaw fractured, her head and neck cut. She had been
beaten so severely that she could barely open her mouth.
</P>
<P>
   ``He beat me up,'' she mumbled. ``He beat me up.''
</P>
<P>
   Chad Goetz told The Courier-Journal in Louisville that the young
woman pointed out into the darkness and said, ``My friend's down
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Summoned by Goetz, police arrived and found the bound body of
Christopher Maier, 21, a student and Phi Kappa Psi fraternity
member from North Canton, Ohio. He had been beaten to death. His
date, also a student, told them that a man in his 20s had emerged
from the darkness and attacked them. He struck Maier with a board
or rock, then tied his hands and feet with a cord.
</P>
<P>
   Before killing Maier, he raped and beat the young woman and left
her for dead.
</P>
<P>
   Police soon learned that the Aug. 29, 1997, attack occurred as
the couple walked from one party to another. They had taken a
shortcut popular with university students.
</P>
<P>
   The shortcut took them along the railroad tracks.
</P>
<P>
   XXX &QL;
</P>
<P>
   IN ONE SENSE, the deadly saga dates back to Aug. 31, 1976, when
a teen-ager from Puebla, Mexico, entered the United States at
Brownsville, the southern tip of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   According to FBI records obtained by the Star-Telegram, that was
the first recorded appearance in this country of the man known
today as Rafael Resendez-Ramirez. It is but one of many names or
aliases he has used during two decades of nonviolent brushes with
the law.
</P>
<P>
   Despite more than three dozen notations in the FBI's criminal
history, little is known about the suspect.
</P>
<P>
   Wanted posters showing five of the many faces of
Resendez-Ramirez decorate virtually every shop, convenience store,
office building and service station on Weimar's main streets.
Police say he changes his appearance at will.
</P>
<P>
   Resendez-Ramirez is named in a Harris County burglary indictment
and charged by the federal government with unlawful flight to avoid
prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   He has been linked by forensic evidence to five beating deaths
in Texas and the one in Kentucky. He is also a suspect in several
other killings.
</P>
<P>
   Rewards total at least $60,000.
</P>
<P>
   The suspect's criminal repertoire includes burglary, car theft,
aggravated assault, battery, trespassing on railroad property,
false representation as a U.S. citizen, illegal re-entry,
defrauding an innkeeper, illegal possession of a concealed weapon,
false statements to a federal officer, possession of a firearm by a
felon, and possession of false identification documents. MORE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
