<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-19 21:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2236 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-2TAKES-1     06-19 1448
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-2TAKES-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSTON JUGGLES RATTLES AND THE SPURS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: In Nets' item, corrects Van Gundy's agent to Rob Ades, sted
Rod.) 
(bl)  
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Allan Houston's main chore in the last week has been figuring
out how to shake free from Mario Elie, the relentless San Antonio
swingman who keeps tugging at Houston's jersey and his confidence.
The playoffs being about adjustments, it is easily the
second-toughest job the Knicks' shooting guard has this
post-season.
</P>
<P>
   The first: 2 a.m. feedings.
</P>
<P>
   After a week without being with his newborn daughter, Remi-Jean,
Houston was planning to celebrate his first Father's Day in his
Greenwich, Conn., home on Sunday with his wife, Tamara, and their
first child.
</P>
<P>
   It will probably not have a tremendous impact on his performance
in the National Basketball Association finals or help him cope with
Elie and the Spurs any better than he and Knicks already have
through two games.
</P>
<P>
   But it has helped him further strike a balance between his
professional and personal life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like when you first get married and you have to go on the
road, that's kind of an adjustment,'' Houston said. ``But then,
when you have a baby, and then you go on the road to the NBA
finals, that's like, you've just got a lot of stuff going on in
your mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston telephoned home often in the last week, usually getting
the standard response: ``I'm feeding her. I'll call you back.''
</P>
<P>
   Remi-Jean was born the day after Houston's phenomenal Game 6
performance against Indiana _ a game Tamara attended before labor
was induced the next day. Before Game 2 against San Antonio, he was
looking forward to the reunion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe someone went out and got her a Knicks uniform,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the emotions he felt watching his daughter being
born, he added: ``To be honest, I don't know what in the world I
was feeling. It's an emotion that I had never experienced before.
Obviously, joy was a lot of it. But it is different.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to my sister last night, and I said, `You better call
me on Father's Day.' And she was like, `Man, that sounds funny.'''
</P>
<P>
   Allan Houston, new father. Kind of takes the sting away from
those 7-for-17 nights, no?
</P>
<P>
   The Don Nelson Connection
</P>
<P>
   Aside from his messy divorces with the Knicks and Golden State,
Don Nelson is credited with being one of the game's modern-day
innovators, a man who would put a 7-foot-6-inch center behind the
3-point line if he thought it would help his team's chance of
winning.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson presided over very good teams in Milwaukee and lackluster
teams in the Bay Area before contentious power struggles with Chris
Webber and Patrick Ewing tarnished his career.
</P>
<P>
   But Nelson has never got to the NBA finals as a coach. Even so,
as perhaps the only connecting thread between Jeff Van Gundy and
Gregg Popovich, he is not envious that two of his former unheralded
assistants got the opportunity this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``They deserve it,'' Nelson said from his home in Dallas, where
he serves as the Mavericks' coach and general manager. ``They're
the kind of guys you wouldn't mind being in a fox hole with. Pop is
a little more military than Jeff, but there are a lot of
similarities.''
</P>
<P>
   The most obvious is that neither Van Gundy nor Popovich played
in the league, and therefore had to work harder to gain respect
among their players than many coaches. They have also been on the
firing line recently, with Popovich's job in question after the
Spurs' 6-8 start and Van Gundy weathering two attempts made at
relieving him of his duties during the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   But, as Nelson points out, the largest common denominator may be
their knack for getting emotional about their relationships with
their peers. In the macho culture of the NBA, Van Gundy and
Popovich have no trouble expressing their sentimentality.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson is closer to Popovich, having worked with him for four
seasons at Golden State. But Van Gundy also endeared himself to
Nelson during the 59 games he coached in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The day Nelson was fired by the Knicks in March 1996, the first
person to console him in his Philadelphia hotel room was Van Gundy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't crying, but Jeff came to my room in tears,'' Nelson
said. ``I felt worse for him than I did for myself.
</P>
<P>
   ``We became pretty close,'' he added. ``I really appreciated
that he and Don Chaney would come up to my room to spend some
quality time with me that day. That's the kind of people they
are.''
</P>
<P>
   Popovich became the victim of one of Nelson's greatest pranks
while they were with the Warriors.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing that Popovich was an art lover, Nelson procured a
portrait of an American Indian from an artist Popovich once coached
with at the Air Force Academy. The artist did not charge Nelson for
the painting, but instead gave it to him as a gift for Popovich's
birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson then took the painting to the owner of an art gallery he
knew in San Francisco. He had the gallery owner mount and display
the painting for $25,000, then brought Popovich into the gallery
with the other coaches after a lunch at Fisherman's Wharf.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said to him, `Hey, Pop, isn't this the guy you used to work
with?''' Nelson said. ``And he just went wild. `That's him! That's
him!' I said, `Why don't you buy it?' He said, `Oh, no, I can't
afford that.' I told my friend to put it on my bill and wrap it
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson and the assistant coaches, who were in on the gag, were
about to break the news to Popovich when he suddenly got emotional.
</P>
<P>
   ``He starts bawling,'' Nelson said. ``He says: `I can't believe
you guys did this for me, a $25,000 piece of art painted by this
guy I know. This is really something.' At that point, we're all
feeling bad. We got him hooked in so good. That's probably as good
as I ever hooked anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-2NDTAKE-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: hooked anybody.'' &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Why Are the Nets Stalling?
</P>
<P>
   The Nets have not yet asked the Knicks for permission to speak
with Jeff Van Gundy about becoming New Jersey's next head coach,
and who knows if the team will. Any attempt to sway Van Gundy
toward the Meadowlands would most likely involve a concession of
draft picks and cash shipped to the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   But the longer the Nets go without hiring the interim coach Don
Casey on a permanent basis, the more they are open to speculation
that the club is merely waiting to see what happens with Van
Gundy's future. What must Casey be feeling?
</P>
<P>
   The Nets have already offered Phil Jackson a reported $21
million for three seasons, an offer turned town three weeks ago by
Jackson's agent. Rumors of Mike Fratello's returning to his
Hackensack roots are also circulating.
</P>
<P>
   If Nets owner Lewis Katz continues to bide his time with the
interim coach, one wonders if Van Gundy's shadow is going to become
as ominous to Casey's future as Jackson's shadow once was to Van
Gundy's.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, Van Gundy's agent, Rob Ades, has been Casey's
personal friend and lawyer for 30 years. If Van Gundy was in the
running, the first thing he would have to do is pick up the phone
and make a courtesy call to Casey, who in turn would finally
realize the truth about his once-noble profession: coaching is now
an incestuous, shady, off-season business in which people respect
their peers while trying to make sure they first cut the best deal
for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Evaluating the Front Office
</P>
<P>
   After all the early season criticism, it is now clear that the
deposed general manager Ernie Grunfeld and Madison Square Garden
president Dave Checketts made some hard but ultimately wise
decisions when it came to trading away aging veterans in the off
season for an infusion of young talent.
</P>
<P>
   Two months after Latrell Sprewell and Marcus Camby were on the
verge of being declared busts, it is hard to say that they are
long-term cures for the franchise's future. But without them, the
Knicks do not embark on this nice little post-season run.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, one wonders how different the Knicks would look in the
championship round with a decent big man coming off the bench. Herb
Williams has been invaluable to the locker room this season during
troubled times and it is admirable that the club has shown that
kind of loyalty to the NBA's elder statesmen, but it is hard to
envision him being a 20-minute role player at age 41.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing can be done about Charles Oakley, whom the Knicks needed
to move to get Camby. Or Buck Williams, who retired, and Terry
Cummings, who was trade bait for Sprewell. But somewhere, anywhere,
the Knicks could have used a body for the stretch run. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
