<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-WHITT-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S JUST A MATTER OF TIME FOR THE SPURS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Madison Square Garden may be the hallowed Mecca of
basketball, but making the Spurs travel 1,865 miles just to pick up
their NBA championship trophy there seems a little silly.
</P>
<P>
   On a record roll strengthened by 12- and 13-point victories over
the punchless Knicks in Games 1 and 2, the question for the Spurs
now is not whether they will win their first title, just when.
</P>
<P>
   Not since 1987 has a team won the first two games of the Finals
by double digits. That Lakers team, led by Magic Johnson and Kareem
Abdul-Jabbar, whipped the Celtics by 13 and 19 en route to a 4-2
series victory.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to imagine the hobbling Knicks denting San Antonio's
armor. Since Sean Elliott's Memorial Day Miracle to beat the
Blazers in the West finals, the Spurs have steamrolled to their
past four victories by an average of 15.2 points and can climax the
NBA's best-ever playoff run at 15-1 with a sweep.
</P>
<P>
   And now, the really bad news for New York:
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a better, more focused team on the road,'' said San
Antonio guard Mario Elie, whose team takes a commanding 2-0 lead in
the series and a 6-0 road playoff record into tomorrow night's Game
3. ``From an intensity standpoint, we've got to keep grinding. But
from X's and O's, we're in good shape. We've got them looking
around a little confused.''
</P>
<P>
   After their anemic offensive performances in the first two
games, the overmatched Knicks will have to be sneakier than a
Chinese spy and Bobby Valentine combined to steal even one game
against a clearly superior opponent. San Antonio has handcuffed New
York's transition offense into a half-court disaster that is
painful to watch, putting the Knicks on pace to obliterate the
Finals record for fewest points in a four-game series. The
Baltimore Bullets scored 376 in a four-game loss to the Milwaukee
Bucks in 1971. Through two games, the Knicks have 144.
</P>
<P>
   New York's scrambling energy is creating 82 shots per game to
San Antonio's 65, but starting big men Chris Dudley and Larry
Johnson are a combined 3-of-20, leading scorer Latrell Sprewell is
17-of-46 and the Knicks have more turnovers (28) than assists (20).
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to find a way to score against these guys,'' said
forward Kurt Thomas, ``or those screaming fans will be right.''
</P>
<P>
   Knowing the Spurs have won a record 12 consecutive playoff games
and that no team since 1977 has rallied from an 0-2 deficit to win
the title, The Alamodome's almost 40,000 fans erupted in chants of
``Sweep, sweep'' late in Game 2. Best and worst
</P>
<P>
   Best strategy: While the Knicks' Sprewell and Marcus Camby tried
to interlock arms in front of him during a free throw, Tim Duncan
played Red Rover and broke through for a crucial offensive rebound
putback that pushed the Spurs' lead from five to seven in the final
2.5 seconds of the third quarter of Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   Worst strategy: The Knicks' decision to attack the rim early
totally backfired in Game 2. They had four shots blocked, but the
Spurs were called for no fouls in the first quarter, and only had a
Finals record-low 13 fouls in the game. Numbers game 1: Times
during their Texas 12-step that the Spurs have allowed more than 91
points.
</P>
<P>
   4: Quarters of 15 points or less for the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   117: Total number of points the Knicks have scored in the past
seven quarters. 24 seconds
</P>
<P>
   Duncan is averaging 29 points and 15.5 rebounds, but he has a
ways to go to catch the Finals records of 41 points per game by
Michael Jordan in '93 and Bill Russell's 29.5 rebounds per game in
'59. ... Since a 92-86 loss to the Mavericks at Reunion Arena on
April 13, the Spurs are 23-2. ... How lopsided is this Finals? The
Spurs are shooting 45 percent from the field, 65 percent from the
free-throw line, have yet to break 90 and have trailed for only
four minutes.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
