<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-19 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2249 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEX-BULLOCK-COX     06-19 1332
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEX-BULLOCK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bob Bullock, lieutenant governor, average Joe
 &HT;    By Mike Ward
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The eggs and bacon were frying, the hotcakes
bubbling. Gus Vayas was busy at the grill Saturday, just as he has
been most others during the 20 years he has been the proprietor of
the G-M Steakhouse Breakfast Luncheonette at 624 N. Lamar Blvd.
</P>
<P>
   But the back table, a two-seater with the red-checked
tablecloth, was empty. Bob Bullock, its steady occupant on
Wednesdays and Saturdays for the past four years, died Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a great Texan and my friend,'' lamented Vayas, 56, as
he flipped hash browns onto a plate. ``Bacon and eggs, extra bacon,
three eggs over easy and coffee. He had the same thing every time.
I started it when I saw his car drive up.''
</P>
<P>
   Vayas and other customers at the rail-thin diner featured in the
cult movie ``Slacker'' remembered Bullock for his easy-going,
average-citizen demeanor, as a guy who chatted about the weather
and news events, but never politics _ even though he was one of the
most powerful men in Texas politics, the lieutenant governor.
</P>
<P>
   He once told a reporter he liked Vayas' place because he could
smoke at the table if he wanted to, something not allowed anymore
at most Austin restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Vayas proudly pointed to a wall near the cash register, where an
autographed photo of Bullock hangs beside an official proclamation
designating his eatery ``the official restaurant of the Senate of
Texas'' _ both gifts from Bullock.
</P>
<P>
   Bullock last stopped by about a week ago, Vayas said. Though he
seemed thinner and frail, having just left the hospital a day
earlier, an outgoing Bullock greeted and shook hands as always.
``You're a great Texan. I love Texas,'' he would say.
</P>
<P>
   And as always, he ``wasn't like the other politicians who get
their nose up in the air. He was just like me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I get up at 5 o'clock every morning . . . and work until 9 at
night, every day, seven days a week,'' Vayas said. ``I like to work
hard. (Bullock) liked to work hard. He was a common man. He loved
people. And people liked him.''
</P>
<P>
   It will be with sadness at the passing of a friend that Vayas
plans to attend his friend's funeral today, ``even if I have to
close up.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Turning slowly on her heels, Arlington resident Deanna Hannerly
scanned the portraits on the walls in the Capitol Rotunda. And then
scowled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where is he?'' she asked Saturday morning, while touring the
statehouse with her daughter and three grandchildren. ``Bob
Bullock's not here?''
</P>
<P>
   Paintings of Texas' chief executives hang here, and Bob Bullock
was only a lieutenant governor, she was told, and surprise flashed
across her face. ``I thought he was governor,'' said Hannerly, 66.
``Well, he ran Texas like he was. And he did a good job at it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He should've been governor. He was a real leader,'' remarked a
nearby kibitzer. ``He was the Average Joe, just like us. Not like
the rest of these fancy politicians up here.''
</P>
<P>
   Several other tourists in the seat of state government Bullock
called home for so many years nodded in agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Such was the reaction Saturday from Capitol tourists _ some of
whom had once met Bullock, most of whom had not, all of whom said
they felt like they knew him well.
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio retiree Sam Herrera, 59, explained it this way: ``I
only met him once, about 20 years ago. He shook my hand when he was
campaigning. But I voted for him every time because he did what he
said he would. He kept his promises.''
</P>
<P>
   In crisp detail, Herrera recalled almost every word of the brief
exchange he had with Bullock, in the middle of a steamy day outside
a cafe in Harlingen, near where Herrera grew up and where Bullock
had briefly worked as a lawyer years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``He shook my hand, told me he needed my help to make Texas a
better place, to help him make sure the tax money was spent
better,'' Herrera said. ``Ever since I always thought of him that
way. He was for the little guys of the world like me.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the public Bullock, the demanding, cajoling
workaholic whom everyone at the Capitol seemed to know or fear,
there was a private man, several friends said.
</P>
<P>
   Glen Castlebury, who worked for Bullock from 1974 until 1994,
from speechwriter at the comptroller's office to the chief of
correspondence in the lieutenant governor's, explains:
</P>
<P>
   ``His personal generosity has been his life's secret. It did not
matter, employee or friend, if he knew you needed help, he was
there. Over the years, I have seen him help with money for
medicine, help them if their kid got in trouble with the law, help
people who got in financial trouble _ $25 or $50, nothing big _ but
he was always willing to help.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you needed a push for a job, if you needed moral support
and he knew about it, he was there.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big people usually didn't need any help. This is where he
really helped the little guy, and never asked for anything in
return.''
</P>
<P>
   When Bullock first came to Austin in 1950 or 1951, he was a
little guy.
</P>
<P>
   As he explained during a 1994 interview, Bullock's first state
job was working as a go-fer in the Railroad Commission's mailroom _
while he attended the University of Texas for a semester, majoring
in architecture. ``You couldn't get much lower than the loading
dock,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Other signs of Bullock's connection to average Texans might be
in the hundreds, possibly thousands, of state employees who once
worked for him, alumni who are now scattered through most state
agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Like Harry Bradley, 56, superintendent at the State Cemetery,
where Bullock is to be buried today.
</P>
<P>
   After an 11-year career at various state agencies, Bradley
volunteered in Bullock's 1990 campaign for lieutenant governor,
then joined the General Services Commission. When Bullock prodded
state officials to restore the run-down cemetery, Bradley said he
was picked ``because it was Bullock's project, and I'd worked for
Bullock. I've known him and his people for 20 years.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bullock influenced state government because of the way he
influenced people . . . by raising the bar so high that only the
best job was acceptable,'' Bradley said. ``He and (legendary
football coach) Vince Lombardi were carbon copies: hard
disciplinarians, tough but the most compassionate people in the
world. And you loved working for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps those connections could be seen best in the infamous
file of hundreds of thousands of index cards that Bullock
established in 1966 to help then-Lt. Gov. Preston Smith run for
governor. The cards got Bullock in trouble in 1975 when reporters
questioned why state employees were being used to maintain them.
</P>
<P>
   Each card listed a name, address, phone number and other
information such as campaign contributions _ a level of detail that
made Bullock famous.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could get a total picture of people on those cards,'' said
Castlebury, now the chief spokesman for Texas' prison system.
``Most of those cards represented average Texans, and to the extent
that Bullock brought about better government services, the little
guy was better served.''
</P>
<P>
   But just as Vayas and the Capitol tourists remembered Bullock on
Saturday more as a common Texan like themselves, not as the
well-to-do politician he was, other friends said he truly never
lost touch with his humble roots in Hillsboro _ or the naive young
man visiting the State Capitol for the first time who took off his
shoes and promptly got a splinter in his foot from the wooden
floors.
</P>
<P>
   Bullock could joke about the different world in which he lived.
</P>
<P>
   Asked once what he thought of a reception for the visiting Queen
of England, Bullock laughed and remarked about the fancy food that
was served.
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably would've been just as happy with a foot-long
chilidog from Sonic,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
