<DOCNO> NYT19990619.0266 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-19 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2251 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEX-BULLOCK-FUNERAL-C     06-19 1154
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEX-BULLOCK-FUNERAL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Former Texas lieutenant governor to be buried today
 &HT;    By Christian Davenport
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ On top of Republic Hill, where live oaks and
cedars provide shade for the state's fallen warriors and most noble
politicians, Bob Bullock will be buried today in the cemetery he
rescued from neglect.
</P>
<P>
   Bullock, one of the most powerful forces in Texas politics for
the past 25 years, will take his place behind Stephen F. Austin,
who organized the first Anglo settlement in Texas and became known
as the state's father.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas State Cemetery, home to 11 governors, two
Revolutionary War veterans and 64 Republic of Texas veterans, is
the state's foremost shrine to its dignitaries and a popular
tourist attraction and educational institution. For Bullock, the
former lieutenant governor who died Friday at 69, it was a beloved
oasis away from the rigors of the Capitol. He often sought refuge
in its pastoral landscape, strolling and ruminating in peace and
allowing the names etched on tombstones to spark memory and inspire
stories.
</P>
<P>
   Bullock's grave is on top of Republic Hill, the most prestigious
area in a cemetery that requires its entombed to have been elected
to the state legislature or to ``have made a significant
contribution to Texas culture and history as determined by the
State Cemetery Committee.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He felt this was hallowed ground,'' said Bullock's longtime
friend Ralph Wayne, the head of the Texas Civil Justice League and
a former state senator from Plainview. ``He is in heaven, but his
remains are here. And he wouldn't want them anywhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   Bullock will be buried directly between Edward Burleson, who
died in 1851 and was the first ever to be buried at Texas State
Cemetery, and Stephen Williams, who fought in the Revolutionary
War, the War of 1812 and the Siege of Bexar.
</P>
<P>
   Friday afternoon, as the teeth of the backhoe began digging
Bullock's grave, it was Wayne's turn to reminisce about the most
recent Texas legend to pass away.
</P>
<P>
   He was with Bullock on Tuesday. When he asked if Bullock was
breathing all right, Bullock, in his typical tough-guy fashion,
ignored the question and asked about Wayne's wife and child.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, 'Give them a hug for me,''' Wayne recalled. ``Can you
believe that? Here he is with an oxygen mask on his face and he's
thinking about others. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be a lot of people here Sunday,'' Wayne continued.
``But that's only the beginning. They'll be coming for weeks and
months after that to say goodbye privately. He just touched so many
people.''
</P>
<P>
   As mourners make their way to his grave, they'll pass some of
the great protagonists in state history.
</P>
<P>
   Bullock, who governed as he lived _ with gusto and heart _ will
be among the tombs of a lawyer who took on the Ku Klux Klan (Dan
Moody), a U.S. senator (Ralph Yarborough), the woman who designed
and made the first Texas Lone Star flag (Joanna Troutman) and the
first black woman from the south elected to Congress (Barbara
Jordan).
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids can come out here and, in one day, learn more about Texas
history than in a whole semester of class,'' Bullock once said.
</P>
<P>
   Today, thousands of school children each year participate in a
history program at the cemetery, 909 Navasota St.
</P>
<P>
   That was his wish.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob Bullock told me I had to do two things out here,'' said
Harry Bradley, the cemetery's superintendent, who also worked on
Bullock's campaigns. ``He told me to be helpful to people and give
guided history tours of this place.''
</P>
<P>
   Just over two weeks ago, Bullock visited the cemetery and _ as
he had countless times before _ he ``walked around, talking about
this guy buried over here, that guy buried over there,'' Bradley
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was big on Texas history. And there's a lot of history out
here.''
</P>
<P>
   And Bullock, ever mindful of detail, was just as likely to
mention that the grass needed to be mowed or a fence mended or
litter picked up on the cemetery grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Bullock, who was accompanied by his wife, Jan, during that
visit, ``was walking a little slower,'' but he spent more than two
hours reminiscing in what will become his final resting place,
Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   His affinity for the cemetery became public four years ago when
he prodded state officials into a $4.7 million renovation project
that began in 1994. But the cemetery, which had begun to show its
age, had been a long-running interest.
</P>
<P>
   Glen Castlebury, a former Bullock aide who is chief spokesman
for Texas' prison system, said Bullock was making frequent
late-afternoon treks to the cemetery in the 1960s to talk history.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was one of his favorite deals,'' recalled Castlebury,
then a reporter for the Austin American-Statesman. ``He'd call and
say, ``Let's go get a beer,' and we'd grab a hamburger and a
six-pack and go to the cemetery, to picnic tables on the west side.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knew great stories about a lot of the people buried out
there. ... He was a great storyteller.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as he departed Bullock's staff in 1994, Bullock had orders
for the cemetery: ``I was on my way out the door. He told me he
wanted me to find some way to have inmates work out there. And
that's exactly the message I conveyed to (then-prisons director)
Andy Collins.
</P>
<P>
   ``It got done.''
</P>
<P>
   While Bullock said he was always intrigued by Texas history, it
was his appointment to the Texas Historical Commission in the 1960s
by then-Gov. John Connally, whose tomb lies near Bullock's, that
spurred much of his subsequent interest in historical preservation.
Bullock went on to champion the Capitol restoration project in
addition to the Texas State Cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   That project gained momentum after he attended the funeral of
Harry Whitworth, the former state representative and lobbyist who
died in 1994. During the next three years, he spearheaded the
renovation project.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did more for this cemetery than anyone else,'' Bradley
said. ``This is where he ought to be. There is no other place.''
</P>
<P>
   A visitor's center, made of limestone, was built and modeled
after the Alamo barracks. About 2,200 Confederate graves were
restored. And a grand entrance called the Columbarium Wall was
erected.
</P>
<P>
   Today, mourners will pass through that wall's archway, march
along a path lined by 50 Texas flags and loop around to Republic
Hill Section 1, Row Q, Plot 11, where Bullock's remains will be
lowered into a hole 44 inches wide and nine feet long.
</P>
<P>
   They will also pass a flagpole 150 feet tall that Bullock could
see from his office in the capital.
</P>
<P>
   About five years ago, Bullock wanted the flagpole installed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We finished it at 9:30 at night in the rain, because I
promised he'd be able to see it the next morning,'' Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   Like flags all over the state, it is flying at half-staff.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
