<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990619.0267 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-19 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2252 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEX-BULLOCK-REMEMBERE     06-19 1450
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEX-BULLOCK-REMEMBERED-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bullock opened doors to women, minorities
 &HT;    (Eds: Funeral is Sunday.)
 &HT;    By A. Phillips Brooks
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ To Charles Miles and so many other minorities
and women, Bob Bullock was not just another legendary Texas
politician.
</P>
<P>
   He was opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bullock started the trend among state agencies to hire and
promote women and minorities,'' said Miles, 59, whom Bullock hired
in 1974 as one of six assistant comptrollers. ``Bullock didn't just
bring them in as entry-level employees. He put them in high
places.''
</P>
<P>
   Miles, owner of the Capital City Argus weekly newspaper, said
when he went to work for Bullock, the agency had fewer than 50
African Americans and Hispanics. When he left a year later, there
were more than 200 out of about 1,000 employees.
</P>
<P>
   As Texans today pay their respects to the man whose financial
and political acumen made him a household name and whose service to
Texas won him respect from Democrats and Republicans, Texans of a
darker hue and different gender are remembering Bullock as the man
who opened doors of opportunity when few others would.
</P>
<P>
   More than once he told employees he tackled equal opportunity so
fiercely to make up for his segregationist roots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bullock was the first head of a state agency to aggressively
hire women and minorities,'' said Cecelia Burke, a former Bullock
employee and the first woman to be elected Travis County tax
assessor-collector. ``He was a visionary who found the brightest
and best, then gave them opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   The country boy from Hillsboro did more than break down
entrenched racial and gender barriers in state government.
Throughout his career as comptroller and later as lieutenant
governor, Bullock rose time and again to defend state contracting
and employment programs aimed at assisting minorities and women.
</P>
<P>
   By today's standards, that might seem a politically safe _ if
not smart _ bet. But it was the early 1970s. Austin was
experiencing race riots as whites resisted integrating public
schools. A former comptroller had called then-Rep. Eddie Bernice
Johnson, a Dallas Democrat, ``a stupid nigger woman'' when she
pushed the agency to hire women. The University of Texas was in the
early stages of integration, still with segregated dormitories.
Blacks and women _ even college educated _ largely were relegated
to menial jobs.
</P>
<P>
   It was in such a climate that Bullock plowed ahead, hiring
blacks, Hispanics and women into well-paying and secure jobs. And
he did so disarmingly, maintaining a good ol' boy demeanor while
reaching out to what he would later describe as Texas' rich
diversity. Bullock is credited with reshaping the face of state
government to look more like the population it served and expanding
a burgeoning minority middle class in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bullock set the trend for what was to follow,'' said Nelda
Wells Spears, Travis County tax assessor-collector. She remembers
that it was Bullock who first opened the door of opportunity to a
public service career which ultimately would result in her being
the first African American in Texas elected to the post she now
holds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a (bachelor's) and a master's degree, but could not find
meaningful, well-paying work,'' said Spears, 52. ``Then came
Bullock.''
</P>
<P>
   Spears was called to an interview on Christmas Eve 1974 she
never will forget.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was raining, and I was nervous,'' she recounted. ``When I
walked in, there was Bob Bullock, working on Christmas Eve day. He
hired me.''
</P>
<P>
   Spears quickly rose through the ranks and became director of
personnel. During her nearly five-year tenure, she saw the agency
transformed from one that was ``lily white'' to the most ethnically
and gender diverse of all state agencies, ``in a very short time.''
</P>
<P>
   Other state agencies followed suit, Miles and others said, but
when they didn't _ well, Bullock convinced them it was the right
thing to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``He opened his agency up and he was proud of it,'' said Bill
Aleshire, former County Travis county judge who as a young man
worked for Bullock. ``Because he was comptroller, he was able to
use that position to shake up other agencies. He would get
interested in how they were performing.''
</P>
<P>
   Miles said Bullock's ``contributions to equal opportunity in
employment surely make him a civil rights figure.''
</P>
<P>
   If Bullock was civil rights mover, then he was an unlikely one.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Hillsboro in 1929, Bullock was reared in a segregated
farming community during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas was different back then,'' Bullock said in a 1994
interview. ``I was straight in from Hillsboro. I didn't even ride
in an elevator until after I was out of high school.''
</P>
<P>
   Bullock came to Austin in 1957 after being elected to the Texas
House. He later told Miles and others who asked why he worked so
ferociously to open doors for minorities that he had been a
segregationist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hell, I probably voted for all of those (segregationist)
bills,'' he said in the interview. ``Wish I hadn't now.''
</P>
<P>
   Miles said: ``He sat me down and said, 'Charlie, I never saw a
segregation bill I didn't like. I can't go back. I can't change
that. But I can make things right now.' ``
</P>
<P>
   Miles, Burke, Spears and a host of other women and minorities
were the beneficiaries of Bullock's hiring and promoting policies,
which they and others say helped expand Austin's minority middle
class. But millions more have benefited from economic and
educational policies he helped create, and later saved.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, minority lawmakers succeeded in creating a state
program aimed at directing more state contracts to businesses owned
by women and minorities. The program lacked teeth. In 1993, when
Sen. Royce West, D-Dallas, was a freshmen, he wanted to strengthen
the program but didn't know how.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Bullock.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know what the hell I was doing,'' West recalls. ``But
Bullock did. With his assistance, I amended the budget so that the
program for the first time had goals for state agencies.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Bullock put his muscle behind another West initiative,
which created teaching centers at historically black colleges and
universities. The centers train teachers especially for work in
inner-city schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``He understood the demographics of Texas were changing,
becoming more urban and more minority,'' West said.
</P>
<P>
   But long before that, Bullock got involved in fighting for equal
rights, Johnson said. When, as a state senator, she tried to pass
legislation in 1987 laying the foundation for the state contracting
program, senators would blow her off, refusing to come to her
hearings.
</P>
<P>
   ``They would break quorum,'' she said, ``so I went to Mr.
Bullock. Back then, women and minorities weren't getting any state
contracts. It was a good ol' boy network.''
</P>
<P>
   Bullock gathered together all the senators for a discussion and
directed all to talk about their most important bills. With the
senators present and under Bullock's watchful eye, she got the
committee hearing and the votes to pass the language into law.
Bullock also was instrumental in setting up Johnson's district,
Dallas' first black congressional district, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Morin, executive director of the Texas Association of
Mexican American Chambers of Commerce, said Bullock helped save
that same state contracting program when Republicans attempted to
dismantle it in 1997. The program has steered billions of dollars
to businesses owned by women and minorities since its inception in
1991.
</P>
<P>
   Wardaleen Belvin, a top aide to Bullock, said her boss was
deeply concerned that Texas would retreat from equal opportunity
programs and end up in a racial feud similar to California's highly
publicized affirmative action wars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember him sitting me down and saying, 'I don't know what
it's like to be black. I don't know what it's like to feel racial
discrimination. I can't change the past. But I can do what is
right, and I promise you I will do everything I can to make this
right.' ``
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Bullock set the stage for a compromise this year
that brought Democrats and Republicans together and salvaged the
state contracting program. That was the Bullock style, which
minorities say is his lasting legacy to Texas, a state where
African Americans and Hispanics will form the majority within 20
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a civil rights activist in his own right,'' said U.S.
Rep. Sheila Jackson Lee of Houston. ``He set the tone that it was
OK that all of us _ African Americans, Hispanics, women and white
men _ live under the Texas flag.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
