<DOCNO> NYT19990619.0268 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-19 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2254 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-1STLD-WRIT     06-19 1058
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE KNICKS, WOUNDED AND WEARY, FEEL THE PRESSURE TO AVOID A SWEEP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas)   (Eds: Fixes grammar in 3rd graf; SUBS 4th graf from bottom, They
made ... , to correct to Effect, sted Affect. )  
 (DW) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Marcus Camby was moving with the wobbly and awkward steps of a
newborn colt as he drove into the paint and nearly fell down while
twisting and turning, all in an effort to get off a shot that would
find the net before David Robinson and Tim Duncan found it.
</P>
<P>
   The two Spurs did not have to work hard on this late-game
occasion Friday night. The shot squirted into the air like a bar of
soap that got away and landed on top of the backboard before
kissing the shot clock. But this is what Robinson and Duncan do.
They make a fool out of effort.
</P>
<P>
   Camby was trying. So was Larry Johnson and Kurt Thomas and Chris
Childs. But they were a combined 5 for 26 in the Knicks' Game 2
loss to San Antonio, and they made for a shaky support group for
Latrell Sprewell and Allan Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of pressure on Allan and Sprewell to score,''
said Mario Elie, who continually funneled Houston inside on the
baseline where Robinson and Duncan were waiting for him. ``Those
guys are terrific players, but I always say that two can't beat
12.''
</P>
<P>
   If Sprewell and Houston have to keep playing on their own _ as
they did in Game 2 to finish a combined 17 for 42 from the field _
the Knicks will be in a potentially devastating situation when they
play Game 3 of the four-of-seven-game National Basketball
Association finals on Monday at Madison Square Garden. Even as the
crowd filtered out of the dome Friday night, there were chants of
``Sweep'' by the Spurs fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our guys on this team have a lot of pride,'' Camby said. ``We
don't want to get swept, and I don't think that's going to
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Down two games to none, the Knicks maintained a feisty good
spirit on the surface, but they have to find some points from
alternate sources to give themselves a chance against the Spurs.
Although they are banged up, the Knicks can tap a few options. The
obvious one is Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   During Game 2, he was as alone on the perimeter as a scarecrow
in a field but on a sprained knee he had little lift when he
launched 7 3-pointers and hit just 1. With two days of rest, he may
feel better for Game 3 and get a hit of adrenaline from the home
crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Childs could also be a threat. He was able to dart inside for
open looks on runners but missed when he noticed Robinson and
Duncan closing in on him. He finished 2 for 8. If he can spot up
and knock down a 3-pointer, Childs _ or Charlie Ward, for that
matter _ could give the Knicks a little boost. If Houston and
Sprewell can drive-and-kick the ball out, Childs poses much more of
a threat outside, than going inside against the Twin Towers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have great lane intimidation as far as making each shot
in the paint difficult,'' Coach Jeff Van Gundy said. ``I thought we
had some good looks in there. But nothing comes easy with those two
guys there.''
</P>
<P>
   To make it easier on themselves, the Knicks could run a
pick-and-roll now and again and be less predictable. So far,
Robinson and Duncan have been able to lurk in the background and
await the one-on-one drives of Sprewell and Houston.
</P>
<P>
   On occasion, Thomas could diffuse some of that predictability
with his ability to nail a base-line jumper. Thomas was 1 for 6 in
Game 1, but if the mood hits him, he is capable of scoring in
double figures.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just need a third or fourth guy to help,'' Elie said.
``Larry is not 100 percent. Kurt is a role player. Maybe Camby, but
he just does a great job giving them energy on the offensive
boards. We can't let Allan or Sprewell beat us. We've got to try
and make Kurt Thomas, Marcus Camby and Chris Dudley beat us.''
</P>
<P>
   No one has stepped forward so far. Camby was the X factor in the
Knicks' Indiana series, but has had trouble staying out of foul
trouble when matched against Robinson. He has had difficulty making
a shot without wondering when and if it &UR;  &LR; will be blocked.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have two guys in there like they have, you worry
about them blocking shots and altering the shot,'' Camby said.
``It's tough to get into the lane. But then when you get to the
lane, you still have to face two intimidators inside and try to
shoot over them.''
</P>
<P>
   For Camby, those shots are usually putbacks. With the quickness
of Duncan, those second-chance shots can end up partly blocked. In
Game 3, Camby may have more plays run for him, and may be more
effective down the stretch if he can avoid early foul trouble.
</P>
<P>
   It's that final stretch that has been the melting point for the
Knicks. As the games have worn on, Houston and Sprewell have begun
to wilt under the Spurs' 48-minutes of defensive pressure. In the
fourth quarters of Games 1 and 2, Houston was 1 for 7 and Sprewell
was 4 for 13. They've fallen into the Spurs plan to wear out the
Knicks by the fourth quarter in an effort to steal their energy for
a comeback.
</P>
<P>
   ``They made some mistakes at the end, like dribbling off their
foot or trying to make something happen,'' Robinson said. ``You can
see those type of things starting to take effect after a long
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Another long night ended Friday. The Knicks were left to wander
off the court with visions of Robinson and Duncan still fresh in
their heads.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where we are right now, we have to be efficient and get some
unexpected scoring, as we did the other night from Kurt,'' said Van
Gundy, referring to Thomas' 13 points in Game 1. ``We have to have
some other guys who are going to put the ball in the basket,
especially when they come to block shots.''
</P>
<P>
   And they will come.
</P>
<P>
   REBOUNDS
</P>
<P>
   Chris Dudley played just 13 minutes in Game 2 with a bruised
elbow that limited his mobility throughout the game. Dudley is just
another in a line of banged-up Knicks. The team dressed 10 players
for Game 2, but have just 8 of them playing healthy. ``Obviously,
you'd like to have your full complement,'' Jeff Van Gundy said.
``But the one thing I've learned in the NBA is that there's no
mercy. Nor should there be. As I've told our team, it's not about
who we have or don't have, it's who we have to play. We have to
play better.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
