<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-USOPEN-STRICKER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONE SUB-PAR ROUND LIFTS STRICKER
</HEADLINE>
  (With GLF-USOPEN) 
 (nk) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINEHURST, N.C. _ When Steve Stricker teed off in Saturday's
third round of the U.S. Open, he was six strokes off the lead. When
he birdied the second hole, he was five behind. And when his 8-iron
shot into the wind out of a fairway bunker from 136 yards spun into
the cup on the 335-yard third hole for an eagle 2, he suddenly was
only three strokes off the lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have that go in, you don't expect that,'' he said later.
</P>
<P>
   And on a windy afternoon that had scores soaring at Pinehurst
No. 2, you do not expect any golfer to shoot one-under-par 69, but
that's what Stricker did. He was the only golfer to shoot under par
for the day and, with a 54-hole total of 212, he is three strokes
behind the leader, Payne Stewart, entering Sunday's final round.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel like I shot the round of the year,'' Stricker
said. ``I feel great that I shot a 69, but getting off to the start
I did really fueled my whole round. I mean, three under through
three, you don't expect to start off that way. But it got me into
position to shoot 69.''
</P>
<P>
   Stricker, 32, is a two-time winner on the PGA Tour. He has been
on the leader board in three of the last five major tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   At last year's Open at Olympic, Stricker also shot 69 in the
third round, for 213, six shots off Stewart's lead. He finished
with a 73 that tied for fifth as Lee Janzen won. At last year's
Professional Golfers' Association Championship, he shared the
third-round lead with Vijay Singh and closed with a 70, but
finished second to Singh by two strokes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Shinnecock in '95, that was extremely difficult as
well _ windy, extremely fast greens,'' he said, referring to the
1995 Open. ``But this is one of the toughest courses I've ever
played, if not the toughest.''
</P>
<P>
   Other pros complained that some of the hole locations were
unfair, but Stricker disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how reasonable they are,'' he said, ``but they're
fair. But the pins are put in positions where you have to play
extremely smart. If you don't, if you try to be too greedy, you're
going to pay the price. You have to take your 20- and 30- and
40-footers and two-putt them.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first got on tour, I couldn't handle that. I thought,
this isn't golf. They force you into situations that you're not
comfortable with, but I've learned to deal with that over the years
because everybody has got to play it. They're trying to find out
who the toughest person is mentally.''
</P>
<P>
   Stricker acknowledged being too aggressive on the 16th and 17th
holes, which he bogeyed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking 3-iron all the time on 16,'' he said of the
489-yard hole, the longest par-4 in Open history. ``I ended up
taking a 2-iron and trying to get it all the way back there to the
hole and it went over the green too far. On 17, I tried to stuff it
in there. I should have put it in the center of the green and tried
to make a 20-footer. But maybe that's a lesson I learned for
tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   And a lesson for if, and when, the Open returns to Pinehurst No.
2.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to see the Open come back here,'' Stricker said. ``I
think it's going to bring out the best winner _ the person who
thinks his way around, who hits it probably better than anybody
during that week, although I've probably proven that theory wrong.
I don't feel I'm hitting enough fairways and greens. I'm doing it
with my short game.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
