A2455 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-CHARTER-SCHOOLS-NY     06-19 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CHARTER-SCHOOLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE ACCUSED OF APPROVING CHARTER SCHOOLS WITHOUT PUBLIC COMMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By ANEMONA HARTOCOLLIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A loose coalition of legislators, school and union
officials charged Saturday that New York state officials violated
state law when they approved the state's first eight charter
schools last week without providing a chance for public comment.
</P>
<P>
   State officials denied the charge, saying that since the
charters had not been formally issued, there was still time for
public input. But the dispute, and the threat of legal action by
teachers' unions, could delay the first three charter schools _ two
in New York City and one in Albany _ from opening in September as
planned.
</P>
<P>
   Charter schools get public subsidies and independence from local
school districts, as long as they meet academic objectives outlined
in their charter, or operating permit.
</P>
<P>
   State law calls for school districts to be notified before
charters are issued and at every ``significant'' step in the
approval process. The idea, state education officials said
Saturday, was for parents, community leaders and educators to be
able to endorse the schools or to describe any adverse impact they
might have on the community and existing schools before a decision
was made.
</P>
<P>
   Under the law, which was adopted in December, up to 50 charters
can be granted by the trustees of the State University of New York
and up to 50 more by the State Board of Regents. The SUNY trustees
approved the eight charter schools, out of 15 applications, on
Tuesday. The names of the applicants were kept confidential until
the vote.
</P>
<P>
   SUNY officials confirmed that the vote occurred before any
school districts had been notified in writing that the applications
had been filed. In some cases, notice was given by telephone before
the vote, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Those who charged that state law was violated have consulted one
another about the issue, but have not agreed to act together
formally. Some oppose charter schools; others support them under
certain conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Sanders, chairman of the Assembly Education Committee and
a Manhattan Democrat, said that he was troubled by what he called
the secrecy surrounding the approval process and that he would ask
the state attorney general to review it.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one is suggesting that these schools ought not at some
point be allowed to open up,'' Sanders said. ``But it is now
clearly precipitous for that to happen this fall.''
</P>
<P>
   But a spokesman for Gov. George Pataki called the issue
``nothing more than a red herring.'' The spokesman, Charles H.
Deister, added, ``Unfortunately, there are always going to be
defenders of the status quo who oppose innovative ideas in
education.''
</P>
<P>
   Susan Amlung, a spokeswoman for the United Federation of
Teachers, the New York City teachers' union, said the UFt and the
New York State United Teachers were contemplating legal action.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question really is what was there to hide?'' Ms. Amlung
said. ``Why the big rush? These are public schools. So it's
impossible right now for the public or for parents to say whether
these are good programs, whether they have high academic
standards.''
</P>
<P>
   Timothy G. Kremer, executive director of the New York State
School Boards Association, said several school districts had
complained about not receiving advance notice of charter schools
planned for their districts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a small matter,'' Sanders said. ``The charter
school law required full disclosure and input by the local school
district and community prior to any charter being issued. SUNY
either willfully ignored this requirement, or in its rush to open
charter schools this fall, it neglected to follow all the necessary
procedures.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Steffey, president of the Charter Schools Institute, a
newly created arm of the state university, said that the law had
not been violated because the charter documents had not been
issued. He said applications were due at the end of May and that he
thought it was important to move quickly to approve them, even
before soliciting comment, so that charter schools would have time
to prepare to open in September.
</P>
<P>
   He said there was still time for public notification and comment
before the applications go before the Regents for another review on
July 15. If significant objections arise, he said, the approvals
could be revoked.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the vote was on Tuesday was a vote to empower the
president of the Charter Schools Institute, me, to enter into a
charter with the approved applicants,'' Steffey said. ``I have not
done so.''
</P>
<P>
   The Regents have 60 days to raise objections to the charters,
and SUNY has 30 days to answer in writing. But SUNY can issue the
charters over the objections of the Regents after the full 90 days
have expired.
</P>
<P>
   State law calls for the SUNY trustees to notify school districts
that would be affected by a charter school ``at each significant
stage of the chartering process.'' It also says that the district
must have the opportunity to comment on the proposed charter and
that it can choose to hold public hearings.
</P>
<P>
   Chiara Coletti, a spokeswoman for New York City schools
Chancellor Rudy Crew, said Crew still had not been notified by SUNY
of the five charter schools to be located in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   ``My feeling is that the law never intended for the local school
district to be in the dark,'' Ms. Coletti said. ``This elaborate
concealment could be a violation of the spirit of the law, if not
the letter of the law.''
</P>
<P>
   Steffey acknowledged that none of the school district
superintendents had been formally notified until Saturday, at the
earliest. Letters were sent out either by mail or by fax Saturday,
or would be sent out Monday, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
