<HEADER>
A2457 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS     06-19 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 27)  
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; NO PICNIC ON MOUNT KENYA &LR;  By Felice Benuzzi. Lyons, $14.95. In
1943 the author and two Italian compatriots escaped from a British
POW camp and embarked on a loony quest to scale Mount Kenya and
plant their nation's flag on its summit, knowing they would
eventually wind up in solitary. This lively account is both a
ripping yarn and a self-mocking survival tale. ``Gay adventure,
this, with the quality of truth,'' Robert Payne wrote in The New
York Times Book Review in 1953.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THIS SIDE OF BRIGHTNESS &LR;  By Colum McCann. Owl/Holt, $13. This
gritty, intense novel by a young Irish writer chronicles the
eroding fortunes of three generations of a disturbed family whose
members once helped to build the New York City subway system but
now live in its darkened tunnels. ``This Side of Brightness'' is a
``deft feat of balance and fancy footwork,'' David Willis
McCullough wrote in The New York Times Book Review last year. ``It
is also a disturbingly beautiful portrait of a family whose dreams
are never quite able to stae off the painful reality of their
circumstances, a portrait that ends without sentimentality and yet
with renewed hope.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE UNFINISHED PRESIDENCY: JIMMY CARTER'S JOURNEY BEYOND THE
WHITE HOUSE &LR;  By Douglas Brinkley. Penguin, $15.95. This account of
the ex-president's second career as poet, teacher and crusader for
human rights also explores the two sides of his personality: his
Christian values and his fierce egotism. ``Even Carter's severest
critics ... will find it hard to be unmoved by his blend of
idealism and practicality,'' Godfrey Hodgson wrote in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHERE OR WHEN &LR;  By Anita Shreve. Harvest/Harcourt Brace, $13.
Thirty-one years after a brief teen-age romance, an insurance
broker and a lonely poet rekindle their affair, first through
letters and then in the flesh. ``Throughout this finely wrought
book, Ms. Shreve manages to keep the reader suspended between
despair and hope'' for her characters, Susan Isaacs wrote in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE RINGS OF SATURN &LR;  By W.G. Sebald. New Directions, $14. This
hybrid of fiction, travel, biography, myth and memoir follows the
writer on a walking tour of the English coast but mostly sails
through space and time as he ruminates on everything from silk to
Joseph Conrad. ``The book is so natural and accessible ... that one
is left enchanted,'' Roberta Silman wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE HOUSE OF SLEEP &LR;  By Jonathan Coe. Vintage Contemporaries,
$13. This intricate novel follows the loosely connected lives of
four characters _ among them a narcoleptic woman and a dream addict
who sleeps at least 14 hours a day _ and their shared preoccupation
with dreamland. ``Coe has written a witty, engaging romance,''
Suzanne Berne wrote in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE BOURGEOIS EXPERIENCE: VICTORIA TO FREUD. VOLUME 1:
EDUCATION OF THE SENSES &LR;  By Peter Gay. Norton, $16. The first of
five volumes in the author's provocative study of the American and
European middle classes from the 1820s to World War I focuses on
Victorian sexuality in all its extravagant and surprising variety.
He calls his approach ``history informed by psychoanalysis,'' and
he goes a long way toward disproving stereotypes about the era's
sexless femininity. ``There has been no inquiry of this majestic
import and ambition before,'' Neil McKendrick wrote in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   In  &UR; VOLUME 2: THE TENDER PASSION &LR;  ($16), Gay takes on
19th-century attitudes toward love and argues that bourgeois
marriages were more stable and rewarding (for men and women) than
most people believe. Gay ``shows himself splendidly resourceful in
conjuring up the intimate worlds of these individuals,'' Paul
Robinson wrote in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE BALLAD OF PECKHAM RYE &LR;  By Muriel Spark. New Directions,
$11.95. Set in a working-class London suburb, this frothy comic
novel describes the havoc caused when a textile company hires a
young Scottish consultant ``to bring vision into the lives of the
workers.'' In 1960 the reviewer Gerald Sykes called this a ``genial
popular entertainment of, imaginably, the Alec Guinness kind.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE BIRTH OF BEBOP: A SOCIAL AND MUSICAL HISTORY &LR;  By Scott
DeVeaux. University of California, $18.95. This scholarly study
traces the shift from swing to be-bop in New York in the 1940s,
focusing on musicians like Charlie ``Bird'' Parker, Dizzy Gillespie
and others who transformed the jazz landscape. The book discusses
jazz ``the way musicians have talked about it, not as a matter of
schools and eras but as a slow-boiling stew of experience,'' Ben
Ratliff wrote last year in The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CELEBRATING BIRD: THE TRIUMPH OF CHARLIE PARKER &LR; , by Gary
Giddins (Da Capo, $17.95), is an incisive portrait of the legendary
saxophonist that addresses both his musical genius and his tragic
life. In 1987 the reviewer Jason Berry called this ``as penetrating
a character study of Bird as any yet written.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LAMBS OF GOD &LR;  By Marele Day. Riverhead, $12.95. Three nuns
living in a crumbling convent on a remote island find their
solitude threatened by a young priest who arrives out of nowhere
with plans to turn the property into a luxury resort. The result is
a ``marvelous novel'' that is ``affecting and humorous and always
absorbing,'' Julie Gray wrote last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-99 2219EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990619.0272 </DOCNO>
