<SLUG> BC-SOC-CHINA-SWEDEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CO-FAVORITE HAS TROUBLE BUT STILL WINS ITS OPENER
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By KEN GURNICK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ China, the co-favorite to win the Women's
World Cup, almost failed to win its opening first-round match
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Spotting Sweden a goal in the second minute, China battled back
for a difficult 2-1 victory at Spartan Stadium. Midfielder Liu
Ailing scored the go-ahead goal in the 69th minute, and Sweden
could not answer against acrobatic China goalkeeper Hong Gao.
</P>
<P>
   With speed, experience, technical skill and the fitness that
comes from a nine-game, 48-day prep tour, China is considered a
likely opponent for the United States in the final at the Rose Bowl
on July 10. China has beaten the United States in two of three
matches this year.
</P>
<P>
   In what shaped up as a defensive struggle between teams with two
of the best goalkeepers in the tournament, the game started like a
shootout. Sweden opened aggressively, controlled the midfield and
stunned China with the second-fastest score in Women's World Cup
history.
</P>
<P>
   Midfielder Kristin Bengtsson intercepted a deflected pass from
defender Fan Yunjie 30 yards in front of the Chinese goal, briefly
dribbled closer, then buried a crisp line drive into the upper left
corner.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen minutes into the match, however, a different China team
emerged. Midfielder Zhao Lihong found a soft spot on the left wing
and repeatedly tested the Swedish defense, creating shot
opportunities that kept keeper Ulrika Karlsson busy.
</P>
<P>
   In the 17th minute, the pressure was converted into a goal.
Midfielder Liu Ying launched a corner kick that crossed in front of
the goal, where forward Jin Yan had slipped away from defender
Cecilia Sandell. Yin headed the pass over Karlsson to even the
score at 1-1.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the first half was spent primarily on Sweden's side
of the field, with the inability of Yan and forward Sun Wen to
finish off several easy chances keeping Sweden in the match.
</P>
<P>
   China took the lead in the 69th minute. Liu Ailing took a short
pass from Liu Ying and lofted a touch shot over Karlsson, who had
drifted 10 yards in front of the goal, and the ball found the
center of the net.
</P>
<P>
   This was the latest in what has developed into quite a rivalry.
In the 1991 Women's World Cup, won by the United States, Sweden
eliminated host China in the quarterfinals, a loss so devastating
that China shut down its women's national team program for two
years. In the 1995 Women's World Cup, China eliminated host Sweden
in the quarterfinals, and in the 1996 Olympics, China beat Sweden
on the way to the silver medal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-99 2243EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990619.0279 </DOCNO>
