u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-ANGELS-NYT &LR;      06-19 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-ANGELS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRABU BREAKS A SMILE, AND YANKS RELAX, TOO
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Hideki Irabu has always been an enigma to his
teammates, hidden behind a language barrier he has rarely attempted
to traverse. But Irabu is emerging from his shell, and whether it
is a coincidence or not, it's coming at a time when he is becoming
a significant contributor in the Yankees' rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Irabu permitted three hits and one earned run in seven innings
as the Yankees placed another stake through the walking dead
Anaheim Angels, in a 6-2 victory Saturday night at Yankee Stadium.
Derek Jeter, the Yankees' new No. 3 hitter, had two runs batted in.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels, decimated by injury and beset by clubhouse turmoil,
have lost six consecutive games. The Yankees, on the other hand,
are gaining steam, propelled by their starting pitching.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' rotation has compiled a 2.55 ERA over its last
421/3 innings; from David Cone to Roger Clemens to Orlando
Hernandez to Irabu, all the starters are going good.
</P>
<P>
   Irabu began throwing a cut fastball about three weeks ago and
refined his mechanics, working to keep his weight back longer in
the middle of his delivery. But the most significant change in
Irabu, some teammates say, is that he seems far more relaxed.
Silent and sullen for most of his first two years with the Yankees,
Irabu appears to be having fun playing baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Girardi mentioned it last week, after watching Irabu warm up
in the bullpen. ``Hey, Boo-Boo is smiling,'' Girardi said to Mel
Stottlemyre, the pitching coach. When Irabu pitched against the
Texas Rangers last week, he pointed to his infielders to
congratulate them _ ``Nice play,'' Irabu said in English to third
baseman Scott Brosius, something he had never done before.
</P>
<P>
   The other day, after Paul O'Neill had a couple of hits, Irabu
told his interpreter, George Rose, ``Watch this.'' Irabu walked
over to O'Neill, held up a fist _ this is the Yankees' way of
recognizing one another for a good effort _ and said, ``Nice
game.'' With a grin, Irabu said to Rose, ``I've never done that
before.''
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre believes Irabu (4-3) is getting more comfortable
with his teammates, and more confident _ and all of that is
manifesting itself in how he is performing. On June 8 he allowed
two runs in five and a third innings against Philadelphia, then
stifled the Rangers six days later, and he won again Saturday
night, despite some relatively ordinary stuff.
</P>
<P>
   When Irabu is right, when he dominates, he throws a fastball 92
to 95 mph to either side of the plate, and with two strikes, will
use his diving split-fingered fastball and tempt opposing batters
into swinging and missing. Against the Angels, his splitter was
erratic, often bouncing in front of home plate.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels threatened in the first and second innings last
night. Irabu pinched off the rally both times. With runners at
first and second and one out in the first, Irabu got Todd Greene to
fly out to center and then broke the bat of Garret Anderson on a
grounder back to the mound. With a runner at third and one out in
the second, Irabu used his fastball to jam Matt Walbeck into a
short flyout to left field. By the time the Angels did get on the
board, on Greene's home run in the fourth, the Yankees already had
a lead that must have looked insurmountable to the last-place
Angels.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim's Omar Olivares pitched well against the Yankees at the
Stadium on May 13, and when Manager Joe Torre brought in his
infield in the second inning last night, it was a sign that Torre
was leery of another strong outing by Olivares. But the
right-hander waded into trouble in almost every inning, some of the
mess created by his defense.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, the Angels' center fielder, loped in to catch an easy
fly by O'Neill to open the second inning _ and simply dropped it,
like a youngster losing the head off an ice cream cone. O'Neill
stole second. Chili Davis pulled a grounder to the right side to
advance O'Neill to third. Terry Collins, the manager of the Angels,
ordered his infield in, and Jorge Posada bounced a single through
the right side, scoring O'Neill.
</P>
<P>
   Bernie Williams, moved from cleanup to the No. 2 spot in the
Yankees' lineup in part because he is not getting enough extra-base
hits, slammed a line drive to right-center one out into the third
inning, the ball leaving an indent in the padding as it bounced off
the top of the wall; Williams slid into second base headfirst with
a double. Jeter, shifted from No. 2 to No. 3 because Torre is
seeking more run production, singled to score Williams and give the
Yankees a 2-0 edge.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees finished off Olivares in the sixth, turning a 3-1
lead into one of 5-1. Brosius and Chuck Knoblauch singled, Williams
rammed a double to drive home Brosius, and, following a pitching
change, Knoblauch scored on Jeter's sacrifice fly. Yankees 5,
Angels 1.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
