r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBA-COLUMN-LADN     06-19 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARLY WARNING SIGNS: ODOM HAD ALREADY STARTED TO DESTRUCT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ If you think the erratic behavior displayed by
Lamar Odom this week hurt his draft status, think again. Odom had
already begun to slip before his 11th-hour decision to try to
return to Rhode Island for another year.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago Bulls had apparently already decided to either
select Maryland's Steve Francis, or better yet, trade the pick
before Odom canceled his workout with the club and announced he
would try to regain his college eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   It was a nice try by Odom, considering he had signed last month
with agent Jeff Klein, a major violation by NCAA standards. His
case was so weak that even Rhode Island refused to present an
appeal to the NCAA.
</P>
<P>
   There was speculation that Odom was injured, and that was why he
canceled workouts with the Bulls and Charlotte. But it turned out
to be false. He has already rescheduled with both teams this week,
so chalk up this strange display to immaturity.
</P>
<P>
   Where does this leave Odom? Barring an exceptional workout, he
will not be taken by the Bulls. Chicago is busy hammering Toronto
to send it Tracy McGrady and the No. 5 pick, so the Raptors can
select Francis.
</P>
<P>
   But Toronto is reluctant to part with McGrady, especially since
he is close to rookie of the year Vince Carter, who the Raptors
want to keep happy at all costs.
</P>
<P>
   There is also the possibility that Bulls GM Jerry Krause will
select Francis, and then trade him later. Either way, the Bulls are
putting a ``for sale'' sign on their draft pick, something
considered unlikely when they won the lottery last month.
</P>
<P>
   The team watching all of this with great amusement is Vancouver,
which has the second pick. The Grizzlies were thought to be certain
to trade their choice for a power forward, but now that Odom has
slipped they may decide to keep him.
</P>
<P>
   Odom had a better-than-average workout with the Grizzlies before
he went AWOL, and a good interview with Grizzlies GM Stu Jackson.
Vancouver thinks he could play three positions (shooting guard,
small forward, power forward), and likes the idea of pairing him
with Mike Bibby and Shareef Abdur-Rahim.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is Charlotte, which is ignoring offers for the No. 3
selection, and would be perfectly happy to take Baron Davis. The
Hornets would also take Odom if he slides down that far.
</P>
<P>
   Then we have the Clippers. They have no chance of landing
Francis or Davis without moving up, and desperately need a point
guard.
</P>
<P>
   But forward Wally Szczerbiak is the best-player available when
the Clippers' name pops up on the draft board, thereby presenting a
dilemma. Should they take Andre Miller or Jason Terry a little
higher than they are valued, or select Szczerbiak?
</P>
<P>
   Option No. 3 might be better? Trade the pick.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota considered sending Terrell Brandon and the No.6 pick
to the Clippers for Lorenzen Wright and the No. 4 pick, but that
was when there was hope Davis or Francis might slip a few spots.
</P>
<P>
   Put down your Dukes: Two players who have caused the most
intrigue are Duke's Elton Brand and Corey Maggette. Brand has been
knocked for his size, but last week in Chicago, the Bulls said he
was actually 6-foot-8\. He also had a 7-5 horizontal reach and
vertical reach of more than 9 feet, which is typical of 7-foot
centers. That means Brand is back in the top five, and the the
Bulls are even considering him again.
</P>
<P>
   Maggette, however, has not been so fortunate. He has been woeful
from the outside during workouts, and has still not signed with an
agent, although he said he still has no thoughts of returning to
Duke.
</P>
<P>
   He figures to be a taken in the lower half of the lottery.
</P>
<P>
   Knicks had their point: While the Knicks struggle with Charlie
Ward and Chris Childs at point guard, they probably can't help but
think what would have happened if the NBA had avoided a lockout.
The Knicks were set to sign Oded Katash, a 6-5 Israeli who is
considered the best point guard in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   When the NBA season appeared doomed, Katash signed with Maccabi
Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
   The Glove stays in Seattle: Despite all the speculation, Seattle
intends to keep point guard Gary Payton. Sonics executive Wally
Walker said he will keep Payton and forward Vin Baker.
</P>
<P>
   Much less certain is whether Hersey Hawkins will return
(doubtful), or if the Sonics will keep the 13th pick, which they
believe is too low to get a quality player.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
