<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROSECUTING MENTALLY ILL IS INSANE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   One day in August 1997, 29-year-old Carrie May didn't report to
work at a local convenience store, and instead locked herself in
her Phoenix apartment, put a newly purchased pistol to her head
and, speaking through the closed front door, told her mother she
was going to kill herself.
</P>
<P>
   Again.
</P>
<P>
   Carrie May has been trying to kill herself since she was 16,
when she slit her wrists. She spent time in a mental hospital and,
after about a year, tried to slit her wrists again.
</P>
<P>
   When she was 18 or so, she augmented the slashing by injecting
herself with lighter fluid.
</P>
<P>
   In her 20s, she tried to hang herself.
</P>
<P>
   Later, she injected herself with carburetor fluid.
</P>
<P>
   After that, she cut herself again.
</P>
<P>
   After that, she shot herself in the chest with an electric nail
gun, spent time in a psychiatric ward and, upon release, shot
herself in the chest with the nail gun again.
</P>
<P>
   Because she never tried to harm anyone but herself, however, and
had no criminal history, Carrie easily was able to pick up a
handgun in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   (And we have the nerve to say ``she'' is out of whack.)
</P>
<P>
   That day in August 1997, the Phoenix police surrounded the
apartment where Carrie was holed up. Negotiators spoke with her on
the telephone while some officers drilled a peephole through a
neighboring wall and others peeked in through the front door, which
they opened with a passkey. &QL; 
TRYING `COPICIDE'
</P>
<P>
   Carrie told a police negotiator she didn't have the nerve to
shoot herself. Later, she'd tell psychiatrist Gwen Levitt she was
hoping to commit what the police call ``copicide,'' in which a
suicidal person gets the police to shoot him or her.
</P>
<P>
   During the hours of negotiations, police say Carrie waved the
pistol at officers looking at her through the front door. And, at
least once, she fired the weapon, though not at anyone.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, she simply put the gun down and walked out.
</P>
<P>
   Almost from the beginning, Carrie's attorneys have tried to have
their client placed in an intensive probation program in which
she's monitored to make sure she is working, taking medication and
getting therapy.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has never been a threat to anyone but herself,'' attorney
Charles Arnold said. ``To treat her as a criminal, and want to send
her to jail, is both a waste of taxpayer money and a shame.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, though, that's exactly what the Maricopa County
Attorney's Office has been trying to do.
</P>
<P>
   Because a weapon was waved at police officers and a shot was
fired, the best offer prosecutors have made to Carrie May involves
pleading guilty to one count of aggravated assault, which could
send her to prison for up to nine years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how many prosecutors have been on this case,''
Arnold said. ``There have been a few. Essentially, all of them have
indicated at one time or another that they'd like to do probation,
but say they can't because of an in-house policy of mandating
prison time for those who threaten police.'' &QL; 
PSYCHIATRIST'S FEAR
</P>
<P>
   Arnold doesn't believe Carrie May was a threat to the police, or
to anyone else. In Dr. Levitt's psychiatric evaluation, May is
described as having borderline personality disorder, depression,
bipolar disorder and more. She wrote, ``I believe it would be
appropriate for the court to consider probation as an option in
this case.'' Adding, ``I fear that Ms. May will make multiple
suicide attempts in prison, and may be successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Because prosecutors haven't gone along with that recommendation,
a trial date for Carrie May has been set for September. A spokesman
for the County Attorney's Office said Friday, however, that the
case is still being evaluated.
</P>
<P>
   Hopefully, by someone with all his marbles. And a heart.
</P>
<P>
   Carrie May suffers from a mental disorder, which can be treated
with therapy and medication. A justice system that chooses to lock
her up is incurably nuts. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-99 2258EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990619.0282 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-19 22:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2485 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR &LR;      06-19 0673
</HEADER>
