<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHASS-COLUMN-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN IMPORTANT TWO WEEKS FOR REDS  
 VALENTINE'S ALTERATIONS 
RIPKEN BIDS FOR RETURN 
THE HOMERLESS RACE 
IT'S A BLUE JAY! IT'S FERNANDEZ
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: SUBS homerless item to UPDATE Castillo's and Stocker's
at-bats for the season to include Saturday's games.)  (rk) 
 By   MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Cincinnati Reds are giving Jim Bowden, their general
manager, ``every reason to believe they can play with the wild-card
teams.'' In the next two weeks, though, the upstart and unheralded
Reds will let him know if they can play with the division leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning Monday night, the Reds, who have been in the middle of
a wild-card race that commands little attention, play 14
consecutive games against the Arizona Diamondbacks, the National
League West leaders, and the Houston Astros, the Central leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The eight games against the Astros figure to be more
enlightening for the Reds, because they play in the same division.
But the two-week span overall will provide Bowden with an idea of
what he might be doing later in July.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come July 31, we'll know a lot better where we are,'' Bowden
said.
</P>
<P>
   That's the deadline for making trades without waivers, and it's
a key date for the Reds. When Bowden made off-season trades that
brought high-priced Greg Vaughn and Denny Neagle to Cincinnati, he
said that if the Reds were not in contention for something by the
deadline, he could trade the players to teams that were.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll just have to find out,'' he said. ``I always keep an
open mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Entering Saturday's games, the Reds were 1 1/2 games behind San
Francisco in the wild-card race, with the Mets in between. They
were in second place in the division race, four games behind the
Astros. They have been as close as 1 1/2 games.
</P>
<P>
   Why are the Reds in these positions? Weren't they supposed to be
more at home lower in the standings?
</P>
<P>
   Sean Casey, their young first baseman, is one reason the Reds
have become a first-half contender. He took a league-leading .377
batting average into Saturday night's game, and he led the team in
RBIs with 44.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds' defense, especially up the middle, is another reason.
Pokey Reese, their young second baseman, has teamed well with
veteran Barry Larkin and had made only one error in 61 games. He
was hitting well, too, with a .287 average.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get spoiled watching guys like him,'' Jack McKeon, the
Reds' manager, said. ``He has great range, great hands, great
instincts and a strong arm.''
</P>
<P>
   Another youngster, Mike Cameron, performs a similar role in
center field. ``He catches everything in center,'' Bowden said.
</P>
<P>
   But the heart of the unexpectedly competitive Reds has been
their relief corps, a group of no-name pitchers who have made
themselves the most effective bullpen in the major leagues. The
Reds would not be where they are without Scott Williamson, Danny
Graves, Gabe White, Scott Sullivan and Dennis Reyes, who among them
had seven years of major league experience when the season began.
</P>
<P>
   The bullpen's 2.72 ERA is the only bullpen ERA in the majors
below 3.00. The .211 batting average the relievers have allowed
opponents is the only average below .225. Their effort has been
season-saving because the Reds' starting pitchers have averaged
only five innings a start, making them the shortest-working
starters in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not going to get it done,'' McKeon said. So the
relievers have had to get the job done. Sullivan, Graves and
Williamson began the weekend with more innings in relief than
anyone in the league except Brian Edmondson of Florida. Williamson,
who in his third year as a professional throws a fastball 96 to 98
mph, leads National League relievers with six victories, and his
1.39 ERA and 54 strikeouts are second.
</P>
<P>
   Bowden and McKeon appreciate what the bullpen has done, but they
know they can't expect to get that kind of production for the
entire season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need our starters to pitch well or we'll burn out the
bullpen,'' Bowden said. ``We could use another starting pitcher or
two.''
</P>
<P>
   Neagle, who is on the disabled list strengthening his left
shoulder, has won no games this season. Brett Tomko, who was
demoted to the minors briefly earlier in the season, has won two
games. The Reds had counted on 15 victories each from Neagle, Tomko
and Pete Harnisch.
</P>
<P>
   Bowden is on the prowl for starters who might be available in
trades but said: ``Thirty clubs can't agree on a salary cap,
revenue sharing, realignment, the designated hitter or Astroturf,
but I found one thing they all agree on. All of them want starting
pitching and none of them wants to trade it.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, it will be up to McKeon to navigate the team through
the hazardous waters filled with Diamondbacks and Astros. Trader
Jack noted that the Reds beat each team two out of three in earlier
series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm quite sure we're not intimidated by them,'' he said.
``It's a good test for us. If we want to stay where we are, we have
to at least split with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentine's Alterations
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Valentine feels he is a marked man, but the Mets' manager
invites scrutiny and retaliation. In the past few weeks, Jack
McKeon, the Cincinnati manager, has questioned Jason Isringhausen's
glove and the shirt Pat Mahomes wore under his uniform, forcing the
Mets to alter the glove and Mahomes to change the shirt.
</P>
<P>
   It was McKeon's turn in the art of baseball gamesmanship. He
acted after the Mets' grounds crew applied an excessive amount of
water in front of home plate before a game at Shea Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``He watered the field down purposely,'' McKeon said, speaking
of Valentine. ``Someone overheard him say it the night before to
the groundskeepers.'' The start of the game was delayed as the
grounds crew, at McKeon's request to the umpires, put down a
substance to soak up the water. ``I was worried about getting
Piazza hurt,'' McKeon said with a straight face, referring to the
Mets' catcher.
</P>
<P>
   Ripken Bids for Return
</P>
<P>
   When Cal Ripken was on the disabled list earlier this season _
recovering from a chronic back ailment, dealing with his father's
death and facing a .179 batting average and five errors in eight
games _ he brushed off suggestions that he was just about finished
as a productive player.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to arm yourself with your tools and go out there and
find out,'' he said, discussing the ability that might remain.
``Then you'll know yourself. You're being judged in front of all
these people, but nobody can make that judgment except you.''
</P>
<P>
   Others' rush to judgment has suffered a setback. Since his
return from the disabled list, Ripken was hitting .363 (45 for 124)
with 24 RBIS, eight home runs and two errors in 31 games before
Saturday night. His rejuvenated performance will help the Orioles
take an important step with greater ease.
</P>
<P>
   They must decide by July 13 if they want to exercise the $6.3
million option in Ripken's contract for next season or pay him a
$2.5 million buyout. Although club officials have not talked about
their plans, they are prepared to pick up the option.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Ripken should play only part time next year, the Orioles
figure they can pay him the high salary for what he has done for
the franchise.
 &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-99 2343EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
