<DOCNO> NYT19990619.0284 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-19 23:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2489 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHASS-COLUMN-2TAKES-N     06-19 0506
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHASS-COLUMN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: for the franchise. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Homerless Race
</P>
<P>
   On successive days last week, the race for most times at bat
without a home run underwent a dramatic change. Last Monday, Tony
Womack of Arizona relinquished his lead in the race with a home run
against Ryan Dempster of Florida in his 227th at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   A day earlier Mike Caruso of the Chicago White Sox, in his 216th
at-bat, hit his first home run of the season against Rick Aguilera
of the Chicago Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   Their exit from the race left Luis Castillo of Florida all alone
at the top. He ha &UR; s &LR;  batted 235 times without hitting a home run.
Rey Ordonez of the Mets is a distant second with 193 at-bats, and
Kevin Stocker of Tampa Bay is next at 187.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Karl probably cannot understand their power problem. The
Milwaukee pitcher has 29 at-bats in his 14 starts, and he has hit
two home runs.
</P>
<P>
   It's a Blue Jay! It's Fernandez
</P>
<P>
   Some people might swear that Tony Fernandez stepped into a
telephone booth last Aug. 1, but all he did, really, was move from
second base to third base. Since that day, however, American League
pitchers have suffered from Fernandez's transformation.
</P>
<P>
   Not even balls made of Kryptonite can get him out. ``This is not
a phenomenon this year,'' Gord Ash, the Toronto general manager,
said. ``You go back to last August, when we moved him from second
to third. He didn't have to worry about a lack of range. He seemed
to take off offensively.''
</P>
<P>
   A .282 career hitter for his first 14 years in the majors,
Fernandez was hitting .287 when the month of July ended last year.
The next day he began playing third, and he proceeded to hit .381
in his last 67 games, finishing with a .321 average, just one point
below the career-high .322 he batted in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's always been a fairly good hitter,'' Ash said, ``but he's
moved into another level.''
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez is batting a league-leading .409. When the first phase
of interleague play began June 4, he was hitting .383. In 15 games
since, he has amassed 27 hits in 55 at-bats (.491). Besides
catapulting him beyond .400, his torrid stretch has given Fernandez
a share of Dominican Republic baseball history. His two hits
Saturday gave him 2,177, moving him into a tie with Julio Franco
for most ever by a Dominican native.
</P>
<P>
   ``His work ethic, his concentration and, I think, his comfort
level all play a role in it,'' Ash said of Fernandez's remarkable
late-life improvement as a hitter. ``I've never seen anybody, and I
underline anybody, work like this guy works. Pre- and post-game, he
conditions himself. He sets a work tone second to none.''
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez, who turns 37 on June 30, is in his third tour of duty
with Toronto, with which he has spent nine years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony has always been a hard worker,'' Ash added, ``even when
we had him as a youngster. He always had dedication. Everybody
talks about the pressure that comes with hitting .400. He's a guy
who has the ability to shut it out. That doesn't seem to bother
him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-99 2343EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990619.0285 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-19 23:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2491 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     06-19 0952
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A STRAIGHT SHOT FROM THE HEART
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Phil Mickelson caused a commotion when he set his
priorities down like a Cessna on the first fairway at the U.S.
Open. For days people have been carrying on as if he's piloting
fatherhood into a whole new frontier.
</P>
<P>
   With Mickelson's wife Amy due to deliver their first child any
day and Mickelson adamant about attending the birth even if it
costs him a chance at his first major title, the announcers in the
primmest and most proper of sports have been prattling on about
water breaking, not putts.
</P>
<P>
   If you ask us, it's the best thing to happen to golf
broadcasting since Johnny Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Enough, already, about golfers who go to Japan for months at a
time, chasing the pot of gold while their spouses remain back in
the States raising the children. Some nuclear family, that. And
don't aggravate us with stories of athletes who casually,
carelessly father children they have no intention of claiming, much
less raising.
</P>
<P>
   You ought to know, when it comes to his commitment to
fatherhood, Mickelson's not flying solo. Anymore, he's not even
flying in the face of convention. Winger Brian Bellows of the
Washington Capitals flew home between Games 1 and 2 of the 1998
Stanley Cup Finals to be with his wife during the birth of their
second child and Detroit Red Wings captain Steve Yzerman nearly
missed a game in this year's playoffs because he insisted on
attending the birth of his third child.
</P>
<P>
   If Mickelson thinks his yet-to-be-born daughter is weighing on
his mind now, just wait until she's old enough to miss him. Just
wait until she can tug on his pant legs as well as his paternal
instincts.
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson is lucky that way. The Scottsdale resident won't have
to look far for athletes who have balanced with uncommon grace the
sometimes conflicting interests of professional sports and
parenting.
</P>
<P>
   Fellow golfer and Scottsdale resident Tom Lehman, for example,
can tell him a really long drive isn't 325 yards _ it's the five
miles back to your hotel on a Saturday night of a PGA Tour event
after seeing your wife and kids off at the airport.
</P>
<P>
   And Matt Williams, a slugger for the Arizona Diamondbacks, can
tell Mickelson a sacrifice isn't a way of advancing runners, it's a
conscious life decision.
</P>
<P>
   What they have to say, fathers everywhere probably could stand
to hear it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing to remember,'' said Williams, ``is
when you're on your deathbed, do you want to be able to say, `Jeez,
I made a million bucks' or do you want to be able to say you were a
good father? It's all a matter of putting your priorities in
order.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago Williams was on a Cleveland team that advanced to
the World Series. He had reached the pinnacle of his profession. He
should have been ecstatic. Instead, he was miserable.
</P>
<P>
   He and his first wife had split and she was living in Phoenix
with the couple's three children. He missed his two daughters and
son. They visited him often that summer, but it wasn't the same.
The children's lives were scattered in two cities and they began to
show the strain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It got to the point where they didn't want to get on that damn
plane again,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland was the perfect place for Williams, the ballplayer.
But he also knew baseball wouldn't be there to comfort him in his
old age and neither would his kids, if he didn't do something. So
Williams asked for _ and was granted _ a trade to the expansion
Diamondbacks. For the sake of his relationship with his kids, he
went from one of the best teams in major-league baseball to one of
the worst.
</P>
<P>
   The move has worked out well for everyone. The second-year
Diamondbacks have one of the best records in baseball, Williams
leads the National League in runs batted in and his children are a
lot happier now that their dad is a constant presence in their
lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game doesn't allow you to have the perfect family life
under the best of circumstances,'' Williams said. ``You have to try
to do the best you can. Because baseball doesn't last forever.''
</P>
<P>
   The PGA Tour season can stretch from January to December if
golfers let it. As it is, Lehman spends half the year on the road.
``I don't get to sleep at home nearly enough,'' he has lamented.
</P>
<P>
   The itinerant life was OK when his children were preschoolers.
They could be carted along with the carry-on luggage from one event
to the next. But now his two daughters are 9 and 6 and his son is
almost 4. They are growing up. They have lives that clash with
their dad's nomadic existence.
</P>
<P>
   Lehman dotes on them whenever he can. Some athletes hurt
themselves by punching walls or striking water coolers or throwing
patrons through bar windows; Lehman required surgery on his right
shoulder last year when he injured it performing handstands for his
children before the British Open.
</P>
<P>
   It's awesome and awful when his family accompanies him on Tour.
They have a great time, until wife Melissa and the kids have to
return home to their lives. The goodbyes can be heartrending. On
the weekend of the Heritage Classic in Hilton Head, S.C., in April,
Lehman stood with his daughters in the galley of a flight bound for
Atlanta until the plane was ready to push back.
</P>
<P>
   Both girls cried when he disappeared up the jetway and his
younger daughter, Holly, sobbed, ``I want my daddy,'' until after
takeoff.
</P>
<P>
   It would be two weeks before she would get her daddy back.
</P>
<P>
   All too soon, Lehman will have to let his daughters go. But he
doesn't have to tell Mickelson that. He'll find out fast enough.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
