<DOCNO> NYT19990619.0286 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-19 23:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2492 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FREE-MAN-KAN &LR;      06-19 1345
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FREE-MAN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WRONGLY CONVICTED MAN TAKES CAUTIOUS STEPS BACK INTO SOCIETY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MALCOLM GARCIA  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A station wagon lurches past the house that Dennis Fritz shares
with his mother, the car's exhaust exploding from a rusted tailpipe
scraping the pavement.
</P>
<P>
   Next door, a neighbor rips the air with a chain saw.
</P>
<P>
   Down the street, boom boxes blast music that gets lost in
static.
</P>
<P>
   Fritz doesn't blink. This isn't noise.
</P>
<P>
   Noise is the Conner Correctional Center, a medium-security
prison in Hominy, Okla., where Fritz was sentenced in 1988 to life
imprisonment for a murder he did not commit.
</P>
<P>
   Noise is the echo of cell doors slamming shut, guards shouting
in your ear, radios blaring on every tier, inmates yelling for
someone just inches away.
</P>
<P>
   Noise is the roar inside his head for the years he lost behind
bars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things that irritated me before _ noisy neighbors, whooping
and hollering, power tools _ it's just nothing to the madness in
the pen,'' says Fritz, a Kansas City, Mo., native who grew up in
Lee's Summit, Mo., and moved to Oklahoma when he was 17. ``This is
serenity. Everything now I take with a grain of salt.''
</P>
<P>
   In April an Ada, Okla., judge, taking into consideration that
DNA tests of semen and hair samples did not genetically match
Fritz, 49, or his co-defendant, Ron Williamson, 46, dismissed the
murder charges against them for the slaying of Debra Sue Carter,
who was sexually molested and strangled in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still overwhelmed. At various times during the day, once
or twice a day, I think, `You're free,' '' Fritz says quietly in a
soft drawl. ``I find myself wanting to restrict myself a little bit
as if I were still in prison. Just being able to make decisions
puts me in a state of exhilaration, of excitement that is
unbelievable.''
Every day Fritz thinks about prison. Sometimes he dreams about it;
other times he talks about it. He has interviewed writers who want
to tell his story, but he has begun to think that he should write
it himself.
</P>
<P>
   He was one of two inmates in a concrete cell, 8 feet by 10 feet.
The only furnishings were a sink, a toilet and a bunk bed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in the same cell for 10 years,'' he says. ``The cells
are so naked, the only place you can sit is on your bunk....At
least once a day I'd think, `I hate this place.' I had total
disgust for being there.''
</P>
<P>
   He spent hundreds of hours in the prison law library working on
his case, promoting his innocence. His daily routine rarely varied:
He ate his meals, lifted weights and studied in the library. When
it was time to return to his cell, he wrote legal briefs into the
late hours of the night until his back ached.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can remember the first two or three years were a real
struggle,'' Fritz says. ``I was innocent; I knew it but had no way
to place my feelings. A guilty person, they can assign blame to
themselves and feel remorse and begin healing. It is different when
you're innocent. You carry around a set of bitter feelings. It's
harder emotionally than actual prison life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to think, `How did this happen to me?' I had to quit
asking that question. It took me five years to realize that there
was a possibility I might be spending my life there.''
</P>
<P>
   At times marijuana eased the stress. The guards overlooked the
drug because it calmed the inmates, Fritz says. A more serious
offense was alcohol. Anyone caught making brew was automatically
sent to a maximum-security prison. Alcohol caused too many fights.
</P>
<P>
   In the social order of prison life, Fritz had respect as a
murder convict with a life sentence. He quickly learned, however,
to keep quiet about the specific nature of his conviction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baby rapers and women killers are frowned upon,'' he says. ``I
got some hard looks. In the penitentiary, you're around an element
of violence all the time. It's a world of madness. How you say
something and when you say it is real important. Timing is
everything.''
Sometimes Fritz wonders whether he can be totally independent
again. The thought makes him uneasy. He helps around the house or
works outside to regain a level of responsibility denied him in
prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find myself taking small steps,'' he says. ``Every now and
then I drive to the store. I'm not really working to get back into
the mainstream too fast. I don't really feel a part of society yet.
I don't think I ever will. I've grown to be relatively careful in
the things I do.''
</P>
<P>
   So many things have changed. Plastic cards, instead of keys,
open hotel doors. And there's voice mail, ``that telephone message
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee's Summit, a small town when Fritz was there last, is just
one of many growing suburbs connected to the city by a maze of
highways. He feels lost just looking at a map. He remembers many
people but has called only a few old friends whom he hasn't seen
yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I missed access to small stuff like being able to get a metal
finger file,'' Fritz says. ``The bigger things you accept aren't
going to come to you, but it's the little things you always took
for granted that caused a little irritation.''
</P>
<P>
   He remains mindful of his surroundings, aware that someone might
be watching him, sizing him up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why, but I always used to keep my hands in my
pockets when I'd go into a store,'' he said. ``Now I feel
self-conscious, like the store owner would think I'm lifting
something. I catch myself and take my hands out of my pockets.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Resch, district administrator of the Kansas City Probation
and Parole Office, said it would take time for the anxiety to fade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Incarceration is an incredibly dehumanizing experience, more
so when you know you're innocent,'' Resch said. ``I'm not sure it's
possible for any of us who haven't gone through it to know what
it's like to come back out.''
Since their release, Fritz and Williamson have appeared on ``Good
Morning America,'' ``The Leeza Show,'' ``Inside Edition,'' ``Burden
of Proof,'' a German television station and ``Dateline.'' They used
the publicity to push for state-mandated DNA testing for prisoners
who cannot afford to pay for it themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Fritz is content to have behind him the frenzied talk-show
circuit that at times left him feeling like a rag doll. He lives
with his mother, her dog and six cats. He spends his days writing
letters thanking people who supported him in prison. He calls his
daughter in Oklahoma City. She was 12 when he was sentenced; she's
24 now.
</P>
<P>
   Fritz would not let her visit him at Conner. They spoke on the
telephone and wrote letters during those years. He did not want her
exposed to prison life.
</P>
<P>
   He keeps in touch with his lawyer, Barry Scheck, co-founder of
the Innocence Project, a New York-based organization that provides
assistance to inmates who believe they've been wrongfully convicted
of capital offenses. He also maintains contact with Williamson, who
has moved to Springfield.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors wanted the death penalty for both men, but only
Williamson received that sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1973 and 1993, an average of two persons a year were
released nationwide from death row because of DNA test results or
other significant evidence of their innocence, said Richard Dieter,
director of the Washington-based Death Row Information Center.
</P>
<P>
   In the last six years that number increased to an average of
four inmates a year. This year alone, six inmates have been
released from death row.
</P>
<P>
   Fritz knows that he came close to spending his prison time with
Williamson on death row. He holds his bitterness deep inside. Time
is rushing by too fast for him to dwell on what might have been.
</P>
<P>
   ``Me and a buddy inside, we'd talk about what it would be like
to open an icebox or go to the bathroom and close the door and not
have some idiot or guard bust in on you,'' Fritz says. ``We'd keep
an open mind in the belief that we'd be out one of these days. And
when we did walk out, we would have an added perception of life. A
real appreciation of life itself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
